{Hello and welcome to my course on the Anti-Sicilians! My name is Aljoscha Feuerstack, I am an International Master and chess coach. As a friend of dynamic and complicated positions, I have always felt drawn to the Sicilian Defense. In my childhood and teenage years, the flexible Kan Sicilian was my main defense against e4 : c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 . I soon internalized the necessary theoretical knowledge. But what if White didn't want to go for the Open Sicilian, i.e. didn't play Nf3 e6 followed by d4 ? I remember that it wasn't so easy to build up a good repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians back then: The books I knew only dealt with the Anti-Sicilians on move Move order tricks e. g. e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 ) and Anti-Sicilians after Nf3 e6 (e.g. g3 or b3 ) were not considered. It was therefore necessary, equipped with a database and an engine and unfortunately too often only after bitter experiences to do my research. I later expanded my repertoire to include the tricky Four Knights Sicilian. The transition was easy for me because, as in the Kan Sicilian, the opening moves are e4 c5 Nf3 e6 . I already had a lot of knowledge about the Anti-Sicilians and was therefore able to concentrate on the possibilities in the Open Sicilian. My first course on Chessable is also dedicated to the Four Knights Sicilian . On the one hand, this present course is intended to complement my course on the Sicilian Four Knights, because together the two courses form a complete repertoire against 1.e4 . On the other hand, this course can also be used independently. It is aimed at all those who play a Sicilian with 2...e6 . It is suitable for players of the following Sicilian systems: ➤ Four Knights Sicilian ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 Nf6 Nc3 Nc6 ) ➤ Taimanov Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 Nc6 ) ➤ Kan Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 ) . For those Anti-Sicilians which still allow a transition to the Open Sicilian (e.g. e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 , I have therefore given specific alternatives in each case. These ensure that we do not inadvertently end up in an unknown Open Sicilian. In selecting my recommendations, I have been guided by three basic principles: ➤ Reliability . Of course, all lines are tested with the latest engines, but apart from that they are also based on a sound positional foundation and are not dependent on tactical details. I am confident that this repertoire will still be playable many years from now, even if there will certainly be further developments in the details. ➤ Simplicity . What good is the best theoretical knowledge if we can't remember it at the board? When selecting specific lines, I made sure that Black had clear plans and that the positions could be played without move-by-move knowledge (I didn't always find a suitable solution. I therefore recommend a particularly careful study of the chapters on the Alapin Sicilian and – for Kan players – the possible transitions to the Open Sicilian). ➤ Similarity . Against, almost all Anti-Sicilians, I recommend fighting for the center with ...e7-e6 and ...d7-d5 . The kingside is then usually developed with ...Nf6 , ...Be7 , and ...O-O . In the later stages of the game, too, we often follow similar plans; in closed positions, for example, Black usually plays to win space on the queenside. This makes learning easier because we don't have to deal with a multitude of different types of positions. I have often heard the following statement in a similar form: 'I would like to play the Sicilian, because the dynamic play in the Open Sicilian attracts me. But there are so many Anti-Sicilians... I don't have time to learn them all.' That's true, there are a lot of Anti-Sicilians! On the other hand, my experience and work on this course tells me: Only a few of them are worth a headache. In most Anti-Sicilians, Black achieves good play with simple means. Not infrequently, White even falls behind quickly. I think it's worth the effort. The course consists of three parts:   1) The Quickstarter chapter is ideal for a quick introduction to the repertoire. It contains the most important lines and ideas. The knowledge in this chapter is a good basis for initial practical experience. I recommend that you start your study of the course with it.   2) The Theory chapters naturally form the main content of the course. The chapters are arranged in relatively random order, although I have roughly based them on their theoretical importance. It is of course up to you to decide in which order you want to learn them.  3) In the Model games chapter you will find a selection of annotated games. These give an idea of how play can develop in practice, beyond the theoretical knowledge. Now let's get an overview of the content of the course. e4 c5 Nf3 Against the Sicilian with 2... e6 there are some popular Anti-Sicilians on move 3. c3 The Alapin or c3 Sicilian is a popular alternative to the Open Sicilian at all levels. In my opinion it is a dangerous weapon and should be studied carefully. I have devoted the first two chapters to it. d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 e6 At this point White has four similarly popular continuations, each requiring different reactions from Black. For this reason, it's not easy to play against the c3 -Sicilian. Na3 The modern main move and the subject of the second chapter . All other moves ( Be2 , Bd3 , Be3 , and earlier deviations) are considered in the first chapter . Nc3 After that, various Anti-Sicilians are still possible. e6 g3 The Closed Sicilian. It is especially popular at amateur level, as White can get by without much theoretical knowledge. In my opinion, however, it does not present Black with any great challenges. Nge2 A relatively rare continuation, but we should be careful here: White could still transition to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 . Nc6 If you have the Four Knights Sicilian or the Taimanov variation in your repertoire, this is a good choice. In addition, Nf6 is an interesting alternative that fits the Four Knights Sicilian. The details can be found in the sixth chapter . a6 Kan players are best served by this move. This variation can be very sharp and forced. I recommend a careful study of chapter seven . d5 We will deal with this position in the fourth chapter . f4 The Grand Prix Attack. Often White does not advance the f-pawn directly but first plays Nc3 , d3 , or Be2 , only following up with 3.f4 after e6 . We examine all these variations of the Grand Prix Attack in the fifth chapter . Black can achieve at least equal chances with straightforward play in the center. d4 cxd4 c3 The Morra Gambit. dxc3 Nxc3 e6 Accepting the gambit gives Black a good chance of gaining an advantage, as we will see in Chapter 14 . b4 White could also initiate the Wing Gambit with a3 or Nf3 e6 . It is quite rarely played. cxb4 a3 e6 White gets a strong center for the pawn. We analyze the Wing Gambit in chapter 15 . g3 The kingside fianchetto on the second move is rarely encountered. Black can play directly in the center with d5 exd5 Qxd5 – Chapter 16 . b3 Like with g2 - g3 and Bg2 , the fianchetto of the queen's bishop is also more dangerous with the insertion of the moves 2.Nf3 e6 . 2.b3 is the subject of Chapter 17 . Bc4 A dubious move, as the bishop can soon be attacked by a black pawn, as can be seen in Chapter 18 . Na3!? In Chapter 19 we examine this unusual knight move, which is an occasional surprise weapon. The knight usually finds its way back to the center later via c2 . With Ne2 White maintains the possibilities of both the Open Sicilian and a closed game with g2 - g3 . This is very rarely played and is dealt with in Chapter 20 . e6 Nc3 As with Nc3 e6 Nge2 , Black must now continue to reckon with the Open Sicilian. c3 Alapin Sicilian but there is a twist compared to 2.c3 . d5 e5!? This is played relatively rarely and leads to unusual positions. (More popular is exd5 , which after Qxd5 leads to the conventional Alapin Sicilian, which we deal with in the first two chapters.) White 'threatens' the transition to the French Advance Variation with d2-d4 . We therefore play d4 There are more details in chapter three . c4 A mixture of the English opening and the Sicilian. Less popular, but also possible, is 2.c4 . I deal with both in the tenth chapter . Nc6 White could now switch to a harmless variation of the Taimanov Sicilian with 4.d4 , or continue with Nc3 , after which we finally deny the transition to the Open Sicilian with Nd4! . Great theoretical knowledge is not required here, the typical ideas are more important. d3 The King's Indian Attack is a classic, which can be reached via many other move orders as well. Nc6 g3 d5 The game here is usually relatively schematic. It is important to know the ideas of both sides. More details in chapter eleven . g3 A trendy variation against 2...e6 , with which White aims for a quiet positional battle. d5 Playing in the center gives Black easy and free play. We will deal with this in chapter 12 . b3 The queenside fianchetto is more effective here than on move 2. a6 Bb2 d5 Once again I recommend playing in the center. This position is dealt with in chapter 13 . Nc6 My recommendation for the Four Knights Sicilian or Taimanov repertoire. The resulting positions are quite specific, but not particularly dangerous. We will deal with this in chapter eight . a6 The Kan alternative, which we will deal with in chapter nine . If White avoids transitioning to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , Black doesn't have much to fear. Finally, it only remains for me to wish you much joy and success in your games against the Anti-Sicilians! I look forward to your feedback and your experiences with the material. If you have questions about specific positions, spot a mistake, or miss the analysis of a move, I would appreciate your comments. The interactivity of Chessable allows us to improve the course together in this way.}  *

