{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Nf3 {The most natural and – by far – most common developing move.} e6 {This setup is one of the most solid systems against the Alapin-Sicilian. Black focuses on quick kingside development, ensuring king safety. Additionally, two of White's typical ideas are neutralized: on the one hand, gaining space in the center with c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In the first chapter of the main course we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Be3 {With this, White wants to clarify the situation in the center in order to be able to develop the knight to c3 . There is now a threat of 7.dxc5 , winning a pawn, so it is best for Black to release the tension.} cxd4 7. cxd4 {White can't pose any problems with the other recapturing options. Black then gets a good position with natural developing moves. Now White wants to drive away the black queen with Nc3 and then prepare for play on the kingside with Bd3 .} Bb4+ {With this very direct approach, the white plan is thwarted.} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bd3 ({Black would react the same way against} 9. Be2 {. On d3 the bishop is more active and gives White chances to attack on the kingside.}) 9... b6 {The active bishop on d3 should be exchanged.} 10. O-O {The c3 -knight is no longer pinned and now attacks the queen.} Bxc3 {This may seem like a positional concession, but it is necessary here. After queen moves, the black kingside would not be well defended and White would have chances for an attack.} 11. bxc3 Ba6 {The point of the sequence initiated with Bb4+ . The exchange of bishops takes the sting out of White's setup. Black's play comes just in time: White would only have had to play c3 - c4 to be clearly better with the bishop pair and a strong center. That is not possible now.} 12. Bxa6 {White cannot avoid exchanging bishops and this way at least the black knight is forced onto a bad square.} Nxa6 {Most of the time the knight later goes back to b8 and then to c6 or d7 . White should now push for c3 - c4 so that the pawn on c3 does not remain backward and weak and Black is prevented from creating a blockade on the c4 -square.} 13. Qa4 Qb7 (13... Nb8 {is also good. Nc7?! , however, would be weaker because the knight doesn't have good prospects there after} 14. c4 {.}) 14. c4 Rac8 {The position is equal. Next comes ... Nb8 and then either ... Nc6 or ... Nbd7 . Both sides will focus their forces on the center. White is hoping for the d4 - d5 advance, Black wants to prevent that and put White’s hanging pawns under pressure. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 1: Alapin with 6.Be3 / 6.Be2 / 6.Bd2 / 6.a3   ➤ Variation 1B: Alapin with 6.Be3} *

