{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Nf3 {The most natural and – by far – most common developing move.} e6 {This setup is one of the most solid systems against the Alapin-Sicilian. Black focuses on quick kingside development, ensuring king safety. Additionally, two of White's typical ideas are neutralized: on the one hand, gaining space in the center with c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In the first chapter of the main course we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Be2 {A popular and natural developing move that White uses to prepare for short castling. However, the e2 -square is somewhat passive for the bishop. It is often better on d3 , where it can participate in an attack against the black king.} cxd4 {It is usually a good idea to wait before making this exchange, because afterwards White can develop the knight to c3, with tempo. In this case, however, it seems to me that the advantages outweigh the drawbacks, as the direct capture on d4 deprives White of some options.} 7. cxd4 {A typical pawn structure in the Alapin Sicilian. White's d-pawn and the square in front of it are weak. On the other hand, White has some space advantage and the more active pieces.} Nc6 {Sooner or later Ne5 should be prevented.} 8. Nc3 (8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 Qd6 {is a transposition.}) 8... Qd6 ({This is more active than} 8... Qd8 {, where the queen would later get in the way of the rooks.}) 9. O-O Be7 {Black follows a simple development pattern. After short castling, the light-squared bishop should be fianchettoed with ... b6 and ... Bb7 .} 10. Nb5 {The main line. Through direct play, White disrupts Black's development.} Qd8 11. Bf4 {That was the idea of the previous knight jump.} O-O ({A rare move, but one that leads to an equal position through a relatively forced sequence. Black is now ready to drive away the knight with ...a7-a6 , after which White would not have achieved much. The more popular} 11... Nd5 {is also good, but requires a little more theoretical knowledge.}) 12. Bc7 ({With this, White forces the action.} 12. Nc7 $6 {brings White nothing and even leads to a worse position after} Nh5 $1 13. Be5 $1 Rb8 {, e.g.} 14. Rc1 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Nf4 {Black has the bishop pair and the c7 -knight is in danger.}) 12... Qd7 13. Ne5 {Otherwise ... a7 - a6 comes.} Nxe5 14. dxe5 (14. Bxe5 a6 15. Nc7 ({(Or} 15. Nc3 b5 {)}) 15... Ra7 {The position is still equal, but White now has to be careful as the knight does not have a safe way back. ...Bd6 is a threat.}) 14... Nd5 {Once again threatening ... a7 - a6 .} 15. Bd6 a6 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nd6 {On d6 the knight disrupts Black's play. Other knight moves are weaker.} Bd7 ({Black does not have to worry about protecting the b7 -pawn and can therefore now complete development. The bishop goes to c6 . While the previous sequence was relatively forced, the situation has now clarified and play becomes calmer. The following moves are a sample line. Winning a pawn with} 17... Qg5 $6 18. Qd4 Nf4 19. Bf3 Qxg2+ 20. Bxg2 Ne2+ 21. Kh1 Nxd4 {is not worth it, because White will win it right back after} 22. Rac1 {and now has more play. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 1: Alapin with 6.Be3 / 6.Be2 / 6.Bd2 / 6.a3   ➤ Variation 1D: Alapin with 6.Be2}) *

