{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Nf3 {The most natural and – by far – most common developing move.} e6 {This setup is one of the most solid systems against the Alapin-Sicilian. Black focuses on quick kingside development, ensuring king safety. Additionally, two of White's typical ideas are neutralized: on the one hand, gaining space in the center with c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In the first chapter of the main course we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Be2 {White develops the kingside. At the same time, this prepares an attack on the black queen: White would like to play O-O and Nfe5 , after which Bf3 would be a threat. We should therefore react energetically.} b5 {It is best to force the white knight to make a decision directly and continue developing the queenside.} ({After} 8... Be7 $6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nfe5 {White is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 ({White puts pressure on the queenside. Specifically, White is threatening to win a pawn with} 10. Z0 {axb5 axb5 Bxb5 , because the black queen is overloaded with the defense of the b-pawn and the rook.}) 10... Bb7 {Protects the rook and defends against White's threat. It is important to keep the pawn on b5 , as it prevents the activation of the e3 -knight via c4 . White can now isolate the black b-pawn and has a good chance of winning it later, but, as we will see, Black gains positional trumps in return. Many moves are now possible, as White can play axb5 , dxc5 and O-O in any order.} (10... b4 $2 {In his book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' GM Khalifman only considers this cooperative move. White now gets good squares for their pieces and strong pressure on the queenside, e.g.} 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Rc1 Qd6 14. Nc4 Qd5 15. a5 Be7 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 18. Qxb4 {with a clear extra pawn for White in Zhigalko-Hoffmann .}) 11. axb5 {The logical continuation after the previous move.} axb5 12. Rxa8+ Bxa8 13. O-O Be7 ({The right square for the bishop. On d6 it is less safe and can be attacked later:} 13... Bd6 $6 {. The two Indian super stars GM Praggnanandhaa and GM Erigaisi opted for the more active bishop development in blitz and rapid games, but after} 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nd4 b4 16. Nb5 $1 {the bishop has to move again and White wins time – Yoo-Praggnanandhaa .}) ({Black cannot keep the position on the queenside closed, because} 13... c4 $2 {is answered with} 14. b3 {.}) 14. dxc5 {Thus White isolates the black b-pawn.} Qxc5 ({Here, too,} 14... Bxc5 $2 {fails to} 15. Nd4 {.}) 15. Nc2 {White wants to win the black b-pawn, but direct attacks would have been met with ... b5 - b4 . The knight move prevents this resource and at the same time prepares development of the c1 -bishop.} O-O {This amounts to a pawn sacrifice. As we will see, Black gets good compensation.} 16. Be3 {The black queen can no longer keep the b-pawn protected.} Qc7 ({Trying to keep the pawn protected is not advisable:} 16... Qh5 17. Ncd4 Rb8 $2 {(better is 17...Ne5 )} 18. Ng5 Qg6 19. h4 {and the black queen gets into trouble.}) 17. Bxb5 {The most principled move, but not yet tested in practice. White has won a pawn, but the black pieces are very active and exert pressure on both wings.} (17. Nfd4 {In most games that reached this position, the white players opted for this move. White would prefer to capture the b-pawn with the knight, as the bishop is not so well placed on b5 . However, Black can now defend the pawn.} Qb7 {Due to the mating threat on g2 , White must now either give up hope of capturing the b-pawn or accept a weakening of squares around their king.}) 17... Rb8 {White is forced to make a decision.} ({After} 17... Rd8 18. Qe2 Ng4 {, White has the defense} 19. Qc4 {.}) 18. Bxd7 {White giving up the bishop pair means that Black has very good compensation for the pawn even in the long term.} (18. Ncd4 Nc5 {White comes under pressure. Besides ...e6-e5 , ...Ng4 is a threat with an attack on the kingside.} ({(The direct} 18... e5 {would be met with} 19. Nf5 {.)})) 18... Nxd7 19. Bc1 Nf8 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. The bishop pair is strong and the major pieces on the queenside ensure that White cannot move the queenside pawns forward. Next the knight can be activated via g6 . The bishop positions can also be improved: the light-squared bishop has both wings in view on d5 and the dark-squared bishop can increase the pressure on the queenside or kingside from f6 or d6 , respectively. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 2: Alapin with 6.Na3  ➤ Variation 2C: Alapin with 6.Na3 and 7.Nc4} *

