{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. f4 {The most direct way to the Grand Prix attack. This has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this:} ({➤} 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4) ({➤} 2. d3 Nc6 3. f4) ({➤} 2. Be2 Nc6 3. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea.}) 2... d5 {The attack in the center is a well-established response, ensuring that White cannot develop the kingside undisturbed.} 3. exd5 {The most natural and common continuation. But White's position would be better if the f-pawn had not yet moved. The missing pawn on f2 makes the white king's position less secure; the squares e3 and e4 are weakened, on f4 the pawn blocks the dark-squared bishop and, last but not least, the f4 -pawn can be weak later down the road.} Nf6 ({This strong pawn sacrifice was introduced to high-level chess by none other than Mikhail Tal. After} 3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 {White gains some time for development – similar to the Scandinavian Defense. Black would therefore prefer to capture with the knight on d5 . As we will see, Black gets strong compensation if White defends the pawn.}) 4. Bb5+ {White aims to defend the pawn on d5 with c2 - c4 without restricting the bishop.} Bd7 ({The alternative} 4... Nbd7 {gives Black good compensation as well.}) 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 ({Not} 5... Nbxd7 $6 6. c4 {The knight is better developed to c6 , where it controls d4 .}) 6. c4 {After other moves, Black wins back the pawn.} e6 {By moving the c-pawn, White has weakened the d3- and d4 -squares and especially the pawn on d2 , which is now backward. Exchanging the e6 and d5 -pawns helps Black to exploit these weaknesses.} 7. Qe2 {This ensures that Black gets an isolated e-pawn after the exchange on e6 . However, the queen on e2 is not well-placed because it can later be attacked by the black pieces.} Bd6 {Black prepares castling and develops the bishop to its most active square. Now the f4 -pawn is under attack.} 8. d3 ({White defends the f4 -pawn.} 8. dxe6 fxe6 9. d3 O-O {is a transposition.}) 8... O-O 9. dxe6 {Forced, because Black was threatening to capture on d5 .} fxe6 {The exchange has the positive effect for Black that the f8 -rook is already well placed. Black now wants to open up the position and prepares the break ... e6 - e5 for this purpose.} 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. O-O Rae8 {White can no longer prevent ... e6 - e5 .} 12. Nc3 e5 13. f5 {White is lagging behind in development and has weaknesses, so it's best to keep the position as closed as possible. With the text move, White gives back the pawn and plays for a blockade on the e4 -square.} ({After} 13. fxe5 $2 Nxe5 {both the Bishop d6 and the Rook e8 become active. Black has a strong attack.}) 13... Nd4 ({More accurate than} 13... Qxf5 {. The pawn does not run away.}) 14. Qd1 ({White cannot keep the extra pawn with} 14. Nxd4 $2 exd4 15. Ne4 {. Black plays} Nxe4 16. dxe4 Rxf5 $1 {and has a big advantage. The pawn on e4 will soon fall and the passed passed pawn on d4 is an important trump card in the endgame.}) 14... h6 ({After} 14... Nxf5 {White plays} 15. Bg5 {. That's not too bad, but with the text move we can pose greater challenges for White. The c1 -bishop now has no good perspective and it's not clear how White should complete development of the queenside. Black wants to capture with the knight on f5 next and then play against the weak pawn on d3 . There are also attacking ideas such as ...Ng4 and ...e5-e4 . Black is slightly better.  In the game Barle-Lenic, 2008 , followed} Ne4 ({(White can hold on to the extra pawn with} 15... Nh4 {, but after e4! dxe4} 16. Ne4 {the position opens up and Black gets a strong attack.)}) ({(} 15... Nd4 {exd4 also leads to a dangerous opening of the position. The point h2 is vulnerable and Black has a good chance of winning back the pawn on f5 soon.)}) {Nxf5} 16. Bd2 {Nxe4! dxe4} Nd4 {. The knight on d4 is very strong and puts a strain on the white position. Yet White can't exchange it easily, because after ...exd4 Black gets a strong passed pawn and the rook e8 and the bishop d6 become active. Lenic had no difficulty in converting the advantage. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 5: Grand Prix  ➤ Variation 5A: Grand Prix with 2.f4 | 3.Bb5 / 5.d3}) *

