{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 .} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} Nc6 {Black is ready for the transition to the Taimanov or the Four Knights Sicilian.} (3... Nf6 {If you have the Sicilian Four Knights in your repertoire, you can also choose the rare 3...Nf6 instead of the usual 3...Nc6 and thus fight directly for the initiative. This is based on a very interesting and as yet barely tested idea.} 4. g3 {White wants to play a Closed Sicilian.} ({(The alternative is} 4. d4 {, which after} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {leads to the Four Knights Sicilian.)}) 4... b5 $5 {Black exploits the fact that the pawn e4 is only protected by the knight c3 . This idea was introduced in practice in the game Iskov-Kindermann , and has only been repeated in a handful of games since, although Black has a very good score and the engines are also convinced of Black's position. You can find the details in chapter 6 .}) 4. g3 ({This keeps the game within the framework of the Closed Sicilian. After} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {Black chooses between} Nf6 {(the Four Knights Sicilian), Qc7 and a6 (different variations of the Taimanov).}) 4... d5 {Black gains space in the center. White must now be prepared for the further advance of the pawn, which would come with tempo.} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {This stops the further advance of the d-pawn.} cxd4 ({The idea of this move is very concrete: Black wants to exploit White's lack of development. The main line starts with} 6... Bg4 7. Bg2 $1 Nxd4 {and now White decides between} 8. h3 Bf3 9. Kf1 {and . White either wins back the pawn on d5 or gets good play against the centralized king.}) 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Bg2 ({This position can also arise from the Fianchetto Variation of the Four Knights Sicilian: e4 c5} 8. Nf3 {e6} d4 {cxd4} 9. Nxd4 {Nf6 Nc3 Nc6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2 . If you have my course on this opening, there's no need to read further – I still stand by the recommendations I gave there!}) 8... Bg4 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. Not} 8... Bc5 {because of} 9. Qe2+ {and all reactions to the check have drawbacks for Black.}) 9. Qd3 Bc5 {The next bishop is developed with tempo. White now has to make a concession.} 10. Be3 Qb6 ({White can no longer maintain the blockade on d4 . After} 10... Bxd4 11. Bxd4 Qe7+ {Deac-Dubov , the novelty} 12. Kd2 $5 {leads to sharp play.}) 11. Nxc6 (11. Nb3 $4 Nb4 $1 {Black wins material, for example:} 12. Qd2 d4 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 {.}) 11... Bxe3 {Compromises White's pawn structure.} 12. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 13. fxe3 bxc6 ({Black has solved all the opening problems. On e4 ,} 13... d4 {is the simplest: e5 can be answered with} 14. O-O {, preventing White from capturing on c6 with check. To maintain the balance, White now needs to find Nb5! Rae8} O-O $1 {[%eval 32752,0] cxb5 exf6 Re2= . Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 6: Four Knights/Taimanov  ➤ Variation 6: 2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 | 5.exd5 / 9.Qd3}) *

