{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 .} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} a6 ({This is the solution for the Kan repertoire. If White transposes to the Kan Variation with d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , this is no longer within the scope of this course. Instead, our focus will be on 4.g3 and especially on the different variations of the Open Sicilian that can arise after a later d2-d4 .} 3... Nf6 {If you have the Sicilian Four Knights in your repertoire, you can also choose the rare 3...Nf6 instead of the usual 3...Nc6 and thus fight directly for the initiative. This is based on a very interesting and as yet barely tested idea.} 4. g3 {White wants to play a Closed Sicilian.} ({(The alternative is} 4. d4 {, which after} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {leads to the Four Knights Sicilian.)}) 4... b5 $5 {Black exploits the fact that the pawn e4 is only protected by the knight c3 . This idea was introduced in practice in the game Iskov-Kindermann , and has only been repeated in a handful of games since, although Black has a very good score and the engines are also convinced of Black's position. You can find the details in chapter 6 .}) 4. g3 ({White has provoked ...a7-a6 by the 'threat' of an Open Sicilian. Although this is a useful move, it does not correspond to my recommendation 3...d5 against the Closed Sicilian Nc3 e6} 4. g3 {.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this advance to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} (4... d5 $2 {does not work well here. White gains an advantage with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {. Compared to the analogous lines after g3 d5 , ...a7-a6 is a loss of tempo, while Nge2 clearly improves White's position.}) 5. Bg2 Bb7 {From here the bishop puts pressure on the e4 -pawn, which can be further attacked with ... Nf6 and ... b5 - b4 .} 6. O-O Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn with ...b5-b4 . White could defend against this or sacrifice the pawn for initiative with d4 .} 7. d3 {After that, the game remains in the territory of the Closed Sicilian. To me this seems to be far less dangerous than an early d2 - d4 .} ({We consider} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {via the move order d4 cxd4 Nxd4 Nf6 O-O .}) 7... d6 ({Here as well, Black should take control of the e5 -square.} 7... Be7 $2 {allows the typical tactic} 8. e5 Bxg2 9. exf6 Bxf1 10. fxe7 Qxe7 11. Qxf1 {.}) 8. h3 {White wants push their kingside pawns: g3 - g4 , f2 - f4 and Ng3 would be a typical setup.} Nc6 {I like this better than developing the knight to d7 , as the knight has more influence on the center here. Black can become later active in the center with ... d6 - d5 . In addition, Black keeps the d7 -square free, which can be useful in case of g3 - g4 - g5 .} 9. Be3 {A natural developing move and White's most frequent choice.} Be7 10. f4 ({White continues the play on the kingside. It is too late for a transition to an Open Sicilian:} 10. d4 $2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Ne5 {White has lost too much time here. Black is threatening to win a pawn with ...b5-b4 and the knight could soon move to c4 .}) 10... O-O {The white attack is very slow, so the black king has little to fear on the kingside. Black has a good position. On the agenda is play in the center with ... d6 - d5 or on the queenside with ... b5 - b4 and ... a6 - a5 -a4 .} ({After g4} 10... d5 {the black play in the center is stronger than the white attack on the kingside, e.g.:   A ) g5} 11. d4 {gxf6 Bxf6⩱ .}) ({B ) After} 10... e5 {Nd7} 11. Bf2 {Black could play} g5 $5 {to win a pawn. The less sharp f6 exf6 Nxf6⩱ is also good.}) ({C ) Bf2 dxe4 dxe4} 10... Qc7 {[%eval 32764,0] with some advantage for Black, who will bring a rook to d8 next. Then ...Nd4 is possible. If White attacks the knight f6 , it will be transferred to the queenside via d7 . Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 7: Kan (2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2)  ➤ Variation 7B: Kan (2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2) with 4.g3 | 6.O-O / 7.d3}) *

