{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 .} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} a6 ({This is the solution for the Kan repertoire. If White transposes to the Kan Variation with d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , this is no longer within the scope of this course. Instead, our focus will be on 4.g3 and especially on the different variations of the Open Sicilian that can arise after a later d2-d4 .} 3... Nf6 {If you have the Sicilian Four Knights in your repertoire, you can also choose the rare 3...Nf6 instead of the usual 3...Nc6 and thus fight directly for the initiative. This is based on a very interesting and as yet barely tested idea.} 4. g3 {White wants to play a Closed Sicilian.} ({(The alternative is} 4. d4 {, which after} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {leads to the Four Knights Sicilian.)}) 4... b5 $5 {Black exploits the fact that the pawn e4 is only protected by the knight c3 . This idea was introduced in practice in the game Iskov-Kindermann , and has only been repeated in a handful of games since, although Black has a very good score and the engines are also convinced of Black's position. You can find the details in chapter 6 .}) 4. g3 ({White has provoked ...a7-a6 by the 'threat' of an Open Sicilian. Although this is a useful move, it does not correspond to my recommendation 3...d5 against the Closed Sicilian Nc3 e6} 4. g3 {.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this advance to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} (4... d5 $2 {does not work well here. White gains an advantage with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {. Compared to the analogous lines after g3 d5 , ...a7-a6 is a loss of tempo, while Nge2 clearly improves White's position.}) 5. Bg2 Bb7 {From here the bishop puts pressure on the e4 -pawn, which can be further attacked with ... Nf6 and ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d4 {Finally White decides to go for the Open Sicilian after all.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 ({This position is also reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 7. Nxd4 {a6 Nc3 b5 g3 Bb7 Bg2 . So why doesn't White play this way right away? The point behind the detour via the Closed Sicilian is that Black has been tempted into the early ...b7-b5 .  In fact, in the Kan after Nc3 ,} Qc7 {is more popular than b5 . Black is now behind in development in an open position, so accuracy is required.}) 7... Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn with ...b5-b4 . White can defend against this or sacrifice the pawn for initiative with O-O .} 8. Qe2 {White defends the pawn on e4 . Besides, the queen on e2 could be useful for an attack on the black king – either in combination with e4 - e5 or Nd5 .} b4 ({The knight must now either return to the back rank, which would be a great loss of time, or to a4 , where it can be attacked.  Black cannot afford to play carelessly, as the following line demonstrates.} 8... d6 $2 9. O-O Nbd7 {The opposition of the bishops already allows a tactical sequence:} 10. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 11. e5 Bxg2 ({(} 11... Nd5 $2 12. exd6 {is worse.)}) 12. exf6 {Threatening Qxe6+ and Kxg2 . White wins back the sacrificed piece.} Qxf6 ({(} 12... Bxf1 $2 13. Qxe6+ Be7 14. fxg7 {)}) ({(} 12... Bh3 $2 13. fxg7 Bxg7 14. Qh5+ Kf8 15. Qxh3 {)}) 13. Kxg2 {The material balance is restored. White is better because the black king as well as the pawns e6 and d6 are vulnerable.}) 9. Na4 ({Harmless is} 9. Nb1 {, e.g.} Qb6 10. c3 Nc6 {with good play for Black.}) 9... Qa5 {Black gets good counterplay against the knight a4 .} 10. b3 Nc6 {Ideally the bishop should move to this square, but for this the knight d4 must first be exchanged.} 11. Bb2 (11. Be3 {amounts to the same thing.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 {A useful move. The bishop is forced to make a decision and e4 - e5 as well as Bxf6 are removed from the position.} 13. Bb6 Qb5 {[%eval 32764,0] Black is threatening to exchange queens, after which the pawn on e4 would no longer be sufficiently protected. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 7: Kan (2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2)  ➤ Variation 7B: Kan (2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2) with 4.g3 | 6.d4 / 8.Qe2} *

