{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 .} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} a6 ({This is the solution for the Kan repertoire. If White transposes to the Kan Variation with d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , this is no longer within the scope of this course. Instead, our focus will be on 4.g3 and especially on the different variations of the Open Sicilian that can arise after a later d2-d4 .} 3... Nf6 {If you have the Sicilian Four Knights in your repertoire, you can also choose the rare 3...Nf6 instead of the usual 3...Nc6 and thus fight directly for the initiative. This is based on a very interesting and as yet barely tested idea.} 4. g3 {White wants to play a Closed Sicilian.} ({(The alternative is} 4. d4 {, which after} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {leads to the Four Knights Sicilian.)}) 4... b5 $5 {Black exploits the fact that the pawn e4 is only protected by the knight c3 . This idea was introduced in practice in the game Iskov-Kindermann , and has only been repeated in a handful of games since, although Black has a very good score and the engines are also convinced of Black's position. You can find the details in chapter 6 .}) 4. g3 ({White has provoked ...a7-a6 by the 'threat' of an Open Sicilian. Although this is a useful move, it does not correspond to my recommendation 3...d5 against the Closed Sicilian Nc3 e6} 4. g3 {.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this advance to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} (4... d5 $2 {does not work well here. White gains an advantage with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {. Compared to the analogous lines after g3 d5 , ...a7-a6 is a loss of tempo, while Nge2 clearly improves White's position.}) 5. Bg2 Bb7 {From here the bishop puts pressure on the e4 -pawn, which can be further attacked with ... Nf6 and ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d4 {Finally White decides to go for the Open Sicilian after all.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 ({This position is also reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 7. Nxd4 {a6 Nc3 b5 g3 Bb7 Bg2 . So why doesn't White play this way right away? The point behind the detour via the Closed Sicilian is that Black has been tempted into the early ...b7-b5 .  In fact, in the Kan after Nc3 ,} Qc7 {is more popular than b5 . Black is now behind in development in an open position, so accuracy is required.}) 7... Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn with ...b5-b4 . White can defend against this or sacrifice the pawn for initiative with O-O .} 8. O-O {The most common continuation. White sacrifices the e-pawn in exchange for a lead in development. Since the g2 -bishop is now defended, White is threatening e4 - e5 . In addition, the piece sacrifice Nd5 is a common motif, aiming to open the e-file and attack the king. The pawn sacrifice with 8.O-O was introduced into tournament practice by none other than the young Mikhail Tal.} b4 {Black should not shy away from the complications.} ({The second most common move,} 8... d6 $2 {, leads to a very dangerous position for Black, e.g.} 9. Re1 Qc7 ({(after} 9... Nbd7 {,} 10. e5 $1 Bxg2 11. exf6 Bb7 12. fxg7 Bxg7 13. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Rxe6+ Kf8 15. Rxd6 {is winning.)}) 10. a4 bxa4 11. Nd5 $1 {. This strong piece sacrifice has been known for a long time and was tested in many games. Black is too far behind in development and now the king is also under attack. White is already winning.}) 9. Na4 {This is of course not the ideal square for the knight, but at least it prevents ... Bc5 and attacks the weakened b6 -square.} (9. Nd5 $6 {The position is not yet ready for the piece sacrifice.} exd5 10. exd5 Bc5 $1 {The bishop is safe here and the king has a flight square on f8 .}) (9. e5 {This only leads to exchanges and is not dangerous.} Bxg2 10. Kxg2 bxc3 11. exf6 Qxf6 12. bxc3 Bc5 {Black can finish development without interference and doesn't have any problems.}) 9... Bxe4 ({Again there are no good alternatives. Much worse is} 9... Nxe4 $2 10. Re1 d5 {and now} 11. c4 $1 {is strongest for White. After} bxc3 12. bxc3 {followed by Rb1 Black can no longer defend against the threats on the queenside.}) 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 {The black position looks tactically vulnerable. The only developed piece is the unprotected knight on e4 . The queenside is weakened and the rook on a8 is also unprotected. However, as practice and analysis show, these factors do not give White more than sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} 11. Re1 ({The most common move. Besides,} 11. c4 {is dangerous, which we deal with in detail in the theory chapter.}) 11... Nc5 {The strongest continuation. Black wants to exchange knights and develop the bishop to c5 .} ({The old main continuation is} 11... d5 {. This has the drawback that the pawn e6 is no longer reliably defended. White can exploit this with} 12. c4 $1 bxc3 13. Nxc3 {. Now the knight on e4 is attacked, and it is needed to block the e-file. After} Nxc3 $2 {(it is better to return the pawn with 13...Be7 ) there follows the piece sacrifice} 14. Qh5 $1 Ne4 ({(} 14... g6 15. Qe5 {)}) 15. Nxe6 {, e.g.} g6 16. Nc7+ $1 Qxc7 17. Qxd5 {. White wins back the material and the attack continues.}) 12. c3 {White defends the knight on a4 and attacks the pawn on b4 .} Nxa4 13. Qxa4 {The queen is pinning the d-pawn. Black should therefore be wary of the piece sacrifice Nxe6 .} Qb6 ({This not only defends the b4 -pawn but also protects against the piece sacrifice on e6 .  ➤ A good alternative is to return the pawn with} 13... Be7 {.  ➤ After bxc3} 14. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Rxe6 {Black should return the piece with Be7!} ({(Not Kf7?} 15. Re5 $1 {and the white attack is too strong. Zapata-Bruzon Batista )}) {Bg5} 15... Nc6 {Bxe7 Nxe7 Rae1 O-O} 16. Rxe7+ {.}) 14. Be3 {Once again the piece sacrifice on e6 is a threat.} Bc5 ({White should now play the novelty Qd1 to keep the balance. We will look at this position in more detail in chapter 7 . The piece sacrifice Nxe6?! is a typical motif and should always be checked. Here, White's compensation is not convincing. fxe6} 14... Bc5 {Qxc5 Rxe6+ Kd8} 15. cxb4 {Qf5∓ Black will continue with moves like ...Rf8 , ...Ra7 and ...Nc6 and has a safe king. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 7: Kan (2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2)  ➤ Variation 7B: Kan (2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2) with 4.g3 | 6.d4 / 8.O-O}) *

