{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ({White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose a6 and are in familiar territory after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {.} ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after d4 cxd4} 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights).}) ({(➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal!) ➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.}) ({➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nc3 Qb6 {) would only be left with the exotic . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!})) 3... a6 {The solution for the Kan repertoire. White could now transition to the Kan Variation with d4 ; however, the attempts g3 and Be2 , which leave open a later transition to the Open Sicilian, are trickier. In addition, we look at a4 , with which White wants to stop Black's play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 .} 4. g3 ({White decides against the transposition to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 {. However, d2-d4 remains to be reckoned with. White keeps their options open and first develops the bishop to g2 . This is reminiscent of the Closed Sicilian, but there White usually places the knight on e2 , where it does not block the bishop's diagonal.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this move to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} 5. Bg2 Bb7 {Black is threatening to win a pawn with ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d3 ({We deal with the transposition to the Open Sicilian after} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 {in detail via the move order Nc3 e6 Nge2 a6 g3 b5 Bg2 Bb7 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 .}) 6... d6 {Takes control of e5 and thus prepares ...Nf6 .} 7. O-O Nf6 {The black moves are easy. Next on the agenda is ...Be7 and ...O-O . Meanwhile, it's not easy for White to make progress. The knight on f3 blocks the advance of the f-pawn, which would be the natural plan in similar positions in the Closed Sicilian. In practice, White usually chooses between one of the following two approaches:  ➤ preparing f2-f4 by Ng5 or Nh4 ,  ➤ opening the position with e4-e5 (either directly or after the preparatory ) .} 8. Re1 {White prepares e4 - e5 .} Be7 ({I see no need for} 8... Nbd7 {, which would make e4-e5 more difficult.}) 9. e5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 O-O ({Black would now like to exchange the knight e5 with ...Nfd7 . The immediate} 11... Nfd7 $2 {was not possible because of} 12. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 13. Qf3+ {and 14.Qxa8 .}) 12. Qf3 Ra7 {Black should keep the square c6 protected and leave the knight b8 on its starting square for the time being. First the knight e5 must be driven away or exchanged, which can be achieved with ... Nfd7 .} 13. a4 ({Other moves such as} 13. Be3 {or Bf4 have also been tried. Black then gets good play with .}) ({With} 13. a4 {White fights for the potential outpost c4 for the knight on e5 .}) 13... b4 14. Ne4 Nfd7 {Again, this is the easiest. The knight on e5 prevents the development of the queenside.} 15. Nc4 ({The knight is quite stable here, but not particularly threatening either. After} 15. Nxd7 {,} Rxd7 $1 {is the strongest. The knight can then be developed via c6 , where it targets the important central square} 16. d4 {. White must also watch out for ...b4-b3 , which undermines the d3 -pawn. After Be3 , Black first protects the c5 -pawn with} Rd5 {and then plays ...Nc6 . Black is already slightly better.}) 15... Nc6 {Black has completed development. The knight strives towards d4 , but ... Nde5 is also a strong resource, especially in combination with ... b4 -b3 .} ({In practice, in both games where this position was reached, White played Bf4?! This controls the square e5 , but now Black gets the upper hand with Instead, White should play Nf6+! to equalize. After Nxf6 Qxc6 b3!? (or Nd5 ) cxb3 Qxd3 , White defends best with Nb6 Qxb3 Nc8 Rb7 Nxe7+ Rxe7 Qxa6 with equality. Nd4 Qd1} 15... b3 $1 {. This prevents the strong knight on} 16. d4 {from being driven away, as c3 is met with the fork ...Nc2 . White must therefore play cxb3 , after which Black further supports the d4 -knight with Nb8 and ...Nbc6 . Black will be able to play moves like ...Qd5 and ...Rb7 , exerting pressure on both wings. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 9: 9 Kan (2.Nf3 e6 3.Nc3)  ➤ Variation 9C: Kan (2.Nf3 e6 3.Nc3) with 4.g3 | 8.Re1}) *

