{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most popular move. White develops a piece and preserves the option d2 - d4 .} Nd4 ({The knight occupies d4 and thus thwarts White's plan to subsequently transition to the Maroczy structure with d2-d4 . We take advantage of the fact that White loses time after an exchange on d4 because the knight c3 is attacked. This idea is familiar from the chapter on the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 $1 {) . If White does not capture on d4 now, we will increase our control of the square with ...Ne7-c6 .}) ({A good alternative is} 4... Nf6 5. Be2 d5 {. The main line is now} 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 {. This queenless middlegame is close to equality, but doesn't promise Black good winning chances.}) 5. d3 {The most popular move. White now threatens to evict the intruder on d4 with 6.Be3 .} Ne7 6. g3 {White invests a tempo in the bishop's development. It has better prospects on g2 than on e2 .} Nec6 7. Bg2 Be7 {Black could also have copied the opponent's idea and fianchettoed their bishop as well. However, it is not clear whether it is better on g7 than on e7 . b2 - b4 is one of White's main ideas and from e7 the bishop makes this plan more difficult. If it is needed on the long diagonal, it can still move to f6 .} 8. O-O ({It is not yet a good moment for the exchange on d4 , because after} 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 {, Black can play} b5 $1 {without further preparation. The pawn is indirectly defended thanks to the queen check on a5 .}) 8... Rb8 ({A small subtlety. Black gets ready for a quick ...b7-b5 . The more natural} 8... O-O {is also playable, but has the drawback that White can prevent the pawn break ...b7-b5 with} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Nb1 $1 {, e.g.} a6 11. a4 Rb8 12. Na3 {. As a result, the black position is relatively passive.}) 9. a3 ({Similarly, gaining space on the queenside with b2-b4 is a natural plan for White as well. Thanks to the rook move White now achieves nothing with} 9. Nxd4 {. After} cxd4 10. Nb1 ({(or} 10. Ne2 b5 {. Hakiki, K-Fedorchuk, S )}) 10... b5 $1 {Black has activity on the queenside and is already slightly better.}) 9... O-O 10. Rb1 {Further preparations for b2 - b4 ...} a6 ({and for ...b7-b5 . After the direct} 10... b5 11. cxb5 Nxb5 12. Nxb5 Rxb5 {White finally gets in the long sought-after} 13. d4 {and is slightly better. Petrova-Hrebenshchykova}) 11. Bf4 {This also serves to prepare for b2 - b4 : by provoking ... d7 - d6 , White cuts off the e7 -bishop from controlling the b4 -square.} d6 12. b4 {White comes first. The threat is b4xc5 , but apart from that White's play on the queenside is not very dangerous.} Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bg5 {Exchanging the dark-squared bishops gives Black good control of the central squares d4 and e5 .} 14. Bxg5 Qxg5 {[%eval 32760,0] We have been following the game Petrova-Vega Gutierrez . Black is on the slightly more comfortable side of an equal position. As before, ... b7 - b5 is a good plan, as it would lead to an advantageous opening of the position. The queen and knight play on the dark squares and the bishop goes to d7 . White will probably prepare f2 - f4 to get counterplay on the kingside. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 10: English Hybrid  ➤ Variation 10B: English Hybrid with 3.c4 | 4.Nc3 / 5.d3} *

