{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 {With this move, White initiates the King's Indian attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Qe2 {By leaving the d-file, White avoids a possible queen trade, which would otherwise be possible after the exchange on e4 . Additionally, White preemptively defends the e-pawn. Compared to the main line, 5.Nbd2 , the queen move has the advantage that White retains more flexibility on the queenside. The c1 -bishop can be developed directly and the knight can be brought to c3 (or even a3 ). As we will see, White also pursues a very specific idea which is not possible after 5.Nbd2 .} Nf6 {The standard setup for Black: the knight goes to f6 , where it puts pressure on e4 . If White plays e4 - e5 , the knight goes to d7 and attacks the e-pawn again.} ({The e7 -square is reserved for the bishop. Black could also start with} 5... Be7 {.}) 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O ({White could also start with} 7. e5 {. But after} Nd7 8. c4 O-O {there is nothing better than} 9. O-O {, with a transposition to 7.O-O .}) 7... O-O ({After both sides have brought their king to safety, it is now up to White to decide on a plan. Interesting is} 7... b5 {to prevent c2-c4 . However, White could avoid this possibility with the move order} 8. e5 Nd7 9. c4 {.}) 8. e5 ({White closes the center and prepares the following move. The direct} 8. c4 $6 {would give Black comfortable play after} dxc4 9. dxc4 e5 {.}) 8... Nd7 {The usual square for the knight, which from here ties the white pieces to the defense of the e5 -pawn.} 9. c4 {This is the point of the line starting with 5.Qe2 . We will see in the main line 5.Nbd2 that Black develops a strong attack on the queenside, which is initiated with the move ... b7 - b5 . In contrast, here White has already protected the pawn on e5 and therefore has time to complicate Black's play on the queenside.} a6 ({Black does not lose sight of the goal and again prepares ...b7-b5 . The most common move is} 9... d4 {. After that, however, Black lacks counterplay, while White has a free hand on the kingside. A good illustration is the rapid game Carlsen-Ding .}) 10. h4 {Typical play for the King's Indian Attack. The pawn can later be moved further forward, and it also controls g5 .} b5 11. Bf4 {Another move typical of the King's Indian Attack. The bishop stabilizes the center and cannot itself be attacked.} Nb6 ({Black increases the pressure on the c4 -pawn. With the knight on b6 , Black no longer has to reckon with the exchange on d5 .} 11... Bb7 $6 {is premature:} 12. cxd5 $1 exd5 13. e6 {With this opening of the position, the bishop is needed on c8 .}) 12. b3 ({With this defensive move, White keeps open how the knight on b1 will be developed and avoids the concrete problems that Black can pose after both} 12. Nbd2 {and Na3 .}) 12... Bb7 ({Here} 12... bxc4 13. dxc4 a5 {doesn't work so well – White plays} 14. Nc3 Ba6 15. Rad1 {and gets pressure against the d-pawn.}) 13. Nbd2 ({The human move. White develops the last piece. In both games with classical time control in which this position was reached, this move was played. Stockfish suggests} 13. Rc1 {instead. The idea is probably to keep the knight's options open: it could be developed to c3 , d2 , or even a3 .} Qd7 {The queen clears the way for the f8 -rook. A complex middlegame position has been reached in which both sides have equal chances.} ({(} 13... Qc7 $6 14. Nc3 $1 {would be slightly better for White.)}) {In the correspondence game Dawson-Lumsdon , there followed} 14. Nbd2 h6 {(A useful move that stabilizes the kingside. But there was also nothing to be said against 14...Rfc8 .)} 15. d4 {(White resolves the tension in the center.)} bxc4 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. bxc4 Qe7 {with equality.}) (13. Nc3 {allows} Nd4 {. After the exchange on d4 , the knight on c3 must move again.}) 13... Qc7 ({This is stronger than both} 13... Rc8 {and Qd7 , which were played before. Black wants to bring a rook to d8 and can then open the d-file at a favorable moment.}) 14. Rfd1 {Among the many options, this looks like the most logical. White prepares for the opening of the d-file and prepares the regrouping of the knight via f1 .} Rfd8 {The right rook. The a-rook is good on c8 or b8 .} 15. Nf1 {Again, there are many other options, but it's not so clear how White should proceed. Black can strengthen the position with ... Rac8 and ... h6 .} bxc4 ({It's just as good to wait with this decision and strengthen the position with, say,} 15... Rac8 {.}) 16. bxc4 dxc4 17. dxc4 Nd4 {This leads to an favorable exchange.} 18. Nxd4 cxd4 {Black is better. The pawn on c4 is weak and can be attacked by Black's major pieces. On the other hand, White has no good way to attack the d4 -pawn, and it is therefore more of a strength. If White defends the pawn on c4 , Black can further improve their position with ... Na4 . The knight can go to c3 or to c5 , where it supports the d-pawn.} ({A possible continuation is Bxb7 Qxb7 Nd2 (intending Nb3 )} 18... Na4 {(threatening the fork …Nc3 ) Ne4 Rac8 followed by …Qc6 . Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 11: King's Indian Attack  ➤ Variation 11B: KIA with 5.Qe2 | 10.h4 / 12.b3}) *

