{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {The fianchetto of the king's bishop means that White is out for a quiet, positional battle. From g2 the bishop supports the center and aims in the long term towards the black queenside. The position initially remains closed and the situation in the center unresolved. The move has become quite popular in recent years and has been adopted by many top players. GM Wesley So recommends the move in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 on Chessable.} d5 ({The more popular alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, which keeps Black's options open: ...d7-d5 is still possible, but also the blockade of the center with ...e6-e5 or a setup with ...d7-d6 . But d5 is easier in my opinion. We exploit the fact that the bishop's development to g2 is somewhat slow and fight directly for the initiative. Black is prepared to accept an isolated queen's pawn for this. As we will see, however, White does not manage to achieve their strategic goals without making concessions.}) 4. exd5 exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a perennial problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop is no longer blocked by the e-pawn and can be actively developed. However, the altered pawn structure also has drawbacks. White will try to isolate the black d-pawn with d2 - d4 .} {In addition to the direct d4 , White can also focus on development first by starting with Bg2 .} 5. Bg2 {White wants to castle and only then become active in the center. We won't allow that.} Qe7+ {Exploits the opponent's move order. White is prevented from castling.} 6. Qe2 Qxe2+ 7. Kxe2 Nc6 {Black increases their influence on the d4 -square.} 8. Re1 {White prepares 'castling by hand' – the rook is activated before the king returns to f1 .} h6 {A simple solution against the impending rook check. Black first takes control of the g5 -square.} 9. Kf1+ Be6 {The point of the previous move. White can now no longer play Ng5 and Black can finish development without interference. The position is equal. Let's look at some attempts for White:} ({A ) Bh3?!} 9... Kd7 {leads to nothing. The exchange on e6 would give Black an extra center pawn and play on the f-file.}) ({) Nc3? is a tactical mistake. After Nb4! White can no longer protect the pawn c2 . C ) Possible is the pawn sacrifice d4 cxd4 (Not Nxd4? Nxd4 cxd4 Bxd5 .) Nbd2 Bc5 Nb3 Bb6 . The black d-pawn is weak, but it is not so easy for White to win it back. Black has no worries. D ) c3 is too slow to cause problems, e.g. O-O-O d4 Nf6 ( 11...cxd4= ) Nbd2 cxd4 Nxd4 . In the game Marinkovic-Sax , the players agreed on a draw. After the exchange of knights on d4 , both sides are indeed very solid. E ) b3 White wants to develop the bishop to b2 and then play d2-d4 .} 9... Be7 {[%eval 0,0] Bb2 Bf6 The exchange of bishops makes the black game easier, as White's dark-squared bishop was quite strong. Bxf6 Nxf6} 10. Nc3 {O-O Black doesn't have any problems. Holland, J-Bezuidenhout, R . Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 12: Delayed Kingside Fianchetto  ➤ Variation 12B: Delayed Kingside Fianchetto with 4.exd5 | 5.Bg2 / 6.Qe2}) *

