{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {The fianchetto of the king's bishop means that White is out for a quiet, positional battle. From g2 the bishop supports the center and aims in the long term towards the black queenside. The position initially remains closed and the situation in the center unresolved. The move has become quite popular in recent years and has been adopted by many top players. GM Wesley So recommends the move in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 on Chessable.} d5 ({The more popular alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, which keeps Black's options open: ...d7-d5 is still possible, but also the blockade of the center with ...e6-e5 or a setup with ...d7-d6 . But d5 is easier in my opinion. We exploit the fact that the bishop's development to g2 is somewhat slow and fight directly for the initiative. Black is prepared to accept an isolated queen's pawn for this. As we will see, however, White does not manage to achieve their strategic goals without making concessions.}) 4. exd5 exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a perennial problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop is no longer blocked by the e-pawn and can be actively developed. However, the altered pawn structure also has drawbacks. White will try to isolate the black d-pawn with d2 - d4 .} {In addition to the direct d4 , White can also focus on development first by starting with Bg2 .} 5. d4 {The main move. White wants to capture on c5 at an opportune moment and play against the isolated d-pawn.} cxd4 ({I like this better than the more popular moves} 5... Nc6 {and . The idea behind it is very concrete: Black takes advantage of the fact that the white king is still on e1 .}) (5... Nc6 6. Bg2 cxd4 {would transpose to my recommendation after} 7. Nxd4 {, but White has the additional option} ({( Bg4 is the main move. The pawn sacrifice} 7. O-O {gives White some initiative.)})) {O-O .} 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 {One move is still missing – castling short – and White's opening concept would be a complete success: the pawn on d5 is isolated and weak, giving White a small but permanent advantage.} Bc5 {This is the idea of our previous moves. While White can easily fend off the attack on the knight, they cannot do so without making a concession.} 8. Nb3 {The most popular continuation. White attacks the bishop c5 and the pawn d5 .} (8. Be3 $6 {White would like to maintain the blockade on d4 . But there is a concrete problem with this.} Nxd4 $1 9. Bxd4 Qe7+ {White loses the right to castle. In the chapter on 3.g3 we investigate this position more deeply.}) 8... Qe7+ {A key idea in the line with 5...cxd4 . White is prevented from castling.} 9. Qe2 Bb6 ({Exchanging queens first is also possible. Less strong, however, is} 9... Be6 10. O-O {with some advantage for White. As we will see, it is not necessary to defend the d-pawn.}) 10. Qxe7+ ({Grabbing the pawn runs into concrete problems:} 10. Bxd5 $2 Qxe2+ 11. Kxe2 Nb4 $1 {The double attack on d5 and c2 forces the white reply.} 12. Be4 Nf6 {The knight is developed with tempo. Once again the white reply is forced.} 13. Bd3 {Not a good square for the bishop. It no longer defends the weakened squares on the kingside and Black could capture it any time and secure the advantage of the bishop pair. But there is no reason to hurry.} O-O {Even though the queens are exchanged, Black has an attack. The threat is ...Bg4+ and ...Re8+ .}) 10... Ngxe7 {Conveniently, the d-pawn is now protected.} 11. O-O Bf5 {White is faced with a choice between two evils: after the defensive move Na3 the knight is misplaced. If White opts for c3 , the knight can no longer be developed to c3 and Black could later disperse the isolated pawn with ...d5-d4 .} 12. c3 O-O ({Black has free play and no problems. Next the rooks are centralized.} 12... O-O-O {, followed by ...d5-d4 , also leads to equality. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 12: Delayed Kingside Fianchetto  ➤ Variation 12B: Delayed Kingside Fianchetto with 4.exd5 | 5.d4 / 6.Nxd4}) *

