{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {Against the Sicilian with 2...e6 , the fianchetto of the queen's bishop is a viable sideline. In other Sicilians, Black could easily neutralize the bishop on b2 , for instance by the pawn setup d6 + e5 or developing the king's bishop to g7 . With 2...e6 , however, Black has already signaled that the bishop will be developed on the diagonal ... f8 - a3 and it is also not very tempting to lose a tempo with another move of the e-pawn. This means that the white bishop can take up a strong attacking position on the long diagonal, as it has the black kingside directly in its sights. If Black allows it, White could also later transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or go for the Maroczy structure with c2 - c4 .} a6 {I recommend playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 also against the queenside fianchetto. This is prepared with 3... a7 -a6 , which is, unlike in the Kan Sicilian, less about expanding on the queenside and more about denying the white bishop the b5 -square. The latter now has no good prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal as long as White has not played d2 - d4 : on c4 it would be easy to attack, on d3 it would be in the way of the d-pawn and e2 is a very passive square.} ({The direct} 3... d5 {allows} 4. Bb5+ $1 {.   A )} Nc6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {transposes to a variation of the Rossolimo Sicilian ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 Bb5 ) . White has very good long-term chances here due to the weakened black queenside.)}) ({) Bd7 is now best, but after Bxd7+ Qxd7 exd5 exd5 O-O White benefits from the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The most common move is} 3... Nc6 {[%eval 0,0] . Here White could already transpose to a kind of Rossolimo-Sicilian with} 4. Bb5 {. More popular, however, is Bb2 . Black now has various moves to choose from, but playing in the center with} d5 {would already be quite dangerous, because after Bb5! dxe4?! (better would be Nf6 or Nge7 )} 5. Ne5 {followed by an exchange on c6 , the shattered pawn structure on the queenside and the strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. Bb2 d5 {The central advance is a standard idea, though not yet very popular in this specific position. I believe this will change, as many strong grandmasters have played this way recently.} ({It's a good time for ...d7-d5 , as the bishop check on b5 has been eliminated.  If Black waits any longer, White could preempt Black's play in the center. The most popular move is} 4... Nc6 {, but I don't like the fact that White can now determine the character of the game. With} 5. c4 {White can increase control in the center and prevent ...d7-d5 . The developing moves g3 and Be2 give Black more freedom, as 5...d5 would again be possible.  Finally, d4 cxd4} Nd4 {is occasionally played, although Black need not worry about this version of the Open Sicilian, because Qf6! followed by ...Bc5 promises good play.}) 5. exd5 ({White is practically forced to make this exchange.} 5. e5 $2 {would be a positional mistake. Not only does the e5 -pawn block the b2 -bishop's diagonal – it can hardly be saved. Black can increase the pressure further with ... Nc6 , ... g7 - g5 , ... Bg7 etc. and White will soon run out of defensive moves.}) 5... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a typical problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop can be developed freely. White now most commonly plays d4 , which amounts to an exchange against the black c-pawn and subsequent play against the isolated pawn on d5 . Alternatively, White could go for piece activity.} 6. Qe2+ {The queen check is the second most popular move and the engine's favorite. Black needs to play accurately here.} Be6 ({Worse is} 6... Qe7 {. After} 7. Qxe7+ {(or Nc3 Nf6 d4⩲ )} Nxe7 8. Nc3 {White has the more harmonious seetup and – after a later d2-d4 followed by dxc5 – the better pawn structure.}) 7. g3 {This not only prepares the development of the bishop to g2 . Black should also pay attention to the possibility of Bh3 .} Nc6 ({After all other moves, Black is worse} 7... Nf6 $2 {allows} 8. Ng5 {– the square is no longer defended by the queen. After} Qe7 9. Nxe6 fxe6 ({(or} 9... Qxe6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bg2 {)}) 10. Bh3 {, Black comes under strong pressure.}) ({It may seem natural to prepare ...Nf6 with} 7... h6 $2 {, but that is too slow. White's best continuation now is} 8. Bh3 Qe7 9. Bxe6 Qxe6 ({(even worse is} 9... fxe6 $2 10. Ne5 {)}) 10. Nc3 {, after which Nxd5 is a threat. If Black defends the d-pawn, d2-d4 follows along with an exchange on c5 , after which the black d-pawn will be very weak. The defense} d4 $2 {does not work here because of} 11. Nd5 $1 {. Black does not succeed in defending the queenside, e.g. the natural} Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bd6 $2 {loses because of the unusual fork} 13. Nb6 Ra7 14. Nc8 $1 {.}) 8. Bg2 {The more conventional bishop development is not without its poison - how should Black complete development?} d4 {Shuts out the b2 -bishop, which had put unpleasant pressure on the g7 -pawn. Now Black can proceed with the setup ...Be7 , ...Nf6 and ...O-O .} (8... Nf6 $2 {was played in the top-class online rapid game Chigaev-Le , but, as before, this is no good due to} 9. Ng5 $1 {. After} Qd7 10. Nxe6 fxe6 {,} 11. Bh3 {would have been the strongest continuation.}) ({After} 8... h6 $6 9. O-O Nf6 {as well, White gets strong pressure along the e-file with} 10. Bh3 $1 {.}) ({However,} 8... Nh6 $5 9. O-O Nf5 {is possible, which was under discussion in Sasikiran-Movsesian . The knight defends g7 so that Black can then complete development with ...Be7 and ...O-O .}) 9. O-O Be7 10. Ne5 {With 8...d4 we had taken the b2 -bishop out of play, but on the other hand cleared the view for its colleague on g2 .} ({White tries to exploit this. A developing move like} 10. Na3 {is met with} Nf6 {, after which Black is ready to castle.} 11. Ng5 $6 {is now only a loss of time – the bishop e6 is no longer pinned.} Bd5 {.}) 10... Nxe5 11. Qxe5 Rb8 ({The pawn g7 needs no protection, since the queen would be trapped after Qxg7?} 11... Bf6 {. Now Black is again ready for development of the kingside with ...Nf6 .}) 12. c3 {The hardest test.} b6 ({This doesn't allow White's planned activation of the minor pieces on the queenside. Black sacrifices a pawn for this. After} 12... dxc3 $6 13. Nxc3 {or d3?! Re1} Nf6 {c4⩲ the two white bishops are very strong.}) 13. cxd4 ({The game Ivic-Predke , ended in the repetition} 13. Qe4 Nf6 14. Qc6+ Bd7 15. Qf3 Bg4 16. Qc6+ Bd7 17. Qf3 Bg4 {.}) ({After} 13. Na3 {or Re1 , Black finishes development with} Bf6 {and ...Ne7 .}) 13... Bf6 {It was necessary to prepare this move with 12...b6 because otherwise the pawn c5 would have been unprotected.} 14. Qe2 Ne7 ({Development first. The d4-pawn is pinned and doesn't run away. The knight move is more precise than} 14... Bxd4 $6 15. Bxd4 Qxd4 {, as happened the blitz game Caruana-Chigaev . Here the well-known motif} 16. Bh3 $1 {would have given White some advantage, because after} Qxa1 $2 17. Nc3 Qb2 18. Bxe6 {White wins back material and has a strong attack.}) 15. Qxa6 O-O {[%eval 32760,0] Black is currently two pawns down, but will soon regain one of them on d4 . There's still no reason to hurry: instead of ... Bxd4 Black could also play ... Nf5 and ... Nxd4 . White won't have much fun with the remaining extra pawn: the d2 -pawn is weak and backward, the black pieces are active and Black has the outpost square d4 under control. The position is equal. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 13: Delayed Queenside Fianchetto  ➤ Variation 13: Delayed Queenside Fianchetto | 4.Bb2 / 6.Qe2+} *

