{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {Against the Sicilian with 2...e6 , the fianchetto of the queen's bishop is a viable sideline. In other Sicilians, Black could easily neutralize the bishop on b2 , for instance by the pawn setup d6 + e5 or developing the king's bishop to g7 . With 2...e6 , however, Black has already signaled that the bishop will be developed on the diagonal ... f8 - a3 and it is also not very tempting to lose a tempo with another move of the e-pawn. This means that the white bishop can take up a strong attacking position on the long diagonal, as it has the black kingside directly in its sights. If Black allows it, White could also later transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or go for the Maroczy structure with c2 - c4 .} a6 {I recommend playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 also against the queenside fianchetto. This is prepared with 3... a7 -a6 , which is, unlike in the Kan Sicilian, less about expanding on the queenside and more about denying the white bishop the b5 -square. The latter now has no good prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal as long as White has not played d2 - d4 : on c4 it would be easy to attack, on d3 it would be in the way of the d-pawn and e2 is a very passive square.} ({The direct} 3... d5 {allows} 4. Bb5+ $1 {.   A )} Nc6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {transposes to a variation of the Rossolimo Sicilian ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 Bb5 ) . White has very good long-term chances here due to the weakened black queenside.)}) ({) Bd7 is now best, but after Bxd7+ Qxd7 exd5 exd5 O-O White benefits from the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The most common move is} 3... Nc6 {[%eval 0,0] . Here White could already transpose to a kind of Rossolimo-Sicilian with} 4. Bb5 {. More popular, however, is Bb2 . Black now has various moves to choose from, but playing in the center with} d5 {would already be quite dangerous, because after Bb5! dxe4?! (better would be Nf6 or Nge7 )} 5. Ne5 {followed by an exchange on c6 , the shattered pawn structure on the queenside and the strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. Bb2 d5 {The central advance is a standard idea, though not yet very popular in this specific position. I believe this will change, as many strong grandmasters have played this way recently.} ({It's a good time for ...d7-d5 , as the bishop check on b5 has been eliminated.  If Black waits any longer, White could preempt Black's play in the center. The most popular move is} 4... Nc6 {, but I don't like the fact that White can now determine the character of the game. With} 5. c4 {White can increase control in the center and prevent ...d7-d5 . The developing moves g3 and Be2 give Black more freedom, as 5...d5 would again be possible.  Finally, d4 cxd4} Nd4 {is occasionally played, although Black need not worry about this version of the Open Sicilian, because Qf6! followed by ...Bc5 promises good play.}) 5. exd5 ({White is practically forced to make this exchange.} 5. e5 $2 {would be a positional mistake. Not only does the e5 -pawn block the b2 -bishop's diagonal – it can hardly be saved. Black can increase the pressure further with ... Nc6 , ... g7 - g5 , ... Bg7 etc. and White will soon run out of defensive moves.}) 5... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a typical problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop can be developed freely. White now most commonly plays d4 , which amounts to an exchange against the black c-pawn and subsequent play against the isolated pawn on d5 . Alternatively, White could go for piece activity.} 6. d4 {The main line. White wants to capture on c5 later and play against the isolated pawn on d5 .} Nf6 7. Bd3 ({White should only capture on c5 after the f8 -bishop has moved, otherwise Black will save a tempo.} 7. Be2 {is also played, but on e2 the bishop is more passive and blocks the e-file. Black can continue as against Bd3 and doesn't have any problems.}) 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 {White doesn't have to hurry with the exchange on c5 as Black has no good way of resolving the tension. 9.h3 denies the c8 -bishop its most active square on g4 .} Nc6 {Our strategy is simple: we make sensible developing moves (like ... Be6 , ... Re8 and ... Rc8 ) while waiting for White to exchange on c5 . This is better than exchanging on d4 ourselves, after which Nxd4 would open the way to the kingside for White's queen. White can try to maintain the tension and also make developing moves. However, the useful moves are limited – White will not be able to avoid the exchange on c5 for long.} 10. a3 ({Denies the knight the b4 -square. This is not absolutely necessary, but in practice it is the most common move. After} 10. Re1 {, Black can also continue development with} Be6 {, threatening ...c5-c4 .} ({There is no need to fear Ng5 because of} 10... Nxd4 {.}) {White should therefore play} 11. Nbd2 {, but after} Rc8 {it is not obvious how White can improve their position. The exchange on c5 will probably follow soon, with an equal position.}) 10... Be6 ({A novelty. Other moves like} 10... Re8 {or cxd4 also lead to an equal position. Black would now like to play ...c5-c4 and thus forestall the exchange on c5 .}) 11. Nbd2 ({Defends c4 once more. White could secure the bishop pair with} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Ng5 {, but in return Black gets a more stable center and pressure against the pawn f2 after} h6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 {.}) 11... Re8 ({Another useful waiting move. Also good is} 11... Nd7 {with the idea ...Bf6 .}) 12. dxc5 ({Finally White resolves the tension in the center. If White maintains the tension with} 12. Re1 {,} Qb6 {could follow with an attack on the d4 -pawn.} ({(} 12... Nd7 {is a good alternative.)}) {After} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 {the pawn f2 is attacked, so White has nothing better than} 14. Rf1 {, after which} Qd8 {leads us to the position we consider after the text moves.}) 12... Bxc5 {Despite the isolated pawn on d5 , White has no chance of gaining an advantage in this middlegame. The white position is too passive and the d2 -knight has no good prospects. The black minor pieces, on the other hand, are on good central squares.} 13. Re1 ({The most obvious continuation, with the aim of transferring the d2 -knight to the kingside. But it doesn't come to this. If White hunts for the bishop pair with} 13. Ng5 {, Black can allow the exchange with a clear conscience: after} h6 14. Nxe6 Rxe6 {the piece activity gives Black full compensation.}) ({An interesting alternative is Bd7 , which might lead to complications after} 13. Bxf6 gxf6 $5 {Nxf7!? .}) 13... Qb6 {White should move the rook back to f1 , with a repetition after 14...Qd8 .} ({Playing for a win with Re2 runs into the strong reply} 13... Nh5 {[%eval 32764,0] , after which Black gains the upper hand with the threats ...Nf4 and ...Ng3 . Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 13: Delayed Queenside Fianchetto  ➤ Variation 13: Delayed Queenside Fianchetto | 4.Bb2 / 6.d4}) *

