{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. b3 ({White fianchettoes the queen's bishop. There are some strong grandmasters who have specialized in this sideline and use it mainly in blitz and rapid chess, such as Durarbayli, Gelashvili, Chigaev and Morozevich. However, compared to the delayed fianchetto} 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {, Black has considerably more freedom here.}) 2... d6 {Against almost all Anti-Sicilians I recommend a setup with ... e7 -e6 , but here I would like to make an exception. If Black sets up with ... e7 -e6 and later ...Be7 , the white bishop will exert unpleasant pressure against the kingside from b2 .} ({With} 2... d6 {, we aim for a setup that neutralizes the b2 -bishop: ...Nf6 , ...g7-g6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . The black king is then very safe. d6 serves to prepare for ...Nf6 by defending against e4-e5 . A good alternative is the direct g6} 3. Bb2 Nf6 {. Nf6 allows} 4. e5 {.}) 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({To my taste, it is still too early for} 3... e5 {, with which Black could try to shut the b2 -bishop out of the game. Since the knight on g1 is not yet developed, White can fight for the long diagonal with} 4. f4 $1 {.}) 4. Nc3 ({The other main line besides} 4. Bb5+ {.}) ({The doubling of pawns after} 4. Bxf6 exf6 {is not to be feared, e.g.} 5. Nc3 g6 {. Black wants to continue with ...Bg7 , ...O-O and ...f7-f5 . The bishop pair gives Black slightly better chances.}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {is more accurate than the immediate g6 , against which White can react with} 5. Nd5 {. With our move we wait for White's next move and can then decide on the best setup.}) 5. Bb5 {The most common continuation. White wants to capture on c6 and damage our pawn structure. The light-squared bishop otherwise has few active prospects in this pawn structure.} Bd7 {We should keep the pawn structure intact. Otherwise the black pawns on the queenside would be rather immobile.} 6. f4 {White first wants to increase control of the center and only then develop the knight to f3 .} ({After} 6. Nf3 e5 $1 {the game develops similarly to the line starting with Nf3 e5 .}) 6... g6 {Now is the right time to develop the kingside.} 7. Bxc6 ({White wants to continue with Qe2 and long castling. In preparation, the exchange is necessary so that Black does not have ...Nd4 .} 7. Nf3 Bg7 {gives Black comfortable play. Specifically, ...Nxe4 is a threat. After White has defended the pawn, Black castles and has the more harmonious setup.}) 7... Bxc6 8. Qe2 Bg7 9. O-O-O {Black had been threatening ... Nxe4 , but now the b2 -bishop is protected. The aggressive white setup is very successful in practice and scores almost 80% according to my database. However, analysis shows that with accurate play it is actually Black who is in control.} O-O 10. Nf3 {White is threatening d2 - d4 . After that it would be difficult for Black to get counterplay on the queenside.} b5 {Black must not lose any time. ... b5 - b4 is threatening to win the e4 -pawn.} 11. e5 (11. Nxb5 $6 Bxe4 12. Bxf6 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {( Qxe7? fails to Bxd1 Qxd8 Rfxd8 Bxd8 Be2!-+ , winning a piece.)} Bxf6 {is good for Black. The black king is safer than its white counterpart.}) 11... Nh5 12. Qe3 ({White defends the f4 -pawn and is threatening to win the knight on h5 with g2-g4 . In Delgado Ramirez-Cuartas ,} 12. g3 b4 $6 13. Ne4 a5 14. d4 c4 $2 15. d5 c3 16. Bxc3 bxc3 17. dxc6 {followed with a winning position for White. Instead, Black could have gained an advantage with c4 , because now a move of the d-pawn will be met with ...b5-b4 and ...c4-c3 .}) 12... Qc8 {Black prevents g2 - g4 and threatens to win a pawn with ... Qg4 .} (12... Qd7 {follows the same idea and has been played in some games, but the queen is worse on d7 : With the queen on c8 , the pawn break ...f7-f6 is sometimes a good idea. If the queen were on d7 , White could respond with e5-e6 , gaining a tempo.  Black is slightly better. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 17: Queenside Fianchetto  ➤ Variation 17: Queenside Fianchetto | 4.Nc3 / 5.Bb5}) *

