{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. b3 ({White fianchettoes the queen's bishop. There are some strong grandmasters who have specialized in this sideline and use it mainly in blitz and rapid chess, such as Durarbayli, Gelashvili, Chigaev and Morozevich. However, compared to the delayed fianchetto} 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {, Black has considerably more freedom here.}) 2... d6 {Against almost all Anti-Sicilians I recommend a setup with ... e7 -e6 , but here I would like to make an exception. If Black sets up with ... e7 -e6 and later ...Be7 , the white bishop will exert unpleasant pressure against the kingside from b2 .} ({With} 2... d6 {, we aim for a setup that neutralizes the b2 -bishop: ...Nf6 , ...g7-g6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . The black king is then very safe. d6 serves to prepare for ...Nf6 by defending against e4-e5 . A good alternative is the direct g6} 3. Bb2 Nf6 {. Nf6 allows} 4. e5 {.}) 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({To my taste, it is still too early for} 3... e5 {, with which Black could try to shut the b2 -bishop out of the game. Since the knight on g1 is not yet developed, White can fight for the long diagonal with} 4. f4 $1 {.}) 4. Bb5+ ({The bishop check is favored by Georgian GMs Gelashvili and Paichadze, who are experts on the 2.b3 system. This move ensures that White can exchange the bishop, preventing it from being passively locked behind a pawn chain. Along with} 4. Nc3 {, Bb5+ is one of the main moves.  The doubling of pawns after Bxf6 exf6 is not to be feared, e.g. Nc3} g6 {. Black wants to continue with ...Bg7 , ...O-O and ...f7-f5 . The bishop pair gives Black slightly better chances.}) 4... Nbd7 ({More ambitious than} 4... Bd7 {. White will probably have to exchange the bishop for the knight later, giving Black the bishop pair. Nc6 allows White to damage our queenside pawn structure with} 5. Bc6 bxc6 {, which carries strategic risks for Black. Bd7 Bxd7+ Qxd7 is also playable. (Weaker is Nbxd7} 6. Qe2 {, after which White can attack on the kingside with f2-f4 and g2-g4 .) White now either plays d3 and thus maintains the closed character of the position, or plays against the black pawn structure with Bxf6 gxf6 Qh5 Spassky-Huebner .}) 5. Qe2 {White wants to continue with f2 - f4 . The queen supports a possible play in the center with e4 - e5 .} g6 {Our preferred setup in the 2.b3 variation. From g7 , our dark-squared bishop will challenge its white counterpart on b2 .} 6. f4 ({White is threatening e4-e5 , but Black is in time.  The exchange} 6. Bxf6 {is a double-edged decision. Black gets a strong pair of bishops in return for a weakened pawn structure. Bxf6 at this point is a novelty.} exf6 7. Qd3 $1 {The attack on the d6 -pawn complicates the development of the f8 -bishop. This position has been reached in some games by transposition.} a6 8. Bxd7+ Bxd7 {Black can now easily complete development with ...Bc6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . Then the pawn breaks ...f6-f5 and ...d6-d5 are on the agenda. Black already has the slightly better game.}) 6... Bg7 7. Nf3 ({After} 7. e5 $2 Nd5 {, Black has pressure against the pawns on f4 and e5 .}) 7... O-O 8. O-O ({White could also castle long. After} 8. Nc3 Nh5 $1 9. g3 a6 10. Bd3 e5 {a complicated position arises in which Black has the slightly better chances. The kingside is well defended, while on the queenside Black will play ...b7-b5 and prepare a break against the b3 -pawn. Nickel-Emelyanov}) 8... a6 9. Bxd7 Qxd7 {Black can be satisfied with the outcome of the opening. With ... b7 -b5 and ...Bb7 , development will be complete, resulting in a harmonious position. To fully capitalize on the bishop pair, it is in Black's interest to open up the position. The pawn break ... c5 -c4 is a good plan to achieve this. If White plays c2-c4 , Black can exchange on c4 and become active on the b-file. Papaioannou-Gelfand . Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 17: Queenside Fianchetto  ➤ Variation 17: Queenside Fianchetto | 4.Bb5+ / 5.Qe2} *

