{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Na3 e6 ({There is no reason to deviate from our usual setup. Many other moves also give Black good play. The most common is} 2... Nc6 {.}) 3. c3 {White prepares the occupation of the center with d2 - d4 and clears c2 for the knight.} Nc6 ({The knight controls the important central squares e5 and d4 . After} 3... d5 {White could go for the Alapin Sicilian with} 4. exd5 {, or try a version of the French Advance Variation with} e5 {.}) 4. Nf3 ({White is not yet ready for} 4. d4 $6 {, because after} cxd4 5. cxd4 Nf6 {the knight on a3 is missing in the defense of the center. E.g.} 6. e5 {(or f3} Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxa3 8. bxa3 Nxd4 {)} 9. Bb4 {Bd2 Bxa3 bxa3} Ne4 {and Black has the better pawn structure.}) 4... Nf6 ({This invites a transposition to the Alapin Sicilian with} 4... Nf6 {, where the early knight development to a3 is not critical.}) 5. e5 ({After the alternative} 5. d3 {, Black has many good continuations, e.g.} d5 6. e5 Nd7 7. d4 {. White plays a French with a minus tempo.} f6 8. exf6 Nxf6 {Lagarde-Kirk . I also like the untested Be7 , which does not yet commit Black to either the double or the single step of the d-pawn.}) 5... Nd5 ({The position is more often reached via the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5} 5... Nd5 {Nf3 Nc6 Na3 e6 . There, 5.Na3 is a rare sideline.}) 6. Nc4 {The knight attacks the weakened d6 -square and defends the e5 -pawn, but it is not very stable on c4 .} Qc7 {The queen attacks the e5 -pawn. ... b7 - b5 is a threat.} 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 b5 {Black takes the initiative.} 9. Ne3 Ncb4 {The c2 -square is not so easy to defend.} 10. Nxd5 exd5 ({Black accepts a weakening of the pawn structure but maintains the threat of a fork on c2 . Not} 10... Nc2+ $4 11. Kd2 {and White wins a piece.}) 11. Bd3 ({The alternative} 11. Kd2 {doesn't look very tempting either.} Be7) 11... Nxd3+ {The light-squared bishop is an important piece in this pawn structure. The remaining bishop on c1 , on the other hand, is less impressive because it is restricted by its pawns.} 12. Qxd3 Qc4 ({Black has the better chances. After} 12... Qc4 {[%eval 32762,0] (If White chooses Qe3 instead, b4!⩱ follows so that the queen can stay on the a6-f1 diagonal and prevent White from castling.) dxc4 Black has improved the pawn structure and has a strong pair of bishops. Bontempi-Jurcik Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 19: Zvjaginsev  ➤ Variation 19: Zvjaginsev | 3.c3 / 4.Nf3}) *

