{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and the most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire against the Anti-Sicilians with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {A flexible move. White could later transition to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or develop the bishop to g2 as in the Closed Sicilian.} e6 ({This is the simplest solution for our repertoire. We make sure that after d4 cxd4 Nxd4 we end up in an e6 -Sicilian. We also prepare ...d7-d5 . Alternatively, Black could try to exploit the white move order by attacking the center directly:} 2... Nf6 $5 3. Nbc3 d5 $1 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Nxd5 Qxd5 {.}) 3. g3 ({The game is now reminiscent of the Closed Sicilian, but some particularities tend to weigh in Black's favor. We examine the position after} 3. Nbc3 {via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 Nge2 , while d4 cxd4 Nxd4 transposes to the Open Sicilian.}) 3... d5 4. Bg2 ({In contrast to the Closed Sicilian, White does not have the possibility} 4. exd5 $6 {because after} Qxd5 $1 {the rook on h1 is attacked.}) 4... dxe4 ({White will lose time to win back the pawn. Meanwhile, Black can transfer the bishop to c6 , where it neutralizes the strong white bishop. After} 4... Nf6 {White could go for an isolated queen's pawn position with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {.}) 5. Bxe4 {This meets a surprising refutation.} Nf6 6. Bg2 Bd7 {The fight for the light squares is worth a pawn and an exchange. Black wants to trade light-squared bishops. This strong move has only been played once.} 7. Bxb7 {Accepting the sacrifice is very risky for White.} ({Stockfish recommends} 7. Ng1 $5 Bc6 8. Nf3 {. This illustrates a fundamental problem with White's setup: If the light-squared bishops are traded, White's king position is weakened. Combining g2-g3 with the development of the king's knight to e2 is therefore risky.} g5 $1 9. h3 h5 {Here, too, White does not succeed in avoiding the exchange of bishops in the long run.}) 7... Nc6 {The bishop on b7 won't find its way back now.} 8. Bxa8 {This loses.} Qxa8 {The threat is ... Ne5 or ... Nd4 .} 9. O-O Ne5 10. f4 {White must defend against the check on f3 .} Neg4 ({White is helpless against the attack because the pieces on the queenside cannot join the defense in time. Black wants to involve the rook in the attack with ...h7-h5-h4 . Other ideas are to threaten mate with ...Bd7-c6-h1 , or to bring the dark-squared bishop into the attack with ...c5-c4 followed by ...Bc5+ .} 10... Nf3+ 11. Rxf3 Qxf3 {is too modest.}) 11. h3 ({Another sample line:} 11. d4 h5 12. h4 {White has prevented ...h5-h4 , but now the g4 -knight cannot be driven away.} Bc6 {White has no defense against the threat of ...Bh1 followed by ...Qg2 mate.}) 11... h5 {Black wants to include the rook in the attack. The threat is ... h5 - h4 .} 12. hxg4 {This loses, but there was already no defense.} hxg4 13. Kf2 Qf3+ 14. Ke1 Rh1 {[%eval 32764,0] White will soon be mated. Chapter, further analysis and Model Games   ➤ Chapter 20: Unusual Knight move  ➤ Variation 20: Unusual Knight move | 5.Bxe4 / 7.Bxb7} *

