[Black "About the Alternative 2.c3 Nf"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B22"]
[PlyCount "12"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... Nf6 {The second important continuation for Black is also an attack on the e4 -pawn. White should now move it forward, after which Black can continue attacking it.} 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 e6 ({More popular is a setup with ...Nc6 and ...d7-d6 . But that's not an option for us, because White could have reached this position via the move order e4 c5 Nf3} 4... e6 {c3 Nf6 e5 Nd5 and thus forced us to commit to an early ...e7-e6 .}) 5. d4 ({Or first} 5. Bc4 {.}) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {The black setup is very solid and, according to theory, leads to equality. In practice, however, things are not that simple – I believe in White’s chances here! Since the knight has been driven away from f6 , Black's kingside is largely unprotected and White can prepare an attack there. White also has a variety of different setups that Black has to defend against very carefully. I therefore cannot recommend this pawn structure.} *

