1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. e5 ({This gives White space and aims for a pawn structure akin to the advance variations in the French and Caro-Kann. The move is quite rare, so I propose a pragmatic solution: transitioning to the lines we consider in the delayed Alapin-Sicilian after e4 c5} 3. Nf3 e6 {c3} 4. exd5 e5 {.}) 3... d4 ({This prevents White from building a solid pawn center with d2-d4 . The e5 -pawn could now become vulnerable. Also good is} 3... Bf5 4. d4 e6 {. This position is reminiscent of the Caro-Kann advance variation with 3...c5 ( e4 c6 d4 d5 e5} 5. dxc5 {), but with an extra tempo for Black.}) 4. Nf3 e6 ({We deal with this position in more detail via the move order e4 c5 Nf3} 4... e6 {c3 d5 e5} 5. cxd4 {in chapter 3 .}) *

