1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. Nf3 {There's nothing wrong with developing the knight first. But anyway, White needs the move d2 - d4 to be able to develop the queenside. A transition to the main line is therefore very likely.} Nf6 {We should develop the pieces as in the main line 4.d4  in order to be ready for a transposition after a subsequent d2 - d4 .} 5. Na3 {An attempt to further delay d2 - d4 .} e6 6. Bc4 (6. d4 {with a transition to the main line is the more likely continuation.}) 6... Qd8 7. O-O Be7 8. d4 {There's no point in waiting any longer. White has to develop the bishop c1 at some point.} O-O 9. Nc2 ({Or} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 {with equality.}) 9... Qc7 {The queen clears the way for the rooks and indirectly attacks the bishop c4 , because White now always has to reckon with ... cxd4 .} 10. Qe2 a6 ({Black prepares ...b7-b5 . If White prevents this with a4 ,} 10... b6 {follows. In both cases the bishop is developed to b7 . It is best for the knight to go to d7 so as not to block the bishop's diagonal. Both sides reach a fully developed position with no weaknesses. The position is equal.}) *

