1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Na3 ({As far as I can see, this move order has no advantages for White compared to} 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {, but gives Black additional options.}) 5... a6 {As in the main line we prevent the knight from jumping to b5 .} 6. Nf3 (6. Nc4 Nbd7 ({(} 6... cxd4 $5 {=)}) 7. Nf3 e6 {is also a transposition: Nf3 e6} 8. Na3 {a6 Nc4 Nbd7 .}) 6... e6 ({See the move order Nf3} 6... e6 {Na3 a6 in chapter 2 . Black could exploit the opponent's move order with cxd4 . After Qxd4 Qxd4 Nxd4 e5 Ndc2 Nc6= Black has comfortable equality.}) *

