1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. dxc5 {The exchange on c5 is well known in those lines of the Alapin in which Black has developed the bishop to g4 . White combines play on the queenside with attacks on the bishop. Here, however, capturing is rather unusual and does not pose any problems for Black.} Qxc5 6. Nf3 g6 ({Compared to} 6... e6 {, this setup has the advantage that the c8 -bishop is not blocked and the d6 -square not weakened.}) 7. Be3 Qa5 8. Na3 {The typical square for the knight, from where it reaches the two active posts b5 and c4 .} Bg7 9. Nb5 ({The most common move. White wants to gain access to the c7 -square with b2-b4 . As we will see, this is too ambitious. White doesn't achieve anything with} 9. Nc4 {either, because Black has avoided weakening the b6 -square with ...a7-a6 . After} Qc7 {Black has a comfortable game.}) 9... O-O 10. b4 {The consistent continuation after 9.Nb5 . But now the c3 -pawn and thus the entire queenside are weakened.} (10. Bc4 Bd7 {is also a little better for Black, because the knight's trip to b5 has brought nothing. The knight will soon be driven away with b5 .}) 10... Qd8 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Nc7 ({In the game Vallejo Pons-Vera Gonzalez, 2005, White realized their mistake, played} 12. Rc1 Nd5 13. Bd4 {and offered a draw, which was accepted. But Black should have continued playing with} Nc6 {. The white queenside is very weak and the kingside not yet developed.}) ({Even after} 12. Bxa7 Bd7 13. Bb6 Rc8 {, Black deserves preference. The pawn on c3 will soon fall, after which the pawns on b4 and a2 will also be weak.}) 12... Ne8 {The punchline of Black’s play. The c3 -pawn is attacked, so White doesn’t win material.} 13. Nb5 {There's nothing better.} Nc6 {Black has a lead in development and strong pressure against the weakened white queenside. Specifically, ...Nxb4 is a threat.} *

