1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. dxc5 {The exchange on c5 is well known in those lines of the Alapin in which Black has developed the bishop to g4 . White combines play on the queenside with attacks on the bishop. Here, however, capturing is rather unusual and does not pose any problems for Black.} Qxc5 6. Be3 Qc7 7. Na3 {White wants to continue chasing the black queen with Nb5 .} a6 {Prevents Nb5 .} 8. Nc4 {The logical continuation, since the knight can no longer go to b5 . Nb6 is a threat.} Nbd7 9. a4 {This is necessary because otherwise Black will play ... b7 - b5 and drive the knight away from its strong position.} b6 {Since the knight has to stay on d7 , the bishop is best developed to the long diagonal.} 10. a5 {White tries to use the b6 -square. After other moves, Black completes development with ... Bb7 , ... e7 - e6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O and has no problems either.} b5 11. Nb6 Rb8 {White's play on the queenside has led to nothing. After moving the e-pawn, Black will develop the f8 -bishop, castle, and has at least equal play.} *

