{This reveals a downside of the queen’s position on e2 : White cannot respond with Be2 . This means that White has to allow either the exchange of queens (after Ne5 ) or the exchange on f3 . In both cases, Black has an easy game, because White does not have the active piece play that is typical of positions with the isolated queen pawn.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Nf3 {The most natural and – by far – most common developing move.} e6 {This setup is one of the most solid systems against the Alapin-Sicilian. Black focuses on quick kingside development, ensuring king safety. Additionally, two of White's typical ideas are neutralized: on the one hand, gaining space in the center with c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In this chapter we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Be3 {With this, White wants to clarify the situation in the center in order to be able to develop the knight to c3 . There is now a threat of 7.dxc5 , winning a pawn, so it is best for Black to release the tension.} cxd4 7. cxd4 {White can't pose any problems with the other recapturing options. Black then gets a good position with natural developing moves. Now White wants to drive away the black queen with Nc3 and then prepare for play on the kingside with Bd3 .} Bb4+ {With this very direct approach, the white plan is thwarted.} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bd3 ({Black would react the same way against} 9. Be2 {. On d3 the bishop is more active and gives White chances to attack on the kingside.}) 9... b6 {The active bishop on d3 should be exchanged.} 10. Qe2 {The idea of the queen move is to prevent Black from exchanging bishops with ... Ba6 .} Bb7 ({In fact, 10.Qe2 misses its goal: Black could still trade bishops with} 10... Ba6 $5 {! After} 11. Bxa6 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qa5 {, the double attack against the c3 -pawn and the a6 -bishop allows Black to regain the piece.}) {The position is then similar to the main move O-O and is equal.} 11. O-O Qh5 *

