1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Nf3 {The most natural and – by far – most common developing move.} e6 {This setup is one of the most solid systems against the Alapin-Sicilian. Black focuses on quick kingside development, ensuring king safety. Additionally, two of White's typical ideas are neutralized: on the one hand, gaining space in the center with c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In this chapter we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. a3 ({As we have seen, after} 6. Be3 {Black gets good play with} cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {.}) ({With} 6. a3 {, White wants to remove the check on b4 and only then play Be3 . This is a rare sideline.}) 6... Be7 ({Black often plays} 6... Nc6 {instead, which is also good. I prefer to maintain flexibility in terms of knight development.}) 7. Be3 ({White wants to win a pawn with dxc5 . Compared to} 7. Be3 {, we have a little more freedom here because White has lost time with a3 .}) 7... O-O ({This will thwart the enemy's plans. White can momentarily win a pawn, but cannot hold on to it in the long run.} 7... cxd4 {is of course also playable, but after} 8. cxd4 {c3 is accessible to the knight and White has the freer game.}) 8. c4 {A typical move that vacates the c3 -square for the knight. But here White has lost too much time and is coming under pressure.} Qh5 {This is the best square for the queen, as it doesn't get in the way of the other pieces and is close to the white kingside. Black is now threatening to attack the d4 -pawn with ... Rd8 and ... Nc6 .} 9. Be2 ({After} 9. dxc5 $2 Ng4 $1 {∓, White has to allow the positionally disadvantageous exchange on e3 .}) 9... cxd4 (9... Rd8 $6 {allows} 10. Ng5 Qg6 11. Bd3 Qh5 12. Be2 {with a draw by repetition.}) 10. Nxd4 (10. Ng5 $2 {doesn’t work now for various reasons. The strongest is} Qg6 11. Bd3 {and now Black doesn't have to repeat moves, but can force a favorable sequence with the sham sacrifice} ({(or} 11. Qxd4 $2 Rd8 12. Qc3 Nc6 {, after which the white pieces are misplaced.)}) 11... Ne4 $1 12. Bxe4 f5 {. The best option for White is} 13. Qxd4 Bxg5 14. Bf3 Nc6 15. Bxc6 Bf6 $1 16. Qd2 bxc6 17. O-O {, but the strong pair of bishops gives Black a clear advantage.}) 10... Qg6 11. O-O ({In the game Stevanic-Lashkin, 2018, the weakening} 11. h4 $6 {followed. After} h5 12. Bg5 e5 13. Nb5 Rd8 14. Nd2 Nc6 {Black had a big advantage. Stevanic, D (2237)-Lashkin, J (2367), Konya 2018.}) 11... e5 {Black thus frees the c8 -bishop and develops an initiative.} 12. Nf3 Ng4 ({Easier than the equally strong} 12... Rd8 13. Qc1 Nc6 {. With the text move Black secures the bishop pair and gives White a weak pawn on e3 .}) ({But not} 12... Bh3 $2 {on account of} 13. Nh4 {.}) 13. Nc3 ({Best. The knight targets the weakened d5 -square.} 13. Bc1 $2 {White can't afford this – Black's lead in development after} Rd8 14. Qe1 Nc6 {is too big.}) 13... Nxe3 14. fxe3 Nc6 {The bishop pair and the opponent’s weak pawn on e3 give Black slightly better chances.} *

