{After this strong break, White is no longer able to hold the position together. Black has a big advantage.  After cxb6 (Relatively best is Be2 , but after Nxe3 fxe3 Bxc5 Black has won back the pawn, commands a strong pair of bishops and will play against the opponent's weak pawns on e3 and a3 .) Bxa3 Rc2 Bb4 the white king cannot withstand the onslaught of the black pieces. c6 is met with the same reaction.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Nf3 {The most natural and – by far – most common developing move.} e6 {This setup is one of the most solid systems against the Alapin-Sicilian. Black focuses on quick kingside development, ensuring king safety. Additionally, two of White's typical ideas are neutralized: on the one hand, gaining space in the center with c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In this chapter we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. a3 ({As we have seen, after} 6. Be3 {Black gets good play with} cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {.}) ({With} 6. a3 {, White wants to remove the check on b4 and only then play Be3 . This is a rare sideline.}) 6... Be7 ({Black often plays} 6... Nc6 {instead, which is also good. I prefer to maintain flexibility in terms of knight development.}) 7. Be3 ({White wants to win a pawn with dxc5 . Compared to} 7. Be3 {, we have a little more freedom here because White has lost time with a3 .}) 7... O-O ({This will thwart the enemy's plans. White can momentarily win a pawn, but cannot hold on to it in the long run.} 7... cxd4 {is of course also playable, but after} 8. cxd4 {c3 is accessible to the knight and White has the freer game.}) 8. dxc5 ({The consistent continuation. After} 8. Bd3 {, the move 6.a3 turns out to be a loss of time. We can continue with} Rd8 {as in the line starting with 6.Bd3 and thus prevent dxc5 .} 9. O-O b6 {Black already has the better game.}) 8... Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 a5 ({Black wants to play ...a5-a4 and cut off the c5 -pawn from a possible defense by the b-pawn. After} 9... Ng4 $6 10. b4 a5 11. Bb5 $1 {, Black did not have sufficient compensation for the pawn in Ekstroem-Papp, 2006.}) 10. b4 {White cannot afford this natural defensive move.} axb4 11. cxb4 Nc6 {Threatening ... Nxb4 .} 12. b5 ({This advance is forced, but after that the c5 -pawn is no longer reliably defended.} 12. Bd2 {is even worse, e.g.} Ne4 13. Be1 Nxb4 $1 14. Bxb4 Nxf2+ 15. Ke1 Nxh1 {.}) 12... Na5 {Threatening ... Nb3 .} 13. Nbd2 Nd5 ({An improvement over} 13... Ng4 {which was played in two games that reached this position. In addition to e3 , the knight also has the c3 -square in view. Specifically, ...Nxe3 is a threat followed by ...Bxc5 .}) 14. Rc1 ({Defending the c5 -pawn.} 14. Bd4 {doesn't help White in view of f6 and ...e6-e5 .}) 14... Rd8 {Black builds up pressure along the d-file. There is a threat of ... Nxe3 + followed by Nb3 .} 15. Ke1 b6 *

