th c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In this chapter we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Be2 {A popular and natural developing move that White uses to prepare for short castling. However, the e2 -square is somewhat passive for the bishop. It is often better on d3 , where it can participate in an attack against the black king. Let's look at two alternatives for comparison:} Be7 (6... Nc6 7. O-O Be7 {. Here it would have been possible to exchange on d4 instead and transition to our main line. White now has a number of options that a prior capture on d4 would have prevented:  ➤ The direct} 8. dxc5 $5 {is not very popular, but is an engine favorite. If Black recaptures on c5 , White gains space on the queenside with b2-b4 .  ➤ Na3 With this typical move, White can avoid playing with an isolated queen's pawn. After cxd4 there follows Nb5} Qd8 {Nbxd4 .  ➤} 9. Be3 {threatening to win a pawn with dxc5 . cxd4 cxd4 or} Nd4 {.  ➤} 10. c4 {Qd8 dxc5 . White has the more active pieces and good chances of gaining a small edge.}) 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 ({We reach a similar position, but with the white bishop on d3 , after} 8. Bd3 {Be7 O-O O-O} c4 {. There I suggest Qh5 , which is not recommended here because of the opposition with the white bishop.}) 8... Qd8 9. Nc3 {White enjoys a space advantage and chances of pressure on the queenside.} *

