1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Nf3 {The most natural and – by far – most common developing move.} e6 {This setup is one of the most solid systems against the Alapin-Sicilian. Black focuses on quick kingside development, ensuring king safety. Additionally, two of White's typical ideas are neutralized: on the one hand, gaining space in the center with c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In this chapter we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Be2 {A popular and natural developing move that White uses to prepare for short castling. However, the e2 -square is somewhat passive for the bishop. It is often better on d3 , where it can participate in an attack against the black king.} cxd4 {It is usually a good idea to wait before making this exchange, because afterwards White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo. In this case, however, it seems to me that the advantages outweigh the drawbacks, as the direct capture on d4 deprives White of some options.} 7. cxd4 {A typical pawn structure in the Alapin Sicilian. White's d-pawn and the square in front of it are weak. On the other hand, White has some space advantage and the more active pieces.} Nc6 {Sooner or later Ne5 should be prevented.} 8. Nc3 (8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 Qd6 {is a transposition.}) 8... Qd6 ({This is more active than} 8... Qd8 {, where the queen would later get in the way of the rooks.}) 9. O-O Be7 {Black follows a simple development pattern. After short castling, the light-squared bishop should be fianchettoed with ... b6 and ... Bb7 .} 10. Nb5 {The main line. Through direct play, White disrupts Black's development.} Qd8 11. Ne5 O-O 12. Bf3 Nd5 {White hasn't achieved anything on the queenside. The exchange on c6 would weaken the black pawn structure, but at the same time open the b-file for the black rook and allow the bishop to develop to a6 . The position is equal.} *

