th c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In this chapter we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Be2 {A popular and natural developing move that White uses to prepare for short castling. However, the e2 -square is somewhat passive for the bishop. It is often better on d3 , where it can participate in an attack against the black king.} cxd4 {It is usually a good idea to wait before making this exchange, because afterwards White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo. In this case, however, it seems to me that the advantages outweigh the drawbacks, as the direct capture on d4 deprives White of some options.} 7. cxd4 {A typical pawn structure in the Alapin Sicilian. White's d-pawn and the square in front of it are weak. On the other hand, White has some space advantage and the more active pieces.} Nc6 {Sooner or later Ne5 should be prevented.} 8. Nc3 (8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 Qd6 {is a transposition.}) 8... Qd6 ({This