1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin Sicilian is one of the most popular alternatives to the Open Sicilian for White. And it’s easy to see why: with the pawn move, White renews the threat of establishing a strong pawn center with d2 - d4 , the very thing we aimed to prevent with our first move, ... c7 - c5 . However, c2 - c3 also has drawbacks. We will subsequently take advantage of the fact that the white knight can no longer be developed to c3 .} ({In addition to 2.c3 , White has an alternative way to reach the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5} 2. Nf3 e6 {. As a result, White has significantly reduced the number of possible defensive setups, since Black has already played ...e7-e6 . When choosing a defense, we should definitely take this change of move order into account and choose a setup containing ...e7-e6 from the outset.}) 2... d5 {We can't conveniently prevent White from playing d2 - d4 . However, by attacking the e4 -pawn we prevent White from occupying the center with both pawns. 2...d5 is one of the two main moves, alongside 2...Nf6 .} 3. exd5 Qxd5 ({The position is reminiscent of the Scandinavian defense ( e4 d5 exd5} 3... Qxd5 {) . However, the two additional moves c2-c3 and ...c7-c5 are clearly in Black's favor: the queen cannot be driven away with Nc3 and after d2-d4 , White is often left with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. d4 {White implements the plan started with 2.c3 and occupies the center, ready to play with an isolated queen's pawn. However, we shouldn't rush to capture on d4 : when the c-pawns are gone, White can develop the knight to c3 with tempo.} Nf6 {This leaves Black with all options open, because it is clear that the knight belongs to f6 .} 5. Nf3 {The most natural and – by far – most common developing move.} e6 {This setup is one of the most solid systems against the Alapin-Sicilian. Black focuses on quick kingside development, ensuring king safety. Additionally, two of White's typical ideas are neutralized: on the one hand, gaining space in the center with c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In this chapter we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Bd3 ({The bishop is aimed at the black kingside. We should therefore react differently than to} 6. Be2 {, because after} cxd4 7. cxd4 {the active bishop on d3 gives White a chance of a later attack against our king. But the more active bishop position also has downsides, namely:  ➤ Black can pin the d-pawn with a later ...Rd8   ➤ against c3-c4 the black queen can go to h5 , after which it does not get in the way of the rooks and the pieces on the queenside.}) 6... Be7 ({Castling has the highest priority here so that the rook can move to d8 . Therefore developing the bishop is stronger than} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. O-O O-O {White is now faced with the question of how to develop the queenside. The knight is best placed on c3 , but of course this square is currently occupied.} 8. Be3 {White is threatening 9.dxc5 .} Rd8 {In similar positions, Black usually reacts to Be3 with ... cxd4 . This is not necessary here, which means that the white knight still cannot be developed to c3 .} 9. Qe2 Nc6 10. Rd1 {White's moves are of course not forced, but are the most common in practice. Now dxc5 is a threat again.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 {Exchanging the light-squared bishop would deprive White of all chances for an attack.} 12. Nc3 Qh5 13. Bc4 b6 {Black will finish development with ... Bb7 and attack the f3 -knight. Black's position is a bit more pleasant because the white d-pawn is weak in the long term.} *

