th c3 - c4 followed by d4 - d5 , and on the other, the exchange on c5 (since Black can now recapture with the bishop). The downside of the pawn move is that the bishop on c8 remains passive for the time being.} ({White has now reached an important crossroads and has to decide on a setup for their minor pieces. The solid but somewhat passive Be2 , the more active bishop development Bd3 and the dynamic Na3 come into question. Also popular is Be3 , which can resolve tension in the center and vacate c3 for the knight. In this chapter we will deal with the bishop moves, while the modern Na3 is the subject of the following chapter .} 5... Bg4 {This is the most important alternative. Black wants to develop the bishop first and only then take care of developing the kingside with ...e7-e6 . However, this line is not an option for our repertoire; White could choose the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {Nf3} e6 {c3 and thus force us to an early ...e7-e6 . dxc5!? A drawback of Black's last move. If Black now recaptures on c5 , White gains time by attacking the queen. On the other hand, if Black trades queens on d1 , White has a good chance of keeping the extra pawn on c5 .}) 6. Bd3 ({The bishop is aimed at the black kingside. We should therefore react differently than to} 6. Be2 {, because after} cxd4 7. cxd4 {the active bishop on d3 gives White a chance of a later attack against our king. But the more active bishop position also has downsides, namely:  ➤ Black can pin the d-pawn with a later ...Rd8   ➤ against c3-c4 the black queen can go to h5 , after which it does not get in the way of the rooks and the pieces on the queenside.}) 6... Be7 ({Castling has the highest priority here so that the rook can move to d8 . Therefore developing the bishop is stronger than} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. O-O O-O {White is now faced with the question of how to develop the queenside. The knight is best placed on c3 , but of course this square is currently occupied.} 8. c4 {This vacates the c3 -square for the knight.} Qh5 ({Here the queen doesn't get in the way of our own pieces. Black wants to put pressure on the d4 -pawn and on the d-file more generally with ...Nc6 and ...Rd8 . White can then force a draw by attacking the queen. If that result doesn't suit you, I recommend the alternative} 8... Qd7 {.}) 9. Be2 Rd8 {Black increases the pressure on the d4 -pawn. It seems as if the queen on h5 is in danger, but that is not the case. Attacks on the queen are only enough to achieve a draw by repetition.} 10. Be3 Nc6 ({The pressure on d4 is increasing, so White has nothing better now than repeating moves. Black could also continue the game with} 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qh4 {. The position is equal.}) 11. Ng5 ({Or} 11. Ne5 Qh4 12. Nf3 Qh5 {, also with a repetition.}) 11... Qg6 12. Bd3 Qh5 13. Be2 Qg6 {With a draw.} *

