[ECO "B22"]
[PlyCount "20"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Bc4 {White only seems to win a tempo. The bishop is in the way of the knight and can be attacked later.} Qd8 {The safest square for the queen.} 8. O-O cxd4 (8... b5 {is also possible, but I am not in favor of it because it forces Black to always keep an eye on the pawn break a2-a4 .}) 9. Nxd4 Qc7 ({Threatening ...Bxa3 , after which the bishop on c4 would no longer be protected.} 9... Bxa3 {now leads to a complicated position after} 10. Qa4+ $1 b5 11. Bxb5+ axb5 12. Qxa8 Bd6 13. Nxb5 {, which is probably slightly better for White. The queenside pawns have a lot of potential.}) 10. Bb3 Bd6 {By attacking the h2 -pawn, Black gains a tempo for development. Next, ... b7 - b5 or ... O-O could follow. Black has no worries.} *

