1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Bg5 {Developing the bishop prepares retreating the knight to e3 , which would now no longer block the bishop there.} cxd4 9. Qxd4 ({After} 9. Bxf6 {Black could take back with the pawn, because the strong pair of bishops is more than sufficient compensation for the slight weakening of the pawn structure. Equally possible is} Nxf6 {, because} 10. Nb6 {can be answered with} Qe4+ 11. Be2 Rb8 {. In both cases the black position is somewhat more comfortable.}) 9... Bc5 {Black agrees to exchange queens, but on their own terms.} 10. Qxd5 Nxd5 {White has failed to create problems. Black will complete development without much interference: the light-squared bishop goes to b7 (after ... b7 - b5 or ... b7 - b6 ) and the king can castle short or (after ... f7 - f6 ) go to f7 . The position is equal.} *

