1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Ne3 {It is more logical to wait with this move until Black has played ... b7 - b5 . The knight is not particularly well placed on e3 as it doesn't have any active prospects and prevents the development of the c1 -bishop.} Qc6 ({There is also nothing to be said against} 8... Qd6 {. However, since I recommend retreating to c6 in the main line, I've decided to go for it here as well.}) 9. Be2 Be7 ({At this point,} 9... b5 {also allows the transition to our main line , which we consider via the move order Be2 b5 Ne3 Qc6 . (However, the text move seems even simpler to me, as White cannot develop any pressure against the black queenside now.)}) 10. O-O O-O 11. a4 ({In some games} 11. Nc4 {was played, which is tantamount to admitting that 8.Ne3 was not effective. Black gets comfortable play, e.g. with} b5 12. Nce5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qb6 {with equality. In the game Paehtz-Muzychuk , the players agreed to a draw after a few more moves.}) 11... b6 ({The standard reaction against a2-a4 . If White now plays a4-a5 , we can always react with ...b6-b5 .} 11... Rd8 {is also good here.}) 12. Ne5 Qc7 (12... Nxe5 $2 {leads to a loss of material after} 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Bf3 {.}) 13. N3c4 ({White clears the way for their dark-squared bishop. Harmless is also} 13. Bf3 Bb7 {, e.g.} 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. Bf4 $6 {(better was 16.Bxb7 with equality)} Qxf4 17. Bxb7 {In the game Paragua-Blomqvist . Black could now have won the d-pawn with} Rad8 {and achieved a slightly better position.}) 13... Nd5 {Most accurate, as this prevents 14.Bf4 . It is also useful to protect the b6 -pawn one more time so that the queen is not tied to its defense. Black has equalized.} *

