1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. a4 {The second most common move. White prevents ... b7 - b5 and wants to gain space with a4 - a5 .} cxd4 {A good moment for the exchange. If White recaptures with the knight, the black queen's attack on the g2 -pawn makes the development of the light-squared bishop more difficult.} ({The alternative} 8... b6 {is also playable, with Black developing the queenside first. However, the recently played game Nepomniachtchi-Vachier Lagrave, shows that the position is not without dangers for Black. I have dealt with this instructive game in more detail here .}) 9. Nxd4 {This is not a critical try.} Bc5 ({Not} 9... b6 $6 10. Be2 $1 {followed by Bf3 .}) 10. Ne3 {The knight leaves its good position, but at least the bishop can now be developed.} Qd6 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Qc7 {Black wants to finish development with ... Rd8 , ... Nf8 and ... Bd7 . The position is equal.} ({The direct} 12... Rd8 {allows} 13. Nb3 {, after which Black has to part with the bishop pair..}) *

