irst. However, the recently played game Nepomniachtchi-Vachier Lagrave, shows that the position is not without dangers for Black. I have dealt with this instructive game in more detail here .}) 9. Nxd4 {This is not a critical try.} Bc5 ({Not} 9... b6 $6 10. Be2 $1 {followed by Bf3 .}) 10. Be3 O-O 11. a5 {White plays for a queenside squeeze. The next move frees Black from the stranglehold.} b5 (11... Ne5 {is also good.}) 12. axb6 Nxb6 {White has not achieved much with their play on the queenside.} 13. Nxb6 Bxb6 14. Be2 {Finally White manages to develop the bishop. The pawn on g2 is out of bounds because of 15.Bf3 .} Bb7 15. Bf3 Qd7 ({An obvious improvement over the blitz game Korobov-Lammens , in which Black pinned their own knight with} 15... Ne4 {. Black has comfortable equality. The knight can go to d5 and with ...Rab8 the white b-pawn can be targeted.}) *

