irst. However, the recently played game Nepomniachtchi-Vachier Lagrave, shows that the position is not without dangers for Black. I have dealt with this instructive game in more detail here .}) 9. Qxd4 Bc5 {Black agrees to exchange queens, but on their own terms.} 10. Qh4 Qe4+ {The white position is more active, so the exchange of queens is favorable for Black.} 11. Qxe4 Nxe4 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. fxe3 {White accepts a weak pawn in order to keep the knight in its strong position on c4 .} ({Or} 13. Nxe3 b6 {Kos-Lazar followed by ...Bb7 and ...Ke7 .}) 13... Ke7 14. Bd3 Nd6 {Grawe-Fogaras , Black has equalized. The bishop c8 can be developed either by ... b7 - b6 via b7 or (after a move of the knight) via d7 .} *

