1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. a4 {The second most common move. White prevents ... b7 - b5 and wants to gain space with a4 - a5 .} cxd4 {A good moment for the exchange. If White recaptures with the knight, the black queen's attack on the g2 -pawn makes the development of the light-squared bishop more difficult.} ({The alternative} 8... b6 {is also playable, with Black developing the queenside first. However, the recently played game Nepomniachtchi-Vachier Lagrave, shows that the position is not without dangers for Black. I have dealt with this instructive game in more detail here .}) 9. Qxd4 Bc5 {Black agrees to exchange queens, but on their own terms.} 10. Qxd5 exd5 ({How to recapture on d5 is a matter of taste. With} 10... Nxd5 {the pawn structure could be kept intact. Black is then very solid and should equalize. exd5 gives the black pieces more activity, but accepts a weak pawn.}) 11. Ne3 {Otherwise Black would soon bring the rook to e8 and disrupt White's development. However, the knight is in the way of the c1 -bishop.} O-O 12. Bd3 ({In a blitz game Nakamura opted for the more modest bishop development to e2 .} 12. Be2 {After} Re8 13. O-O {Nakamura-Artemiev} Bxe3 {would now have been easiest.} 14. Bxe3 Ng4 15. Rfe1 Nxe3 16. Bd1 Nf6 17. Rxe3 Rxe3 18. fxe3 {Although White has avoided losing a pawn, they now also have a weakness on e3 and no chance of gaining an advantage.}) 12... Re8 {The order of Black's moves is interchangeable here. The rook move is threatening ... Ng4 .} 13. O-O Ba7 ({Black prepares to activate the knight via c5 . Not} 13... Ne5 $6 14. Nxe5 Rxe5 15. Nc2 $1 {White has prevented ...d5-d4 and retains a small advantage due to the weakness of the black d-pawn.}) 14. Rd1 Nc5 {Primarily threatening ... Nb3 , but even after capturing on d3 Black wouldn't have any worries due to the pair of bishops.} 15. Bc2 Nce4 ({Attacks the pawn f2 . The knight e3 must therefore not move and Black is already threatening the tactic} 15... Z0 {Nxf2 Kxf2} 16. Ng4 {.}) 16. Nd4 Bd7 ({Black has finished development and has equalized. The piece activity is sufficient compensation for the isolated queen's pawn. It is not so easy for White to develop the queenside. After Nf1 the regrouping} 16... Nd6 {is strong. The knight goes to c4 and ties a white piece to the defense of the b-pawn. If White plays b2-b3 , the c-pawn will become weak.}) *

