1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Be2 {White develops the kingside. At the same time, this prepares an attack on the black queen: White would like to play O-O and Nfe5 , after which Bf3 would be a threat. We should therefore react energetically.} b5 {It is best to force the white knight to make a decision directly and continue developing the queenside.} ({After} 8... Be7 $6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nfe5 {White is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Nfd2 {White postpones the decision on the knight c4 and is threatening to win the rook on a8 with Bf3 . In practice, this has only been rarely played, but the move is likely to be seen more often in the future: it is one of the engine's top suggestions and is recommended by Kasimdzhanov and Ganguly in Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation .   The move poses practical problems because Black should react precisely and the correct moves are not obvious. In the main line I follow the analysis of the two grandmasters who have already shown the right way for Black.} (9. Ng5 {, also with the idea Bf3 , doesn't work:} h6 $1 10. Bf3 Qxc4 11. Bxa8 hxg5 {.}) 9... Ra7 {The right square for the rook. From here it can later be activated via the 7th rank, while it wouldn't have any prospects on b8 .} ({In two older games, Black opted for the natural-looking} 9... Rb8 $6 {. After} 10. Bf3 Qf5 11. Na5 $1 {White exerts strong pressure on the queenside. The rook on b8 is passive and it is difficult to develop the c8 -bishop.}) 10. Bf3 ({Drives the queen towards the kingside in the hope of pressure on the queenside. Harmless is} 10. Ne3 {because the black queen can now help defend the queenside, e.g.} Qa8 {or Qd6 .}) 10... Qf5 11. Na5 Rc7 {The difference to the analogous line we looked at after 9... Rb8 ?! . The black rook is much better here and can soon become active on the c-file. The direct exchange on d4 is also good.} 12. O-O cxd4 13. cxd4 Bd6 {Black will castle next and has no worries. There are two plausible plans for the bishop on c8 : ... Nb6 followed by ... Bd7 , or ... e6 - e5 , after which the bishop can be developed on the c8-h3 diagonal.} *

