1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Be2 {White develops the kingside. At the same time, this prepares an attack on the black queen: White would like to play O-O and Nfe5 , after which Bf3 would be a threat. We should therefore react energetically.} b5 {It is best to force the white knight to make a decision directly and continue developing the queenside.} ({After} 8... Be7 $6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nfe5 {White is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Nfd2 {White postpones the decision on the knight c4 and is threatening to win the rook on a8 with Bf3 . In practice, this has only been rarely played, but the move is likely to be seen more often in the future: it is one of the engine's top suggestions and is recommended by Kasimdzhanov and Ganguly in Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation .   The move poses practical problems because Black should react precisely and the correct moves are not obvious. In the main line I follow the analysis of the two grandmasters who have already shown the right way for Black.} (9. Ng5 {, also with the idea Bf3 , doesn't work:} h6 $1 10. Bf3 Qxc4 11. Bxa8 hxg5 {.}) 9... Ra7 {The right square for the rook. From here it can later be activated via the 7th rank, while it wouldn't have any prospects on b8 .} ({In two older games, Black opted for the natural-looking} 9... Rb8 $6 {. After} 10. Bf3 Qf5 11. Na5 $1 {White exerts strong pressure on the queenside. The rook on b8 is passive and it is difficult to develop the c8 -bishop.}) 10. Bf3 ({Drives the queen towards the kingside in the hope of pressure on the queenside. Harmless is} 10. Ne3 {because the black queen can now help defend the queenside, e.g.} Qa8 {or Qd6 .}) 10... Qf5 11. g4 {Kasimdzhanov and Ganguly mention this aggressive possibility. Of course, this is very risky, as White weakens their own king position.} Qd3 ({Into the lion's den! White won't manage to trap the queen and the d4 -pawn is now attacked twice. Alternatively,} 11... Qg6 {and Qf4 are also playable.}) 12. Ne5 (12. Be2 Qh3 {is good for Black.}) 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 {Now the pawn e5 is attacked, so White doesn't have a choice.} 14. Be4 Qh3 15. a4 ({White turns their attention to the queenside again, as the black queen is far away and cannot help with the defense. After} 15. Qf3 {Black can exchange queens, which leads to an equal position, or enter a sharp, unclear fight with} Qh4 $5 {.}) ({The pawn sacrifice} 15. Nf3 $5 Qxg4 16. Qe2 {is also possible. Black now best plays either} Bb7 {or h6 (to prevent a subsequent Rg1-Rg5 ), in each case with an unclear position.}) 15... Nxe5 16. axb5 Nd3+ {This brings the queen back to the action.} 17. Bxd3 Qxd3 18. Qe2 Qd5 {After the queen exchange White would have managed to get b5 - b6 and Nc4 in.} 19. O-O Qb7 {This move is less about preventing the capture on a6 and more about countering the positional threat of 20.Nc4 (after which the pawn b5 could now be captured). The position remains very sharp and unbalanced. Black's position is healthier from a positional standpoint, so it is now up to White to justify their risky play.} *

