ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Nfd2 {White postpones the decision on the knight c4 and is threatening to win the rook on a8 with Bf3 . In practice, this has only been rarely played, but the move is likely to be seen more often in the future: it is one of the engine's top suggestions and is recommended by Kasimdzhanov and Ganguly in Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation .   The move poses practical problems because Black should react precisely and the correct moves are not obvious. In the main line I follow the analysis of the two grandmasters who have already shown the right way for Black.} (9. Ng5 {, also with the idea Bf3 , doesn't work:} h6 $1 10. Bf3 Qxc4 11. Bxa8 hxg5 {.}) 9... Ra7 {The right square for the rook. From here it can later be activated via the 7th rank, while it wouldn't have any prospects on b8 .} ({In two older games, Black opted for the natural-looking} 9... Rb8 $6 {. After} 10. Bf3 Qf5 11. Na5 $1 {White exerts strong pressure on the queenside. The rook on b8 is passive and it is difficult to develop the c8 -bishop.}) 10. Bf3 ({Drives the queen towards the kingside in the hope of pressure on the queenside. Harmless is} 10. Ne3 {because the black queen can now help defend the queenside, e.g.} Qa8 {or Qd6 .}) 10... Qf5 11. Ne3 {Kasimdzhanov and Ganguly's recommendation. Once again Black must react precisely.} Qf4 {The queen is on the same diagonal as the bishop c1 , but an attack is still a long way off. From f4 the queen attacks the pawn on d4 and on the other hand can be brought back via c7 or b8 to defend the queenside.} (11... Qg6 {This square may look safer, but the main action will take place on the queenside and the black queen is needed in defense.} 12. O-O {An improvement over Saravana-Das . White soon plays a2-a4 and is slightly better.}) 12. a4 cxd4 ({The direct} 12... Qb8 {(or Qc7 ) is also possible, but this gives White the option} 13. Nb3 {, after which the exchange on d4 would no longer be good because it leads to an activation of the white pieces.}) 13. cxd4 Qb8 ({Kasimdzhanov and Ganguly also analyze} 13... Qxd4 {Qxd4 , which also leads to equality.} 14. Qc2 Qc5 15. axb5 {White wins back the pawn. The queen comes to the defense in time.}) 14. axb5 axb5 15. Rxa7 Qxa7 16. Qc2 {Kasimdzhanov and Ganguly end their analysis at this point. They assess the position as equal, but still see practical chances for White.} Qb8 {White's ideas on the queenside have been exhausted. Black will be able to play ... Bd6 and ... O-O to finish development. The light-squared bishop can go to b7 or be activated on the c8 - h3 diagonal after ... e6 - e5 . The position is equal.} *

