1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Be2 {White develops the kingside. At the same time, this prepares an attack on the black queen: White would like to play O-O and Nfe5 , after which Bf3 would be a threat. We should therefore react energetically.} b5 {It is best to force the white knight to make a decision directly and continue developing the queenside.} ({After} 8... Be7 $6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nfe5 {White is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Na5 {A rare move, but the main recommendation of Ganguly and Kasimdzhanov. White prevents ... Bb7 and later wants to put pressure on the black queenside with c3 - c4 or a2 - a4 . We should also watch out for another idea from White: The f3 -knight could move and clear the way for the bishop to f3 .} Bd6 {Black wants to drive away the troublesome knight from a5 with ... Bc7 . In addition, the bishop has the white kingside in its sights.} ({Weaker would be} 9... Be7 $6 {because after} 10. O-O Bd8 $2 {does not work due to} 11. Ng5 $1 {followed by Bf3 .}) (9... Qd6 {is also possible and leads to equality, as Ganguly/Kasimdzhanov show. After their strong novelty} 10. a4 Qc7 11. dxc5 $1 {, however, Black still has to find some precise moves.}) 10. Ng5 {Too hasty. White should first get the king out of the center. Nevertheless, the analysis is worthwhile, because the outcome of the following complications is anything but obvious.} cxd4 11. Bf3 (11. O-O {is too slow.} dxc3 {The simple solution. (Interesting is 11...h6 .)} 12. Bf3 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Nd5 {Black will keep an extra pawn. I don't see sufficient compensation.}) ({After} 11. Qxd4 {White doesn't have any threats. The black position is slightly better after} Bc7 {.}) 11... Qe5+ {This was the idea of the previous move.} 12. Kf1 {The rook on a8 is attacked and cannot really move away because White has the fork 13.Nc6 . In addition, the d4 -pawn is under attack.} dxc3 {Black saves themselves by counter-attacking!} 13. Bxa8 ({After} 13. bxc3 Nd5 {Black has a healthy extra pawn.}) 13... cxb2 14. Bxb2 Qxb2 {The end of a forced sequence. Approximate material balance is restored, but the black position is preferable. The white pieces are scattered all over the board and lack harmony.} 15. Qc1 {Relatively best. By attacking the c8 -bishop White forces an exchange of queens and stays in the game.} Qxc1+ 16. Rxc1 O-O {Now ... Bf4 is a threat. White should take care of the coordination of the pieces as quickly as possible in order to minimize the disadvantage.} *

