ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Na5 {A rare move, but the main recommendation of Ganguly and Kasimdzhanov. White prevents ... Bb7 and later wants to put pressure on the black queenside with c3 - c4 or a2 - a4 . We should also watch out for another idea from White: The f3 -knight could move and clear the way for the bishop to f3 .} Bd6 {Black wants to drive away the troublesome knight from a5 with ... Bc7 . In addition, the bishop has the white kingside in its sights.} ({Weaker would be} 9... Be7 $6 {because after} 10. O-O Bd8 $2 {does not work due to} 11. Ng5 $1 {followed by Bf3 .}) (9... Qd6 {is also possible and leads to equality, as Ganguly/Kasimdzhanov show. After their strong novelty} 10. a4 Qc7 11. dxc5 $1 {, however, Black still has to find some precise moves.}) 10. O-O {After bringing the king to safety, White is now threatening Ng5 (or Nd2 ) followed by Bf3 .} Bc7 {This not only attacks the knight on a5 , but also clears the d6 -square for the queen.} 11. Nb3 (11. Ng5 $2 {no longer works.} Qd6 {Black is threatening mate on h2 and thus defends with tempo against the threat} 12. Bf3 {. g3} Bxa5) 11... cxd4 (11... c4 {is also good.}) 12. Nfxd4 Bb7 13. Bf3 Qd6 {Threatening mate on h2 .} 14. g3 Bxf3 {No matter how White recaptures: Black finishes development with 15...O-O and has equalized.} *

