1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Be2 {White develops the kingside. At the same time, this prepares an attack on the black queen: White would like to play O-O and Nfe5 , after which Bf3 would be a threat. We should therefore react energetically.} b5 {It is best to force the white knight to make a decision directly and continue developing the queenside.} ({After} 8... Be7 $6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nfe5 {White is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Na5 {A rare move, but the main recommendation of Ganguly and Kasimdzhanov. White prevents ... Bb7 and later wants to put pressure on the black queenside with c3 - c4 or a2 - a4 . We should also watch out for another idea from White: The f3 -knight could move and clear the way for the bishop to f3 .} Bd6 {Black wants to drive away the troublesome knight from a5 with ... Bc7 . In addition, the bishop has the white kingside in its sights.} ({Weaker would be} 9... Be7 $6 {because after} 10. O-O Bd8 $2 {does not work due to} 11. Ng5 $1 {followed by Bf3 .}) (9... Qd6 {is also possible and leads to equality, as Ganguly/Kasimdzhanov show. After their strong novelty} 10. a4 Qc7 11. dxc5 $1 {, however, Black still has to find some precise moves.}) 10. c4 {Black was threatening to drive away the knight on a5 , so White brings it back to c4 .} bxc4 11. Nxc4 Be7 ({A novelty. In both games that reached this position,} 11... Bc7 {was played and this is also the move that Ganguly and Kasimdzhanov analyze. I like the bishop on c7 less, because it can be attacked later by a rook on the c-file. In addition, from e7 the bishop protects the c5 -pawn and has the potential to be activated via f6 .}) (11... Bc7 12. O-O Bb7 {( 12...cxd4 looks better)} 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Be3 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Ncd7 {Drazic-Cheparinov happened in one of the games and here White could have exerted strong pressure on the queenside after the simple} 16. Rac1 {.}) 12. O-O Bb7 ({After} 12... O-O {White has the option} 13. Nfe5 $5 {.}) 13. dxc5 {White opens up the position and prevents Black from capturing on d4 .} Bxc5 ({Black can also play} 13... Nxc5 {, but after} 14. Nb6 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 {White has the more active position.}) 14. Qb3 {The most dangerous continuation. Rd1 is a threat, after which the black queen can no longer defend the b7 -bishop.} (14. Na5 $2 {loses a pawn due to} Bxf2+ 15. Rxf2 Qxa5 {.}) 14... a5 {An important move which is primarily of a prophylactic nature: the white knight must not reach a5 . It is also a useful move from a positional point of view, because the gain of space ... a5 - a4 is prepared.} (14... O-O $2 15. Rd1 Qe4 16. Bd3 Qc6 ({(} 16... Qd5 17. Bxh7+ {loses the queen)}) 17. Na5 {and the b7 -bishop is lost.}) 15. Rd1 a4 ({With this intermediate move, Black gains some space on the queenside. Instead, the direct queen moves} 15... Qc6 {or Qe4 are also playable, as White can no longer play Na5 .}) 16. Qc3 (16. Rxd5 $2 axb3 {with a double attack on the d5 -rook and the a2 -pawn.}) 16... Qe4 ({Or} 16... Qc6 {.}) 17. Be3 {Best. White fends off the attack against the bishop e2 and fights for the d6 -square.} (17. Bd3 $6 {overlooks} Qg4 $1 {, giving Black strong pressure on the kingside.} 18. Be2 Bxf2+ $1 {.}) 17... O-O (17... Bxe3 $4 {loses the queen after} 18. Nd6+ {.}) 18. Bxc5 Nxc5 {The position is equal. However, Black has to be careful because the position on the queenside is not yet stabilized and the queen is exposed on e4 . But first White has to take care of the attacked bishop. Some possible continuations:} ({A ) Ne3} 18... Rfc8 19. Rd4 Qc6 {. Next could follow ...Ncd7 or ...a4-a3 .}) ({) Qe1} 18... Qf4 {[%eval 0,0] . Black thus prevents the attack Nd6 . If the queen is attacked, it reaches safety on c7 or b8 .}) ({C ) Bf1 Ncd7! The knight moves to safety. White had been threatening the double attack Nb6 . Nd6} 18... Qc6 {Black has consolidated the position and has nothing to fear.}) *

