ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Na5 {A rare move, but the main recommendation of Ganguly and Kasimdzhanov. White prevents ... Bb7 and later wants to put pressure on the black queenside with c3 - c4 or a2 - a4 . We should also watch out for another idea from White: The f3 -knight could move and clear the way for the bishop to f3 .} Bd6 {Black wants to drive away the troublesome knight from a5 with ... Bc7 . In addition, the bishop has the white kingside in its sights.} ({Weaker would be} 9... Be7 $6 {because after} 10. O-O Bd8 $2 {does not work due to} 11. Ng5 $1 {followed by Bf3 .}) (9... Qd6 {is also possible and leads to equality, as Ganguly/Kasimdzhanov show. After their strong novelty} 10. a4 Qc7 11. dxc5 $1 {, however, Black still has to find some precise moves.}) 10. c4 {Black was threatening to drive away the knight on a5 , so White brings it back to c4 .} bxc4 11. Nxc4 Be7 ({A novelty. In both games that reached this position,} 11... Bc7 {was played and this is also the move that Ganguly and Kasimdzhanov analyze. I like the bishop on c7 less, because it can be attacked later by a rook on the c-file. In addition, from e7 the bishop protects the c5 -pawn and has the potential to be activated via f6 .}) (11... Bc7 12. O-O Bb7 {( 12...cxd4 looks better)} 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Be3 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Ncd7 {Drazic-Cheparinov happened in one of the games and here White could have exerted strong pressure on the queenside after the simple} 16. Rac1 {.}) 12. O-O Bb7 ({After} 12... O-O {White has the option} 13. Nfe5 $5 {.}) 13. Na5 {This is the drawback of 11...Be7 compared to 11...Bc7 . White now secures the bishop pair.} cxd4 {White was threatening 14.Bc4 , so this move is practically forced. Now the knight a5 is under attack, so White has no choice either.} 14. Nxb7 Qxb7 15. Nxd4 O-O {For the bishop pair Black has good central control and pressure along the b-file. After moves like ... Ne5 , ... Rfd8 and ... Rac8 , Black can quickly take the initiative. Therefore White should now act energetically.} 16. Bf3 Nd5 17. Nf5 {The knight position on d4 was not very stable, so White transfers it to greener pastures.} Bf6 {Here the bishop is ideal and puts pressure on the b2 -pawn.} 18. Ne3 N7b6 {The position is equal. For the bishop pair, Black has good activity and pressure against the b2 -pawn, which prevents White from developing the c1 -bishop. Black now plans to advance the a-pawn to increase the pressure on the queenside. The rooks will probably go to d8 and c8 . If White does not play 19.Ng4 directly, ... g7 - g6 is an option to give the bishop a flight square on g7 .} ({Ng4 is best met with Qe7 . After an exchange on f6 the queen would take over the role of the bishop and attack the b2 -pawn. The game could continue as follows: Rb1 The rook protects b2 -pawn so that the bishop can now be developed.} 18... Rac8 {And now:  ➤} 19. Bd2 Bg5 {. White fails to keep the bishop pair.}) ({➤ Nxf6+ Qxf6 Bd2 Nc4 . Again White has to part with the bishop pair. ➤ Qe2} 18... a5 {Rd1} 19. a4 {. Black has gained space on the queenside and is threatening to advance the a-pawn further. White has still not managed to develop the c1 -bishop.}) *

