ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. Ne5 {This only leads to exchanges and is quite harmless.} Qc7 ({We should avoid} 10... Nxe5 $2 11. dxe5 Nd5 12. Bf3 {with strong pressure for White.}) 11. Bf3 ({Or} 11. a4 Rb8 {. White cannot build up pressure on the queenside.}) 11... Bb7 {The position is equal. The exchange of two pairs of minor pieces is now very likely. If White allows it, we can capture on d4 so that White has to play with an isolated pawn.} *

