1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Be2 {White develops the kingside. At the same time, this prepares an attack on the black queen: White would like to play O-O and Nfe5 , after which Bf3 would be a threat. We should therefore react energetically.} b5 {It is best to force the white knight to make a decision directly and continue developing the queenside.} ({After} 8... Be7 $6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nfe5 {White is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. O-O Be7 ({More precise than Mamedyarov's and Firouzja's 10...Bb7 .} 10... Bb7 {gives White the additional possibility} 11. c4 $1 {with the threat d4-d5 . This has so far only been tested in the correspondence game Hausdorf-Greig , which illustrates the dangers for Black very well:} Bd6 $6 {more solid is probably Be7 .} 12. d5 $1 exd5 13. Nf5 {That was the idea of 11.c4 . White gets a strong attack.} bxc4 ({(} 13... O-O $2 {doesn't work because of} 14. Bf4 $1 {, winning material.)}) 14. Bxc4 $1 Kf8 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. b4 {The black king is in the way of the rooks and White has a strong pair of bishops.}) 11. c4 {Against 10...Bb7 this move can be quite dangerous, but now it is harmless.} (11. a4 Bb7 {We look at this position via the move order a4 Bb7 O-O Be7 .}) 11... O-O {The difference to 10...Bb7 . Black manages to castle.} (11... Bb7 $6 {gives White chances to attack} 12. d5 $1 exd5 13. Nf5 {.}) 12. d5 exd5 13. cxd5 (13. Nf5 $2 {does not work here. Black simply plays} Bd8 {and has an extra pawn.}) 13... Qb6 {Black has no problems and even the better chances in the long run, because the white d-pawn is vulnerable.} *

