1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Be2 {White develops the kingside. At the same time, this prepares an attack on the black queen: White would like to play O-O and Nfe5 , after which Bf3 would be a threat. We should therefore react energetically.} b5 {It is best to force the white knight to make a decision directly and continue developing the queenside.} ({After} 8... Be7 $6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nfe5 {White is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. c4 {White not only puts pressure on the queenside, but is also threatening d4 - d5 . This move has so far only been tested in correspondence chess.} cxd4 {This prevents d4 - d5 and gives the f8 -bishop additional possibilities.} (10... Bb7 $6 11. O-O {with the threat d4-d5 is dangerous for Black – we have seen an example of this when looking at the move order O-O Bb7?!} bxc4 $1) (10... Be7 $6 {allows the direct} 11. d5 $1 {and if} exd5 12. cxd5 Qb6 13. Nf5 {with an attack.}) 11. Nxd4 Qb6 12. cxb5 {White cannot afford to win the pawn.} Bb4+ 13. Kf1 {Forced. Now Black gets very strong compensation for the pawn. The white king on f1 prevents the rook on h1 from joining the game and on the queenside Black gets play on the open files reminiscent of the Volga Gambit.} axb5 14. Nxb5 ({After} 14. Bxb5 $2 e5 {White would have to exchange the important light-squared bishop.}) 14... Ba6 15. a4 O-O {Despite the pawn deficit, Black is clearly better. With moves like ... Rfd8 and ... Nc5 the pressure on the queenside can be increased.} *

