ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. c4 {White not only puts pressure on the queenside, but is also threatening d4 - d5 . This move has so far only been tested in correspondence chess.} cxd4 {This prevents d4 - d5 and gives the f8 -bishop additional possibilities.} (10... Bb7 $6 11. O-O {with the threat d4-d5 is dangerous for Black – we have seen an example of this when looking at the move order O-O Bb7?!} bxc4 $1) (10... Be7 $6 {allows the direct} 11. d5 $1 {and if} exd5 12. cxd5 Qb6 13. Nf5 {with an attack.}) 11. Nxd4 Qb6 12. O-O {With the king on e1 the b-pawn was taboo, but now cxb5 is a threat.} b4 {The queenside is now closed. Next, Black wants to finish development with the moves ... Bb7 , ... Be7 /... Bc5 and ... O-O . White currently has a lead in development, but their pieces lack harmony while the position will remain closed for the foreseeable future. The position is equal and the correspondence game Young-Mazumdar , ended in a draw after a few moves.} *

