ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 ({White puts pressure on the queenside. Specifically, White is threatening to win a pawn with} 10. Z0 {axb5 axb5 Bxb5 , because the black queen is overloaded with the defense of the b-pawn and the rook.}) 10... Bb7 {Protects the rook and defends against White's threat. It is important to keep the pawn on b5 , as it prevents the activation of the e3 -knight via c4 . White can now isolate the black b-pawn and has a good chance of winning it later, but, as we will see, Black gains positional trumps in return. Many moves are now possible, as White can play axb5 , dxc5 and O-O in any order.} (10... b4 $2 {In his book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' GM Khalifman only considers this cooperative move. White now gets good squares for their pieces and strong pressure on the queenside, e.g.} 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Rc1 Qd6 14. Nc4 Qd5 15. a5 Be7 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 18. Qxb4 {with a clear extra pawn for White in Zhigalko-Hoffmann .}) 11. dxc5 {Johann-Sebastian Christiansen's recommendation. The exchange of pawns gives White more space for their pieces: the knight can go to d4 and the bishop can support White's play on the queenside from e3 .} Qxc5 {This is more accurate than capturing with the bishop.} ({After} 11... Bxc5 $6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 {comes} 14. Nd4 {and Black must part with either the bishop pair or the b5 -pawn.}) 12. axb5 {The most direct attempt and GM Christiansen's recommendation. After the exchange the b5 -pawn becomes weak. A transition to the lines after 11.axb5 is now very likely.} axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Nc2 {Christiansen ends his analysis at this point with the assessment that White retains some pressure with the moves Be3 and O-O .} Be7 15. O-O (15. Be3 {White can now hardly avoid a transition to the lines after 11.axb5 , so we won't consider this separately here.} Qc7 {The best square for the queen. The b5 -pawn cannot be defended anyway.   A )} 16. Bxb5 O-O 17. O-O {See 11.axb5  here .   B ) O-O O-O We will consider this position via the move order axb5 axb5 Rxa8 Bxa8 O-O Be7 dxc5} Qc5 {Nc2 O-O Be3 Qc7 .}) 15... O-O ({We also deal with this via the move order axb5 axb5 Rxa8 Bxa8} 15... O-O {Be7 dxc5 Qxc5 Nc2 O-O .}) *

