1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {This is probably the most popular choice at the moment. The knight move is recommended, for example, in the book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' (2020) by GM Alexander Khalifman and the Alapin courses on Chessable The High Pressure Alapin Sicilian (2020) by GM Johann-Sebastian Christiansen and Tame the Sicilian: The Alapin Variation (2022) by GMs Rustam Kasimdzhanov and Surya Shekhar Ganguly. IM Christoph Selicki also argues in favor of the knight move in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 – 2.0 .   White is threatening to attack the c7 -square with Nb5 . Additionally, the knight can be rerouted toward the center via c4 or c2 , and White can sometimes gain a tempo with Bc4 .} a6 {With this move, we not only prevent the white knight from appearing on b5 , but also prepare development of the queenside: ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 . The knight usually goes to d7 , where it covers the weakened square b6 and does not block the view of the bishop on b7 .} ({Defending c7 is also well tested and playable – either} 6... Qd8 {or Nc6} 7. Nb5 {and only now Qd8 .}) (6... cxd4 7. Nb5 $1 {shows one of the main ideas of 6.Na3 . Black has to respond to the threat of a fork on c7 , after which White recaptures with the queen or knight on d4 and avoids an isolated queen's pawn.}) 7. Nc4 {The most logical continuation. The knight is centralized and is threatening a fork on b6 .} Nbd7 ({Covers the b6 -square. Instead,} 7... Qd8 {has also been played, but this is an unnecessary loss of time. Black has sufficient defensive resources against attacks on the queen on d5 .}) 8. Be2 {White develops the kingside. At the same time, this prepares an attack on the black queen: White would like to play O-O and Nfe5 , after which Bf3 would be a threat. We should therefore react energetically.} b5 {It is best to force the white knight to make a decision directly and continue developing the queenside.} ({After} 8... Be7 $6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nfe5 {White is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 ({White puts pressure on the queenside. Specifically, White is threatening to win a pawn with} 10. Z0 {axb5 axb5 Bxb5 , because the black queen is overloaded with the defense of the b-pawn and the rook.}) 10... Bb7 {Protects the rook and defends against White's threat. It is important to keep the pawn on b5 , as it prevents the activation of the e3 -knight via c4 . White can now isolate the black b-pawn and has a good chance of winning it later, but, as we will see, Black gains positional trumps in return. Many moves are now possible, as White can play axb5 , dxc5 and O-O in any order.} (10... b4 $2 {In his book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' GM Khalifman only considers this cooperative move. White now gets good squares for their pieces and strong pressure on the queenside, e.g.} 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Rc1 Qd6 14. Nc4 Qd5 15. a5 Be7 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 18. Qxb4 {with a clear extra pawn for White in Zhigalko-Hoffmann .}) 11. dxc5 {Johann-Sebastian Christiansen's recommendation. The exchange of pawns gives White more space for their pieces: the knight can go to d4 and the bishop can support White's play on the queenside from e3 .} Qxc5 {This is more accurate than capturing with the bishop.} ({After} 11... Bxc5 $6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 {comes} 14. Nd4 {and Black must part with either the bishop pair or the b5 -pawn.}) 12. axb5 {The most direct attempt and GM Christiansen's recommendation. After the exchange the b5 -pawn becomes weak. A transition to the lines after 11.axb5 is now very likely.} axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Qb3 ({Comparable to} 14. Nd4 {, White provokes a move of the b-pawn.}) 14... b4 15. Qa4 Bxf3 ({Easiest, but other moves of the bishop are also good.  However, it is important not to confuse this position with the variation Nd4 b4 Qa4 .  After} 15... Qc8 $6 {White has the resource} 16. Ne5 $1 {with strong pressure on the queenside.}) (15... Bb7 16. O-O bxc3 17. bxc3 {and now the precise} Qc7 $1 {is best, after which the queenside is reliably defended and Black has no problems finishing development with ...Bc5 and ...O-O .}) 16. Bxf3 Bd6 {White had been threatening Qa8+ , which can now be met with ...Bb8 . Therefore, Black is now threatening to capture on c3 . In addition, the bishop move prepares castling or the evacuation of the king to e7 . The position is equal.} ({Clearly weaker is} 16... Be7 $2 {because of} 17. Bc6 $1 {with castling prevented.}) ({Not} 16... bxc3 $2 17. Qa8+ {.}) *

