ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 ({White puts pressure on the queenside. Specifically, White is threatening to win a pawn with} 10. Z0 {axb5 axb5 Bxb5 , because the black queen is overloaded with the defense of the b-pawn and the rook.}) 10... Bb7 {Protects the rook and defends against White's threat. It is important to keep the pawn on b5 , as it prevents the activation of the e3 -knight via c4 . White can now isolate the black b-pawn and has a good chance of winning it later, but, as we will see, Black gains positional trumps in return. Many moves are now possible, as White can play axb5 , dxc5 and O-O in any order.} (10... b4 $2 {In his book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' GM Khalifman only considers this cooperative move. White now gets good squares for their pieces and strong pressure on the queenside, e.g.} 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Rc1 Qd6 14. Nc4 Qd5 15. a5 Be7 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 18. Qxb4 {with a clear extra pawn for White in Zhigalko-Hoffmann .}) 11. dxc5 {Johann-Sebastian Christiansen's recommendation. The exchange of pawns gives White more space for their pieces: the knight can go to d4 and the bishop can support White's play on the queenside from e3 .} Qxc5 {This is more accurate than capturing with the bishop.} ({After} 11... Bxc5 $6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 {comes} 14. Nd4 {and Black must part with either the bishop pair or the b5 -pawn.}) 12. axb5 {The most direct attempt and GM Christiansen's recommendation. After the exchange the b5 -pawn becomes weak. A transition to the lines after 11.axb5 is now very likely.} axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Nd4 {A logical way to increase pressure on the queenside. Now the b-pawn has to move, giving the white pieces access to a4 and c4 .} b4 {Otherwise the b-pawn cannot be defended and a sacrifice is out of the question due to the activity of the white pieces.} 15. Qa4 Qc8 {This defends the bishop on a8 and clears the way for the other bishop to c5 .} 16. O-O {Now White is threatening to capture on b4 . Previously this was not possible because the bishop on c1 was unprotected.} bxc3 17. bxc3 Bc5 {We prepare castling.} ({But not} 17... Be7 $2 18. Ba3 $1 {after which the black king cannot escape from the center.}) ({However, it is also possible to play} 17... Bb7 {with the idea} 18. Ba3 Bxa3 19. Qxa3 Qc5 {.}) 18. Nb3 {This secures White the advantage of the bishop pair. Other moves achieve nothing.} O-O ({Once again} 18... Be7 $2 {does not work because of} 19. Ba3 $1 {.}) 19. Nxc5 Nxc5 {White has the bishop pair, but the pawn on c3 is weak and there are no weaknesses in the black position. The position is equal.} *

