ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 ({White puts pressure on the queenside. Specifically, White is threatening to win a pawn with} 10. Z0 {axb5 axb5 Bxb5 , because the black queen is overloaded with the defense of the b-pawn and the rook.}) 10... Bb7 {Protects the rook and defends against White's threat. It is important to keep the pawn on b5 , as it prevents the activation of the e3 -knight via c4 . White can now isolate the black b-pawn and has a good chance of winning it later, but, as we will see, Black gains positional trumps in return. Many moves are now possible, as White can play axb5 , dxc5 and O-O in any order.} (10... b4 $2 {In his book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' GM Khalifman only considers this cooperative move. White now gets good squares for their pieces and strong pressure on the queenside, e.g.} 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Rc1 Qd6 14. Nc4 Qd5 15. a5 Be7 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 18. Qxb4 {with a clear extra pawn for White in Zhigalko-Hoffmann .}) 11. dxc5 {Johann-Sebastian Christiansen's recommendation. The exchange of pawns gives White more space for their pieces: the knight can go to d4 and the bishop can support White's play on the queenside from e3 .} Qxc5 {This is more accurate than capturing with the bishop.} ({After} 11... Bxc5 $6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 {comes} 14. Nd4 {and Black must part with either the bishop pair or the b5 -pawn.}) 12. O-O Be7 13. Qb3 {White increases the pressure on the b-pawn. This was discussed in a rapid game between the two world-class players Mamedyarov and Firouzja.} (13. axb5 {is the most common move and after} axb5 14. Rxa8+ Bxa8 {play transposes to our main line  11.axb5 .}) 13... Nd5 {We should give up the b-pawn without a fight and use the time to improve our piece play. The knight is on its way to f4 .} ({Again,} 13... b4 $6 {– Firouzja's choice – is not a good idea because it gives the white pieces good squares. After} 14. Bd2 Ne4 15. Be1 a5 16. cxb4 axb4 17. Bb5 {Mamedyarov-Firouzja Mamedyarov had reached a dominant position, but later lost the game.}) 14. axb5 {The most principled continuation.} ({After} 14. Nxd5 {Bxd5...}) ({or} 14. g3 Nc7 {Black keeps the b-pawn and doesn't have any worries.}) 14... Nf4 15. Nd4 ({White cannot afford to weaken their king position with} 15. Bc4 $2 Bxf3 16. gxf3 {. Black gets a decisive attack after} Ne5 {.}) 15... Nxe2+ 16. Nxe2 O-O {Black has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn. The pair of bishops and especially the light-squared bishop are very strong. On the queenside it is now the black pieces that can exert pressure. White, on the other hand, has a passive bishop which is blocked by the somewhat misplaced knight on e3 . Black's next moves could be ... Qc7 and ... Nc5 . The f8 -rook goes to d8 or b8 .} *

