ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 ({White puts pressure on the queenside. Specifically, White is threatening to win a pawn with} 10. Z0 {axb5 axb5 Bxb5 , because the black queen is overloaded with the defense of the b-pawn and the rook.}) 10... Bb7 {Protects the rook and defends against White's threat. It is important to keep the pawn on b5 , as it prevents the activation of the e3 -knight via c4 . White can now isolate the black b-pawn and has a good chance of winning it later, but, as we will see, Black gains positional trumps in return. Many moves are now possible, as White can play axb5 , dxc5 and O-O in any order.} (10... b4 $2 {In his book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' GM Khalifman only considers this cooperative move. White now gets good squares for their pieces and strong pressure on the queenside, e.g.} 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Rc1 Qd6 14. Nc4 Qd5 15. a5 Be7 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 18. Qxb4 {with a clear extra pawn for White in Zhigalko-Hoffmann .}) 11. axb5 ({The logical continuation after the previous move.} 11. O-O {has no independent significance here, because after} Be7 {White has nothing better than capturing on b5 or c5 , which we consider via a different move order.}) 11... axb5 12. Rxa8+ Bxa8 13. O-O ({We have considered the position after} 13. dxc5 Qxc5 {via the move order dxc5 Qxc5 axb5 axb5 Rxa8 Bxa8 .}) {( Bxc5 is inaccurate because of Nd4⩲ .)} 13... Be7 ({The right square for the bishop. On d6 it is less safe and can be attacked later:} 13... Bd6 $6 {. The two Indian super stars GM Praggnanandhaa and GM Erigaisi opted for the more active bishop development in blitz and rapid games, but after} 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nd4 b4 16. Nb5 $1 {the bishop has to move again and White wins time – Yoo-Praggnanandhaa .}) ({Black cannot keep the position on the queenside closed, because} 13... c4 $2 {is answered with} 14. b3 {.}) 14. Ne5 {This was tested at the highest level in the rapid games Aronian-Kovalenko and Aronian-Erigaisi .} Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. c4 {White first improves the pawn structure on the queenside. Otherwise Black might later play ... c5 - c4 themselves and use the vacated c5 -square for their pieces.} b4 {A novelty. The square c4 should not be accessible to the white pieces.} ({Kovalenko played} 16... bxc4 $6 {instead, which gave White a strong initiative after} 17. Bf3 Qa6 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 19. Nxc4 {. Black cannot castle and the defensive move} Qc6 $2 {was strongly met with} 20. Qg4 $1 g6 21. Bh6 {with a decisive advantage for White, Aronian-Kovalenko .}) (16... Nxe5 $6 {, chosen by GM Erigaisi, also gives White the better chances:} 17. cxb5 Qd7 $6 {Aronian-Erigaisi and now} ({(} 17... Qc7 18. b3 {)}) 18. b3 {would have been best. White has active piece play.}) 17. f4 O-O {Black doesn't have any worries. White's pieces are not particularly well placed. If White plays carelessly, Black can open up the position with ... f7 - f6 and take the initiative. After e5xf6 Black would recapture with the bishop and then place it on d4 .} *

