ite is threatening Bf3 , when the black queen would be in danger. The exchange of queens after} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {offers no relief, as Black now comes under strong pressure on the queenside.}) ({The most common move} 8... cxd4 $6 {is not good for Black either, as White has the strong pawn sacrifice} 9. Nxd4 {, after which the white pieces are very active. Black cannot afford to accept the sacrifice:} Qxg2 $6 10. Bf3 Qg6 11. Qe2 {The white pieces exert pressure across the whole board.}) 9. Ne3 {The most popular move. By attacking the queen, White gains a tempo and then wants to put pressure on Black's queenside. However, the knight is not necessarily well-placed here, and above all interferes with the development of the bishop c1 .} Qc6 {The right square. From here the queen helps to defend the queenside, especially the b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 ({White puts pressure on the queenside. Specifically, White is threatening to win a pawn with} 10. Z0 {axb5 axb5 Bxb5 , because the black queen is overloaded with the defense of the b-pawn and the rook.}) 10... Bb7 {Protects the rook and defends against White's threat. It is important to keep the pawn on b5 , as it prevents the activation of the e3 -knight via c4 . White can now isolate the black b-pawn and has a good chance of winning it later, but, as we will see, Black gains positional trumps in return. Many moves are now possible, as White can play axb5 , dxc5 and O-O in any order.} (10... b4 $2 {In his book 'Squeezing the Sicilian. The Alapin Variation' GM Khalifman only considers this cooperative move. White now gets good squares for their pieces and strong pressure on the queenside, e.g.} 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Rc1 Qd6 14. Nc4 Qd5 15. a5 Be7 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Bxb4 Bxb4+ 18. Qxb4 {with a clear extra pawn for White in Zhigalko-Hoffmann .}) 11. axb5 ({The logical continuation after the previous move.} 11. O-O {has no independent significance here, because after} Be7 {White has nothing better than capturing on b5 or c5 , which we consider via a different move order.}) 11... axb5 12. Rxa8+ Bxa8 13. O-O ({We have considered the position after} 13. dxc5 Qxc5 {via the move order dxc5 Qxc5 axb5 axb5 Rxa8 Bxa8 .}) {( Bxc5 is inaccurate because of Nd4⩲ .)} 13... Be7 ({The right square for the bishop. On d6 it is less safe and can be attacked later:} 13... Bd6 $6 {. The two Indian super stars GM Praggnanandhaa and GM Erigaisi opted for the more active bishop development in blitz and rapid games, but after} 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nd4 b4 16. Nb5 $1 {the bishop has to move again and White wins time – Yoo-Praggnanandhaa .}) ({Black cannot keep the position on the queenside closed, because} 13... c4 $2 {is answered with} 14. b3 {.}) 14. dxc5 {Thus White isolates the black b-pawn.} Qxc5 ({Here, too,} 14... Bxc5 $2 {fails to} 15. Nd4 {.}) 15. Nd4 b4 {Black keeps the b-pawn. White can now try to prevent Black from castling.} 16. cxb4 ({After} 16. Bb5 bxc3 17. bxc3 Qc7 {Black was already in control in the game Alsina Leal-Jankovic , because the c3 -pawn is weak and the c1 -bishop is not participating in the game.}) 16... Qxb4 17. Bb5 {White still has some initiative. The attack on d7 is intended to prevent Black from castling.} Qd6 {Protects the knight and prepares castling. But now we have to watch out for the resource Ndf5 .} ({Black can still castle, because the complications ultimately lead to equality.} 17... O-O 18. Bxd7 Rd8 $1 ({(} 18... Nxd7 $2 19. Nxe6 {)}) 19. Nec2 Qb6 {Black wins back the piece through the pin along the d-file.}) 18. Re1 (18. Qd2 $5 {An engine suggestion with a hidden idea.} O-O {Queen moves are also possible.} 19. Ndf5 $1 exf5 20. Nxf5 Qe6 21. Qg5 {This is what White had in mind with 18.Qd2 . But it's only enough for a draw.} g6 22. Nxe7+ Qxe7 23. Bxd7 h6 $1 {The queen must maintain the pin of the knight, otherwise the d7 -bishop will be lost.} 24. Qh4 g5 $1 {Now White loses a piece and the game ends in perpetual check:} 25. Bxg5 hxg5 26. Qxg5+ Kh8 27. Qh6+ Kg8 28. Qg5+ {.}) 18... g6 {Protecting the f5 -square. Next comes castling. In such positions Black has the slightly better chances in the long term because White's b-pawn is weak.} (18... O-O $6 {runs into the white trap} 19. Ndf5 $1 {after which White secures at least the bishop pair and is slightly better.}) *

