tion in the correspondence game Vasquez-Sternik , thanks to the bishop pair and pressure on the queenside.}) 18. Bf3 {An admission that White has achieved nothing in the opening. The black b-pawn is now safe.} Nd5 19. Bf4 {Black was threatening to gain an advantage with ... Ne5 .} Qb6 ({The position is equal. The two games Mammadov-Abasov , and Kulkarni-Swiercz , ended in draws.  Swiercz showed a good plan for Black: Bg3} 19... Rd8 {First the rook is activated.} 20. Qd3 b4 {And now a pawn is exchanged on the queenside.} 21. cxb4 Bxb4 22. Nxb4 Nxb4 23. Qc3 Nc5 {The remaining white pawn on the queenside is somewhat weak, which gives Black practical winning chances. Objectively, the position remains equal.}) *

