r c5 , which we consider via a different move order.}) 11... axb5 12. Rxa8+ Bxa8 13. O-O ({We have considered the position after} 13. dxc5 Qxc5 {via the move order dxc5 Qxc5 axb5 axb5 Rxa8 Bxa8 .}) {( Bxc5 is inaccurate because of Nd4⩲ .)} 13... Be7 ({The right square for the bishop. On d6 it is less safe and can be attacked later:} 13... Bd6 $6 {. The two Indian super stars GM Praggnanandhaa and GM Erigaisi opted for the more active bishop development in blitz and rapid games, but after} 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nd4 b4 16. Nb5 $1 {the bishop has to move again and White wins time – Yoo-Praggnanandhaa .}) ({Black cannot keep the position on the queenside closed, because} 13... c4 $2 {is answered with} 14. b3 {.}) 14. dxc5 {Thus White isolates the black b-pawn.} Qxc5 ({Here, too,} 14... Bxc5 $2 {fails to} 15. Nd4 {.}) 15. Nc2 {White wants to win the black b-pawn, but direct attacks would have been met with ... b5 - b4 . The knight move prevents this resource and at the same time prepares development of the c1 -bishop.} O-O {This amounts to a pawn sacrifice. As we will see, Black gets good compensation.} 16. Be3 {The black queen can no longer keep the b-pawn protected.} ({After} 16. Nfd4 {Black can either sacrifice the pawn with} Ne5 $5 17. Bxb5 Qc7 {with typical compensation, or protect it with 16...Rb8 .}) 16... Qc7 ({Trying to keep the pawn protected is not advisable:} 16... Qh5 17. Ncd4 Rb8 $2 {(better is 17...Ne5 )} 18. Ng5 Qg6 19. h4 {and the black queen gets into trouble.}) 17. Bxb5 {The most principled move, but not yet tested in practice. White has won a pawn, but the black pieces are very active and exert pressure on both wings.} (17. Nfd4 {In most games that reached this position, the white players opted for this move. White would prefer to capture the b-pawn with the knight, as the bishop is not so well placed on b5 . However, Black can now defend the pawn.} Qb7 {Due to the mating threat on g2 , White must now either give up hope of capturing the b-pawn or accept a weakening of squares around their king.}) 17... Rb8 {White is forced to make a decision.} ({After} 17... Rd8 18. Qe2 Ng4 {, White has the defense} 19. Qc4 {.}) 18. c4 {A natural move, but one which reduces White's defensive options.} Rd8 {Threatening ... Ng4 and ... Ne5 . The black initiative is very strong and worth more than the lost pawn.} ({After Qe2} 18... Ng4 {it becomes clear why Black had to play 17...Rb8 first. The threat is ...Bxf3 followed by ...Qxh2# and with the pawn already on c4 , White no longer has the defense Qc4 . After} 19. Nce1 {or Ncd4 Black has the superior minor pieces and is clearly for choice. The bishop on e3 can be exchanged at will.}) *

