[Black "3A | Delayed Alapin with 5.Bb"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B40"]
[PlyCount "18"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. Bb5+ {A harmless move.} Bd7 6. Bxd7+ {The logical continuation after the previous move. However, the exchange comes in handy for Black, as it was not so easy to bring the light-squared bishop into play.} Qxd7 {Black already has the better chances. The pawn on e5 is weak and can be easily attacked. In contrast, the pawn on d4 is easier to defend.} 7. cxd4 {The most common continuation. Other moves don't pose any challenges for Black either.} cxd4 8. d3 Ne7 ({More flexible than} 8... Nc6 {.}) 9. O-O Nec6 {The idea of the previous move. Black plans to continue attacking the e5 -pawn with ...Qd5 and ...Nd7 . The black pieces are on safe squares. Black is slightly better, as the Latvian grandmaster Viesturs Meijers has demonstrated in two games ( Ronchetti-Meijers and Wilson-Meijers ).} ({The more natural} 9... Nbc6 10. Re1 Ng6 {has the drawback that the knight on g6 can be attacked with} 11. h4 {.}) *

