1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. cxd4 {White usually tries to win the d4 -pawn after this exchange.} cxd4 6. Qa4+ {White plays to win a pawn. However, the queen is not well placed here.} Nc6 7. Bb5 Bd7 {Black is now ready to defend the pawn on the next move. White can either allow this or exchange directly on c6 .} 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Qxd4 Ne7 {It was also possible to win back the pawn directly. But the pawn sacrifice is even stronger. Black is now threatening to exchange on f3 and thus to jeopardize the white pawn structure on the kingside. The e5 -pawn would then be almost impossible to defend.} ({The white position is full of weaknesses, so Black is clearly better despite being a pawn down.} 9... Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Rg1 Be4 {is also slightly better for Black.}) *

