1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. cxd4 {White usually tries to win the d4 -pawn after this exchange.} cxd4 6. Qa4+ {White plays to win a pawn. However, the queen is not well placed here.} Nc6 7. Bb5 Bd7 {Black is now ready to defend the pawn on the next move. White can either allow this or exchange directly on c6 .} 8. O-O ({After} 8. Nxd4 $4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 {(or Bxd7+ Qxd7 )} Bxb5 {White loses a piece.}) 8... Nge7 (8... Bc5 {was also possible. But it's not necessary to protect the d4 -pawn, because White has no good way of capturing it. The knight is on its way to g6 , from where it will attack the e5 -pawn. The positioning of the white queen and bishop on the a4-e8 diagnoal has led to nothing. White will probably soon have to exchange the bishop on c6 , giving Black a strong pair of bishops. Moreover, White's position is full of weak squares. Black is already clearly better.}) 9. Bxc6 {After other moves, Black plays ... Ng6 or ... a7 - a6 with the better position. Nevertheless, capturing the pawn is not a good idea.} Bxc6 10. Qxd4 Bxf3 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. gxf3 Nc6 13. f4 {White cannot afford to lose the e-pawn, as the d-pawn and the f-pawns would then be isolated.} Nb4 14. Nc3 Nd3 15. Ne2 {There is no other way to protect the f4 -pawn.} Rg8 {One of many good moves. Now ... g7 - g5 is threatening to win the f4 - or e5 -pawn. Black could also increase the pressure with ... Bc5 . The knight on d3 prevents White from developing the queenside. Black is clearly better.} *

