1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. cxd4 {White usually tries to win the d4 -pawn after this exchange.} cxd4 6. Bb5+ Bd7 {Black need not fear the loss of the d-pawn.} 7. Nxd4 ({White accepts weaknesses and loses time for the pawn.} 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {We examine this position via the move order Bb5+ Bd7 Bxd7+ Qxd7 cxd4 cxd4 .}) 7... Bxb5 8. Nxb5 a6 9. N5c3 {The knight takes away the most natural square from its colleague on b1 .} Nc6 {Preventing d2 - d4 .} 10. O-O Nge7 {On the one hand, this controls the d5 -square, so that Black is now ready to capture the e-pawn. On the other hand, Black wants to finish development with ... Nf5 or ... Ng6 , ... Bc5 and ...O-O . White doesn't just have to worry about the weak e-pawn: the d-pawn is also backward and weak. Moreover, it's not easy to develop the queenside.} ({Black therefore has excellent compensation for the pawn. Torre-Huebner Black should not be tempted to win back the pawn directly:} 10... Nxe5 $2 11. d4 {White is better developed and will next open up the position with d4-d5 .}) *

