[ECO "B40"]
[PlyCount "30"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. g3 {White develops the bishop to g2 , where it puts pressure on the black queenside.} Nc6 {The most natural reaction. The knight attacks the opponent's pawn on e5 and protects its own pawn on d4 .} 6. Bg2 ({This is of course the logical continuation after the previous move. However, White's play is quite risky. Here White still has the opportunity for} 6. d3 {, which we consider here via the move order d3 Nc6 g3 .}) 6... d3 ({Now it will be very difficult for White to develop the queenside. However, the pawn on d3 is far away from the rest of Black's troops and therefore difficult to protect. This is also the reason why we wait with the advance until the bishop is on g2 .  After} 6... Nge7 7. O-O Ng6 8. Re1 {White can comfortably protect the e5 -pawn and has the more active position.}) 7. O-O Rb8 {Black wants to play ... b7 -b5 and thus further paralyze the white queenside. The knight on b1 would then have no prospects.} ({The immediate} 7... b5 {is also playable, but it gives White some tactical ideas based on the unprotected position of the rook on a8 . For example, after} 8. b4 $5 {Black does not get to fortify the structure on the queenside because} c4 $2 {fails to} 9. a4 {. Black is not ready to defend the pawn chain with} a6 {, which means that the pawns c4 and d3 will soon fall.}) 8. a4 {White does well to thwart Black's plan.} a6 {Black again prepares ... b7 -b5 .} 9. Na3 Nh6 {Both sides develop the knight to the edge of the board, but it is the best square in each case. The knight development to e7 would come with a loss of time as it blocks the bishop.} (9... b5 $6 {is premature:} 10. axb5 axb5 11. Nd4 $1 Nxd4 12. cxd4 {and the black queenside comes under pressure.} Qxd4 $2 {fails to} 13. Bc6+ Bd7 14. Nxb5 $1 Rxb5 15. Ra8+ Ke7 16. Ra7 {.}) 10. Qe1 {A novelty and the engine's favorite. White wants to win the pawn on d3 with Qe4 and Ne1 .} (10. Re1 {With this superficial move White does not address the main problem of their position, namely the strong pawn on d3 . Dionisi-Narayanan .}) 10... b6 {The bishop's development to b7 forces White to act quickly. Black clearly has the better position if the d3 -pawn remains on the board. The following two moves are therefore forced.} 11. Qe4 Bb7 12. Ne1 Nd4 ({A pawn sacrifice for strong positional compensation.} 12... c4 13. Qxc4 {( Nxc4?} Na5 {) Nxe5 and Nf5} 14. Qxd3 {Nxe5 are good alternatives.}) 13. Qxd3 Nf3+ {The idea of the previous move. White cannot capture with the knight, because then the queen would no longer be protected.} 14. Bxf3 Qxd3 15. Nxd3 Bxf3 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. The light-squared bishop is very strong and has no counterpart. White's e5 -pawn is weak and their queenside is underdeveloped. Specifically, Black is threatening to win the exchange with ... Be2 .} *

