bly protect the e5 -pawn and has the more active position.}) 7. O-O Rb8 {Black wants to play ... b7 -b5 and thus further paralyze the white queenside. The knight on b1 would then have no prospects.} ({The immediate} 7... b5 {is also playable, but it gives White some tactical ideas based on the unprotected position of the rook on a8 . For example, after} 8. b4 $5 {Black does not get to fortify the structure on the queenside because} c4 $2 {fails to} 9. a4 {. Black is not ready to defend the pawn chain with} a6 {, which means that the pawns c4 and d3 will soon fall.}) 8. a4 {White does well to thwart Black's plan.} a6 {Black again prepares ... b7 -b5 .} 9. Na3 Nh6 {Both sides develop the knight to the edge of the board, but it is the best square in each case. The knight development to e7 would come with a loss of time as it blocks the bishop.} (9... b5 $6 {is premature:} 10. axb5 axb5 11. Nd4 $1 Nxd4 12. cxd4 {and the black queenside comes under pressure.} Qxd4 $2 {fails to} 13. Bc6+ Bd7 14. Nxb5 $1 Rxb5 15. Ra8+ Ke7 16. Ra7 {.}) 10. Qe1 {A novelty and the engine's favorite. White wants to win the pawn on d3 with Qe4 and Ne1 .} (10. Re1 {With this superficial move White does not address the main problem of their position, namely the strong pawn on d3 . Dionisi-Narayanan .}) 10... b6 {The bishop's development to b7 forces White to act quickly. Black clearly has the better position if the d3 -pawn remains on the board. The following two moves are therefore forced.} 11. Qe4 Bb7 12. Ne1 Nd4 ({A pawn sacrifice for strong positional compensation.} 12... c4 13. Qxc4 {( Nxc4?} Na5 {) Nxe5 and Nf5} 14. Qxd3 {Nxe5 are good alternatives.}) 13. Qxd3 Nf3+ {The idea of the previous move. White cannot capture with the knight, because then the queen would no longer be protected.} 14. Kh1 {White does not want to part with the important light-squared bishop.} Qxd3 15. Nxd3 Ng4 {Attacks the h2 -pawn. Capturing on e5 is a less powerful threat as it would allow White to liberate their position.} 16. h3 h5 {White is in trouble. The black knights are in a threatening position and cannot be driven away. Black is also threatening to include the rook in the kingside attack with ... h5 - h4 .} *

