1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. d3 ({As with} 5. g3 {, White wants to develop the bishop to g2 .} d3 {first prevents Black's counterplay with ...d4-d3 or ...g7-g5 . This modest-looking move has recently been played by many strong grandmasters, following the lead of Magnus Carlsen who used it in two blitz and rapid games in 2021.}) 5... Nc6 6. g3 Nge7 {The black game is based on the weak white pawn on e5 .} 7. Bg2 Ng6 {The attack on e5 comes just in time, as White cannot yet protect the pawn with Re1 . This is an important difference to the analogous line after 5.g3 , where White has not lost any time with d2-d3 and Black's play is therefore less promising.} 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. Bf4 {There is no other way for White to protect the e5 -pawn, so it is not surprising that this move used to be seen very frequently. However, it is better to just sacrifice the pawn, because the exchange of the black knight for the bishop and the resulting change in the pawn structure are favorable for Black.} Nxf4 10. gxf4 {The pawn on f4 is weak in the long term, and there is no dark-squared bishop to defend it.} dxc3 {Otherwise White could capture on d4 and play against the weak pawn on d4 .} 11. bxc3 Ne7 {This clears the way for the bishop development to c6 . The knight has a nice choice between the squares g6 , d5 and f5 . Black is better because White's pawns f4 and d3 are weak.} *

