1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. d3 ({As with} 5. g3 {, White wants to develop the bishop to g2 .} d3 {first prevents Black's counterplay with ...d4-d3 or ...g7-g5 . This modest-looking move has recently been played by many strong grandmasters, following the lead of Magnus Carlsen who used it in two blitz and rapid games in 2021.}) 5... Nc6 6. g3 Nge7 {The black game is based on the weak white pawn on e5 .} 7. Bg2 Ng6 {The attack on e5 comes just in time, as White cannot yet protect the pawn with Re1 . This is an important difference to the analogous line after 5.g3 , where White has not lost any time with d2-d3 and Black's play is therefore less promising.} 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. cxd4 {A pawn sacrifice.} Nxd4 10. Nxd4 cxd4 {White cannot defend the bishop on c1 and the pawn on e5 at the same time.} 11. O-O Qxe5 12. Be4 {Most energetic. White is threatening to open up the position with f4 - f5 , exploiting their lead in development .} f5 13. f4 Qf6 ({Not} 13... Qc7 $2 14. Bxf5 {.}) 14. Bf3 Be7 {White has sufficient compensation for the pawn. The light-squared bishop is strong and puts pressure on the black queenside. The knight can be transferred to c4 , where it has an eye on both the queenside and the center. But Black can also be satisfied with the opening. With the moves ... O-O , ... Rb8 and ... Bd7 , development can be completed. The rooks can then fight for the c-file.} *

