1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. d3 ({As with} 5. g3 {, White wants to develop the bishop to g2 .} d3 {first prevents Black's counterplay with ...d4-d3 or ...g7-g5 . This modest-looking move has recently been played by many strong grandmasters, following the lead of Magnus Carlsen who used it in two blitz and rapid games in 2021.}) 5... Nc6 6. g3 Nge7 {The black game is based on the weak white pawn on e5 .} 7. Bg2 Ng6 {The attack on e5 comes just in time, as White cannot yet protect the pawn with Re1 . This is an important difference to the analogous line after 5.g3 , where White has not lost any time with d2-d3 and Black's play is therefore less promising.} 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. O-O {Carlsen's choice. He sacrifices the e5 -pawn for rapid development.} Ncxe5 ({Weaker is} 9... Ngxe5 $6 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 ({(} 10... Qxe5 $4 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxe5 {)}) 11. Bf4 Bd6 12. Na3 {With the threat Nb5 , White gains a tempo and has a lead in development.}) 10. cxd4 ({We have already examined the position after} 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Be4 f5 12. cxd4 cxd4 {via the move order starting with 9.cxd4  here .}) 10... Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 cxd4 {White has an edge in development for the pawn, but the black position is very solid.} 12. h4 Bd6 {We follow the blitz game Carlsen-Sychev . There are many good alternatives for Black here.} 13. Na3 O-O ({Sychev played} 13... a6 {instead, which loses time and somewhat weakens the queenside.}) 14. Nb5 Qd8 {The pressure against the b7 and d4 -pawns and the possibility of securing the bishop pair give White compensation for the pawn, but no more. The black position is very healthy.} *

