1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. d3 ({As with} 5. g3 {, White wants to develop the bishop to g2 .} d3 {first prevents Black's counterplay with ...d4-d3 or ...g7-g5 . This modest-looking move has recently been played by many strong grandmasters, following the lead of Magnus Carlsen who used it in two blitz and rapid games in 2021.}) 5... Nc6 6. g3 Nge7 {The black game is based on the weak white pawn on e5 .} 7. Bg2 Ng6 {The attack on e5 comes just in time, as White cannot yet protect the pawn with Re1 . This is an important difference to the analogous line after 5.g3 , where White has not lost any time with d2-d3 and Black's play is therefore less promising.} 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. Na3 {This poisonous move was first played by the creative opening expert Jorden van Foreest in a blitz game. The knight can go to b5 or c4 . Black should react precisely.} Bd7 ({Developing the bishop to this square has many advantages:  ➤ the bishop protects the knight on c6 . This makes it safer for Black to drive away the white knight with ...b7-b5 if it goes to c4 .  ➤ if the white knight goes to b5 , it could later be attacked by us moving the c6 -knight.  ➤ after an exchange on d4 , the dark-squared bishop can be developed to b4 , so it is better not to play} 9... Be7 {yet.}) ({Winning a pawn with} 9... Ncxe5 {is now dangerous:} 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Be4 {White wants to attack the black position with Nc4 and h2-h4-h5 .}) 10. Nc4 {From here the knight protects the pawn on e5 and also has the somewhat weakened d6 -square in view.} b5 {It is important to drive away the knight immediately, otherwise White could fortify it with a2 - a4 .} 11. Ncd2 Rc8 {Black will probably win the e5 -pawn soon. But White is better developed and has the initiative.} *

