1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. Bd3 {The most popular continuation. The bishop is now on an active diagonal and has its sights on the black kingside. The drawback is that the bishop blocks the d-pawn, so White cannot develop the queenside so easily.} Bd7 {Black thus activates the light-squared bishop, which now finds a good diagonal on c6 and no longer has to wait behind its own pawn chain.} ({More often} 5... Nc6 {is played, e.g.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. Re1 Ng6 8. g3 {. The position seems a little more comfortable for White, because it is not clear how Black will develop the c8 -bishop.}) 6. cxd4 {Of course this should be checked. White temporarily wins a pawn.} cxd4 ({Also possible is} 6... Bc6 {, regaining the pawn.}) 7. Nxd4 Nc6 8. Nf3 ({After} 8. Nxc6 $6 Bxc6 {the bishop d3 and the pawn g2 are attacked. Black wins back the pawn and is slightly better due to the better pawn structure.}) 8... Qc7 9. O-O (9. Qe2 Nxe5 $1 {does not help White – the bishop on c1 is attacked.}) 9... Nxe5 {Black has won back the pawn and even has slightly better chances because the white d-pawn is isolated and weak. Next, Black will develop the kingside and prepare castling short.} *

