1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. Bd3 {The most popular continuation. The bishop is now on an active diagonal and has its sights on the black kingside. The drawback is that the bishop blocks the d-pawn, so White cannot develop the queenside so easily.} Bd7 {Black thus activates the light-squared bishop, which now finds a good diagonal on c6 and no longer has to wait behind its own pawn chain.} ({More often} 5... Nc6 {is played, e.g.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. Re1 Ng6 8. g3 {. The position seems a little more comfortable for White, because it is not clear how Black will develop the c8 -bishop.}) 6. Be4 {White prepares d2 - d3 and thus the development of the queenside.} Bc6 {Here too, as in the line 5.Bb5+  Bd7 , exchanging the light-squared bishops is good for Black, because afterwards the knight can be developed to the natural square c6 .} 7. Qe2 ({White prepares the centralization of their queen.} 7. Bxc6+ $6 Nxc6 {accelerates the black development.}) 7... Bxe4 8. Qxe4 {The queen now attacks the pawn on d4 and defends White's own pawn on e5 .} Nc6 9. O-O Nge7 {In the lines we have examined so far, Black has usually played this move with the intention of subsequently transferring the knight to g6 . Here we see another idea: Black prepares ... Qd5 , with which the white queen can be exchanged or driven away from its strong position.} 10. d3 ({In the game Kamsky-Svidler , White prevented ...Qd5 with} 10. c4 $6 {. But that's not a good idea, because now White doesn't have any pressure against the d4-pawn, while the white pawn on e5 remains weak. Svidler demonstrated a good plan for Black to exploit this.} h6 $1 ({(After} 10... Ng6 $6 {, the e5 -pawn would be reliably defended. The bishop must therefore be included in the attack on e5 first.)}) 11. d3 g5 $1 {Black now wants to play ...Ng6 and ...Bg7 , after which the pawn e5 can no longer be defended. Black is better, but in the ensuing complications Svidler lost the thread. The game can be found in the annotated games section.}) 10... Qd5 11. Qe2 {It's best for White to prevent the exchange of queens, otherwise it will be difficult to protect the e5 -pawn in the long run.} Ng6 {Attacks the pawn on e5 and prepares development of the dark-squared bishop. White must be careful, because Black can increase the pressure on the e5 -pawn with the maneuver ... Be7 - d8 -c7 .} 12. c4 Qd7 13. h4 {Provokes a weakening in the black pawn structure.} h5 {Otherwise White plays h4 - h5 themselves and the knight would need a lot of time to get back into the game.} 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 {By exchanging bishops, White has achieved that Black cannot significantly increase the pressure on the e5 -pawn. The position is therefore equal. A good plan for Black is now ... f7 - f6 and after exf6 ... gxf6 . This would give Black a mobile pawn center. Petrov-He .} *

