1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. Bd3 {The most popular continuation. The bishop is now on an active diagonal and has its sights on the black kingside. The drawback is that the bishop blocks the d-pawn, so White cannot develop the queenside so easily.} Bd7 {Black thus activates the light-squared bishop, which now finds a good diagonal on c6 and no longer has to wait behind its own pawn chain.} ({More often} 5... Nc6 {is played, e.g.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. Re1 Ng6 8. g3 {. The position seems a little more comfortable for White, because it is not clear how Black will develop the c8 -bishop.}) 6. O-O {The most natural move and White's most common choice.} Bc6 7. Na3 ({White is aware of the dangers of} 7. Re1 g5 $5 {and first develops the queenside. The knight later usually goes to c2 .}) 7... Ne7 ({The usual route for the knight. From g6 it can put pressure on the e5 -pawn.} 7... g5 {would not be as strong here as after 7.Re1 , since the f3 -knight can retreat to e1 if necessary.}) 8. Re1 {After Black has already moved the knight to e7 , there is nothing to be said against this natural move. White protects the e5 -pawn.} Ng6 9. Be4 ({Prepares d2-d3 and thus the development of the queenside.} 9. Nc2 $2 Nf4 $1 10. Bf1 d3 {is good for Black – White will have to spend many moves until the pieces on the queenside take part in the game.}) 9... Be7 (9... d3 {is an interesting but risky alternative. After} 10. Qb3 {White prepares an attack against the d3 -pawn. Grischuk-Vitiugov .}) 10. cxd4 ({White could also start with} 10. d3 {, but this gives Black the opportunity to play} dxc3 {, after which the d4 -pawn is no longer a cause for concern.}) 10... cxd4 11. d3 O-O 12. Nc2 {White comes first with the attack on the d4 -pawn.} Bxe4 ({Weaker is} 12... Bc5 {, because the bishop is needed to defend the kingside. White gets good attacking chances, e.g. after} 13. Bg5 Qd7 14. h4 {.}) 13. Rxe4 Nc6 {The pawn d4 is indirectly defended.} 14. Qe2 ({White protects the e5 -pawn. After} 14. Ncxd4 $6 {Black wins back the pawn with} Ngxe5 $1 {and has the better pawn structure.}) 14... Rc8 {The position is equal, but more difficult for White to play. In both games in which this position was reached, Black was able to win.} ({A ) g3 Prepares h2-h4} 14... Qd5 {This not only prepares ...Rfd8 , but also sets up a hidden threat.   A1 )} 15. h4 Ngxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Rxe5 $6 {(Better is 18.Nxd4⩱ ) Rxc2 Black wins a pawn.} ({A2 )} 17. Nxd4 {Ngxe5! Rxe5 Nxd4 is close to equal, but the weak pawn on d3 still gives Black chances.   A3 ) Nce1?! The knight is not well-placed here. White should have captured d4 .} Rfd8 {The d4 -pawn is safely defended, while the e5 -pawn remains weak. Shimanov-Blomqvist .}) ({B )} 17. b3 $6 {White wants to continue attacking the d4 -pawn with B2 , but this underestimates Black's counterplay and weakens White's position. Qc7! B1 ) After Ncxd4 Ngxe5! Nxe5 Nxe5 Black wins back the pawn, because Bf4 can be answered with ( Rxe5? Qxc1+ Rxc1 Rxc1+ Qf1 Rxf1+ Kxf1 Rd8∓ ) Qc3⩱ .   B2 )} Ba3 {Rfd8 Bxe7 Ngxe7 Re1 Nxe5! Nxe5 Qxc2 Black converted the advantage into a full point. Cnejev-Vetokhin .})) *

