1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. Bd3 {The most popular continuation. The bishop is now on an active diagonal and has its sights on the black kingside. The drawback is that the bishop blocks the d-pawn, so White cannot develop the queenside so easily.} Bd7 {Black thus activates the light-squared bishop, which now finds a good diagonal on c6 and no longer has to wait behind its own pawn chain.} ({More often} 5... Nc6 {is played, e.g.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. Re1 Ng6 8. g3 {. The position seems a little more comfortable for White, because it is not clear how Black will develop the c8 -bishop.}) 6. O-O {The most natural move and White's most common choice.} Bc6 7. Re1 {The most common move. White prophylactically protects the e5 -pawn.} g5 {Black is threatening to win the knight on f3 with ... g5 - g4 , as it has no square to retreat to. Although Black has only developed one piece so far and has not yet brought their king to safety, the aggressive flank play is justified and dangerous for White.} ({The center is closed and the black king has nothing to fear for the time being. The game now becomes very sharp. The more solid alternative is} 7... Ne7 {. White can now try to weaken Black's control of d4 with} 8. b4 $5 {. After} cxb4 {(or 8...Ng6 )} 9. Nxd4 {a complicated position arises with chances for both sides.}) 8. b4 {White ignores the black threat and prepares b4 - b5 . The move involves a piece sacrifice.} g4 9. b5 Bd5 {Black does not accept the sacrifice and continues to play for an attack. It is better to first provoke c3 - c4 and only then take on f3 so that White can no longer capture on d4 .} ({Accepting the piece sacrifice with} 9... Bd7 {is possible, but leads to a very passive position for Black. In the blitz game Zhigalko-Yoo , after} 10. cxd4 gxf3 11. Qxf3 {Yoo continued with the 'reverse development'} Bc8 {, after which the black pieces are already set up for the next game! White has very good compensation for the piece.}) 10. c4 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nd7 {I like this better than the exchange on f3 , which allows the white queen to become active. Black prepares against White's impending attack on the b7 -pawn with Be4 .} 12. Be4 {This not only attacks the b7 -pawn, but also prepares the development of the queenside with d2 - d3 .} (12. fxg4 $2 h5 {is too dangerous for White. Soon the h- and g-file will open up and the white king will come under a strong attack.}) (12. f4 $2 {is not good either.} Qh4 13. Be4 d3 $1 {White was prepared to protect the f4 -pawn with d2-d3 and somewhat stabilize their position. This is now no longer possible. Black wants to build a strong kingside attack with ...Bh6xf4 . White cannot defend the pawn well, because after a bishop move followed by Re4 , Black could either drive away the rook with ...f7-f5 or strengthen the attack on f4 with ...Ne7-g6 . Black is clearly better.}) 12... Nxe5 {The position is very sharp. Black has the better chances because the white king is very vulnerable. The black attack can be strengthened further with ... gxf3 , ... Bd6 and ... Qh4 .} 13. Bxb7 {A logical continuation. Rook and knight are attacked.} Bd6 {Black can ignore the attack on the rook.} 14. Rxe5 ({This eliminates an attacker. White must not mix up the move order:} 14. Bxa8 $2 {loses after} Nd3 $3 {, as White is helpless against the imminent ...Qh4 , e.g.} 15. Qb3 Qh4 16. Qxd3 Qh3 $1 {and White has nothing better than} 17. f4 Qxd3 {.}) 14... Bxe5 15. Bxa8 Qxa8 16. d3 h5 {Even with the somewhat reduced material, Black retains good prospects on the kingside. ... Qb8 with an attack on the h2 -pawn is an unpleasant threat.} *

