treat to. Although Black has only developed one piece so far and has not yet brought their king to safety, the aggressive flank play is justified and dangerous for White.} ({The center is closed and the black king has nothing to fear for the time being. The game now becomes very sharp. The more solid alternative is} 7... Ne7 {. White can now try to weaken Black's control of d4 with} 8. b4 $5 {. After} cxb4 {(or 8...Ng6 )} 9. Nxd4 {a complicated position arises with chances for both sides.}) 8. h4 {This pawn sacrifice is anything but obvious and it is therefore not surprising that there are no practical examples yet. However, it is possibly the best move in the position – at least in Stockfish's opinion. With this move, White creates options for the f3 -knight.} g4 ({The decline of the pawn sacrifice presents White with the greatest difficulties. Where should the knight go? Even after} 8... h6 {White ensures that the position on the kingside remains closed:} 9. h5 $1) ({Black can also accept the sacrifice. After} 8... gxh4 9. cxd4 cxd4 10. Be4 {, however, White gets compensation for the pawn: the pawns on h4 and d4 are weak and Black is underdeveloped. An attack on the white king is also no longer realistic, because White can react to the attempt to open lines with} h3 {with} 11. g3 {and has nothing to fear.}) 9. Ng5 ({White must not shy away from the complications. The passive} 9. Nh2 h5 {leads to a very bad position for White. The h4 -pawn is attacked and after} 10. g3 {the knight on h2 is permanently excluded from the game and the e5 -pawn cannot be defended for much longer.}) 9... h6 10. Nxf7 ({Once again there is no turning back. After} 10. Ne4 $2 Nd7 $1 {∓, Black will soon win a pawn on e5 or h4 .}) 10... Kxf7 11. Qxg4 Ne7 ({Instead, it is also possible to play for a win with} 11... Ke7 $5 {However, Black will then need a long time to get their pieces onto good squares. The knight move is safer, because now Black is threatening 12...Rg8 with a consolidation of the position. White has nothing better than perpetual check.}) 12. Qh5+ Kg8 13. Qg4+ {Otherwise Black plays ...Bg7 , after which the king is safe.} Kf7 ({With a draw by repetition. The ambitious} 13... Bg7 $5 {leads to an unclear position after} 14. Qxe6+ Kf8 {.}) *

