1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 {The delayed Alapin Sicilian. The advantage of this move order for White is that Black has a smaller choice of defensive systems at their disposal, because ... e7 - e6 has already been played. Furthermore, White has the additional option 4.e5 , which we will deal with in this chapter.} d5 4. e5 ({This advance is quite popular, especially with White players who have the Advance Variation in their repertoire against the French ( e4 e6} 4. d4 {d5 ) .}) ({After Nc6} 4. d4 {a direct transition would be possible. With 4.e5 White gains space and would next like to fortify the pawn with d2-d4 . White would then have good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (4. exd5 {The most common move.} Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 {The classic Alapin Sicilian. We deal with it in chapter 1 via the move order e4} 6. dxc5 {c3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 d4 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 4... d4 {This prevents White from building a solid pawn chain in the center with d2-d4 . The pawn e5 is now cut off from protection by its peers and becomes vulnerable. White is now faced with the question of where to develop the f1 -bishop. The most popular squares are d3 and b5 . Recently, the development to g2 has become popular as well.} 5. Bd3 {The most popular continuation. The bishop is now on an active diagonal and has its sights on the black kingside. The drawback is that the bishop blocks the d-pawn, so White cannot develop the queenside so easily.} Bd7 {Black thus activates the light-squared bishop, which now finds a good diagonal on c6 and no longer has to wait behind its own pawn chain.} ({More often} 5... Nc6 {is played, e.g.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. Re1 Ng6 8. g3 {. The position seems a little more comfortable for White, because it is not clear how Black will develop the c8 -bishop.}) 6. O-O {The most natural move and White's most common choice.} Bc6 7. Re1 {The most common move. White prophylactically protects the e5 -pawn.} g5 {Black is threatening to win the knight on f3 with ... g5 - g4 , as it has no square to retreat to. Although Black has only developed one piece so far and has not yet brought their king to safety, the aggressive flank play is justified and dangerous for White.} ({The center is closed and the black king has nothing to fear for the time being. The game now becomes very sharp. The more solid alternative is} 7... Ne7 {. White can now try to weaken Black's control of d4 with} 8. b4 $5 {. After} cxb4 {(or 8...Ng6 )} 9. Nxd4 {a complicated position arises with chances for both sides.}) 8. h3 {A natural reaction and the most common choice in tournament practice. Nevertheless, the move is a mistake: it gives Black the pawn break ... g5 - g4 , which leads to a dangerous opening on the kingside.} h5 9. Nh2 {White takes control of the g4 -square and hopes to prevent ... g5 - g4 .} g4 {White's hopes were unfounded! Of course the g-pawn can be sacrificed to open files.} 10. hxg4 ({We looked at} 10. Na3 gxh3 {via the move order Na3} 11. g4 {Nh2 gxh3 .}) 10... Nh6 ({A novelty. Black prepares to capture on g4 . The obvious} 10... hxg4 {also leads to an advantage for Black, but after} 11. Qxg4 {the queen can then help with the defense, e.g.} dxc3 12. Be4 {, Quillan-Koneru 2012 .}) 11. gxh5 {The h-file remains closed for the time being, but now the g-file becomes White's problem child.} Qh4 {Black brings the queen closer to the action and at the same time prevents the Be4 defense. The threat is now ... Bxg2 or ... Rg8 , both with a deadly attack.} 12. Be2 {A sample line. White prepares Bf3 and covers the square g4 .} d3 (12... Bxg2 $2 13. Kxg2 Rg8+ 14. Kh1 {The bishop on e2 prevents ...Ng4 .}) 13. Bf3 (13. Bxd3 Bxg2 $1 14. Kxg2 Rg8+ 15. Kf1 ({(Now} 15. Kh1 $2 {no longer works; after:} Ng4 {White loses the queen or gets mated.)}) 15... Qxh2 {The white king should not survive the attack.}) 13... Nf5 {White has survived the direct attack, but otherwise there's no good news. The entire queenside doesn't participate in the game, the h-pawn will soon be lost, after which the h-file opens, and the e5 -pawn is weak. Black has a decisive advantage} *

