1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. Bg2 ({This usually transitions to the variations we examine after} 4. d3 {or exd5 .}) 4... Nf6 ({I think this is the simplest solution for our repertoire. White now mostly plays d3 , which we analyze via the move order d3} 4... Nf6 {Bg2 .}) ({exd5 exd5 is analyzed via the move order exd5 exd5 Bg2} 4... Nf6 {.   Alternatives for Black   White's move order has drawbacks which Black could try to exploit. One possibility is} 5. d4 {Nce2 and now} Nc6 {or d3!? cxd3 Nc6 .}) ({Another possibility is} 4... dxe4 {, which gives the position a more open character.}) 5. e5 {This possibility gives the move Bg2 independent value.} Nfd7 ({In the position after d3 Nf6 Bg2} 5... Nc6 6. f4 Be7 {e5 I recommend Ng8 with the idea ...h7-h5 and ...Nh6-f5 . Here the situation is different. White should after Ng8 not play f4 , but e.g.} 7. Nf3 {. Now e3 is not weakened and the c1 -bishop is not blocked by a pawn. This makes the black set-up weaker.}) 6. f4 {The white setup is a kind of mixture between the King's Indian Attack and the Grand Prix Attack. As in those systems, White wants to play on the kingside, while Black is stronger on the queenside.} Nc6 7. Nf3 Be7 8. O-O (8. d3 {would be inaccurate. Black can then play} b5 $1 {without preparation, because} 9. Nxb5 $2 {fails due to} Qa5+ 10. Nc3 d4 {.}) 8... O-O 9. d3 {Both sides have made the natural developing moves.} Rb8 ({Black should now prepare playing on the queenside. Equally possible would be} 9... a6 {.}) 10. a4 {This looks strongest. White can't stop ... b7 - b5 , but with the text move White can open the a-file for the a1 -rook.} a6 11. Ne2 {The most common move. White brings the knight to the kingside.} b5 12. axb5 axb5 13. g4 ({White clears the g3 -square for the knight. After} 13. d4 {Black gets a good position with} b4 {followed by ...Qb6 and ...Ba6 .}) (13. c3 {can also be answered with} b4 {, or} 14. d4 $5 {which leads to promising complications.}) 13... b4 ({Black gains space on the queenside. Next the bishop can be activated with ...Qb6 and ...Ba6 . The position is complicated but equal. A good alternative is} 13... Bb7 14. Ng3 Ra8 {.  The game might continue with Ng3} ({Or} 14... g5 {Qb6} 15. h4 Ba6 {followed by ...Ra8 or ...b3 .}) {Qb6} 15. Kh1 Ba6 {Black now wants to play ...b4-b3 to undermine the protection of the d3 -pawn. In the game Barnes-Commons ,} 16. Re1 {(White prepares f4-f5 ) Ra8} ({(} 16. b3 {c3 Ra8= )}) 16... f5 {followed and now Black's play can be strengthened with} 17. b3 {c3} Bb7 18. Rxa8 {Rxa8 . Black wants to play ...d5-d4 and achieve good counterplay in the center as well as on the queenside.}) *

