1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. d3 {White keeps the position closed. The white setup is reminiscent of the King's Indian Attack, but there the knight goes to d2 and not to c3 .} Nf6 ({A drawback of White's way of playing is that Black can attack the c3 -knight with ...d5-d4 . But I prefer to wait with this. After} 4... d4 {comes} 5. Nce2 {. However, the e2 -square is usually used to develop the g1 -knight. This means that White must either choose a different kingside setup or capture on d5 before developing the king's knight to give the c3 -knight an additional square on e4 .}) 5. Bg2 Nc6 {After both sides have executed the natural developing moves, it is now up to White to decide the character of the battle.} 6. f4 {White opts for a kind of mixture of the Grand Prix and King's Indian attacks.} Be7 {Alternatively, Black could also relieve the tension by exchanging on e4 and thus obtain a slightly more open position.} 7. e5 ({The most common move. White closes the center in order to be able to prepare an attack on the kingside. Possibly} 7. Nf3 {is the better choice, but also after that Black has no problems, e.g.} d4 8. Ne2 b5 {with promising play on the queenside.}) 7... Ng8 ({Much more often the more natural} 7... Nd7 {is played, which also leads to a good position for Black, e.g.} 8. Nf3 b5 $1 {. 7...Ng8 looks even better, however, because the knight can be brought via h6 to f5 , where it is very strong.}) 8. Nf3 h5 {This preparatory move is needed so that the knight is not driven away with g3 - g4 when it lands on f5 .} 9. h3 {A sample line. We follow the game Abramovic-Velimirovic . White prevents a possible further advance of the black h-pawn with 9.h3 , because then White can keep the position closed with g3 - g4 . If necessary, White could also drive away the knight on f5 with g3 - g4 . After other moves, Black also brings the knight to f5 and is slightly better.} Nh6 10. Ne2 {The g3 -pawn would have soon needed protection anyway. In addition, White plans c2 - c3 and d3 - d4 .} Nf5 11. c3 ({Black also has an advantage after} 11. g4 Nh4 {.}) 11... b6 ({This move deviates from the Abramovic-Velimirovic game mentioned earlier, where} 11... b5 {was played. Although Black was still better in that game, Velimirovic was eventually outplayed and lost. The move b6 offers two advantages over b5 : first, it allows the bishop to develop to a6 , where it has a clear view, making it difficult for White to play d3-d4 . Second, Black retains the option to castle long, which would be less safe with the pawn on b5 . I don't see any counterplay for White – Black is better.}) *

