1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. d3 {White keeps the position closed. The white setup is reminiscent of the King's Indian Attack, but there the knight goes to d2 and not to c3 .} Nf6 ({A drawback of White's way of playing is that Black can attack the c3 -knight with ...d5-d4 . But I prefer to wait with this. After} 4... d4 {comes} 5. Nce2 {. However, the e2 -square is usually used to develop the g1 -knight. This means that White must either choose a different kingside setup or capture on d5 before developing the king's knight to give the c3 -knight an additional square on e4 .}) 5. Bg2 Nc6 {After both sides have executed the natural developing moves, it is now up to White to decide the character of the battle.} 6. exd5 {White thus counteracts ... d5 - d4 , because the knight can now move to e4 . Moreover, White can later try to put pressure on the black center.} exd5 7. Nge2 ({White continues development. The knight could later move to f4 and increase the pressure on the d5 -pawn. In comparison with} 7. Nge2 {the knight has a flight square on e4 here.}) 7... d4 ({Sooner or later Black will have to play this anyway. Here it has the advantage that one of the white knights is exchanged. Also good is} 7... Be7 {, which will likely transpose to the line starting with 7.Bg5 after a few moves, e.g.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 ({(After} 9. Nf4 {,} Bg4 $1 10. Qd2 d4 11. Ncd5 Ne5 {is strong.)}) ({(White could isolate the black d-pawn with} 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {, but this is not to be feared either, because Black gets good activity, e.g.} Bg4 11. Qd3 Qd7 {.)}) 9... d4 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Ne4 Be7 {.}) 8. Ne4 Nxe4 9. dxe4 {This gives White a little more space for the queen, but on the other hand the pawn on e4 blocks the bishop's view. Another drawback of changing the pawn structure is that the black pawns become mobile. Black could later play ... c5 - c4 and ... d4 - d3 to create a passed pawn.} h5 {Stockfish evaluates the position as giving Black a clear advantage after this move. While it may not be that obvious, Black can certainly be satisfied with the outcome of the opening. Black is now threatening to move the pawn further forward and open up the h-file. Since White normally castles short, this would put White's king in danger. White will therefore probably stop the pawn's advance.} 10. h3 (10. h4 {has the drawback that White can no longer control the g4 -square with the h-pawn.} Bg4 {The pin is quite unpleasant, so White will probably play f2-f3 sooner or later. This makes the g2 -bishop even more passive and weakens the g3 -pawn. Black is slightly better. A good plan is to win space ...c5-c4 , after which ...d4-d3 is also a possibility.}) 10... g5 ({A novelty and a motif we will see more often throughout the course. Black takes control of the f4 -square, condemning the white minor pieces to passivity. The insertion of} 10... h4 11. g4 g5 {is weaker, because after} 12. f4 {the black position is less stable. The g5 -pawn requires protection and after} f6 {, e4-e5 is a possible motif. As we will see later, it is important not to fix the pawn structure, because the pawns on g5 and h5 have great dynamic potential.}) 11. f4 ({White tries to liberate their minor pieces. An alternative is} 11. O-O Be6 {and only now} 12. f4 {. Here Black best reacts with} g4 {.} 13. f5 {will now be met with} Bc4 {. With ...Bd6 or ...Ne5 Black then develops strong play on the dark squares.}) ({If White opts for} 11. h4 {, Black plays} f5 $1 {. It is not clear how White should activate the knight and the bishop on c1 . Black is clearly better.}) 11... c4 ({Now the white king is the target!} 11... g4 $2 12. f5 {is not good here. White is threatening hxg4 and the c8 -bishop is passive.}) 12. O-O ({White castles before it's too late. However, the king is not yet safe. After} 12. fxg5 Bc5 {the white king finds no refuge.} 13. O-O {is answered with} d3+ {.}) 12... Bc5 {... d4 - d3 + is threatening to win a piece.} 13. Kh2 Bxh3 {This spectacular piece sacrifice is the punch line of Black's play. White cannot keep the kingside closed.} 14. Bxh3 g4 {Black is not only threatening to win back the piece, but also ... h5 - h4 with a deadly attack along the h-file.} 15. Bd2 ({White should give back the piece and reinforce the kingside. After} 15. Bg2 $2 h4 {Black has a mating attack. The threat is 16...hxg3+  17.Kxg3  Qh4# . White can cover the h4 -square with} 16. Rh1 {, but then Black calmly spins a mating net with} d3 {. The threat is ...Bf2 and ...hxg3# . After} 17. Qe1 Qb6 {, once again threatening ...Bf2 ,} 18. Rf1 dxe2 19. Qxe2 Bg1+ $1 20. Rxg1 hxg3+ 21. Kxg3 Qxg1 {would be a possible finale.}) 15... gxh3 ({Sufficient for a clear advantage, although it might be even stronger to wait, for example with} 15... Qf6 $5 {or the prophylactic Bb6!? , which takes the punch out of the counterattack 16.b2-b4 .}) ({After} 15... gxh3 {, Black wants to prepare ...O-O-O and then open the position with ...d4-d3 . White must now find} 16. b4 $1 {to stay in the game at all.}) ({After} 15... h4 {things are not so clear. White defends with} 16. Bxg4 hxg3+ 17. Kxg3 Qh4+ 18. Kf3 d3 19. Be1 $1 {.}) *

