ifferent white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. d3 {White keeps the position closed. The white setup is reminiscent of the King's Indian Attack, but there the knight goes to d2 and not to c3 .} Nf6 ({A drawback of White's way of playing is that Black can attack the c3 -knight with ...d5-d4 . But I prefer to wait with this. After} 4... d4 {comes} 5. Nce2 {. However, the e2 -square is usually used to develop the g1 -knight. This means that White must either choose a different kingside setup or capture on d5 before developing the king's knight to give the c3 -knight an additional square on e4 .}) 5. Bg2 Nc6 {After both sides have executed the natural developing moves, it is now up to White to decide the character of the battle.} 6. exd5 {White thus counteracts ... d5 - d4 , because the knight can now move to e4 . Moreover, White can later try to put pressure on the black center.} exd5 7. Nge2 ({White continues development. The knight could later move to f4 and increase the pressure on the d5 -pawn. In comparison with} 7. Nge2 {the knight has a flight square on e4 here.}) 7... d4 ({Sooner or later Black will have to play this anyway. Here it has the advantage that one of the white knights is exchanged. Also good is} 7... Be7 {, which will likely transpose to the line starting with 7.Bg5 after a few moves, e.g.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 ({(After} 9. Nf4 {,} Bg4 $1 10. Qd2 d4 11. Ncd5 Ne5 {is strong.)}) ({(White could isolate the black d-pawn with} 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {, but this is not to be feared either, because Black gets good activity, e.g.} Bg4 11. Qd3 Qd7 {.)}) 9... d4 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Ne4 Be7 {.}) 8. Ne4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 ({In the line starting with} 9. Bg5 {, we will deal with a similar position, but in which White has exchanged the dark-squared bishop for the knight. Here the c1 -bishop remains quite passive, as the f4 -square is reserved for the knight.}) 9... Bd6 {The bishop is more active here than on e7 . In addition, Black wants to place the rook on the e-file later, where the bishop on e7 would only interfere. Black need not fear the exchange on c6 , because then the light squares on the kingside would be without a defender.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Nf4 {White activates the knight, which was passive on e2 .} Re8 {The black position is already somewhat more comfortable. A typical idea is ... Ne5 followed by ... Bg4 , after which White would have to play the weakening f2 - f3 . Therefore White usually reacts to ... Ne5 with h2 - h3 , which also weakens the king's position. Black could exchange the light-squared bishops with ... Bd7 - c6 and then attack the king's position on the light squares with queen and knight.} *

