1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. d3 {White keeps the position closed. The white setup is reminiscent of the King's Indian Attack, but there the knight goes to d2 and not to c3 .} Nf6 ({A drawback of White's way of playing is that Black can attack the c3 -knight with ...d5-d4 . But I prefer to wait with this. After} 4... d4 {comes} 5. Nce2 {. However, the e2 -square is usually used to develop the g1 -knight. This means that White must either choose a different kingside setup or capture on d5 before developing the king's knight to give the c3 -knight an additional square on e4 .}) 5. Bg2 Nc6 {After both sides have executed the natural developing moves, it is now up to White to decide the character of the battle.} 6. exd5 {White thus counteracts ... d5 - d4 , because the knight can now move to e4 . Moreover, White can later try to put pressure on the black center.} exd5 7. Bg5 {Threatening Nxd5 . White wants to force the d5 -pawn to move, because that would extend the g2 -bishop's operating radius.} Be7 ({After the less accurate} 7... d4 {, White would have additional options, e.g.} 8. Qe2+ $1 {(or Nd5 )} Be6 9. Bxf6 {. Black must now recapture with the pawn, because} Qxf6 $2 {leads to a very bad position after} 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Nf4 $1 {.}) 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nxd5 ({The pawn exchange brings White nothing.} 9. Nge2 d4 10. Ne4 {would go on to Nge2 d4 Bxf6 Bxf6 Ne4 . Of course not Bxd5?? Bxc3+ bxc3} Qd5 {.}) 9... Bxb2 10. Rb1 ({The intermediate check} 10. Qe2+ $2 {only benefits Black:} Be6 11. Rb1 Nd4 $1 12. Qe4 {The queen must maintain the pin of the bishop.} Qa5+ 13. Kf1 Qxa2 {Black is a pawn up and has the better position. After a rook move 14...O-O follows.}) 10... Be5 {With the bishop pair Black has slightly better prospects. Cordovil-Kurajica} *

