ifferent white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. d3 {White keeps the position closed. The white setup is reminiscent of the King's Indian Attack, but there the knight goes to d2 and not to c3 .} Nf6 ({A drawback of White's way of playing is that Black can attack the c3 -knight with ...d5-d4 . But I prefer to wait with this. After} 4... d4 {comes} 5. Nce2 {. However, the e2 -square is usually used to develop the g1 -knight. This means that White must either choose a different kingside setup or capture on d5 before developing the king's knight to give the c3 -knight an additional square on e4 .}) 5. Bg2 Nc6 {After both sides have executed the natural developing moves, it is now up to White to decide the character of the battle.} 6. exd5 {White thus counteracts ... d5 - d4 , because the knight can now move to e4 . Moreover, White can later try to put pressure on the black center.} exd5 7. Bg5 {Threatening Nxd5 . White wants to force the d5 -pawn to move, because that would extend the g2 -bishop's operating radius.} Be7 ({After the less accurate} 7... d4 {, White would have additional options, e.g.} 8. Qe2+ $1 {(or Nd5 )} Be6 9. Bxf6 {. Black must now recapture with the pawn, because} Qxf6 $2 {leads to a very bad position after} 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Nf4 $1 {.}) 8. Nge2 d4 ({Black cannot avoid this move. After} 8... O-O {White still cannot win the pawn under favorable conditions, because} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Bxd5 Bg4 {gives Black very strong play. However, White can continue with} 11. O-O {instead and keep up the pressure against d5 .}) 9. Bxf6 ({White has to part with the bishop pair so that the knight can remain active. After} 9. Ne4 $6 Nxe4 10. Bxe7 {Black can win a pawn with} Qa5+ {or Nxf2 .}) 9... Bxf6 10. Nd5 {Here the knight is worse than on e4 , because the e2 -knight now has no good prospects.} O-O 11. O-O Be5 {One of many good moves. Black has the bishop pair and a space advantage and is therefore a little better.} *

