1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. d3 {White keeps the position closed. The white setup is reminiscent of the King's Indian Attack, but there the knight goes to d2 and not to c3 .} Nf6 ({A drawback of White's way of playing is that Black can attack the c3 -knight with ...d5-d4 . But I prefer to wait with this. After} 4... d4 {comes} 5. Nce2 {. However, the e2 -square is usually used to develop the g1 -knight. This means that White must either choose a different kingside setup or capture on d5 before developing the king's knight to give the c3 -knight an additional square on e4 .}) 5. Bg2 Nc6 {After both sides have executed the natural developing moves, it is now up to White to decide the character of the battle.} 6. exd5 {White thus counteracts ... d5 - d4 , because the knight can now move to e4 . Moreover, White can later try to put pressure on the black center.} exd5 7. Bg5 {Threatening Nxd5 . White wants to force the d5 -pawn to move, because that would extend the g2 -bishop's operating radius.} Be7 ({After the less accurate} 7... d4 {, White would have additional options, e.g.} 8. Qe2+ $1 {(or Nd5 )} Be6 9. Bxf6 {. Black must now recapture with the pawn, because} Qxf6 $2 {leads to a very bad position after} 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Nf4 $1 {.}) 8. Nge2 d4 ({Black cannot avoid this move. After} 8... O-O {White still cannot win the pawn under favorable conditions, because} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Bxd5 Bg4 {gives Black very strong play. However, White can continue with} 11. O-O {instead and keep up the pressure against d5 .}) 9. Bxf6 ({White has to part with the bishop pair so that the knight can remain active. After} 9. Ne4 $6 Nxe4 10. Bxe7 {Black can win a pawn with} Qa5+ {or Nxf2 .}) 9... Bxf6 10. Ne4 Be7 11. Nf4 ({The knight can later go to d5 , and White also clears the way for the queen. Or} 11. O-O O-O 12. Nf4 {.}) 11... O-O 12. O-O Re8 {Black wants to continue with ... Bf8 so that the rook can work on the e-file.} 13. Qh5 ({White is threatening to develop an attack with Rae1 or Nd5 . Black's reply is therefore forced. After} 13. Re1 Bf8 {Black has no worries either.}) 13... g6 14. Qd5 {The queen is impressive here, but White has no threats.} Bf5 {The position is equal. Black can continue with ... Rc8 and ... Kg7 , or drive away the white queen with ... Qc7 and ... Red8 . We have been following the 23rd game of the 1992 Fischer-Spassky rematch. I have annotated the remainder of this tense fight in the Model Games chapter .} *

