1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. exd5 {The exchange is quite logical here. White will later move the bishop to g2 and it will not be blocked by its own pawn on e4 . On the other hand, this also allows the c8 -bishop to develop freely.} exd5 5. Bg2 {The most common move. White continues development and attacks the d5 -pawn. Transpositions to the lines after 4.d3 are very likely here.} Nf6 6. Nge2 (6. d3 {is played more often. White wants to play Bg5 and thus further increase the pressure on d5 .} Nc6 {The alternatives} 7. d4 {and} Be7 {are also playable and lead to similar play. We have now landed in a position which we have examined more closely via the move order d3 Nf6 Bg2 Nc6 exd5 exd5 .}) (6. d4 {no longer works so well here.} cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 {We deal with this position via the move order d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nf6 Bg2 Nc6 .}) 6... d4 ({Instead, Black can also play} 6... Nc6 {, which after} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bg4 {leads to a position that I analyze via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 Nge2} 9. Nxc6 {g3 d5 exd5 exd5} d4 {cxd4} 10. Nxd4 {Nf6 Bg2 Bg4 and which was already subject of my first course on the Four Knights Sicilian. However, this position is not part of the Kan repertoire, so here I give the alternative 6...d4 .}) 7. Ne4 Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Bd6 ({We will soon end up in the line} 8... d3 {Nf6} 9. Bg2 Nc6 {exd5 exd5 Nge2 d4 Ne4 Nxe4} 10. Be4 Bd6 {.}) *

