1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. exd5 {The exchange is quite logical here. White will later move the bishop to g2 and it will not be blocked by its own pawn on e4 . On the other hand, this also allows the c8 -bishop to develop freely.} exd5 5. d4 {This prevents the black d-pawn from advancing and establishes it as a weakness. The game now becomes very concrete.} cxd4 {In this exchange Black benefits from the fact that White has to capture with the queen, which can later be attacked with ... Nc6 .} 6. Qxd4 Nf6 {First the d5 -pawn must be defended.} 7. Bg2 {After this, White is forced back.} Nc6 8. Qd1 ({The queen is worse on a4 because it does not defend the king. This has been known for over a hundred years, as the following miniature illustrates.} 8. Qa4 $6 d4 ({(Also good is} 8... Bd7 {.)}) 9. Nb5 $2 ({(Necessary was} 9. Nce2 d3 10. cxd3 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 Bd7 {. Kobaidze-Alexandria .)}) 9... Bb4+ 10. Bd2 $2 ({(} 10. c3 O-O $1 {gives Black a deadly attack.)}) 10... Bxd2+ 11. Kxd2 O-O {-+ The difference in king safety decides.} 12. Ne2 Qb6 13. Rhf1 Bd7 14. Nbxd4 Na5 $1 {( Walbrodt-Janowski .)}) 8... d4 9. Nce2 ({Relatively best. After} 9. Ne4 $2 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Bb4+ {White loses the castling right.} 11. Bd2 {is met with} Qe7 12. Qe2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 O-O {-+ .}) 9... Bc5 {Sooner or later the d-pawn should be defended and the bishop is well placed here anyway.} 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Bf5 {Black is fully mobilized and has the more active pieces. Specifically, ... d4 - d3 is a threat. In the long term, Black can put pressure on the c2 -pawn or fight for control of the e-file. Black's position deserves preference. Suttles-Tal} *

