1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. exd5 {The exchange is quite logical here. White will later move the bishop to g2 and it will not be blocked by its own pawn on e4 . On the other hand, this also allows the c8 -bishop to develop freely.} exd5 5. d4 {This prevents the black d-pawn from advancing and establishes it as a weakness. The game now becomes very concrete.} cxd4 {In this exchange Black benefits from the fact that White has to capture with the queen, which can later be attacked with ... Nc6 .} 6. Qxd4 Nf6 {First the d5 -pawn must be defended.} 7. Bg5 {White is threatening to capture on f6 and thus increases the pressure on the d5 -pawn.} Nc6 ({Black answers the attack with a counterattack. The alternative} 7... Be7 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. Qa4 {is somewhat more passive.}) 8. Bxf6 {This doesn't work, but without support of an engine this assessment is not obvious.} Nxd4 9. Bxd8 Nxc2+ 10. Kd2 Nxa1 {At the end of this forced line Black is an exchange and a pawn up, but the knight is trapped on a1 . It is less obvious that the White's dark-squared bishop is also in danger.} 11. Bg5 {In practice, this has always been played. White has good results, but Black has never found the correct continuation.} d4 12. Nd5 {The alternatives are worse. From d5 the knight is not only threatening a fork on c7 , but also prevents Black from bringing the bishop to b4 .} f6 13. Bf4 g5 ({This lures the white pieces to less safe squares. Instead,} 13... Kf7 {is also strong.}) 14. Nxf6+ ({After} 14. Bc7 {the bishop occupies the square intended for the knight. Black wins with} Be6 15. Nxf6+ ({(or} 15. Bc4 Rc8 {)}) 15... Kf7 16. Ne4 Bxa2 {. The knight can then be brought to safety via b3 .}) 14... Kf7 15. Bxg5 Bb4+ {First the king is forced onto a worse square.} 16. Kd1 Be7 ({The true target square for the bishop. Black wins material.  It is no use for White to leave the pin with Ne4 , because after} 16... Bf5 {two pieces are attacked. Additionally, the f5 -bishop supports the knight on a1 , which can come back via c2 in some lines.}) *

