1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. exd5 {The exchange is quite logical here. White will later move the bishop to g2 and it will not be blocked by its own pawn on e4 . On the other hand, this also allows the c8 -bishop to develop freely.} exd5 5. d4 {This prevents the black d-pawn from advancing and establishes it as a weakness. The game now becomes very concrete.} cxd4 {In this exchange Black benefits from the fact that White has to capture with the queen, which can later be attacked with ... Nc6 .} 6. Qxd4 Nf6 {First the d5 -pawn must be defended.} 7. Bg5 {White is threatening to capture on f6 and thus increases the pressure on the d5 -pawn.} Nc6 ({Black answers the attack with a counterattack. The alternative} 7... Be7 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. Qa4 {is somewhat more passive.}) 8. Bxf6 {This doesn't work, but without support of an engine this assessment is not obvious.} Nxd4 9. Bxd8 Nxc2+ 10. Kd2 Nxa1 {At the end of this forced line Black is an exchange and a pawn up, but the knight is trapped on a1 . It is less obvious that the White's dark-squared bishop is also in danger.} 11. Bc7 {Relatively best.} d4 12. Nd5 f6 {On the one hand, Black gets the f7 -square for the king, on the other the square e5 is protected. Why this is important will become clear later. Black is now threatening ...Be6 or ...Bf5 , liberating the a1 -knight.} ({After} 12... Be6 $6 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7 15. Ne2 {the a1 -knight is lost. Black does not manage to win a piece here, because} Nc2 $5 16. Kxc2 Kc6 17. Nef4 g5 {is met by} 18. Be5 {.}) 13. Bb5+ Bd7 (13... Kf7 $2 14. Ne2 {Here the white pieces are safe.}) 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7 15. Ne2 {White wins the a1 -knight, but the line is not over yet.} Nc2 {First of all the king is forced to move to the c-file.} 16. Kxc2 Kc6 17. Nef4 g5 {All white minor pieces are attacked. Only now does the purpose of f6 become clear: if the pawn were still on f7 , White could attack the rook on h8 with 18.Be5 and preserve the material balance.} 18. Nxf6 Bg7 ({This is more accurate than} 18... Kxc7 {. Once again all the white minor pieces are under attack. Black will be left with an extra exchange and good winning chances. This line was suggested by GM Harikrishna in Lifetime Repertoire: Taimanov Sicilian on Chessable.}) *

