{In the game Perez Guerra-Materia, 2022, there followed Bxd5 Rfd8 ( 15...Qxc3= ) Bxc6 ( 16.Bh1= ) bxc6 Qc4 Rd5 Black has play against the opponent's weak pawns and the king, which outweighs the minus pawn. Rac1 Rad8 Kf1 Rd2 Qf4 Qxf4 gxf4 .  In this endgame, Black has the slightly better chances as all of White's pawns are weak. Objectively it should be a draw, but White was unable to solve the problems they faced at the board.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. exd5 {The exchange is quite logical here. White will later move the bishop to g2 and it will not be blocked by its own pawn on e4 . On the other hand, this also allows the c8 -bishop to develop freely.} exd5 5. d4 {This prevents the black d-pawn from advancing and establishes it as a weakness. The game now becomes very concrete.} cxd4 {In this exchange Black benefits from the fact that White has to capture with the queen, which can later be attacked with ... Nc6 .} 6. Qxd4 Nf6 {First the d5 -pawn must be defended.} 7. Bg5 {White is threatening to capture on f6 and thus increases the pressure on the d5 -pawn.} Nc6 ({Black answers the attack with a counterattack. The alternative} 7... Be7 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. Qa4 {is somewhat more passive.}) 8. Qa4 {White wants to continue with long castling and put pressure on the d-pawn.} Bb4 ({This is the advantage of Nc6 over} 8... Be7 {. The bishop can be developed more actively.}) 9. Nge2 {White defends against ... Bxc3 , because now the knight can recapture. Long castling is a threat once again.} Bg4 {Black's counterplay comes in time. If White castles now, the knight on e2 would be pinned.} 10. Bg2 {White increases the pressure on d5 and prepares castling short.} (10. O-O-O {is answered with} Bxc3 11. bxc3 Bf3 12. Rg1 O-O {. White now preserves equal chances with} 13. Qf4 $1 Be4 14. Bxf6 gxf6 {.}) 10... Bxe2 {Black exploits the fact that the knight c3 is pinned.} 11. Kxe2 Bxc3 {The second knight is also exchanged. Black thus reduces the pressure on the d5 -pawn and creates targets for attack in the white pawn structure.} 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Rhe1 {White develops the rook so that the king can go back to f1 without trapping the rook.} ({After} 13. Rhd1 Qe8+ {followed by ...Ne4 is best.}) 13... h6 14. Bxf6 {White should get rid of the bishop pair. If the bishop retreats instead, ... Ne4 follows and Black has the initiative.} Qxf6 {The pawns c3 and d5 are weak and may soon be exchanged for each other. The open files make further exchanges likely. The position is equal.} *

