1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian. White thus signals the intention of a quiet fight. As there is typically no direct confrontation in the center, both sides can often develop their pieces without enemy interference. The Closed Sicilian is particularly popular in amateur chess: White avoids the excess of theory that comes with the Open Sicilian. At professional level, on the other hand, it is used less frequently, as Black can achieve a good game with simple means.} (2. Nc3 {is a very flexible move. White can subsequently also play the Grand Prix Attack or the King's Indian Attack, which we will look at in separate chapters.}) {We should pay particular attention to possible transitions to the Open Sicilian so that we don't end up in unfamiliar territory.} 2... e6 ({Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . At the same time we are now ready for transitions to the Open Sicilian after Nf3 or Nge2 followed by d2-d4 . In this chapter, we will look at the move . White's alternatives are covered elsewhere:  ➤ Nf3 is examined via the move order Nf3} 2... e6 {. White 'threatens' the transition to the Open Sicilian, so I offer several alternative answers.  ➤ The situation is similar with the move . Since Black has to be ready for the Open Sicilian, I give several alternatives, which can be found in separate chapters.  ➤ We will deal with} 3. f4 {in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .  ➤ d3 brings us to the chapter on the King's Indian Attack .  ➤ We examine Bc4 via the move order e4 c5 Bc4 e6 Nc3 in this chapter .  ➤ Finally, d4 is covered in the chapter on the early Qxd4 .}) 3. g3 {The most popular move. White plans to develop the bishop to g2 . It didn't have any active prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal because the light-squared positioning of the black pawns would have limited its effect.} d5 {This central advance runs like a common thread through this repertoire, and I recommend it whenever possible. The uniform approach makes it easier to play against the different white setups. Black shouldn't wait here, because otherwise, White would take control of the d5 -square with Bg2 . The pawn will often move on to d4 and attack the knight on c3 . If White does not exchange on d5 , Black can also consider capturing on e4 .} 4. exd5 {The exchange is quite logical here. White will later move the bishop to g2 and it will not be blocked by its own pawn on e4 . On the other hand, this also allows the c8 -bishop to develop freely.} exd5 5. d4 {This prevents the black d-pawn from advancing and establishes it as a weakness. The game now becomes very concrete.} cxd4 {In this exchange Black benefits from the fact that White has to capture with the queen, which can later be attacked with ... Nc6 .} 6. Qxd4 Nf6 {First the d5 -pawn must be defended.} 7. Bg5 {White is threatening to capture on f6 and thus increases the pressure on the d5 -pawn.} Nc6 ({Black answers the attack with a counterattack. The alternative} 7... Be7 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. Qa4 {is somewhat more passive.}) 8. Bb5 {The most popular move. White is now threatening to win the pawn with Bxf6 and Qxd5 .} Be7 {A useful developing move, which at the same time fends off the white threat. Black wants to castle next and thus renew the attack against the white queen.} 9. O-O-O {This natural move already allows Black to gain the upper hand.} O-O {The knight is now no longer pinned and White must react to the attack against the queen.} 10. Qa4 (10. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 {not only strengthens Black's position in the center, but also gives Black attacking chances on the b-file.}) ({Not much better is} 10. Qd2 a6 {, e.g.} 11. Bd3 d4 {, which gives Black a strong attack on the queenside.}) 10... a6 ({An improvement on the previously played} 10... Be6 {, where Black is only slightly better. With a6 Black sacrifices a pawn to open files against the white king.}) 11. Bxf6 ({Not the best, but there is no good defense left for White anyway. After} 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qxc6 Bd7 13. Qb7 Rb8 14. Qxa6 Ne4 {all files on the queenside are open. White should not be able to withstand the attack for long.}) 11... Bxf6 12. Nxd5 axb5 13. Qxa8 ({The intermediate check} 13. Nxf6+ {is of no use, because after} Qxf6 14. Qxa8 Bg4 {Black wins material.}) 13... Bd4 {The only winning move! Now the knight d5 is under attack and the queen on a8 is in danger.} 14. Ne3 ({Or} 14. Nc3 Qb6 {White's queen is not safe, because} 15. Qa3 {is met with the fork} b4 {.}) 14... Bxe3+ 15. fxe3 Qxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Bg4+ 17. Kd2 Rxa8 {Black is left with an extra piece.} *

