1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. f4 {The most direct route to the Grand Prix Attack. White keeps the positions of the f1 -bishop and the b1 -knight flexible.} d5 {The attack in the center is a well-established response, ensuring that White cannot develop the kingside undisturbed.} 3. e5 {This would be better if Black had prepared their play in the center with ... e7 - e6 , as in the French Defense. Since this is not the case here, Black can develop the bishop outside the pawn chain.} Nc6 {By developing the knight, Black controls d4 and avoids committing to a square for the light-squared bishop just yet.} 4. Nf3 Bg4 (4... Bf5 {is also playable, bu the advantage of the text move is that the f5 -square can be used by the knight. The following moves are a sample line. While White has tried various set-ups in practice, they do not alter the general positional assessment: Black's play is simple and good.}) 5. Be2 {The most common move. White unpins the knight and prepares castling. Other moves don't pose any problems for Black either.} e6 6. O-O Nh6 ({This is a little more flexible than} 6... Nge7 {, after which the bishop f8 would be blocked. In any case, the knight wants to go to f5 .}) 7. c3 {With this move, White controls d4 and prepares the maneuver Na3 - c2 . It's not so easy to develop the queenside.} Nf5 {Together with its colleague on c6 , the knight prevents White from playing d2 - d4 .} 8. Na3 h5 {A typical move that serves to fortify the knight on f5 . White will probably play h2 - h3 later, forcing the exchange on f3 . Then g2 - g4 would be an option. This is no longer possible with a black pawn on h5 or even h4 . There are also attacking ideas in connection with opening up the h-file.} 9. Nc2 c4 {The bishop will be developed to c5 . Black has the more active play and is slightly better.} ({The following sample line demonstrates the dangers of White's position: d3 White wants to develop the queenside. cxd3 Bxd3 ( Qxd3 Bc5+ is worse.) Bc5+ Kh1} 9... Ng3 $5 {The piece sacrifice gives Black a dangerous attack against White's king.} 10. hxg3 h4 {Be3 White prepares the monarch's escape. Bxe3} 11. Ne3 hxg3 {Kg1 Bxf3 . Rxf3 Qh4 Kf1} {(After gxf3?? Qh4 mate cannot be prevented.)} 12. d4 {. White should now give back the piece, but the king is not yet safe.}) *

