1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. f4 {The most direct route to the Grand Prix Attack. White keeps the positions of the f1 -bishop and the b1 -knight flexible.} d5 {The attack in the center is a well-established response, ensuring that White cannot develop the kingside undisturbed.} 3. Bb5+ {White brings out the bishop. Then d2 - d3 can follow without the bishop being trapped behind the pawn chain.} Bd7 ({The pawn sacrifice} 3... Nd7 {is an interesting alternative.}) 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. e5 {Again, the advance is a positional mistake, but it has been played in half of the games that have reached this position on Lichess. Black now has good control over the light squares and the potential pawn break ... f7 -f6 . In addition, the c1 -bishop is condemned to passivity.} Nc6 6. Nf3 e6 7. O-O ({Weak is} 7. d4 $6 Nxd4 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 Rc8 {, after which White's queenside comes under pressure while the kingside is also endangered.}) 7... h5 {A typical move in the present pawn structure which pursues two goals:   ➤ Control of the square f5 is secured by preventing g2-g4 . Soon the knight will find itself on the outpost square.   ➤ The h-pawn can advance further. If it reaches h3 , it endangers the white king's security. If White stops the advance with h2 - h3 , the g3 -square is weakened, which in turn benefits a black knight on f5 .} 8. c3 {A sample line. White prepares d2 - d4 .} Nh6 {The knight is on its way to f5 . Compared to the route via e7 this has the advantage that the bishop on f8 is not blocked.} 9. d4 ({Consistent, but it would be better for White to keep the position as closed as possible. However, Black is already better after other moves as well. For example} 9. d3 Be7 10. Qe2 h4 {(or 10...Nf5⩱ )} 11. Bd2 h3 12. g3 b5 {. The pawn on h3 ensures that the white king can never feel completely safe, as mating motifs arise when the position is opened.}) 9... Nf5 {The d4 -pawn comes under pressure. Black could reinforce the attack with ... Qc7 - b6 .} 10. Na3 {White wants to support the d4 -point with Nc2 . This doesn't work, but the white position is already almost impossible to hold.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Bxa3 12. bxa3 Rc8 {Black takes control of the c-file. The pressure can be increased with ... O-O , ... Nce7 , ... Rc4 and .... Rfc8 . White has no counterplay and should lose.} *

