1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. f4 {The most direct route to the Grand Prix Attack. White keeps the positions of the f1 -bishop and the b1 -knight flexible.} d5 {The attack in the center is a well-established response, ensuring that White cannot develop the kingside undisturbed.} 3. Bb5+ {White brings out the bishop. Then d2 - d3 can follow without the bishop being trapped behind the pawn chain.} Bd7 ({The pawn sacrifice} 3... Nd7 {is an interesting alternative.}) 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. d3 ({This is the recommendation of Yuriy Krykun in his Chessable course The Accelerated Rossolimo . White secures the center and can subsequently develop the minor pieces. By exchanging the light-squared bishops, both sides have a little more room for the remaining pieces. More often} 5. exd5 {is played, which leads to exd5 after} Nf6 $1 {.}) 5... e6 ({The queen trade} 5... dxe4 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {leads to an equal position. However, White has the slightly easier game due to their dominance in the center.}) 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bd6 {In the similar variation Nc3 e6 f4 d5 Bb5+ Bd7 Bxd7+ Qxd7 d3 Nc6 Nf3 this is not possible because the d5 -pawn would be insufficiently defended. Instead, there I recommended a set-up with ...Nge7 , ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7 . I don't like it so much here because White hasn't yet developed the knight to c3 and could instead use c2-c3 to restrict the g7 -bishop's operating radius. Instead, we choose a set-up that we will encounter again when analyzing 2.Be2 . The bishop goes to d6 , where it has an eye on the f4 -pawn. The g8 -knight is developed to e7 , where it is outside the white pawns' reach.} 8. Qe2 ({The 'attack'} 8. Nc3 Nge7 9. Qe1 O-O 10. Qh4 {leads to nothing, because White cannot reinforce it. Black gains an advantage with play on the queenside, e.g.} Nd4 11. Rf2 b5 {.}) ({If White starts with} 8. Be3 {, Black has the additional option} Nf6 $5 {(besides 8...Nge7 ), because} 9. e5 {can be answered with} Ng4 {.}) 8... Nge7 9. Be3 {White is threatening e4 - e5 followed by Bxc5 .} f6 ({Prevents e4-e5 .} 9... d4 {also leads to good play for Black, but I prefer maintaining tension in the center and control of the c4 -square.}) 10. Na3 ({Krykun's recommendation. The knight could go to b5 to exchange for the d6 -bishop, or to c2 . The alternative knight development} 10. Nbd2 $2 {fails here due to} d4 11. Bf2 Bxf4 {.}) 10... b6 ({We prophylactically protect the c5 -pawn. If White now plays Nb5 , we can simply play} 10... Bb8 {.}) 11. c3 O-O 12. Nc2 Rad8 {Black fights for the d-file. If White doesn't respond in kind, ... Bc7 , ... dxe4 and ... Qd3 could follow.} 13. Rad1 Qc8 {The queen leaves the opposition with the white rook as a precaution. Now that both sides have completed development, it's time to assess the situation: both sides have positioned themselves sensibly and enter the middlegame with equal chances. The position is closed, indicating a long, maneuvering struggle ahead. Both sides will probably start by looking for ways to improve the position of their pieces. White could, for example, strengthen their control of the e-file with Rfe1 and Bc1 . Similary, Black could bring the f-rook to the e-file and move the d6 -bishop to c7 or b8 so that the d8 -rook has a clear view. The situation in the center is tense. Black can try to open the position with the pawn break... e6 - e5 . If White responds with f4 - f5 , the break ... c5 - c4 becomes an option to undermine the white center. White, of course, has a pawn break of their own in the center: e4 - e5 . Black should not allow White to play e4 - e5 followed by d3 - d4 .} ({For example, after Bc1 Black should either play...  ➤ ...} 13... e5 $1 {themselves} 14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 {now looks a bit more comfortable for Black and after f5} 16. c4 {is strong} dxc4 {dxe4 Qxe4?! Nxf5=+ ...  ➤ ... or Bc7 e5 fxe5 fxe5} 17. d4 {.}) *

