1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. f4 {The most direct route to the Grand Prix Attack. White keeps the positions of the f1 -bishop and the b1 -knight flexible.} d5 {The attack in the center is a well-established response, ensuring that White cannot develop the kingside undisturbed.} 3. exd5 {The most natural and common continuation. But White's position would be better if the f-pawn had not yet moved. The missing pawn on f2 makes the white king's position less secure; the squares e3 and e4 are weakened, on f4 the pawn blocks the dark-squared bishop and, last but not least, the f4 -pawn can be weak later down the road.} Nf6 ({This strong pawn sacrifice was introduced to high-level chess by none other than Mikhail Tal. After} 3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 {White gains some time for development – similar to the Scandinavian Defense. Black would therefore prefer to capture with the knight on d5 . As we will see, Black gets strong compensation if White defends the pawn.}) 4. c4 ({If White wants to hold on to the extra pawn,} 4. Bb5+ {is the right way to start. c4 blocks the view of the light-squared bishop and condemns it to passivity.}) 4... e6 5. dxe6 Bxe6 {White would have a healthy extra pawn if the pawns were still on f2 and c2 . With the pawns on c4 and f4 , however, there are a number of weak squares in White's position that give Black more than enough compensation.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 {Prevents d2 - d4 . The white d-pawn is now backward.} 7. Be2 Bd6 (7... g6 {is also good.}) 8. d3 Qc7 9. g3 O-O-O {The rook is now already in the right position. With ... Bf5 , ... Qd7 and ... Bc7 , Black can increase the pressure along the d-file. If White castles short, Black could initiate an attack by advancing the h-pawn, or continue playing in the center with ... Rhe8 . Black is better.} *

