1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. f4 {The most direct route to the Grand Prix Attack. White keeps the positions of the f1 -bishop and the b1 -knight flexible.} d5 {The attack in the center is a well-established response, ensuring that White cannot develop the kingside undisturbed.} 3. exd5 {The most natural and common continuation. But White's position would be better if the f-pawn had not yet moved. The missing pawn on f2 makes the white king's position less secure; the squares e3 and e4 are weakened, on f4 the pawn blocks the dark-squared bishop and, last but not least, the f4 -pawn can be weak later down the road.} Nf6 ({This strong pawn sacrifice was introduced to high-level chess by none other than Mikhail Tal. After} 3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 {White gains some time for development – similar to the Scandinavian Defense. Black would therefore prefer to capture with the knight on d5 . As we will see, Black gets strong compensation if White defends the pawn.}) 4. Bb5+ {White aims to defend the pawn on d5 with c2 - c4 without restricting the bishop.} Bd7 ({The alternative} 4... Nbd7 {gives Black good compensation as well.}) 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 ({Not} 5... Nbxd7 $6 6. c4 {The knight is better developed to c6 , where it controls d4 .}) 6. c4 {After other moves, Black wins back the pawn.} e6 {By moving the c-pawn, White has weakened the d4 and d4 -squares and especially the pawn on d4 , which is now backward. Exchanging the e6 and d5 -pawns helps Black to exploit these weaknesses.} 7. Nf3 {With the return of the pawn White says goodbye to the fight for an opening advantage.} exd5 8. Ne5 Qc7 9. O-O (9. Nc3 d4 {is good for Black.}) 9... Bd6 {Prepares castling.} 10. Nc3 O-O {Since the knight on e5 is attacked twice, Black doesn't have to worry about defending the d-pawn. Black has a comfortable game.} *

