1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. f4 {The most direct route to the Grand Prix Attack. White keeps the positions of the f1 -bishop and the b1 -knight flexible.} d5 {The attack in the center is a well-established response, ensuring that White cannot develop the kingside undisturbed.} 3. exd5 {The most natural and common continuation. But White's position would be better if the f-pawn had not yet moved. The missing pawn on f2 makes the white king's position less secure; the squares e3 and e4 are weakened, on f4 the pawn blocks the dark-squared bishop and, last but not least, the f4 -pawn can be weak later down the road.} Nf6 ({This strong pawn sacrifice was introduced to high-level chess by none other than Mikhail Tal. After} 3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 {White gains some time for development – similar to the Scandinavian Defense. Black would therefore prefer to capture with the knight on d5 . As we will see, Black gets strong compensation if White defends the pawn.}) 4. Bb5+ {White aims to defend the pawn on d5 with c2 - c4 without restricting the bishop.} Bd7 ({The alternative} 4... Nbd7 {gives Black good compensation as well.}) 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 ({Not} 5... Nbxd7 $6 6. c4 {The knight is better developed to c6 , where it controls d4 .}) 6. c4 {After other moves, Black wins back the pawn.} e6 {By moving the c-pawn, White has weakened the d4 and d4 -squares and especially the pawn on d4 , which is now backward. Exchanging the e6 and d5 -pawns helps Black to exploit these weaknesses.} 7. Qe2 {This ensures that Black gets an isolated e-pawn after the exchange on e6 . However, the queen on e2 is not well-placed because it can later be attacked by the black pieces.} Bd6 {Black prepares castling and develops the bishop to its most active square. Now the f4 -pawn is under attack.} 8. f5 {White plays to win a pawn. In view of the neglected development this is a risky undertaking, moreover White will not be able to defend their conquest for long.} O-O {There is no reason to react to White's threat. Castling brings the rook into play and unpins the e-pawn, which accelerates events.} 9. fxe6 fxe6 10. dxe6 ({With this, White at least wins a tempo. Quite bad would be} 10. Qxe6+ $2 Qxe6+ 11. dxe6 Nc6 {. Even without queens the black advantage in development is worth a lot. A logical continuation would now be} 12. Nf3 Rae8 13. O-O {. Now capturing on e6 is good enough, but even stronger is a direct assault against White's king:} Ng4 $1 {with the threat ...Nxh2 . Relatively best is} 14. g3 {, but after} Rxe6 {White can do nothing to counter their opponent's activity.}) 10... Qe7 11. Nf3 Nc6 {Both sides have made logical developing moves. Now White must play very precisely to stay in the game.} 12. d3 ({Not at all obvious, but this is the only way to preserve chances. The development of the queenside is being prepared.  The natural} 12. O-O $2 {gives Black a decisive attack after} Ng4 $1 {. 13...Nd4 is threatening to win the h-pawn. After} 13. g3 {or h3 follows} Nge5 {and Black wins because the white queenside does not help with the defense.}) (12. Nc3 $2 {is also bad because White continues to lose time after} Nd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 {.} 14. Nb5 d3 $1 15. Qxd3 Qxe6+ 16. Qe2 Qd7 {and the white king comes under a strong attack – regardless of whether it stays in the center or castles.}) 12... Rae8 ({There is nothing better.} 12... Ng4 {brings nothing because White has not yet castled.} 13. Bg5 Qe8 14. Nbd2 {Followed by long castling, and White is doing fine.}) 13. O-O ({Compared to} 13. O-O {, White is now in a better position to bring the pieces from the queenside to the kingside for help.}) 13... Ng4 {Even now this is most dangerous for White. The threat is 14...Nd4 .} 14. h3 ({The best defense.} 14. Nbd2 $2 {lets Black carry out the threat:} Nd4 $1 15. Nxd4 {The queen had no good flight square.} Bxh2+ 16. Kh1 Qh4 17. Rxf8+ ({(After} 17. N4f3 Qh5 {the attack is too strong.} 18. g3 Bxg3+ 19. Kg1 Bd6 20. b3 Ne5 {Santos-Casas )}) 17... Rxf8 18. N4f3 Nf2+ 19. Qxf2 Qxf2 {White gets three pieces for the queen, but in view of the underdeveloped queenside this is not enough. Black is clearly better.}) 14... Nge5 {White is not in an enviable position. The dark squares are weakened, which means a permanently vulnerable king position. The pieces on the queenside still haven't found their way into the game, while the black army is fully mobilized. Black will soon reduce the material deficit to one pawn and then continue to attack. This position was reached in five correspondence games, all of which Black went on to win.} *

