1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. Be2 ({This unusual bishop move has gained some high-class followers in recent years and is particularly popular in blitz. White is aiming for the Grand Prix Attack and with this move order avoids the concrete problems that arise after} 2. f4 d5 $1 {. The bishop move also has advantages over} 3. Nc3 {, as the knight is not always well-placed on c3 in the Grand Prix setup. Despite these advantages, Be2 does not pose any serious problems for us – Black gets a good position with normal developing moves. I recommend direct play in the center.}) 2... e6 {Preparing ... d7 - d5 .} 3. f4 ({That was the idea of 2.Be2 . It is also possible to play} 3. d3 {first, with a transposition after} d5 4. f4 {.}) 3... d5 4. d3 Nc6 {It often makes sense to first develop the piece that has only one good square available. In this case that is the knight. Meanwhile, the other pieces remain flexible.} 5. Nf3 Bd6 ({I like this kingside piece setup best. The bishop has an eye on the f4 -pawn from d6 , leaving the e7 -square to the knight. A good alternative is to exchange queens:} 5... dxe4 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Bxd1 b6 {with an equal position.}) 6. O-O ({After} 6. c3 {play is similar and is likely to transpose soon.}) 6... Nge7 {The knight cannot be attacked by the white pawns here and controls the square f5 , making it harder for White to make progress on the kingside.} 7. e5 {White gains space in the center. The position is now reminiscent of the Advance Variation in the French Defense. Two differences are in Black's favor: The white d-pawn is on d3 instead of d4 and the white bishop is quite passive on e2 ; it would be better placed on d3 .} Bc7 8. c3 {White prepares d3 - d4 .} O-O 9. d4 {White continues with the plan they started. Now the c5 -pawn is under attack.} cxd4 {In the French, Black usually does not hurry with this exchange so that the white knight does not come to c3 . Here there are concrete reasons for this.} 10. Bd3 {This intermediate move is the only way to justify White's play. Black must now reckon with a bishop sacrifice on h7 .} f6 ({After that the sacrifice on h7 is no longer possible because the square g5 is protected.} 10... dxc3 {After this the white idea is revealed.} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 $2 ({(} 11... Kh8 $1 {still looks playable.)}) 12. Ng5+ Kg6 ({(} 12... Kg8 $2 13. Qh5 {leads to mate.)}) 13. Qg4 f5 14. Qg3 {And the white attack is very strong.}) ({Or} 10... Nf5 {. Now the d4 -pawn is protected again. To win back the pawn White must exchange the important bishop.} 11. Bxf5 exf5 12. cxd4 Be6 {Black is very solid.}) 11. cxd4 Bd7 {Black brings the last minor piece into play. The bishop is on its way to the kingside – to h5 or g6 . The position is equal. Staroske-Wunderlich .} *

