{It isn't doing much on e2 and would be more effective on g2 or h3 . A logical move would therefore be Re1 , which would prepare the regrouping of the bishop. The dark-squared bishop is then best moved to f2 so that it doesn't stand in the way of the rook. (There is also potential for improvement in the black position: the queen could go to d7 , where it would protect the e6 -pawn as a precaution and clear the way for the rooks. The a-rook is probably best placed on d8 . As far as the minor pieces are concerned, the bishop on b7 is not yet entirely happy, as the knight c6 blocks its view. A regrouping of the knight via d8 to f7 is therefore a possibility. Of course, the two sides will not move back and forth on their half of the board until the end of the game. So let's look at the pawn breaks: White can't achieve much in the center. Black has the squares f5 and e5 under control and as soon as White plays d3 - d4 , ... dxe4 is an option, after which Black gains control of d5 and f5 . White's best chance of opening the position is therefore on the queenside: a2- a3 and b2 - b4 . Black pins their hopes above all on the break... e6 - e5 . If White doesn't react to this, Black can exchange on f4 and e4 , after which White's pawns become vulnerable. If White captures on e5 , after ... Nxe5 both sides' minor pieces become active. Finally, White could keep the position closed with f4 - f5 . Under very favorable circumstances, Black could then use ... c5 - c4 as another pawn break to undermine the e4 -pawn. However, there is also nothing to be said against keeping the position closed and continuing with ... d5 - d4 , for example.)} 1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. Be2 ({This unusual bishop move has gained some high-class followers in recent years and is particularly popular in blitz. White is aiming for the Grand Prix Attack and with this move order avoids the concrete problems that arise after} 2. f4 d5 $1 {. The bishop move also has advantages over} 3. Nc3 {, as the knight is not always well-placed on c3 in the Grand Prix setup. Despite these advantages, Be2 does not pose any serious problems for us – Black gets a good position with normal developing moves. I recommend direct play in the center.}) 2... e6 {Preparing ... d7 - d5 .} 3. f4 ({That was the idea of 2.Be2 . It is also possible to play} 3. d3 {first, with a transposition after} d5 4. f4 {.}) 3... d5 4. d3 Nc6 {It often makes sense to first develop the piece that has only one good square available. In this case that is the knight. Meanwhile, the other pieces remain flexible.} 5. Nf3 Bd6 ({I like this kingside piece setup best. The bishop has an eye on the f4 -pawn from d6 , leaving the e7 -square to the knight. A good alternative is to exchange queens:} 5... dxe4 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Bxd1 b6 {with an equal position.}) 6. O-O ({After} 6. c3 {play is similar and is likely to transpose soon.}) 6... Nge7 {The knight cannot be attacked by the white pawns here and controls the square f5 , making it harder for White to make progress on the kingside.} 7. c3 ({White was faced with the question of how to develop the queenside. The bishop could go to e3 , but then White must always reckon with ...d5-d4 . The knight would not be particularly well placed on c3 and} 7. Nbd2 {fails due to} Bxf4 {. The pawn move addresses these problems: control over d4 is increased and the knight is given a route via a3 to c2 .}) 7... f6 {This removes the possibility of e4 - e5 from the position. Often moves with the f-pawn in the opening lead to a weakening of the king position, but this is not the case here. White has no access to the e6 -square or the a2 - g8 diagonal.} 8. Be3 {The natural square for the bishop. White thus leaves open whether the knight will be developed via d2 or a3 .} O-O 9. g3 ({As the analysis of the alternative} 9. Nbd2 {shows, it is useful to protect the f4 -pawn once more. Nbd2 gives Black a tactical possibility in addition to continuing development with the natural 9...b6 :} d4 $5 10. cxd4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxf4 {(or first 11...Nxd4 )} 12. Rxf4 Nxd4 {Black has the outpost square d4 under control. The queenside can be developed with ...e6-e5 and ...e6-e5 . In my opinion, Black has the more comfortable position.}) ({After} 9. Na3 {as well, Black develops the queenside with} b6 {followed by ...Bb7 . Black has at least equality.}) 9... b6 {The bishop is best on b7 , where it has the potentially vulnerable e4 -pawn in its sights.} 10. Nbd2 {White has made all the necessary preparatory moves for this to be possible without danger.} Bb7 {All the pieces and pawns are still on the board. Accordingly, a complicated battle of maneuvering lies ahead. Practice – mainly in correspondence chess – shows that both sides have equal chances. White might start by improving the placement of their pieces, with the light-squared bishop being a prime candidate for repositioning.} *

