1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4 {White opts for the Grand Prix Attack. This move order differs from the other Grand Prix versions in several respects:} ({➤ White avoids the concrete play that arises after} 3. f4 d5 $1 {.  ➤ In comparison with} 4. Be2 {and d3 , White retains flexibility with the light-squared bishop. Here it is usually developed to b5 .  ➤ On the other hand, White loses flexibility elsewhere. The knight is not always well-placed on c3 . It could be exposed to attacks by the black pawns and it obstructs the c-pawn, which diminishes White's control of the d4 -square.}) 3... d5 {No surprises. Black occupies the center.} 4. Bb5+ {White brings out the bishop. Then d2 - d3 can follow without the bishop being trapped behind the pawn chain.} Bd7 {Black's light-squared bishop is also hindered by its own pawns. Black therefore has no objection to the exchange.} 5. exd5 Bxb5 ({An important intermediate move.} 5... exd5 {loses the d5 -pawn after} 6. Qe2+ $1 {.}) 6. Nxb5 exd5 {Black is ready to complete development of the kingside with ... Nf6 and ... Be7 . Black would then be slightly better because White has weakened themselves with f2 - f4 .} 7. Qe2+ {White pursues a concrete idea based on the unusual knight position on b5 .} Be7 8. Qe5 {The knight check on c7 is a threat and the pawns g7 and d5 are under attack. However, these threats can easily be fended off.} Kf8 {In return for giving up the right to castle, Black gains significant time, as the white queen will soon have to begin its retreat. The king can later be placed on g7 or h7 .} 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. Qe2 Qb6 {Black clears the way for the rook, which will probably go to e8 . On the kingside, the setup ... Nf6 , ... h7 - h6 and ... Kg8 - h7 is good. The pawns c5 and d5 give Black good control in the center and make it difficult for White to develop the queenside. Black is slightly better.} *

