1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4 {White opts for the Grand Prix Attack. This move order differs from the other Grand Prix versions in several respects:} ({➤ White avoids the concrete play that arises after} 3. f4 d5 $1 {.  ➤ In comparison with} 4. Be2 {and d3 , White retains flexibility with the light-squared bishop. Here it is usually developed to b5 .  ➤ On the other hand, White loses flexibility elsewhere. The knight is not always well-placed on c3 . It could be exposed to attacks by the black pawns and it obstructs the c-pawn, which diminishes White's control of the d4 -square.}) 3... d5 {No surprises. Black occupies the center.} 4. Bb5+ {White brings out the bishop. Then d2 - d3 can follow without the bishop being trapped behind the pawn chain.} Bd7 {Black's light-squared bishop is also hindered by its own pawns. Black therefore has no objection to the exchange.} 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. d3 Nc6 {Black should develop the queenside first, as the moves come rather easily.} 7. Nf3 Nge7 {One of the several possible setups. The knight cannot be attacked here and defends the two important squares d5 and f5 . The bishop later goes to g7 .} 8. O-O g6 9. Qe1 {A standard move in the Grand Prix Attack. The queen is transferred to the kingside.} Bg7 10. Qh4 {White's schematic play leads nowhere here. At the same time, I find it difficult to suggest a sensible plan for White.} Nd4 {Very unpleasant for White. The knight is very strong here. If White keeps it alive and defends the pawn c2 , it's not easy to develop the queenside. The exchange would be even worse: Black recaptures with the pawn and uses the c-file to put pressure on c2 . Meanwhile, White has achieved nothing on the kingside. The black piece setup stops all attempts to attack. Black can therefore castle short without any worries and play in the center and on the queenside.} *

