1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4 {White opts for the Grand Prix Attack. This move order differs from the other Grand Prix versions in several respects:} ({➤ White avoids the concrete play that arises after} 3. f4 d5 $1 {.  ➤ In comparison with} 4. Be2 {and d3 , White retains flexibility with the light-squared bishop. Here it is usually developed to b5 .  ➤ On the other hand, White loses flexibility elsewhere. The knight is not always well-placed on c3 . It could be exposed to attacks by the black pawns and it obstructs the c-pawn, which diminishes White's control of the d4 -square.}) 3... d5 {No surprises. Black occupies the center.} 4. exd5 {The exchange is more likely to help Black, as their light-squared bishop can now be actively developed. However, White's play is based on a concrete idea.} exd5 5. Bb5+ Nc6 ({Unlike with 4.Bb5+ , here the knight should be used to defend against the check.} 5... Bd7 $6 6. Qe2+ {followed by 7.Nxd5 is already known from the analysis of Bb5+ Bd7 exd5 exd5?! .}) 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 {The bishop occupies this somewhat passive square in order to block any checks along the e-file.} 8. Ne5 Bd7 {Black need not fear the loss of the bishop pair: Both white bishops are quite passive. Black will castle short next. Both sides will fight for the open e-file with the major pieces. The chances are even.} *

