1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4 {White opts for the Grand Prix Attack. This move order differs from the other Grand Prix versions in several respects:} ({➤ White avoids the concrete play that arises after} 3. f4 d5 $1 {.  ➤ In comparison with} 4. Be2 {and d3 , White retains flexibility with the light-squared bishop. Here it is usually developed to b5 .  ➤ On the other hand, White loses flexibility elsewhere. The knight is not always well-placed on c3 . It could be exposed to attacks by the black pawns and it obstructs the c-pawn, which diminishes White's control of the d4 -square.}) 3... d5 {No surprises. Black occupies the center.} 4. Nf3 {The most popular move. White develops the kingside.} dxe4 ({The pawn on e4 had been disrupting Black's development. It is a good moment for the exchange, because White has not yet played d2-d3 and cannot recapture with the pawn.} 4... Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. d4 {transposes to a main line of the French Defense.}) ({After} 4... Nc6 {White continues with} 5. Bb5 {and if now} dxe4 {White has the intermediate move} 6. Bxc6+ {. After} bxc6 7. Nxe4 {the bad black pawn structure on the queenside gives White chances for an advantage.}) 5. Nxe4 Nc6 {This prevents White from opening the position with d2 - d4 .} 6. Bb5 {White is threatening to weaken the black pawn structure on the queenside.} Bd7 7. Qe2 {This queen move has aggressive intentions. White wants to attack in the center with f4 - f5 . However, analysis shows that this is not dangerous.} Nf6 ({Instead,} 7... Nh6 {is also possible in order to place the knight on f5 later and prevent the break f4-f5 . I opted for developing the knight to f6 , as I recommend this setup elsewhere in this variation. White can now alter the character of the position, but not its evaluation.}) 8. f5 Be7 9. fxe6 Bxe6 {By exchanging, White has achieved that the knight c6 is no longer defended by the bishop. On the other hand, the bishop e6 is now very active. White would do well to exchange it directly.} 10. Nfg5 {White continues to take advantage of the fact that the black king is still in the center. If the bishop e6 now moves away, White captures on f6 and Black would have to recapture with the pawn.} ({After} 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 {the bishop pair promises Black more than sufficient compensation for the shattered pawn structure on the queenside.}) 10... Nxe4 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Qxe4 O-O (12... Qd5 {( Kindermann-Ankerst ) also leads to an equal position. The text move is a little trickier. White is prevented from castling.}) 13. b3 ({White is aiming for castling queenside. The opening of the e-file after} 13. Qxe6+ {is very dangerous for White.} Kh8 14. Bxc6 {14...Nd4 was a threat.} bxc6 15. Kd1 {Sooner or later the king must leave the e-file. The white rooks are not connected and the rook a1 will take a long time to find its way into the game. Black has excellent compensation for the pawn, e.g. after} Rf2 {.}) 13... Qd5 14. Qxd5 ({After} 14. Bd3 g6 {the threat ...Nb4 is unpleasant.}) 14... exd5 {By exchanging queens, Black has repaired the pawn structure, leading to an equal endgame.} *

