1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we will deal with the Grand Prix Attack, which refers to setups characterized by an early f2 - f4 , and in which White refrains from opening up the position with d2 - d4 . We will examine the following variations:} ({➤ The direct f4 . This version of the Grand Prix has lost popularity because Black immediately gains counterplay in the center. White therefore more often prepares the pawn move. There are several possibilities for this: ➤ Nc3} 1... e6 2. f4) ({➤ d3} 1... Nc6 2. f4) ({➤ Be2} 1... Nc6 2. f4 {.  What is White aiming for with the f-pawn move? As the name 'Grand Prix Attack' suggests, the plan carries aggressive intentions, with White planing to use the f-pawn later to launch an assault on the black kingside. This is usually preceded by long preparations. A typical setup for White would be Nf3 , Be2 , d2 - d3 , O-O , Qe1 - h4 and only then f4 - f5 . To prevent Black from interfering with this scheme, White is keen to keep the position closed. From Black's perspective, attacking the white center is therefore a good idea. My recommendations in this chapter are based on a quick ... d7 - d5 .}) 2. Nc3 e6 3. f4 {White opts for the Grand Prix Attack. This move order differs from the other Grand Prix versions in several respects:} ({➤ White avoids the concrete play that arises after} 3. f4 d5 $1 {.  ➤ In comparison with} 4. Be2 {and d3 , White retains flexibility with the light-squared bishop. Here it is usually developed to b5 .  ➤ On the other hand, White loses flexibility elsewhere. The knight is not always well-placed on c3 . It could be exposed to attacks by the black pawns and it obstructs the c-pawn, which diminishes White's control of the d4 -square.}) 3... d5 {No surprises. Black occupies the center.} 4. Nf3 {The most popular move. White develops the kingside.} dxe4 ({The pawn on e4 had been disrupting Black's development. It is a good moment for the exchange, because White has not yet played d2-d3 and cannot recapture with the pawn.} 4... Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. d4 {transposes to a main line of the French Defense.}) ({After} 4... Nc6 {White continues with} 5. Bb5 {and if now} dxe4 {White has the intermediate move} 6. Bxc6+ {. After} bxc6 7. Nxe4 {the bad black pawn structure on the queenside gives White chances for an advantage.}) 5. Nxe4 Nc6 {This prevents White from opening the position with d2 - d4 .} 6. Bb5 {White is threatening to weaken the black pawn structure on the queenside.} Bd7 7. O-O Nf6 ({The knight is developed to the most natural square. More popular is the preparatory} 7... Be7 {(to be able to recapture with the bishop on f6 ), but as we will see, this is unnecessary.}) 8. d3 a6 9. Bxc6 ({The retreat of the bishop to a4 or c4 allows it to be chased further by ...b7-b5 . Again after} 9. Nxf6+ gxf6 $1 {Black is slightly better. We examine White's problems in the model game Polgar-Kramnik, 2003 .}) 9... Bxc6 ({Black has secured the bishop pair and has a comfortable position. Stockfish now recommends retreating the knight – Ned2 or Nf2 – after which White can later play Ne5 and keep the balance. In practice, Qe2 has been the most frequent continuation. Now Black can secure the bishop pair with} 9... Nxe4 10. dxe4 $1 Bd6 {and claim a small advantage.}) *

