1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . In this chapter we look at Nge2 for the Four Knights or Taimanov repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} Nf6 ({If you have the Sicilian Four Knights in your repertoire, you can also choose the rare} 3... Nf6 {instead of the usual Nc6 and thus fight directly for the initiative. This is based on a very interesting and as yet barely tested idea.}) 4. e5 {This only leads to a weakening of White's position.} Ng4 5. f4 ({Even after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Qxd4 h5 {, White cannot avoid the weakening move} 7. f4 {, because Black had been threatening to win a pawn with ...Nc6 .} Nc6 8. Qd2 b6 {The bishop is developed to b7 . If White drives away the g4 -knight with h2-h3 , it goes to f5 via h6 . The weak squares f2 , e3 and e4 give Black the better play.}) 5... d5 {The weak squares f2 , e3 and e4 give Black the better play. Once again, the knight can be transferred to f5 if White challenges it.} *

