1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . In this chapter we look at Nge2 for the Four Knights or Taimanov repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} Nf6 ({If you have the Sicilian Four Knights in your repertoire, you can also choose the rare} 3... Nf6 {instead of the usual Nc6 and thus fight directly for the initiative. This is based on a very interesting and as yet barely tested idea.}) 4. g3 ({White wants to play a Closed Sicilian. The alternative is} 4. d4 {, which after} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {leads to the Four Knights Sicilian.}) 4... b5 {Black exploits the fact that the pawn e4 is only protected by the knight c3 . This idea was introduced in practice in the game Iskov-Kindermann , and has only been repeated in a handful of games since, although Black has a very good score and the engines are also convinced of Black's position.} 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. d3 {This setup, typical of the Closed Sicilian, is not very convincing here. Black has already achieved a lot on the queenside.} b4 7. Nb1 (7. Na4 d5 {is also slightly better for Black.}) 7... d5 8. e5 ({After} 8. exd5 Bxd5 {Black benefits from the exchange of bishops, as the light squares on the kingside are weakened.}) 8... Nfd7 (8... Ng4 9. f4 h5 $5 {also led to a black advantage in the game Utegaliev-Sindarov .}) 9. f4 Be7 {The character of the game is reminiscent of the King's Indian Attack. White must attack on the kingside, but this is very slow. Black will work towards opening lines on the queenside, which can be achieved by advancing the a-pawn. Black is slightly better. The game Khalaji-Paravyan , is a good demonstration of Black's trumps.} *

