1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . In this chapter we look at Nge2 for the Four Knights or Taimanov repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} Nf6 ({If you have the Sicilian Four Knights in your repertoire, you can also choose the rare} 3... Nf6 {instead of the usual Nc6 and thus fight directly for the initiative. This is based on a very interesting and as yet barely tested idea.}) 4. g3 ({White wants to play a Closed Sicilian. The alternative is} 4. d4 {, which after} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {leads to the Four Knights Sicilian.}) 4... b5 {Black exploits the fact that the pawn e4 is only protected by the knight c3 . This idea was introduced in practice in the game Iskov-Kindermann , and has only been repeated in a handful of games since, although Black has a very good score and the engines are also convinced of Black's position.} 5. Nxb5 ({This is still the best move, even though White exchanges a central pawn for a less important wing pawn.} 5. e5 $2 {overlooks the intermediate move} Bb7 $1 {. After} 6. Rg1 Ng4 {, Black is already winning. The pawns h2 and e5 are attacked (with the subsequent mating threat on f3! ) and Black is also threatening to send the knight c3 back to its starting square with ...b5-b4 .}) 5... Nxe4 6. Bg2 Bb7 {The oppositon of the bishops along the long diagonal creates tension.} 7. O-O ({Now the g2 -bishop is protected and d2-d3 is a threat. An important tactical detail: White cannot exploit the pin of the knight e4 with} 7. d3 {because after} Nc3 $1 {∓ the bishop on g2 is unprotected.}) 7... Qb6 {Black also defends the bishop and attacks the knight on b5 . We can already see that Black has solved all opening problems and it is already up to White to prove equality. Let's look at some possible continuations:} ({A ) a4?!} 7... Nf6 8. b3 Bxg2 9. Kxg2 a6 10. Na3 d5 {The dominance in the center and the unfortunate position of the white knights give Black a clear advantage, even though he later lost in the game Westerinen-Bellon Lopez .}) ({) Nbc3} 7... Nc3 {[%eval 0,0]} 8. dxc3 Be7 {Black has the better pawn structure and therefore the better chances in the long term.}) ({C ) There are many good moves after Na3 . In the game Sindarov-Paravyan ,} 7... Nf6 {Nc4 Qa6} 8. Bxb7 {Qxb7 happened and again the preponderance in the center gives Black a small advantage, which they converted into a whole point.}) ({D ) The strongest move is} 7... c4 $1 {, because with it White not only protects the knight, but also controls the central square d5 , which neutralizes the black pawn majority in the center. White holds the balance here. a6} 8. Na3 Nf6 9. Bxb7 {Qxb7 d4 or Qb3= .}) *

