1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . In this chapter we look at Nge2 for the Four Knights or Taimanov repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} Nc6 {Black is ready for the transition to the Taimanov or the Four Knights Sicilian.} 4. g3 ({This keeps the game within the framework of the Closed Sicilian. After} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {Black chooses between} Nf6 {(the Four Knights Sicilian), Qc7 and a6 (different variations of the Taimanov).}) 4... d5 {Black gains space in the center. White must now be prepared for the further advance of the pawn, which would come with tempo.} 5. d3 {For this setup White would have been better off postponing the development of the king's knight and starting with 3.g3 .} d4 {The problem with White's move order. The knight must return to its starting square because e2 is already occupied.} 6. Nb1 e5 {Black gains space, restricts the knight e2 and opens the diagonal of the bishop on c8 .} 7. Bg2 h5 ({Black wants to move the pawn to h4 and would then have the options of opening the h-file with ...hxg3 , or moving the pawn further to h3 , where it controls a square near the white king.} 7... Nf6 {would transpose to a line from our repertoire against the Closed Sicilian: e4 c5 Nc3 e6 g3 d5 d3 Nf6 Bg2 Nc6 Nge2 d4 Nb1 e5 .}) 8. h4 ({This reliably stops ...h5-h4 . The drawback of the pawn move is that the g4 -square can no longer be controlled by the h-pawn. After} 8. h3 {I like} h4 9. g4 g5 $1 {, as happened in the game Becker-Podzielny . Note the lack of perspective of the white minor pieces! Black will calmly prepare a breakthrough on the queenside.}) 8... Nf6 {The knight can later move to g4 , which is especially strong if White has castled kingside. In that case, Black has attacking ideas with ... Be7 followed by ... g7 - g5 or ... Bxh4 . If the knight on g4 is attacked with f2 - f3 , it goes to e3 . White must then part with the important dark-squared bishop. On the queenside Black will try to achieve the break ... c5 - c4 . Opening the c-file would give Black the prospect of penetrating the white position. Black has the better chances.} *

