s d4 , which after cxd4 Nxd4 brings us back to the line with 6.d4 .}) ({The alternative O-O also leads to a transposition. After} 6. d4 {Ne4 Nxe4 Bxe4} Bd6 {d3 we end up in a position which we analyze in the chapter on the Closed Sicilian via the move order e4} 7. dxc5 {Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {d3 d4} 8. Ne4 Nxe4 {dxe4 Bd6 Ne2 Nc6 O-O .}) 6... cxd4 ({The idea of this move is very concrete: Black wants to exploit White's lack of development. The main line starts with} 6... Bg4 7. Bg2 $1 Nxd4 {and now White decides between} 8. h3 Bf3 9. Kf1 {and . White either wins back the pawn on d5 or gets good play against the centralized king.}) 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Bg2 ({This position can also arise from the Fianchetto Variation of the Four Knights Sicilian: e4 c5} 8. Nf3 {e6} d4 {cxd4} 9. Nxd4 {Nf6 Nc3 Nc6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2 . If you have my course on this opening, there's no need to read further – I still stand by the recommendations I gave there!}) 8... Bg4 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. Not} 8... Bc5 {because of} 9. Qe2+ {and all reactions to the check have drawbacks for Black.}) 9. Nde2 {Clears the way for the queen to attack the d5 -pawn.} Bb4 {Black wants to exchange on c3 . Due to the pin of the knight e2 , White would have to recapture with the pawn. This would reduce White's pressure on d5 on the one hand and lead to weak pawns in the white camp on the other.} 10. h3 Bxc3+ {The right moment, as White cannot recapture with the knight.} 11. bxc3 Bf5 ({The best square for the bishop. From f5 , it keeps an eye on the e4 -square as well as the c2 - and h3 -pawns.} 11... Bh5 $6 12. Rb1 {The b7 -pawn is attacked, and Ba3 is a threat, preventing castling. There is now no good defensive move.} ({(} 12. Ba3 $2 {is premature due to} Qa5 {.)}) {After} 12... Qd7 $6 13. Bg5 {follows, and Black has no defense against Bxf6 .}) (11... Bxe2 $6 {As long as Black has not yet castled, this is not a good idea.} 12. Qxe2+ Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Nxe7 14. Ba3 {The pair of bishops gives White some advantage.}) 12. Ba3 {Prevents short castling.} Qa5 13. Qc1 {A necessary evil. The queen is poorly placed here.} O-O-O {The king is also safe on the queenside.} 14. O-O Be4 ({The g2 -bishop could later become very strong (for example, after exchanging the c3 -pawn for the pawn on d5 ), and it is also an important defender of White's king position. Therefore, it makes sense to exchange it. Black has active, centralized pieces and the better pawn structure. Next, ... Re8 and ... Ne4 could follow. Black is slightly better. Grabbing a pawn with} 14... Bxc2 $2 {is not recommended. After} 15. Qxc2 Qxa3 16. c4 {the position on the queenside opens up and the black king comes under attack.}) *

