s d4 , which after cxd4 Nxd4 brings us back to the line with 6.d4 .}) ({The alternative O-O also leads to a transposition. After} 6. d4 {Ne4 Nxe4 Bxe4} Bd6 {d3 we end up in a position which we analyze in the chapter on the Closed Sicilian via the move order e4} 7. dxc5 {Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {d3 d4} 8. Ne4 Nxe4 {dxe4 Bd6 Ne2 Nc6 O-O .}) 6... cxd4 ({The idea of this move is very concrete: Black wants to exploit White's lack of development. The main line starts with} 6... Bg4 7. Bg2 $1 Nxd4 {and now White decides between} 8. h3 Bf3 9. Kf1 {and . White either wins back the pawn on d5 or gets good play against the centralized king.}) 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Bg2 ({This position can also arise from the Fianchetto Variation of the Four Knights Sicilian: e4 c5} 8. Nf3 {e6} d4 {cxd4} 9. Nxd4 {Nf6 Nc3 Nc6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2 . If you have my course on this opening, there's no need to read further – I still stand by the recommendations I gave there!}) 8... Bg4 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. Not} 8... Bc5 {because of} 9. Qe2+ {and all reactions to the check have drawbacks for Black.}) 9. Qd3 Bc5 {The next bishop is developed with tempo. White now has to make a concession.} 10. Qe3+ {The queen is not well placed here.} Ne7 (10... Be7 {or Kf8 are also good. But not Kd7?!} 11. Nxc6 {Bxe3 Nxd8 Bxc1 Rxc1 Black keeps the weakness on d5 and is slightly worse.}) 11. O-O O-O {Now ... Nf5 is a threat.} 12. Qd3 Bxd4 ({This exchange allows us to execute the advantageous ...d5-d4 .} 12... h6 {is also good.}) 13. Qxd4 Nc6 ({Through a curious transposition of moves, we have arrived at a position usually reached via the Vienna Game: e4 e5 Nc3 Nf6 g3 Bc5 Bg2 c6 Nge2 d5 exd5 cxd5 d4 exd4 Nxd4 O-O O-O Bg4 Qd3 Bxd4 Qxd4} 13... Nc6 {.}) 14. Qf4 Qd7 {Black plans ... Bh3 to exchange the light-squared bishops. The bishop on g2 exerts pressure against the d5 -pawn and defends White's king's position.} 15. Re1 Bh3 {Black is already slightly better. After the exchange of bishops, White's king position and control of the center are weakened. Black can play ... d5 - d4 at an opportune moment.} ({If White avoids the exchange of bishops with Bh1 , the black bishop on h3 makes the white king feel uncomfortable.} 15... Rae8 16. Bd2 Re6) *

