}) 16. Bxh3 dxc3 17. bxc3 ({An interesting decision. White accepts weak pawns, but in return takes the d4 -square from the black knight and opens the b-file for the rook.} 17. Qxc3 Re8 {is also equal. The centralized position of the black pieces outweighs the bishop pair.}) 17... Re8 {We have been following the game Li-Kramnik . The two sides have equal chances. White has weak pawns on the queenside, but a strong pair of bishops. Black has a centralized setup and no weaknesses. The former world champion later achieved a winning position, but was unable to convert it into a full point.} *

