1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ...d7-d5 . In this chapter we look at Nge2 for the Four Knights or Taimanov repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2-g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2-d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian. Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian:  ➤ If you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 .  ➤ Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 .  ➤ To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} Nc6 {Black is ready for the transition to the Taimanov or the Four Knights Sicilian.} 4. g3 ({This keeps the game within the framework of the Closed Sicilian. After} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {Black chooses between} Nf6 {(the Four Knights Sicilian), Qc7 and a6 (different variations of the Taimanov).}) 4... d5 {Black gains space in the center. White must now be prepared for the further advance of the pawn, which would come with tempo.} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 ({This stops the further advance of the d-pawn.} 6. Bg2 {is also played frequently, but has no independent significance for us.   A ) The drawback of White's move order is that Black can drive away the knight with} d4 {, e.g.} 7. Nd5 ({(} 7. Ne4 $4 {fails to} f5 {, winning a piece.)}) 7... Nf6 8. Nef4 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Bd6 {, as happened in the rematch Fischer-Spasski, 1992 . I won't go into a more detailed analysis here, as after 6...Nf6 we end up in familiar territory and don't have to learn a new line.   B )} 10. Nf6+ {Here White now mostly plays d4 , which after cxd4 Nxd4 brings us back to the line with 6.d4 .}) ({The alternative O-O also leads to a transposition. After} 6. d4 {Ne4 Nxe4 Bxe4} Bd6 {d3 we end up in a position which we analyze in the chapter on the Closed Sicilian via the move order e4} 7. dxc5 {Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {d3 d4} 8. Ne4 Nxe4 {dxe4 Bd6 Ne2 Nc6 O-O .}) 6... cxd4 ({The idea of this move is very concrete: Black wants to exploit White's lack of development. The main line starts with} 6... Bg4 7. Bg2 $1 Nxd4 {and now White decides between} 8. h3 Bf3 9. Kf1 {and . White either wins back the pawn on d5 or gets good play against the centralized king.}) 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Bg2 ({This position can also arise from the Fianchetto Variation of the Four Knights Sicilian: e4 c5} 8. Nf3 {e6} d4 {cxd4} 9. Nxd4 {Nf6 Nc3 Nc6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2 . If you have my course on this opening, there's no need to read further – I still stand by the recommendations I gave there!}) 8... Bg4 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. Not} 8... Bc5 {because of} 9. Qe2+ {and all reactions to the check have drawbacks for Black.}) 9. Qd3 Bc5 {The next bishop is developed with tempo. White now has to make a concession.} 10. Be3 Qb6 ({White can no longer maintain the blockade on d4 . After} 10... Bxd4 11. Bxd4 Qe7+ {Deac-Dubov , the novelty} 12. Kd2 $5 {leads to sharp play.}) 11. Nxc6 (11. Na4 $4 Qb4+ {wins a piece.}) (11. Nb3 $4 Nb4 $1 {Black wins material, for example:} 12. Qd2 d4 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 {.}) 11... Bxe3 {Compromises White's pawn structure.} 12. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 13. fxe3 bxc6 ({Black has solved all the opening problems. On e4 ,} 13... d4 {is the simplest: e5 can be answered with} 14. O-O {, preventing White from capturing on c6 with check. To maintain the balance, White now needs to find Nb5! Rae8} O-O $1 {cxb5 exf6 Re2= .}) *

