1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ... d7 - d5 . In this chapter we look at 3.Nge2 for the Kan repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2 - g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2 - d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian.} {Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian: if you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 . Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov Sicilian with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 . To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. If White transitions to the Kan Variation with d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , this is no longer within the scope of this course. Instead, our focus will be on g3 and especially on the different variations of the Open Sicilian that can arise after a later d2-d4 . In addition, we look at a4 , which White uses to prevent Black's play on the queenside.} 4. a4 {This prevents Black from playing ... b7 - b5 . The drawback is that the b4 -square is weakened.} Nf6 ({That's already a novelty! I like the flexibility of this move: Black is ready for the Open Sicilian that would arise after d4 and prepares ...d7-d5 in case White keeps the position closed.} 4... Nc6 {is also good, but after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {Black has already developed the knight to c6 instead of to the square d7 , which is more typical for the Kan Variation.}) 5. g3 ({The typical setup in the Closed Sicilian. Not a good idea is} 5. e5 $6 {, because after} Ng4 {White cannot avoid the weakening f2-f4 to protect the pawn on e5 .}) ({After} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qc7 {a typical Kan position is reached, in which White has committed to a2-a4 somewhat early.} ({(Black also has the interesting alternative} 6... d5 7. exd5 exd5 {. In this Isolani position, the white pawn would be better still on a2 , while ...a7-a6 is a useful move that prevents Bb5+ .)})) 5... d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 ({The Isolani position after} 6... exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {is also playable.}) 7. Bg2 Nb4 {Thanks to the early a2 - a4 the black knight feels very comfortable here. It ties the white queen to the defense of the c2 -pawn. Black has easy play, e.g. with ... N8c6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O .} *

