1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ... d7 - d5 . In this chapter we look at 3.Nge2 for the Kan repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2 - g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2 - d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian.} {Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian: if you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 . Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov Sicilian with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 . To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. If White transitions to the Kan Variation with d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , this is no longer within the scope of this course. Instead, our focus will be on g3 and especially on the different variations of the Open Sicilian that can arise after a later d2-d4 . In addition, we look at a4 , which White uses to prevent Black's play on the queenside.} 4. g3 ({White has provoked ...a7-a6 by the 'threat' of an Open Sicilian. Although this is a useful move, it does not correspond to my recommendation 3...d5 against the Closed Sicilian Nc3 e6} 4. g3 {.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this advance to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} (4... d5 $2 {does not work well here. White gains an advantage with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {. Compared to the analogous lines after g3 d5 , ...a7-a6 is a loss of tempo, while Nge2 clearly improves White's position.}) 5. Bg2 Bb7 {From here the bishop puts pressure on the e4 -pawn, which can be further attacked with ... Nf6 and ... b5 - b4 .} 6. O-O Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn with ...b5-b4 . White could defend against this or sacrifice the pawn for initiative with d4 .} 7. Re1 {A very rare, but all the more poisonous move! It is threatening e4 - e5 and the rook on e1 supports the piece sacrifice Nd5 .} d6 {Directed against e4 - e5 .} ({The alternative} 7... b4 {leads to great complications after} 8. Nd5 $1 exd5 9. exd5 {. The best defense against the threatening check on the e-file is} d6 $1 {.} ({(} 9... Be7 10. d6 {wins back the piece.)}) 10. Nd4+ Kd7 $1 {.} ({(} 10... Be7 $2 11. Nf5 {.)}) {White has a lot of play for the piece after} 11. Nf3 {with the threats Ng5 and d2-d4 . The black position can be defended with an engine, but it is much more difficult over the board. In Yilmazyerli-Manafov , Black couldn't withstand the pressure for long.}) 8. d4 ({White has a lead in development and therefore wants to open up the position.} 8. d3 {would be harmless because then it is not clear what the rook on e1 is doing.}) (8. a3 {, after} Nbd7 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7 {leads to a position which we consider via the move order d4 cxd4 Nxd4 Nf6 a3 d6 O-O Nbd7 Re1 Qc7 .}) 8... b4 ({A novelty. Black plays to win the e4 -pawn and starts by attacking one of its defenders. The automatic} 8... cxd4 $2 {leads to a very dangerous position for Black after} 9. Nxd4 {, e.g.} Qc7 ({(} 9... Nbd7 {loses to} 10. e5 $1 Bxg2 11. exf6 Bb7 12. fxg7 Bxg7 13. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Rxe6+ Kf8 15. Rxd6 {.)}) 10. a4 bxa4 11. Nd5 $1 {. This strong piece sacrifice has been known for a long time and was tested in many games. Black is too far behind in development and now the king comes under attack. White is already winning.}) ({After} 8... Nbd7 {the black position remains very vulnerable, e. g. after} 9. dxc5 {as in Bartel-Nasuta .}) 9. Na4 ({White could also avoid the loss of a pawn with} 9. e5 {, but this does not pose any problems for Black.} Bxg2 10. Kxg2 dxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Nxd1 Nd5 {The position is equal.}) 9... Bxe4 {This looks risky, but it would be even riskier if White were to keep the mobile pawn duo in the center.} 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Nf4 {The most natural continuation. White has to pose threats to prevent Black from castling.} Nf6 12. Nh5 {This disrupts Black's castling plans, because after 12...Be7 White can take on g7 .} cxd4 ({If you want to avoid the following complications, you could instead give back the pawn in favor of king safety with} 12... Nxh5 13. Qxh5 Be7 {. After} 14. Rxe6 O-O 15. Re2 Nc6 16. dxc5 dxc5 17. Be3 {, however, White retains some pressure against the pawn on c5 .}) 13. Nxf6+ ({After} 13. Bg5 Nbd7 14. Qxd4 {, Black free themselves with} Qa5 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. Bxf6 Rg8 17. b3 Rc8 {. Now} 18. Z0 Qf5 19. Bh4 Ne5 {is a threat.}) 13... Qxf6 (13... gxf6 14. c3 {is risky for Black.}) 14. Nb6 Ra7 15. Nd5 {White wins back the two pawns.} Qf5 16. Qxd4 Nc6 17. Qc4 Kd7 {The king is relatively safe here. Black defends the knight c6 and attacks the knight d5 .} 18. Nxb4 Qb5 ({Exchanging queens would of course be in Black's interest, because then their king would no longer be at risk. The position after the queen exchange is equal.  White could also play the sharp piece sacrifice} 18... Qf4 {. After Qxb4!? Qxf7+ Kd8} 19. Qxe6+ {Be7 , however the black position is reliably defended. White has sufficient compensation for the piece, but no more.}) *

