osition.}) 5. Bg2 Bb7 {From here the bishop puts pressure on the e4 -pawn, which can be further attacked with ... Nf6 and ... b5 - b4 .} 6. O-O Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn with ...b5-b4 . White could defend against this or sacrifice the pawn for initiative with d4 .} 7. Re1 {A very rare, but all the more poisonous move! It is threatening e4 - e5 and the rook on e1 supports the piece sacrifice Nd5 .} d6 {Directed against e4 - e5 .} ({The alternative} 7... b4 {leads to great complications after} 8. Nd5 $1 exd5 9. exd5 {. The best defense against the threatening check on the e-file is} d6 $1 {.} ({(} 9... Be7 10. d6 {wins back the piece.)}) 10. Nd4+ Kd7 $1 {.} ({(} 10... Be7 $2 11. Nf5 {.)}) {White has a lot of play for the piece after} 11. Nf3 {with the threats Ng5 and d2-d4 . The black position can be defended with an engine, but it is much more difficult over the board. In Yilmazyerli-Manafov , Black couldn't withstand the pressure for long.}) 8. d4 ({White has a lead in development and therefore wants to open up the position.} 8. d3 {would be harmless because then it is not clear what the rook on e1 is doing.}) (8. a3 {, after} Nbd7 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7 {leads to a position which we consider via the move order d4 cxd4 Nxd4 Nf6 a3 d6 O-O Nbd7 Re1 Qc7 .}) 8... b4 ({A novelty. Black plays to win the e4 -pawn and starts by attacking one of its defenders. The automatic} 8... cxd4 $2 {leads to a very dangerous position for Black after} 9. Nxd4 {, e.g.} Qc7 ({(} 9... Nbd7 {loses to} 10. e5 $1 Bxg2 11. exf6 Bb7 12. fxg7 Bxg7 13. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Rxe6+ Kf8 15. Rxd6 {.)}) 10. a4 bxa4 11. Nd5 $1 {. This strong piece sacrifice has been known for a long time and was tested in many games. Black is too far behind in development and now the king comes under attack. White is already winning.}) ({After} 8... Nbd7 {the black position remains very vulnerable, e. g. after} 9. dxc5 {as in Bartel-Nasuta .}) 9. Nd5 {The typical piece sacrifice does not work so well here