1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ... d7 - d5 . In this chapter we look at 3.Nge2 for the Kan repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2 - g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2 - d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian.} {Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian: if you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 . Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov Sicilian with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 . To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. If White transitions to the Kan Variation with d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , this is no longer within the scope of this course. Instead, our focus will be on g3 and especially on the different variations of the Open Sicilian that can arise after a later d2-d4 . In addition, we look at a4 , which White uses to prevent Black's play on the queenside.} 4. g3 ({White has provoked ...a7-a6 by the 'threat' of an Open Sicilian. Although this is a useful move, it does not correspond to my recommendation 3...d5 against the Closed Sicilian Nc3 e6} 4. g3 {.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this advance to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} (4... d5 $2 {does not work well here. White gains an advantage with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {. Compared to the analogous lines after g3 d5 , ...a7-a6 is a loss of tempo, while Nge2 clearly improves White's position.}) 5. Bg2 Bb7 {From here the bishop puts pressure on the e4 -pawn, which can be further attacked with ... Nf6 and ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d4 ({Finally White decides to go for the Open Sicilian after all.  ➤} 6. d3 {after} Nf6 7. O-O {transposes to the line O-O Nf6 d3 , which is analysed here .}) ({➤} 6. a3 {after} Nf6 7. O-O d6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {transposes to the main line of this variation.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 ({This position is also reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 7. Nxd4 {a6 Nc3 b5 g3 Bb7 Bg2 . So why doesn't White play this way right away? The point behind the detour via the Closed Sicilian is that Black has been tempted into the early ...b7-b5 .  In fact, in the Kan after Nc3 ,} Qc7 {is more popular than b5 . Black is now behind in development in an open position, so accuracy is required.}) 7... Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn with ...b5-b4 . White can defend against this or sacrifice the pawn for initiative with O-O .} 8. a3 {White prevents ... b5 - b4 and thus defends the e-pawn. This is less harmless than it looks. The opposition of the bishops along the long diagonal creates tactical tension.} d6 {Prepares developing the knight to d7 and controls e5 . Black should not allow e4 - e5 .} 9. O-O Nbd7 ({Black could also start with} 9... Qc7 {. But not Be7? , which runs into a typical tactic:} 10. e5 $1 Bxg2 11. exf6 Bxf1 {fxe7 Qxe7} 12. Qxf1 {The two minor pieces are stronger than the rook and pawn here.}) 10. Re1 Qc7 ({Defends the b7 -bishop and thus prepares ...Be7 . The direct} 10... Be7 {would have failed again to} 11. e5 $1 {.}) 11. a4 {A typical break in this pawn structure – even if the a-pawn doesn't usually pause on a3 . However, there’s no longer any need for White to prevent ... b5 -b4 , because the e4 -pawn is sufficiently protected. With 11.a4 , White opens a second front on the queenside.} b4 ({Black should keep the queenside closed.  After} 11... bxa4 $2 12. Nxa4 {would give White some advantage. Even stronger is} Nd5 $1 {with the idea} 13. exd5 {exd5+} Ne5 14. c4 $1 {whereby White defends the d5 -pawn. White threatening to win back the piece with f2-f4 , and} Be7 {doesn't help due to} 15. Nf5 O-O 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. f4 {.}) 12. Na2 ({The idea of the previous move. The pawn on b4 is not easy to defend.} 12. Nd5 {can now be answered with} exd5 13. exd5+ Ne5 14. f4 O-O-O $1 {. White will lose the pawn on d5 , which gives Black the better chances.}) 12... Nc5 {Black defends with the counterattack on the e4 -pawn. For this reason it was important to develop the knight first rather than the f8 -bishop.} ({➤ The protective move} 12... a5 $2 {weakens the b5 -square, and White can also open the position with} 13. c3 {, Florstedt-Schulte .}) ({➤ For the same reason} 12... e5 $2 13. Nb3 a5 14. c3 {is not good either.}) 13. Nxb4 ({➤ After} 13. f3 $2 e5 14. Nf5 a5 {Simonian-Korneev , Black has everything under control. White can't open up the queenside because c2-c3 is answered with ...b4-b3 . The b5 -square is therefore out of reach of the white knights. Black's minor pieces are better placed, which gives them an advantage.}) ({➤ After} 13. c3 {, Black first plays} b3 $1 {(to keep the queenside closed) and only after} 14. Nxb3 Ncxe4 {. The position is equal.}) 13... Ncxe4 {Black has succeeded in maintaining the material balance and keeping the position relatively closed. The two pawns in the center are a trump card that could later turn the tide in Black's favor. For now, however, the safety of the king has priority – ... Be7 and ... O-O are the logical next moves. The position is in dynamic equilibrium.} ({The following engine line illustrates the complexity of the position. I will refrain from annotating in detail, as this would make the analysis too lengthy. Both sides have a variety of alternatives on almost every move: Bf4!?} 13... e5 {( Be7 f3 Nc5 Nf5! is the idea of 14.Bf4 . exf5 now fails due to Bxd6+- .) Rxe4! Nxe4} 14. Qe2 d5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 {Bxe4 Rd8 Re1 Bxe4 Qxe4 Bd6} 16. Bg5 {Rd7 Qa8+} Qb8 17. Qxa6 {O-O . The roughest complications are behind us. The position remains equal.}) *

