1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ... d7 - d5 . In this chapter we look at 3.Nge2 for the Kan repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2 - g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2 - d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian.} {Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian: if you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 . Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov Sicilian with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 . To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. If White transitions to the Kan Variation with d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , this is no longer within the scope of this course. Instead, our focus will be on g3 and especially on the different variations of the Open Sicilian that can arise after a later d2-d4 . In addition, we look at a4 , which White uses to prevent Black's play on the queenside.} 4. g3 ({White has provoked ...a7-a6 by the 'threat' of an Open Sicilian. Although this is a useful move, it does not correspond to my recommendation 3...d5 against the Closed Sicilian Nc3 e6} 4. g3 {.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this advance to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} (4... d5 $2 {does not work well here. White gains an advantage with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {. Compared to the analogous lines after g3 d5 , ...a7-a6 is a loss of tempo, while Nge2 clearly improves White's position.}) 5. Bg2 Bb7 {From here the bishop puts pressure on the e4 -pawn, which can be further attacked with ... Nf6 and ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d4 ({Finally White decides to go for the Open Sicilian after all.  ➤} 6. d3 {after} Nf6 7. O-O {transposes to the line O-O Nf6 d3 , which is analysed here .}) ({➤} 6. a3 {after} Nf6 7. O-O d6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {transposes to the main line of this variation.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 ({This position is also reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 7. Nxd4 {a6 Nc3 b5 g3 Bb7 Bg2 . So why doesn't White play this way right away? The point behind the detour via the Closed Sicilian is that Black has been tempted into the early ...b7-b5 .  In fact, in the Kan after Nc3 ,} Qc7 {is more popular than b5 . Black is now behind in development in an open position, so accuracy is required.}) 7... Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn with ...b5-b4 . White can defend against this or sacrifice the pawn for initiative with O-O .} 8. Qe2 {White defends the pawn on e4 . Besides, the queen on e2 could be useful for an attack on the black king – either in combination with e4 - e5 or Nd5 .} b4 ({The knight must now either return to the back rank, which would be a great loss of time, or to a4 , where it can be attacked.  Black cannot afford to play carelessly, as the following line demonstrates.} 8... d6 $2 9. O-O Nbd7 {The opposition of the bishops already allows a tactical sequence:} 10. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 11. e5 Bxg2 ({(} 11... Nd5 $2 12. exd6 {is worse.)}) 12. exf6 {Threatening Qxe6+ and Kxg2 . White wins back the sacrificed piece.} Qxf6 ({(} 12... Bxf1 $2 13. Qxe6+ Be7 14. fxg7 {)}) ({(} 12... Bh3 $2 13. fxg7 Bxg7 14. Qh5+ Kf8 15. Qxh3 {)}) 13. Kxg2 {The material balance is restored. White is better because the black king as well as the pawns e6 and d6 are vulnerable.}) 9. Na4 ({Harmless is} 9. Nb1 {, e.g.} Qb6 10. c3 Nc6 {with good play for Black.}) 9... Qa5 {Black gets good counterplay against the knight a4 .} 10. b3 Nc6 {Ideally the bishop should move to this square, but for this the knight d4 must first be exchanged.} 11. Bb2 (11. Be3 {amounts to the same thing.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 {A useful move. The bishop is forced to make a decision and e4 - e5 as well as Bxf6 are removed from the position.} 13. Bb2 Bc6 {The knight no longer has a square to retreat to.} 14. f4 ({White must play energetically.} 14. Qe3 $6 Bxa4 15. bxa4 Bc5 16. Qb3 {White has avoided the loss of a pawn, but from a positional point of view, their position is a disaster. The queenside pawns are weak and both bishops are passive (Black will soon play ...d7-d6 ). Domingos-Rohl Montes .}) 14... d6 15. Qd2 {With this novelty, White keeps equal chances. White wants to exploit the pin of the b-pawn with a2 - a3 .} ({Neither} 15. Qe3 $2 Bxa4 16. bxa4 Be7 {Imcke-Schlosser nor} 17. O-O $2 {, after which Black could have won the exchange with Bb5 in Sahoo-Fominyh , are of any help to White.}) 15... Bxa4 {Instead, grabbing the pawn on e4 would open up the position too much.} 16. bxa4 Qxa4 17. a3 (17. fxe5 dxe5 18. Bxe5 Be7 {would be good for Black – White has too many weak pawns.}) 17... b3 {The position is equal. White could now win back the pawn on e5 , or play for compensation with the bishop pair with 18.Qb4 .} ({After} 17... bxa3 18. Rxa3 {White also gets enough play.}) *

