ould move to this square, but for this the knight d4 must first be exchanged.} 11. Bb2 (11. Be3 {amounts to the same thing.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 {A useful move. The bishop is forced to make a decision and e4 - e5 as well as Bxf6 are removed from the position.} 13. Bb6 Qb5 {Black is threatening to exchange queens, after which the pawn on e4 would no longer be sufficiently protected.} 14. Qd3 {White agrees to the queen exchange, but only on their own terms. The queen is better on d3 than on e3 because it does not block the dark-squared bishop's retreat.} ({After} 14. Qxb5 axb5 15. Nc5 {, Black could either capture on c5 and e4 , or play} Bc6 {, e.g.} 16. O-O Rb8 17. Ba7 Ra8 18. Bb6 {with a repetition.}) (14. Qe3 {does not pose any problems for Black either, e.g.} Be7 15. O-O-O O-O 16. Rhe1 Qc6 {(directed against Bf1 ) with equality.}) 14... Be7 ({After} 14... Qxd3 $2 15. cxd3 {the e4 -pawn is reliably protected and there are a lot of weaknesses on the black queenside.}) 15. O-O-O ({In the game Balashov-Chuchelov ,} 15. O-O Rc8 16. Rac1 O-O {followed with equality.}) 15... Rb8 ({An improvement over the game Petrosian-Koneru , in which} 15... Rc8 {followed. After Rc8 White can slowly strengthen their position with moves like Rhe1 and f2-f4 . With the rook on b8 , Black can attack the knight and bishop with ...Bc6 .}) ({If Black plays} 15... O-O 16. Rhe1 Qc6 {, as I recommended in the analogous position with the white queen on e3 , White gets slightly better chances with} 17. f4 d6 18. Bg1 {. The idea is Nb6-d5 .}) 16. f4 ({This forces events. After} 16. f3 {the exchange sacrifice} Bxe4 $1 17. fxe4 Rxb6 18. Nxb6 Qxb6 {is good. Black is not worse here; the dark-squared bishop is very strong and will soon make its way to d4 .}) ({After} 16. Rhe1 $6 Bc6 {White is too slow.} 17. Be3 {is answered with} Ng4 {.}) 16... Qxd3 (16... d6 $2 {loses a pawn because of} 17. Bc7 {.}) 17. cxd3 Bc6 {Black is threatening ... Bxa4 .} 18. fxe5 ({Best. After} 18. Bg1 exf4 19. gxf4 O-O {Black is slightly better. The threat is ...Bxa4 followed by ...b4-b3 and after} 20. Nb2 {,} Nh5 $1 {is unpleasant.}) 18... Bxa4 19. exf6 Bxf6 {The position is equal, regardless of whether White retreats the bishop or accepts the trade.} *

