1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The game begins with the Closed Sicilian.} e6 {Black prepares play in the center with ... d7 - d5 . In this chapter we look at 3.Nge2 for the Kan repertoire.} 3. Nge2 {A tricky move order. White could subsequently continue with g2 - g3 and keep the game in the waters of the Closed Sicilian, or play d2 - d4 , which leads to the Open Sicilian.} {Since we cannot prevent this, it is necessary to react with a move that matches our own repertoire in the Open Sicilian: if you are aiming for the Four Knights Sicilian, you can choose between Nc6 and the rare Nf6 . Those who prefer the Taimanov Variation with 5...Qc7 should choose Nc6 and those who play the Taimanov Sicilian with 5...a6 can choose between Nc6 and a6 . To allow a transition to the Kan Variation, a6 is necessary. This is the most complicated of the options mentioned, because White can first develop the bishop to g2 and only later transfer to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , which leads to sharp positions.} a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. If White transitions to the Kan Variation with d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , this is no longer within the scope of this course. Instead, our focus will be on g3 and especially on the different variations of the Open Sicilian that can arise after a later d2-d4 . In addition, we look at a4 , which White uses to prevent Black's play on the queenside.} 4. g3 ({White has provoked ...a7-a6 by the 'threat' of an Open Sicilian. Although this is a useful move, it does not correspond to my recommendation 3...d5 against the Closed Sicilian Nc3 e6} 4. g3 {.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this advance to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} (4... d5 $2 {does not work well here. White gains an advantage with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {. Compared to the analogous lines after g3 d5 , ...a7-a6 is a loss of tempo, while Nge2 clearly improves White's position.}) 5. Bg2 Bb7 {From here the bishop puts pressure on the e4 -pawn, which can be further attacked with ... Nf6 and ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d4 ({Finally White decides to go for the Open Sicilian after all.  ➤} 6. d3 {after} Nf6 7. O-O {transposes to the line O-O Nf6 d3 , which is analysed here .}) ({➤} 6. a3 {after} Nf6 7. O-O d6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {transposes to the main line of this variation.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 ({This position is also reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 7. Nxd4 {a6 Nc3 b5 g3 Bb7 Bg2 . So why doesn't White play this way right away? The point behind the detour via the Closed Sicilian is that Black has been tempted into the early ...b7-b5 .  In fact, in the Kan after Nc3 ,} Qc7 {is more popular than b5 . Black is now behind in development in an open position, so accuracy is required.}) 7... Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn with ...b5-b4 . White can defend against this or sacrifice the pawn for initiative with O-O .} 8. O-O {The most common continuation. White sacrifices the e-pawn in exchange for a lead in development. Since the g2 -bishop is now defended, White is threatening e4 - e5 . In addition, the piece sacrifice Nd5 is a common motif, aiming to open the e-file and attack the king. The pawn sacrifice with 8.O-O was introduced into tournament practice by none other than the young Mikhail Tal.} b4 {Black should not shy away from the complications.} ({The second most common move,} 8... d6 $2 {, leads to a very dangerous position for Black, e.g.} 9. Re1 Qc7 ({(after} 9... Nbd7 {,} 10. e5 $1 Bxg2 11. exf6 Bb7 12. fxg7 Bxg7 13. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Rxe6+ Kf8 15. Rxd6 {is winning.)}) 10. a4 bxa4 11. Nd5 $1 {. This strong piece sacrifice has been known for a long time and was tested in many games. Black is too far behind in development and now the king is also under attack. White is already winning.}) 9. Na4 {This is of course not the ideal square for the knight, but at least it prevents ... Bc5 and attacks the weakened b6 -square.} Bxe4 ({Again there are no good alternatives. Much worse is} 9... Nxe4 $2 10. Re1 d5 {and now} 11. c4 $1 {is strongest for White. After} bxc3 12. bxc3 {followed by Rb1 Black can no longer defend against the threats on the queenside.}) 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 {The black position looks tactically vulnerable. The only developed piece is the unprotected knight on e4 . The queenside is weakened and the rook on a8 is also unprotected. However, as practice and analysis show, these factors do not give White more than sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} 11. c4 ({This continuation is preferred by the engines and indeed poses greater challenges for Black than the more popular} 11. Re1 {.}) 11... Nc5 {We react as against 11.Re1 . Black wants to exchange knights and develop the bishop to c5 .} ({The alternative} 11... bxc3 {leads to very sharp positions. White can sacrifice another pawn with} 12. Re1 $1 {for rapid development. The best option now is} Nf6 $1 {, after which White maintains the initiative with} 13. Qb3 {(with the threat of Qb7 ) or Qf3 .}) 12. Bf4 {A good position for the bishop. In addition, White sets a trap.} Nxa4 ({After} 12... Nc6 $2 {the exchange of knights} 13. Nxc6 dxc6 {by no means leads to relief for Black, as FM Thomas Thiel showed in two online blitz games:} 14. Qf3 $1 Rc8 ({(} 14... Qc8 $2 15. Nb6 {)}) 15. Rad1 Qa5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 $6 17. Qg4 {. Now, the best option is to give up an exchange with} O-O 18. Bh6 g6 {, because otherwise the black king would no longer be safe. Thiel-Schekachikhin and Thiel-Thorhallsson .}) 13. Qxa4 Be7 ({Another possibility is} 13... Bc5 {.}) 14. Rfd1 Qb6 ({Preparing ...Nc6 and castling. If immediately} 14... O-O {, White can win back the pawn with} 15. Bxb8 Qxb8 16. Qxd7 {, because Rxb8? fails to Nc6 .}) 15. Rac1 {White prepares c4 - c5 .} Nc6 16. c5 {White must play very accurately to keep the balance.} ({Against} 16. Nb3 {Black has the surprising resource} h5 $1 {with a kingside attack. Black wants to play ...h5-h4 and open the h-file. If White prevents this with} 17. h4 $2 ({(stronger is} 17. h3 {, after which Black can renew the threat of ...h5-h4 with} f5 $1 {.)}) {, Black has} 17... g5 $1 {with an attack.}) 16... Bxc5 17. Nxc6 dxc6 18. Bd6 {Forces an equal rook ending.} Bxd6 19. Rxc6 Qb5 20. Qxb5 axb5 21. Rcxd6 Ke7 {Black could not yet capture on a2 because of the check on d8 . White now has various possibilities to win back the lost pawn. The game should end in a draw.} *

