{White's chances lie on the queenside.} bxa3 (16... Bxc5 $2 {runs into the fatal pin} 17. Rac1 {.}) 17. b4 {The idea of the previous move. If White succeeds in moving this pawn another square forward, the black queenside would be paralyzed.} Na6 ({After} 17... O-O {comes} 18. Nb3 {with the threat b4-b5 .}) 18. c6 {White's energetic play has prevented Black from castling so far. Now that the black knight no longer defends c6 , White switches to an attack on the black king.} ({After} 18. Qxa5 $2 {,} Nc7 $1 19. Qb6 Nd5 20. Qb5 Nc3 21. Qd3 Nxd1 {wins.}) ({Possible is} 18. bxa5 {, but after} Nxc5 19. Qxa3 Na6 {(to avoid the pin on the c-file) followed by ...O-O , Black doesn't have any worries.}) 18... Nxb4 ({This is not being greedy, but in fact the only defensive move!} 18... O-O $2 {fails to} 19. cxd7 Qb7 20. Nc6 Bf6 21. b5 {followed by Bc5 . No better is dxc6? Nxc6 Kf8 b5+- followed by Rac1 .}) 19. cxd7+ Qxd7 20. Nb5 Nd5 {The point of 18...Nxb4 : Black can block the d-file.} 21. Nc7+ {Black's knight and queen are pinned.} Kd8 22. Rxd5 ({White continues to attack.} 22. Qxd7+ Kxd7 23. Nxa8 Rxa8 24. Bc1 {should end in a draw.}) 22... exd5 23. Qb3 Rc8 ({Black still cannot capture the knight:} 23... Qxc7 $2 24. Bb6 {or Kxc7?} Qxb6 {Kc8} 25. Rc1 {.}) 24. Nxd5 a4 {White's queen is driven to a less active square.} 25. Qa2 Rc6 {The rook on the sixth rank helps defend the king. Black aims to block the d-file with ... Bd6 or ... Rd6 . Since we've already deviated significantly from familiar lines, I won't delve further into the analysis. In any case, it's unlikely that White will find all the moves up to this point without excellent preparation. The position remains very sharp, and Stockfish evaluates it as "0.00".} *

