.} Bxe4 ({Again there are no good alternatives. Much worse is} 9... Nxe4 $2 10. Re1 d5 {and now} 11. c4 $1 {is strongest for White. After} bxc3 12. bxc3 {followed by Rb1 Black can no longer defend against the threats on the queenside.}) 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 {The black position looks tactically vulnerable. The only developed piece is the unprotected knight on e4 . The queenside is weakened and the rook on a8 is also unprotected. However, as practice and analysis show, these factors do not give White more than sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} 11. Re1 {The most common move.} Nc5 {The strongest continuation. Black wants to exchange knights and develop the bishop to c5 .} ({The old main continuation is} 11... d5 {. This has the drawback that the pawn e6 is no longer reliably defended. White can exploit this with} 12. c4 $1 bxc3 13. Nxc3 {. Now the knight on e4 is attacked, and it is needed to block the e-file. After} Nxc3 $2 {(it is better to return the pawn with 13...Be7 ) there follows the piece sacrifice} 14. Qh5 $1 Ne4 ({(} 14... g6 15. Qe5 {)}) 15. Nxe6 {, e.g.} g6 16. Nc7+ $1 Qxc7 17. Qxd5 {. White wins back material and the attack continues.}) 12. Qf3 {White attacks the rook on a8 . This is quite popular, but it is better to save this trump for later.} Ra7 ({White was hoping for} 12... d5 $2 13. Nxc5 Bxc5 14. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Rxe6+ Be7 16. Bg5 {, after which Black's position is in shambles.}) 13. Nxc5 Bxc5 14. Nb3 ({Stockfish recommends the previously untested} 14. c3 {, but even then Black has better chances, for instance after} bxc3 15. Qxc3 Rc7) ({After} 14. Be3 Qb6 {White cannot prevent castling and therefore has no compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Bb6 {White has not succeeded in creating threats against the black king. Black will castle on the next move and White cannot thwart this plan.} 15. Bf4 {This is the most common continuation, with the bishop heading to d6 .} ({The double attack} 15. Qg4 {is rebutted by the counterattack} Qf6 {.}) 15... Qf6 {Pinning the bishop and attacking the pawn on b2 .} 16. Nd2 {Best. On b3 , the knight was controlled by the bishop b6 . Now it is transferred to the center.} ({After} 16. Qe2 O-O {White cannot win back the pawn with} 17. Bd6 {, because after} Rc8 18. Bxb4 Qxb2 {follows.}) 16... O-O 17. Ne4 Qf5 {Keeps the bishop pinned.} 18. Nd6 Qg6 {White has succeeded in maneuvering the knight to a square where it blocks the black d-pawn and prevents ... Rc8 . However, this is not enough compensation for an important central pawn. Black wants to play ... Nc6 next. This would threaten ... e6 - e5 and ... Nd4 . Black has the better chances, Bellahcene-Sanal,V .} *

