e king is also under attack. White is already winning.}) 9. Na4 {This is of course not the ideal square for the knight, but at least it prevents ... Bc5 and attacks the weakened b6 -square.} Bxe4 ({Again there are no good alternatives. Much worse is} 9... Nxe4 $2 10. Re1 d5 {and now} 11. c4 $1 {is strongest for White. After} bxc3 12. bxc3 {followed by Rb1 Black can no longer defend against the threats on the queenside.}) 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 {The black position looks tactically vulnerable. The only developed piece is the unprotected knight on e4 . The queenside is weakened and the rook on a8 is also unprotected. However, as practice and analysis show, these factors do not give White more than sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} 11. Re1 {The most common move.} Nc5 {The strongest continuation. Black wants to exchange knights and develop the bishop to c5 .} ({The old main continuation is} 11... d5 {. This has the drawback that the pawn e6 is no longer reliably defended. White can exploit this with} 12. c4 $1 bxc3 13. Nxc3 {. Now the knight on e4 is attacked, and it is needed to block the e-file. After} Nxc3 $2 {(it is better to return the pawn with 13...Be7 ) there follows the piece sacrifice} 14. Qh5 $1 Ne4 ({(} 14... g6 15. Qe5 {)}) 15. Nxe6 {, e.g.} g6 16. Nc7+ $1 Qxc7 17. Qxd5 {. White wins back material and the attack continues.}) 12. c3 {White defends the knight on a4 and attacks the pawn on b4 .} Nxa4 13. Qxa4 {The queen is pinning the d-pawn. Black should therefore be wary of the piece sacrifice Nxe6 .} Qb6 ({This not only defends the b4 -pawn but also protects against the piece sacrifice on e6 .  ➤ A good alternative is to return the pawn with} 13... Be7 {.  ➤ After bxc3} 14. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Rxe6 {Black should return the piece with Be7!} ({(Not Kf7?} 15. Re5 $1 {and the white attack is too strong. Zapata-Bruzon Batista )}) {Bg5} 15... Nc6 {Bxe7 Nxe7 Rae1 O-O} 16. Rxe7+ {.}) 14. Be3 {Once again the piece sacrifice on e6 is a threat.} Bc5 15. Qd1 {A novelty with which White can keep the balance. The d4 -knight is now defended once more, which allows White to exchange on b4 . In addition, the queen can be transferred to the kingside.} bxc3 ({The complications after} 15... O-O 16. cxb4 $1 {also lead to equality, e.g.} Qxb4 17. a3 $1 Qxb2 18. Qf3 d5 19. Reb1 Qc3 20. Rc1 Qb2 21. Rcb1 {.}) 16. b4 {On the one hand this lures the black queen to a less safe square, on the other White gains time, because Black was threatening ... cxb2 .} ({After} 16. bxc3 $6 O-O {White's compensation for the pawn looks inadequate.}) 16... Qxb4 17. Qf3 {The idea of the operation initiated with 15.Qd1 . The rook on a8 is not easy to defend.} Bxd4 {It's best to give back some material and keep the king safe.} (17... d5 $6 {has the drawback that the pawn on e6 is less reliably protected. White gets a strong attack with the typical sacrifice} 18. Rab1 Qc4 19. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 20. Qh5+ Kd8 21. Bg5+ Kc8 22. Qf7 {.}) 18. Rab1 ({After} 18. Qxa8 O-O {Black has three pawns for the exchange and therefore slightly better chances. The tactical justification is} 19. Rab1 $6 Qd6 20. Bxd4 Nc6 $1 21. Qxa6 Qxd4 {, after which the c-pawn is very strong.}) 18... Qd6 {The only move. The queen must defend the knight.} 19. Bxd4 (19. Qxa8 {would again be met with} O-O 20. Bxd4 Nc6 $1 {.}) 19... O-O ({Of course not} 19... Qxd4 $4 20. Qxa8 {and the knight can no longer be saved.}) 20. Bxg7 {After other moves, White is worse.} Kxg7 21. Qg4+ ({More risky is} 21. Qxa8 Nc6 22. Qxa6 c2 23. Rbc1 Qd2 {. Black will defend the c2 -pawn with ...Nd4 . Here only Black has winning chances.}) 21... Kh8 22. Qf3 {White wants to give a perpetual with Qf6 + followed by Qg5 + and at the same time attacks the rook on a8 .} Kg7 23. Qg4+ Kh8 *

