1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ({White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose a6 and are in familiar territory after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {.}) ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights). (➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal!)}) ({➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.  ➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 8. Nd4 Bc5 {Nc3 Qb6 ) would only be left with the exotic Qb6 . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... Nc6 4. Bc4 {It's not clear to me what White is aiming for by developing the bishop to this square. The bishop does not pose any threats and can be attacked by the black pawns. According to my database, however, this position has been reached in several thousand games.} Nf6 ({Black prepares ...d7-d5 . Attacking the bishop from the other side is also good:} 4... a6 {with the idea ...b7-b5 .}) 5. d3 {The most common move. White prevents the tactic ...Nxe4 .} ({➤ After} 5. O-O {,} d5 {would be possible, but also Nxe4 Nxe4} 6. exd5 {, after which Black wins back the piece with good play.}) ({➤ After} 5. d4 {Black can also force the minor piece exchange with} Nxe4 $1 6. Nxe4 d5 {in addition to 5...d5 .}) ({➤} 5. e5 $6 {is not a good idea. Black can already win a pawn with} Ng4 6. Qe2 Qc7 7. Nb5 Qb8 {. White's best option now is} 8. d4 a6 9. Nd6+ Bxd6 10. exd6 Qxd6 {, but I don't see sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 5... d5 6. exd5 {Again the most common move.} ({Better is} 6. Bb5 {, after which White maintains equality. However, Black still has a comfortable game after} Bd7 {.}) 6... exd5 7. Bb5 Bd6 {Black has the slightly more active pieces and can secure the bishop pair at any time, as the bishop on b5 cannot retreat. White's opening treatment has been a failure.} *

