1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ({White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose a6 and are in familiar territory after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {.}) ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights). (➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal!)}) ({➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.  ➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 8. Nd4 Bc5 {Nc3 Qb6 ) would only be left with the exotic Qb6 . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... Nc6 4. Be2 {White makes a useful developing move and keeps the option d2 - d4 open. This move order is specifically directed against the Four Knights Sicilian.} {If you have the Taimanov Variation in your repertoire, you can opt for a6 , after which a transition is very likely.} Nd4 {This very rare move is the simplest solution for our repertoire. The knight blocks the d4 -square and thus denies White the possibility of transposing to the Open Sicilian.} (4... Nf6 {Anyone hoping for a transition to the Four Knights Sicilian will be disappointed. White does not play} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bb4 {, after which the Pawn Sacrifice Variation would be reached, but} 7. O-O $1 {. White wants to play d2-d4 next and Black can no longer develop the bishop to b4 .}) 5. Nxd4 {It is always worth checking the knight exchange, even if there are virtually no practical examples at this point.} cxd4 6. Nb5 e5 ({The defensive moves} 6... Qb6 {and Bc5 are worse because Black cannot react to} 7. c3 {with} a6 {.}) 7. c3 a6 8. Na3 Bxa3 {In exchange for the bishop pair Black gets the better pawn structure.} 9. bxa3 dxc3 10. dxc3 Nf6 {The position is equal. Black will castle next and then decide on a diagonal for the c8 -bishop.} *

