1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ({White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose a6 and are in familiar territory after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {.}) ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights). (➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal!)}) ({➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.  ➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 8. Nd4 Bc5 {Nc3 Qb6 ) would only be left with the exotic Qb6 . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... Nc6 4. g3 {White fianchettos the bishop. White's play is similar to the variation e4 c5 Nf3 e6 . Here the two queenside knights are already developed, which rather benefits Black: ...Nc6 is part of our setup anyway, while White usually plays without Nc3 there.} d5 {Black occupies the center. We are prepared to accept an isolated pawn.} 5. exd5 {After other moves, White is already in danger of being worse.} (5. d3 {, after} Nf6 {, leads to a position similar to our repertoire against the Closed Sicilian. For good reason, however, White there develops the knight to e2 and not to f3 . On f3 it stands in the way of the g2 -bishop and White cannot create any pressure against the pawn on d5 . Black achieves comfortable play with moves such as ...Be7 and ...O-O .}) ({Instead of 5...Nf6 there is also the possibility of transitioning to a King's Indian structure with} 5. d4 {Ne2} e5 {, which Stockfish already considers to be favorable for Black.}) 5... exd5 6. Bg2 ({The alternative} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Bg2 Bg4 {leads to a position which we examine via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 Nge2} 9. Nxc6 {g3 d5 exd5 exd5} d4 {cxd4} 10. Nxd4 {Nf6 Bg2 Bg4 and which was already covered in my first on the Four Knights Sicilian.}) 6... Nf6 ({In the chapter on the Closed Sicilian , I recommend} 6... d4 {in this position with the knight on e2 instead of f3 . This is also playable here, but leads to a slightly different type of position, because White can and should react with} 7. Qe2+ {and Ne4 .}) 7. O-O ({As on move six,} 7. d4 {would lead to positions we are familiar with after} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bg4 {.  After castling, d2-d4 would lead to a slightly better position for White, so it's time to prevent it.}) 7... d4 8. Re1+ {White wants to move the knight to e4 .} Be7 9. Ne4 ({In some games} 9. Ne2 {followed, but this looks very passive. After} O-O 10. d3 {Black prevents Bg5 with} h6 {. The f4 -square can only be occupied by one minor piece at a time. Black is slightly better.}) 9... Nxe4 {Black will later win a tempo by attacking the e4 -rook.} 10. Rxe4 O-O 11. d3 Bf5 12. Re1 Bf6 {Black wants to connect the rooks with ... Qd7 and then fight for the e-file. The bishop move prevents the liberating Ne5 . Black has the somewhat easier play, although the white position is very solid.} *

