1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ({White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose a6 and are in familiar territory after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {.}) ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights). (➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal!)}) ({➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.  ➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 8. Nd4 Bc5 {Nc3 Qb6 ) would only be left with the exotic Qb6 . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 ({If White wants to stay in Anti-Sicilian territory, this is the most common choice. White wants to capture on c6 and thus damage the black pawn structure on the queenside. White's play is reminiscent of the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 ) . There, however, White usually does not develop the knight to c3 so early. If White transitions to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {, Black has a choice:  ➤} Qc7 {is the main move in the Taimanov Variation.  ➤ a6 is a sideline in the Taimanov Sicilian.  ➤ Nf6 transitions to the Four Knights.  ➤ d6 is a variation of the Scheveningen Sicilian.}) 4... Nd4 ({Black avoids the exchange on c6 and exploits the knight position on c3 , because after the exchange on d4 it would be attacked. This position is more often reached via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 {Nf3 e6 .}) 5. Nxd4 {The exchange has been played in hundreds of games and even by some strong grandmasters. Nevertheless, it is a tactical mistake.} cxd4 6. Ne2 ({With} 6. Nb1 {White can maintain the material balance. However, this is at the expense of development and was obviously not the intention behind 5.Nxd4 . After} Nf6 {Black is slightly better, because the natural defensive move} 7. d3 $4 {fails to} Qa5+ {e5 is answered with Qa5 .}) 6... Qg5 {The double attack on b5 and g2 wins a pawn for Black.} 7. Bd3 Qxg2 {Black has only the queen in play, which has moreover advanced far into the opponent's camp. Nevertheless, White cannot create any dangerous threats.} 8. Ng3 {Threatening to trap the queen with 9.Bf1 and thus forcing Black's response.} Qh3 9. c3 {White has a lead in development and wants to open up the position.} Ne7 ({There are many good alternatives, e.g.} 9... Bc5 {.  Black should only avoid dxc3 , because after dxc3 the bishop on c1 comes to life.}) 10. cxd4 d5 ({White has won back the pawn, but the better pawn structure promises Black a long-term advantage. White can hardly avoid the exchange on e4 , because} 10... e5 {is met with Qh4 and the d4 -pawn is too weak. After the pawn exchange in the center, the white d-pawns are isolated and weak. Further problem childs in the white position are the bishop on c1 , which does not easily find its way into the game, and the centralized king.}) *

