1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ({White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose a6 and are in familiar territory after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {.}) ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights). (➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal!)}) ({➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.  ➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 8. Nd4 Bc5 {Nc3 Qb6 ) would only be left with the exotic Qb6 . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 ({If White wants to stay in Anti-Sicilian territory, this is the most common choice. White wants to capture on c6 and thus damage the black pawn structure on the queenside. White's play is reminiscent of the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 ) . There, however, White usually does not develop the knight to c3 so early. If White transitions to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {, Black has a choice:  ➤} Qc7 {is the main move in the Taimanov Variation.  ➤ a6 is a sideline in the Taimanov Sicilian.  ➤ Nf6 transitions to the Four Knights.  ➤ d6 is a variation of the Scheveningen Sicilian.}) 4... Nd4 ({Black avoids the exchange on c6 and exploits the knight position on c3 , because after the exchange on d4 it would be attacked. This position is more often reached via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 {Nf3 e6 .}) 5. Bc4 ({This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 5. Nxd4 {Bc4 e6 Nf3 . White removes the bishop from its exposed position on b5 . But it is not very safe on c4 either, as it is within reach of the black d- and b-pawns.}) 5... Nf6 6. O-O ({The advance} 6. e5 {is answered with the typical counterattack} d5 {. Black has an active position and is already slightly better.}) 6... a6 {This prepares the attack ... b7 -b5 and denies the white pieces the b5 -square, which is important in some lines for specific reasons.} ({The direct} 6... d5 $2 {is premature for tactical reasons:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Qh5 {. The knight on d5 cannot move because of the mate on f7 .} Be6 11. Re1 {. Threatening Rxe6+ and Bxd5 . White wins back the piece with an advantage.} Nf4 $2 {doesn't work here because} 12. Bb5+ Ke7 13. Qg5+ {.}) 7. d3 {The main move. White ignores Black's plan on the queenside and goes for rapid development.} b5 ({Black secures the bishop pair. That said, this is a useful move anyway, preparing the development of the bishop to b7 .  Again,} 7... d5 $2 {does not work, as can easily be checked with the already known sequence:} 8. exd5 exd5 9. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Qh5 Be6 12. Re1 {Black has no good defense and cannot hold on to the extra piece.}) 8. Bb3 Nxb3 9. axb3 Bb7 {Directed against the threat of Nxb5 . Black now wants to finish development with ... d7 - d6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O and would then have the better chances thanks to the pair of bishops.} 10. e5 {White tries to exploit their lead in development.} Nd5 11. Ne4 {The knight aims for the weakened d6 -square.} Be7 12. Bg5 {White continues to play energetically to prevent Black from castling, threatening Nd6 + and Nxc5 .} f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Bxf6 {The most common move. White wants to weaken their opponent's king position, but this is a misconception.} ({A move like} 14. Re1 {would be better, but after} O-O {Black has finished development and has good prospects with the bishop pair.}) 14... gxf6 {Next, Black wants to bring the king to safety on h8 . Then the half-open g-file can be used for pressure against the white king position. The mobile pawns in the center can be used to drive away the white knights. The game Hou Yifan-Ushenina , is a good example of how Black can increase the pressure. Ushenina later spoiled the reward for her efforts, but this no longer has anything to do with the opening battle.} *

