 2 ) The other approach is to prepare the opening of the position with d2-d4 . For this, of course, the d3 -bishop must first be moved away, which can be done White in several ways: ➤ Be2 is the most direct preparation of d2-d4 . However, the bishop is not well placed there. ➤ Re1 prepares the regrouping of the bishop to the better square f1 . ➤ With} 6... e5 {White vacates the e4 -square for the bishop.}) ({➤ The extravagant Nd5 is also intended to prepare d2-d4 . White is planning the regrouping c2-c3 , Bc2 and d2-d4 . We first look at the bishop regroupings and finally turn our attention to the fianchetto 7.b3 . After} 6... Ne7 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. c3 {the position opens up and White has the initiative.}) 7. Re1 {White centralizes the rook and prepares the retreat Bf1 . What could be more logical? However, the rook move has a serious drawback which is revealed by Black's reply.} g5 {An unusual situation. The knight on f3 no longer has a square to retreat to!} 8. g3 ({A better defense than} 8. h3 {and Kh1 . The knight remains active and Black can't open files on the kingside easily.}) 8... d6 {Development and central control. Nothing direct could yet be achieved on the kingside.} ({After} 8... g4 {of course} 9. Nh4 {was planned.}) 9. Bf1 g4 10. Nh4 Be7 11. Ng2 ({After} 11. Qxg4 $6 {, Black immediately wins back the pawn and has a strong attack. Qd1 (After Qh3 Nd4 , White cannot protect the c-pawn, because Bd3 is met with c4-+ .)} Bxh4 12. gxh4 Qxh4 {.}) 11... h5 {White must now constantly reckon with the pawn break ... h5 - h4 and the subsequent opening of the h-file. In addition, Black can now take care of development without interference: ... Bd7 , ... Qc7 , ... O-O-O and ... Nf6 is a good setup.   Black is slightly better and was able to slowly increase their advanage in the game Cobic,V-Martirosyan,H . I've annotated the game in the sample games section.} *

