y. If White transitions to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {, Black has a choice:  ➤} Qc7 {is the main move in the Taimanov Variation.  ➤ a6 is a sideline in the Taimanov Sicilian.  ➤ Nf6 transitions to the Four Knights.  ➤ d6 is a variation of the Scheveningen Sicilian.}) 4... Nd4 ({Black avoids the exchange on c6 and exploits the knight position on c3 , because after the exchange on d4 it would be attacked. This position is more often reached via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 {Nf3 e6 .}) 5. O-O {White has a lead in development and therefore does not have to worry about preserving the bishop pair. The knight on d4 prevents White from opening up the position with d2 - d4 , so it would be dangerous for Black to exchange it.   With castling, White has protected the pawn on g2 and is therefore ready to exchange on d4 .} a6 {Black gracefully declines the offered bishop pair. The attacked bishop now lacks a good escape square and merely obstructs the other white pieces.} ({After} 5... Nxb5 6. Nxb5 a6 7. Nc3 {White is ready to open up the position with d2-d4 . Black has not yet developed a piece and must play very precisely to avoid being caught in a strong attack.}) 6. Bd3 ({Still the best square for the bishop. In comparison with} 6. Be2 {White is now threatening to exchange on d4 again, because after ...cxd4 the knight can retreat to e2 . However, the bishop will probably have to move again, because White would like to open up the position with d2-d4 .}) 6... Nc6 {Don't worry, we'll take care of the other pieces too! Although White now has a huge lead in development, they have no direct way of attacking or opening up the position. The out-of-place bishop on d3 prevents White from developing the queenside naturally. There are two fundamentally different approaches to solving this problem:} ({1 ) White could leave the bishop on d3 and develop its dark-squared colleague to b2 . b3 is the most popular move in practice and leads to a closed position. 2 ) The other approach is to prepare the opening of the position with d2-d4 . For this, of course, the d3 -bishop must first be moved away, which can be done White in several ways: ➤ Be2 is the most direct preparation of d2-d4 . However, the bishop is not well placed there. ➤ Re1 prepares the regrouping of the bishop to the better square f1 . ➤ With} 6... e5 {White vacates the e4 -square for the bishop.}) ({➤ The extravagant Nd5 is also intended to prepare d2-d4 . White is planning the regrouping c2-c3 , Bc2 and d2-d4 . We first look at the bishop regroupings and finally turn our attention to the fianchetto 7.b3 . After} 6... Ne7 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. c3 {the position opens up and White has the initiative.}) 7. e5 {White gains space and vacates the square e4 for the knight or the bishop.} d5 (7... d6 {is equally good and probably leads to a transposition. However, White would have the additional option .}) (7... f5 {is an interesting alternative that leads to sharp play. Black takes control of the e4 -square away from the white pieces.}) 8. exd6 {This is now forced, because otherwise the black pawns in the center would take away key squares from the white pieces and the e5 -pawn would be cut off from support.} Bxd6 {Black is now ready to catch up on their development deficit. White does not succeed in thwarting this plan.} 9. Re1 ({➤} 9. Ne4 {is similar to our main variation – Black could continue development with Nf6 or first prevent the bishop from being exchanged with} Be7 {.}) ({➤} 9. Be4 {is of no use here. Black simply protects the knight on c6 with} Nge7 {and White is not yet ready for d2-d4 . After} 10. Re1 {even} O-O {is possible, because the typical bishop sacrifice} 11. Bxh7+ $2 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ {doesn't work here, because the attack doesn't continue after} Kg6 $1 {.}) 9... Nf6 10. Ne4 {White would prefer to place the bishop on e4 and then play d2 - d4 . To do this, the knight f6 must first be exchanged.} O-O {Black loses no time. White could now secure the bishop pair, but Black would then have good central control and active pieces.} (10... Nxe4 $6 {would be cooperative. After} 11. Bxe4 {and d2-d4 White has the initiative.}) ({Possible, but a loss of time, is} 10... Be7 {. Here, too, White tries to force an opening of the position with d2-d4 using} 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Be4 Bd7 13. c3 {.}) 11. Nxf6+ (11. Nxd6 Qxd6 12. b3 e5 $1 {happened in the rapid game Shevchenko-Volokitin . Black plays ...Re8 or ...Bg4 next and is at least not worse.}) 11... Qxf6 12. Be4 {Finally White has managed to move the bishop out of its disadvantageous position and is threatening an exchange on c6 , which would weaken the black pawn structure.} Nd4 {We already know this idea from move four! Black defends against Bxc6 and at the same time prevents d2 - d4 . The exchange of knights that soon follows also means that White has no attack on the kingside.   The bishop on e4 still puts pressure on the b7 -pawn, but this problem can be easily solved by ... Rb8 . Black could then exchange the active white bishop with a move of the b-pawn followed by ... Bb7 . The position is equal. In the game Safarli-Kukelko , Black had no problems securing half a point against his 300 points higher rated opponent.} *

