1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ({White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose a6 and are in familiar territory after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {.}) ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights). (➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal!)}) ({➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.  ➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 8. Nd4 Bc5 {Nc3 Qb6 ) would only be left with the exotic Qb6 . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 ({If White wants to stay in Anti-Sicilian territory, this is the most common choice. White wants to capture on c6 and thus damage the black pawn structure on the queenside. White's play is reminiscent of the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 ) . There, however, White usually does not develop the knight to c3 so early. If White transitions to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {, Black has a choice:  ➤} Qc7 {is the main move in the Taimanov Variation.  ➤ a6 is a sideline in the Taimanov Sicilian.  ➤ Nf6 transitions to the Four Knights.  ➤ d6 is a variation of the Scheveningen Sicilian.}) 4... Nd4 ({Black avoids the exchange on c6 and exploits the knight position on c3 , because after the exchange on d4 it would be attacked. This position is more often reached via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 {Nf3 e6 .}) 5. O-O {White has a lead in development and therefore does not have to worry about preserving the bishop pair. The knight on d4 prevents White from opening up the position with d2 - d4 , so it would be dangerous for Black to exchange it.   With castling, White has protected the pawn on g2 and is therefore ready to exchange on d4 .} a6 {Black gracefully declines the offered bishop pair. The attacked bishop now lacks a good escape square and merely obstructs the other white pieces.} ({After} 5... Nxb5 6. Nxb5 a6 7. Nc3 {White is ready to open up the position with d2-d4 . Black has not yet developed a piece and must play very precisely to avoid being caught in a strong attack.}) 6. Bd3 ({Still the best square for the bishop. In comparison with} 6. Be2 {White is now threatening to exchange on d4 again, because after ...cxd4 the knight can retreat to e2 . However, the bishop will probably have to move again, because White would like to open up the position with d2-d4 .}) 6... Nc6 {Don't worry, we'll take care of the other pieces too! Although White now has a huge lead in development, they have no direct way of attacking or opening up the position. The out-of-place bishop on d3 prevents White from developing the queenside naturally. There are two fundamentally different approaches to solving this problem:} ({1 ) White could leave the bishop on d3 and develop its dark-squared colleague to b2 . b3 is the most popular move in practice and leads to a closed position. 2 ) The other approach is to prepare the opening of the position with d2-d4 . For this, of course, the d3 -bishop must first be moved away, which can be done White in several ways: ➤ Be2 is the most direct preparation of d2-d4 . However, the bishop is not well placed there. ➤ Re1 prepares the regrouping of the bishop to the better square f1 . ➤ With} 6... e5 {White vacates the e4 -square for the bishop.}) ({➤ The extravagant Nd5 is also intended to prepare d2-d4 . White is planning the regrouping c2-c3 , Bc2 and d2-d4 . We first look at the bishop regroupings and finally turn our attention to the fianchetto 7.b3 . After} 6... Ne7 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. c3 {the position opens up and White has the initiative.}) 7. Nd5 {The knight move looks like a sharp Sicilian sacrifice, but actually follows a slow positional plan: White clears the way for the occupation of the center with c2 - c3 , Bc2 and d2 - d4 . The knight normally goes to e3 .} g5 ({The opening principles continue to be cheerfully disregarded. The threat is} 7... Z0 8. g4 {Ne1} exd5 {. Apart from that, the flank attack pursues the idea of preventing White from occupying the center with d2-d4 .}) ({After} 7... exd5 8. exd5 {White immediately wins back the piece, e.g.} Nce7 $6 9. d6 Nc6 $6 10. Re1+ {and Black has no choice but to move a piece to the enemy-controlled e7 -square.}) (7... d6 {is the most common move. Now Black is threatening to capture the knight.} 8. Ne3 Nf6 9. c3 {White pursues the plan described above. Next comes Bc2 and d2-d4 . The space advantage gives White the more comfortable play.}) 8. Nxg5 {This is indeed a genuine piece sacrifice! But as the analysis shows, White will also have to solve difficult problems in the following complications.} exd5 ({Of course not} 8... Qxg5 $2 9. Nc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 {.}) 9. Nxf7 {This is too much.} Kxf7 10. Qh5+ Ke7 11. exd5 Nf6 12. Qe2+ ({After} 12. Qh4 Nb4 {, the white attack is not strong enough either.}) 12... Kd6 13. dxc6 Kc7 {Black's king is safe. In fact, it is its white counterpart that will come under attack soon. Black will play ... Rg8 and ... Bd6 and also bring the light-squared bishop into the attack via b7 or c6 .} ({After} 13... Kxc6 14. b4 {White still has some initiative.}) *

