 2 ) The other approach is to prepare the opening of the position with d2-d4 . For this, of course, the d3 -bishop must first be moved away, which can be done White in several ways: ➤ Be2 is the most direct preparation of d2-d4 . However, the bishop is not well placed there. ➤ Re1 prepares the regrouping of the bishop to the better square f1 . ➤ With} 6... e5 {White vacates the e4 -square for the bishop.}) ({➤ The extravagant Nd5 is also intended to prepare d2-d4 . White is planning the regrouping c2-c3 , Bc2 and d2-d4 . We first look at the bishop regroupings and finally turn our attention to the fianchetto 7.b3 . After} 6... Ne7 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. c3 {the position opens up and White has the initiative.}) 7. Nd5 {The knight move looks like a sharp Sicilian sacrifice, but actually follows a slow positional plan: White clears the way for the occupation of the center with c2 - c3 , Bc2 and d2 - d4 . The knight normally goes to e3 .} g5 ({The opening principles continue to be cheerfully disregarded. The threat is} 7... Z0 8. g4 {Ne1} exd5 {. Apart from that, the flank attack pursues the idea of preventing White from occupying the center with d2-d4 .}) ({After} 7... exd5 8. exd5 {White immediately wins back the piece, e.g.} Nce7 $6 9. d6 Nc6 $6 10. Re1+ {and Black has no choice but to move a piece to the enemy-controlled e7 -square.}) (7... d6 {is the most common move. Now Black is threatening to capture the knight.} 8. Ne3 Nf6 9. c3 {White pursues the plan described above. Next comes Bc2 and d2-d4 . The space advantage gives White the more comfortable play.}) 8. Ne3 {The knight moves to safety and at the same time prevents ... g5 - g4 .} h5 {Black renews control of g4 .} 9. h3 {The attempt to prevent ... g5 - g4 backfires. Black now has a break for opening lines on the kingside.} g4 10. hxg4 hxg4 11. Nxg4 d6 {White is helpless against the looming black attack. Sooner or later the black queen will reach the h-file and the other pieces will also be transferred to the kingside.   With 11...d6 Black prepares ... e6 - e5 . The c8 -bishop, like the rook on h8 , would then be a very strong piece even in its starting position!} *

