y. If White transitions to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {, Black has a choice:  ➤} Qc7 {is the main move in the Taimanov Variation.  ➤ a6 is a sideline in the Taimanov Sicilian.  ➤ Nf6 transitions to the Four Knights.  ➤ d6 is a variation of the Scheveningen Sicilian.}) 4... Nd4 ({Black avoids the exchange on c6 and exploits the knight position on c3 , because after the exchange on d4 it would be attacked. This position is more often reached via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 {Nf3 e6 .}) 5. O-O {White has a lead in development and therefore does not have to worry about preserving the bishop pair. The knight on d4 prevents White from opening up the position with d2 - d4 , so it would be dangerous for Black to exchange it.   With castling, White has protected the pawn on g2 and is therefore ready to exchange on d4 .} a6 {Black gracefully declines the offered bishop pair. The attacked bishop now lacks a good escape square and merely obstructs the other white pieces.} ({After} 5... Nxb5 6. Nxb5 a6 7. Nc3 {White is ready to open up the position with d2-d4 . Black has not yet developed a piece and must play very precisely to avoid being caught in a strong attack.}) 6. Bd3 ({Still the best square for the bishop. In comparison with} 6. Be2 {White is now threatening to exchange on d4 again, because after ...cxd4 the knight can retreat to e2 . However, the bishop will probably have to move again, because White would like to open up the position with d2-d4 .}) 6... Nc6 {Don't worry, we'll take care of the other pieces too! Although White now has a huge lead in development, they have no direct way of attacking or opening up the position. The out-of-place bishop on d3 prevents White from developing the queenside naturally. There are two fundamentally different approaches to solving this problem:} ({1 ) White could leave the bishop on d3 and develop its dark-squared colleague to b2 . b3 is the most popular move in practice and leads to a closed position. 2 ) The other approach is to prepare the opening of the position with d2-d4 . For this, of course, the d3 -bishop must first be moved away, which can be done White in several ways: ➤ Be2 is the most direct preparation of d2-d4 . However, the bishop is not well placed there. ➤ Re1 prepares the regrouping of the bishop to the better square f1 . ➤ With} 6... e5 {White vacates the e4 -square for the bishop.}) ({➤ The extravagant Nd5 is also intended to prepare d2-d4 . White is planning the regrouping c2-c3 , Bc2 and d2-d4 . We first look at the bishop regroupings and finally turn our attention to the fianchetto 7.b3 . After} 6... Ne7 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. c3 {the position opens up and White has the initiative.}) 7. b3 {The most popular move. As we have seen, it was not easy for White to enforce the opening of the position with d2 - d4 . It is therefore logical to choose a different setup.} g6 {I like developing the bishop to g7 , because from there the bishop controls the important central squares e5 and d4 . If the bishop goes to e7 instead, e4 - e5 is often an option for White.} 8. Bb2 Bg7 9. Re1 d6 ({Black has managed to keep the position closed and the center under control. White has not been able to exploit their lead in development and prevent Black from developing. Black therefore doesn't have any worries. For example:   A )} 9... e5 {The crowbar approach leads nowhere for White: dxe5} 10. Na4 Qc7 11. Nxc5 Nge7 12. Bf1 b6 13. Nd3 f6 {The mass of pawns in the center takes away squares from the white pieces. Black is more comfortable.}) ({) Na4} 9... e5 {[%eval 0,0] Easiest. An early opening in the center is now ruled out and Black can finish development with ...Nge7 and ...O-O .}) *

