1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 {White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose 3... a6 and are in familiar territory after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .} ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights).}) ({➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal! ➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.}) ({➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nc3 Qb6 {) would only be left with the exotic . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. White could now transition to the Kan Variation with d4 ; however, the attempts g3 and Be2 , which leave open a later transition to the Open Sicilian, are trickier. In addition, we look at a4 , with which White wants to stop Black's play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 .} 4. a4 {This prevents Black from playing ... b7 - b5 . The drawback is that the square b4 is weakened.} d5 {Occupies the center and offers a transition to a position with an isolated queen's pawn. For this, the insertion of 3...a6  4.a4 is very favourable for Black.} ({In the analogous position with the white knight on e2 instead of f3 I recommended} 4... Nf6 {, but this is out of the question here because of} 5. e5 {.}) 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 Nf6 ({If the two a-pawns were still on their respective starting squares, White could now secure an advantage with Bb5+ and O-O . More often} 6... c4 {was played here, which relieves the tension in the center. However, White benefits more from this: After} 7. g3 {followed by Bg2 and O-O , the d5 -pawn comes under pressure.}) 7. Be2 {White continues development and for the time being does not worry about the situation in the center.} ({Or} 7. Bg5 {. White is threatening Bxf6 , winning the d5 -pawn.} Be6 8. Be2 Nc6 9. dxc5 ({(After} 9. O-O h6 {is strong, because} 10. Bxf6 $6 Qxf6 11. dxc5 Rd8 $1 {∓ and Bxc5 won't earn White anything.)}) 9... Bxc5 10. O-O {Black could now transpose to the analysis of 7.Be2 with} O-O {, or defend the d-pawn with Be7!? = .}) 7... Nc6 8. O-O Be6 ({Prophylactically defending the d5-pawn.} 8... Be7 {, as I played once, is a little less accurate.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Bg5 Be6 11. Bxf6 {and now Black should take back with the pawn, because} Qxf6 $2 {fails to} 12. Nxd5 {.}) 9. Bg5 {That doesn't gain White anything.} h6 10. Bxf6 ({Instead, best is the modest} 10. Be3 {.}) ({Or} 10. Bh4 $6 g5 $1 11. Bg3 Nh5 {.}) 10... Qxf6 11. dxc5 Rd8 {Black first defends the d-pawn and only captures on c5 on the next move. The bishop pair and the more harmonious piece setup give Black a clear advantage.} *

