1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 {White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose 3... a6 and are in familiar territory after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .} ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights).}) ({➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal! ➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.}) ({➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nc3 Qb6 {) would only be left with the exotic . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. White could now transition to the Kan Variation with d4 ; however, the attempts g3 and Be2 , which leave open a later transition to the Open Sicilian, are trickier. In addition, we look at a4 , with which White wants to stop Black's play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 .} 4. Be2 {A rare but poisonous move which has been played with great success in recent years by the Chinese top GM Wei Yi. The idea is simple: White makes natural developing moves and can switch to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 at a desired moment. Black, on the other hand, is less flexible compared to the situation where White plays the Open Sicilian directly.} ({For comparison: After} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {Black usually continues with} Qc7 {and after} 6. Be2 {,} Nf6 {is the main move. A transition to this line is hardly possible here, because as long as the knight is still on f3 , ...Nf6 is out of the question due to e4-e5 .}) 4... b5 {As with 4.g3 , I recommend quick counterplay against the e4 -pawn. Black prepares ...Bb7 and ... b5 -b4 .} ({If you are prepared for the Taimanov Variation, you could go for} 4... Nc6 {here, e.g.} 5. d4 ({(I examine the position after 5.O-O via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6} 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O {a6 Bd3} Nc6 7. Be2 {, see here .)}) 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qc7 {. This is one of the main lines in the Taimanov Sicilian and is usually reached via the move order e4 c5} 7. Nf3 {e6 d4 cxd4} Nd4 {Nc6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 a6 .}) 5. d4 {White transposes to the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 ({This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 6. Nxd4 {a6 Nc3 b5 Be2 . So, strictly speaking, it goes beyond the scope of this course. Nevertheless, I will analyze it here, because this position is not necessarily included in a Kan repertoire: Instead of b5 ,} Qc7 {is the more popular choice. If White prefers to recapture with the queen on d4 instead of the knight,} 7. O-O Bb7 {d4 cxd4 Qxd4 is the more precise move order because it reduces Black's options.}) 6... Bb7 {Black is threatening to win a pawn with ... b5 - b4 followed by ... Bxe4 .} 7. Bf3 ({White defends the e-pawn. White's position is reminiscent of the line} 7. g3 {b5 Bg2 Bb7 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 , but is less harmonious: the bishop on f3 blocks the f-pawn as well as the queen's path to the kingside and could itself be attacked by a knight on e5 .}) (7. a3 {is too slow to pose any problems for Black. Black reaches a good position with natural developing moves, e.g.} Qc7 8. O-O Nf6 {and again White has to take care of the pawn e4 .}) ({More critical is the pawn sacrifice} 7. O-O {!? , which we consider via the move order O-O Bb7 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 .}) 7... Ne7 {A typical idea. The knight could go to g6 and later to e5 , exploiting the unfavorable bishop position on f3 . In addition ... Nbc6 is prepared, because Black could then recapture with the knight if White exchanges. There are many good alternatives for Black; however, it's worth cautioning against developing the knight to f6 , because then White often gains an advantage with e4-e5 .} (7... Nf6 $2 8. e5 $1 {already leads to a winning position for White.}) (7... Qc7 8. O-O Nf6 $2 9. e5 $1 {is not much better.}) 8. O-O Nbc6 {Challenging the knight on d4 . If White exchanges on c6 , Black recaptures with the knight. If White leaves the knight on d4 , Black can exchange themselves and activate the other knight via c6 . And if White moves the knight away, the e7 -knight will find its way into the game via g6 or c6 (after ... Ne5 ). Black has no worries.} ({Be3 Nxd4 Bxd4 Nc6 is a comfortable equalizer. However, Black could also have waited with the exchange on d4 , e.g. 9...Rc8 . Nb3?! Ne5 already looks a bit better for Black. Nxc6 Nxc6} 8... e5 {Qc7 happened in Chumfa-Bacrot, 2014. The pawn e5 is prone to weakness, so Black has the better chances.}) *

