1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 {White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose 3... a6 and are in familiar territory after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .} ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights).}) ({➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal! ➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.}) ({➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nc3 Qb6 {) would only be left with the exotic . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. White could now transition to the Kan Variation with d4 ; however, the attempts g3 and Be2 , which leave open a later transition to the Open Sicilian, are trickier. In addition, we look at a4 , with which White wants to stop Black's play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 .} 4. Be2 {A rare but poisonous move which has been played with great success in recent years by the Chinese top GM Wei Yi. The idea is simple: White makes natural developing moves and can switch to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 at a desired moment. Black, on the other hand, is less flexible compared to the situation where White plays the Open Sicilian directly.} ({For comparison: After} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {Black usually continues with} Qc7 {and after} 6. Be2 {,} Nf6 {is the main move. A transition to this line is hardly possible here, because as long as the knight is still on f3 , ...Nf6 is out of the question due to e4-e5 .}) 4... b5 {As with 4.g3 , I recommend quick counterplay against the e4 -pawn. Black prepares ...Bb7 and ... b5 -b4 .} ({If you are prepared for the Taimanov Variation, you could go for} 4... Nc6 {here, e.g.} 5. d4 ({(I examine the position after 5.O-O via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6} 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O {a6 Bd3} Nc6 7. Be2 {, see here .)}) 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qc7 {. This is one of the main lines in the Taimanov Sicilian and is usually reached via the move order e4 c5} 7. Nf3 {e6 d4 cxd4} Nd4 {Nc6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 a6 .}) 5. O-O {White continues the game of cat and mouse: the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 is still in play.} Bb7 {Black is threatening to win a pawn with ... b5 - b4 followed by ... Bxe4 .} 6. d4 ({Opening up the position is the only dangerous attempt for White. The setup of the white minor pieces does not match the closed character of the position after} 6. d3 {. Black gets a good position with any developing moves. I like the setup} Nc6 7. Re1 Qc7 {followed by ...Bd6 and ...Nge7 .}) 6... cxd4 7. Qxd4 {An original approach. The queen defends the pawn e4 .} Nc6 {This is of course the drawback of the centralized queen. Black wins a tempo.} 8. Qe3 ({This queen position has several advantages: it supports a possible knight sacrifice on d5 (e.g. after} 8. b4 $2 {9.Nd5!); it vacates the d1 -square for the rook; it supports playing on the dark squares with e4-e5 .}) 8... Qc7 {White had been threatening Nd5 , which the queen move prevents. In addition, Black fights for control of the e5 -square.} 9. Rd1 ({White thereby renews the threat of Nd5 . After} 9. Nd5 $6 exd5 10. exd5+ Nce7 {the queen on c7 prevents White from winning back the piece with d5-d6 .}) 9... Ne5 ({An improvement on previous tournament practice. Black thus prevents the piece sacrifice Nd5 and prepares the active development of the f8 -bishop.} 9... Nf6 $2 {allows} 10. a4 b4 11. Nd5 $1 {with an attack. After} exd5 12. exd5+ Ne7 {White wins back the piece with} 13. d6 {.}) ({Also after} 9... d6 $6 {Black is not safe. An impressive demonstration of the dangers is the game Ganguly-Budisavljevic, 2021:} 10. b4 $1 {.} ({(After} 10. a4 {,} b4 {would have come. Now Black cannot prevent a2-a4 .)}) 10... Be7 $2 ({(After} 10... Nxb4 $2 11. Rb1 {the white attack is crashing through, )}) ({(but better was} 10... Nf6 11. a4 Nxb4 {.)}) 11. a4 Nxb4 12. Nd4 $1 bxa4 13. Rxa4 Nc6 14. Rc4 {Black can no longer free themselves from the pressure.}) 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 {The queen is not badly placed here. Specifically, Black is threatening ... b5 - b4 , winning the e-pawn.} 11. Qb6 ({On e3 the queen was in the way of the c1 -bishop. With} 11. Qb6 {White wins a tempo with the attack on the b7 -bishop and clears the way for their own bishop.}) 11... Bc6 12. Be3 {Black had been threatening ... Bc5 or ... b5 - b4 followed by ... Bc5 , after which the queen on b6 would be in trouble.} Nf6 {Black is threatening to win the e-pawn. The position is very tactical.} ({The direct} 12... b4 $2 {fails due to the combination} 13. Nd5 $1 exd5 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. Rxd5 $1 Qxd5 16. Bf3 {, when White wins back the rook and has all the positional trumps.}) 13. Bd4 {It is best to drive the queen out of its centralized position.} Qb8 {The exchange of queens is now forced as the pawn on e4 is under attack.} 14. Qxb8+ Rxb8 15. f3 Be7 {Black will soon castle and could then press with ... Rfc8 along the c-file. White could open the a-file for the rook with a2 - a4 . White is then slightly more active, but this is a rather symbolic advantage. The black position is very solid.} *

