on the dark squares with e4-e5 .}) 8... Qc7 {White had been threatening Nd5 , which the queen move prevents. In addition, Black fights for control of the e5 -square.} 9. Rd1 ({White thereby renews the threat of Nd5 . After} 9. Nd5 $6 exd5 10. exd5+ Nce7 {the queen on c7 prevents White from winning back the piece with d5-d6 .}) 9... Ne5 ({An improvement on previous tournament practice. Black thus prevents the piece sacrifice Nd5 and prepares the active development of the f8 -bishop.} 9... Nf6 $2 {allows} 10. a4 b4 11. Nd5 $1 {with an attack. After} exd5 12. exd5+ Ne7 {White wins back the piece with} 13. d6 {.}) ({Also after} 9... d6 $6 {Black is not safe. An impressive demonstration of the dangers is the game Ganguly-Budisavljevic, 2021:} 10. b4 $1 {.} ({(After} 10. a4 {,} b4 {would have come. Now Black cannot prevent a2-a4 .)}) 10... Be7 $2 ({(After} 10... Nxb4 $2 11. Rb1 {the white attack is crashing through, )}) ({(but better was} 10... Nf6 11. a4 Nxb4 {.)}) 11. a4 Nxb4 12. Nd4 $1 bxa4 13. Rxa4 Nc6 14. Rc4 {Black can no longer free themselves from the pressure.}) 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 {The queen is not badly placed here. Specifically, Black is threatening ... b5 - b4 , winning the e-pawn.} 11. Qf3 {White prepares developing the bishop to f4 .} Bd6 ({A deep move whose idea only becomes apparent a few moves later. Black provokes g2-g3 . Playable is also} 11... b4 12. Bf4 Qc5 13. Nb1 Nf6 14. Nd2 Be7 {.}) 12. g3 Be7 {White had been threatening Bf4 , winning a piece. Hence the bishop must move again.} 13. Bf4 Qc5 14. Qd3 Nf6 ({Now it becomes clear why Black played} 14... Bd6 {first and not Be7 directly. If the white pawn were still on g2 , White could now gain an advantage with e4-e5 .}) 15. Bf3 ({White is threatening e4-e5 . After} 15. e5 $6 {Black not only saves the d7 -pawn with} Qc6 16. f3 Ng4 {, but also gets attacking chances. The threat is ...Qb6+ .}) 15... Qc6 {Black defends against the threat e4 - e5 and is now ready for short castling. The position is complex, but roughly equal.} *

