1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 {White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose 3... a6 and are in familiar territory after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .} ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights).}) ({➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal! ➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.}) ({➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nc3 Qb6 {) would only be left with the exotic . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. White could now transition to the Kan Variation with d4 ; however, the attempts g3 and Be2 , which leave open a later transition to the Open Sicilian, are trickier. In addition, we look at a4 , with which White wants to stop Black's play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 .} 4. Be2 {A rare but poisonous move which has been played with great success in recent years by the Chinese top GM Wei Yi. The idea is simple: White makes natural developing moves and can switch to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 at a desired moment. Black, on the other hand, is less flexible compared to the situation where White plays the Open Sicilian directly.} ({For comparison: After} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {Black usually continues with} Qc7 {and after} 6. Be2 {,} Nf6 {is the main move. A transition to this line is hardly possible here, because as long as the knight is still on f3 , ...Nf6 is out of the question due to e4-e5 .}) 4... b5 {As with 4.g3 , I recommend quick counterplay against the e4 -pawn. Black prepares ...Bb7 and ... b5 -b4 .} ({If you are prepared for the Taimanov Variation, you could go for} 4... Nc6 {here, e.g.} 5. d4 ({(I examine the position after 5.O-O via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6} 5. Bb5 Nd4 6. O-O {a6 Bd3} Nc6 7. Be2 {, see here .)}) 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qc7 {. This is one of the main lines in the Taimanov Sicilian and is usually reached via the move order e4 c5} 7. Nf3 {e6 d4 cxd4} Nd4 {Nc6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 a6 .}) 5. O-O {White continues the game of cat and mouse: the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 is still in play.} Bb7 {Black is threatening to win a pawn with ... b5 - b4 followed by ... Bxe4 .} 6. d4 ({Opening up the position is the only dangerous attempt for White. The setup of the white minor pieces does not match the closed character of the position after} 6. d3 {. Black gets a good position with any developing moves. I like the setup} Nc6 7. Re1 Qc7 {followed by ...Bd6 and ...Nge7 .}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 ({White sacrifices a pawn. This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 7. Nxd4 {a6 Nc3 b5 Be2 Bb7 O-O . So, strictly speaking, it goes beyond the scope of this course. (Nevertheless, I will analyze it here, because this position is not necessarily included in a Kan repertoire: Instead of 5...b5 , 5....Qc7 is the more popular choice.)}) 7... b4 {I think it's best to accept the pawn sacrifice, even if the game now becomes very sharp. With this move, Black can not only win an important central pawn, but also enable the development of the knight to f6 , which is currently made difficult by the move e4-e5 .} ({The position after} 7... Qc7 {is often reached via the move order e4 c5} 8. Nf3 {e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b5 O-O Bb7 . But I am a little skeptical about Black's chances; White has a big lead in development.}) 8. Na4 {This is of course not the ideal square for the knight, but at least it prevents ... Bc5 and takes aim at the weakened square b6 .} Bxe4 9. Bf3 ({White exchanges Black's only developed piece. Weaker is} 9. Re1 $6 Nc6 {, because now} 10. Bf3 $6 {no longer works so well due to} Bxf3 {and White cannot recapture with the queen anymore.}) 9... Bxf3 ({The alternative} 9... Nf6 {is also playable, but after} 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Re1 d5 {, Black has not yet solved all problems after the novelty} 12. c4 $1 {.}) 10. Qxf3 d5 {Black defends against the threat of Qxa8 and gains space in the center. A drawback is that the e6 -pawn is less reliably protected – piece sacrifices on this square could become dangerous.} 11. Re1 {Other moves are less direct. White is already threatening Nxe6 with a strong attack.} Nf6 {The only good move. Black must take care of development as soon as possible.} (11... Be7 $2 {prevents the knight sacrifice, but not the rook sacrifice on e6 :} 12. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 13. Nxe6 {followed by Nxg7+ gives White a decisive attack.}) 12. Bg5 ({White increases the pressure by renewing the threat of a knight sacrifice on e6 .} 12. Nxe6 $2 fxe6 13. Rxe6+ Kf7 {leads to nothing.}) 12... Nbd7 ({It is important to remember this subtlety. Black stabilizes the knight on f6 . It looks like castling has priority, but} 12... Be7 $2 {allows two versions of the sacrifice on e6 , which give White a strong attack. White can either sacrifice the rook on e6 , or...} 13. Bxf6 ({(} 13. Rxe6 $5 fxe6 14. Nxe6 Qa5 {and now after} 15. Re1 $1 {it is not easy to get the king to safety.)}) 13... Bxf6 14. Nc5 $1 Bxd4 15. Nxe6 $1 {... the a4 -knight! White wins back the sacrificed material after} fxe6 16. Rxe6+ Kd7 17. Qxd5+ Kc7 18. Qxa8 {and still has attacking chances.}) 13. Nxe6 {The piece sacrifice is not enough for more than perpetual check.} fxe6 14. Rxe6+ Kf7 15. Rae1 Kg8 ({Black gets out of the pin. This is more accurate than} 15... h6 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Nb6 Ra7 18. Nxd5 {with an attack.}) 16. Qf5 {White prepares perpetual check. There is nothing better.} h6 {Black can't avoid the perpetual either.} 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Rxf6 gxf6 (18... Qxf6 $2 {loses material after} 19. Qxd5+ Kh7 20. Qxa8 {.}) 19. Qe6+ Kh7 20. Qf5+ Kg8 {Draw by perpetual check.} *

