{exf5 O-O∓ is no better for White. Black can prepare the exchange of the light-squared bishops with ...Qd7 , after which the white king position is endangered. Black also has an advantage on the queenside and in the center.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 {White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose 3... a6 and are in familiar territory after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .} ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights).}) ({➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal! ➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.}) ({➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nc3 Qb6 {) would only be left with the exotic . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. White could now transition to the Kan Variation with d4 ; however, the attempts g3 and Be2 , which leave open a later transition to the Open Sicilian, are trickier. In addition, we look at a4 , with which White wants to stop Black's play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 .} 4. g3 ({White decides against the transposition to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 {. However, d2-d4 remains to be reckoned with. White keeps their options open and first develops the bishop to g2 . This is reminiscent of the Closed Sicilian, but there White usually places the knight on e2 , where it does not block the bishop's diagonal.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this move to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} 5. Bg2 Bb7 {Black is threatening to win a pawn with ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d3 ({We deal with the transposition to the Open Sicilian after} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 {in detail via the move order Nc3 e6 Nge2 a6 g3 b5 Bg2 Bb7 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 .}) 6... d6 ({Takes control of e5 and thus prepares ...Nf6 . A difference to the analogous position with the knight on e2 instead of f3 is that the direct} 6... Nf6 $6 {is not good because of} 7. e5 {.}) 7. O-O Nf6 {The black moves are easy. Next on the agenda is ...Be7 and ...O-O . Meanwhile, it's not easy for White to make progress. The knight on f3 blocks the advance of the f-pawn, which would be the natural plan in similar positions in the Closed Sicilian. In practice, White usually chooses between one of the following two approaches:  ➤ preparing f2-f4 by Ng5 or Nh4 ,  ➤ opening the position with e4-e5 (either directly or after the preparatory ) .} 8. Ng5 {This is the most popular move, which has also been played by many strong grandmasters. White clears the way for the f-pawn. To me, this seems a rather dubious concept. White loses a lot of time and the advance of the f-pawn is not particularly dangerous.} h6 9. Nh3 Nc6 ({Or first} 9... Be7 {, because here the tactic} 10. e5 $2 {fails to} Bxg2 11. exf6 Bxh3 {.}) 10. f4 ({That was the idea behind} 10. Ng5 {.}) 10... Be7 {The position is very complex and offers both sides a variety of plans. Black can safely castle next, because the white attack on the kingside is not dangerous. If White plays g3 - g4 , Black could stop a further advance of the g-pawn with ... Nh7 . However, it is also quite possible to wait with castling. Long castling is also still an option! In principle, Black is interested in opening up the position because the black pieces are better placed. On the queenside, similar to the King's Indian Attack, Black could move the pawns forward and play to open files. In the center ... d6 - d5 is possible, but usually not very good, because White answers with e4 - e5 . An interesting idea, however, is the preparatory ... b5 - b4 , ... e6 - e5 and only then ... d6 - d5 . On the kingside the pawn break ... f7 - f5 comes into consideration – especially if White has played g3 - g4 and Black ... Nh7 . The engines see Black as having a slight advantage here and I believe this assessment is correct. However, a lot can still happen in a practical game.} ({f5 This is the most common move in practice and was also discussed in the most high-profile game in this position, Zherebukh-Caruana, 2018. Caruana showed the way to Black's advantage.  In the first high-class game of the 8.Ng5 -line, there followed} 10... e5 {After that the position remains closed and White can prepare an attack on the kingside with lengthy maneuvers. Simagin-Portisch .}) ({The alternative is} 10... b4 {First the knight is driven away so that it no longer controls the d5 -square.} 11. Ne2 {exf5! Rxf5 O-O∓ The black pieces are positioned more harmoniously. A queenside attack is now a logical plan to follow. Caruana exploited his advantage in a convincing manner. Here you can find the rest of the game with my annotations.}) *

