1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 {White does not reveal their cards. White could forgo d2-d4 and play a variation of the Closed Sicilian. However, the transition to the Open Sicilian with d2-d4 is also possible. We should of course be prepared for this and choose a move that suits our own main repertoire against the Open Sicilian:  ➤ Those who have Kan in their repertoire should now choose 3... a6 and are in familiar territory after 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 .} ({➤ If you are aiming for the Taimanov main line with 5...Qc7 or the Four Knights Sicilian, opt for Nc6 and after} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 {either} Qc7 {(Taimanov) or Nf6 (Four Knights).}) ({➤ Players who prefer the rarer 5...a6 in the Taimanov are spoilt for choice: both of these moves lead to the goal! ➤ To reach the Scheveningen Variation, d6 is the right choice. I won't analyze this because the Scheveningen is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 d6 . ➤ There is not a satisfactory solution for all repertoires. If you want to play the Pin Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {), you could try Nf6 , but after} 6. e5 Nd5 {Nxd5 exd5 d4 you end up with the Nimzowitsch Sicilian ( e4 c5} 7. Nf3 Nf6 {), which is considered slightly better for White.}) ({➤ Adherents of the Kveinys Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nc3 Qb6 {) would only be left with the exotic . After that, however, White could bring about a favorable queen exchange with d4 cxd4 Qxd4! because White has a lead in development and there are weaknesses in the black camp.  For these two rare variations I have no better recommendation than to add one of the main Sicilian systems to your repertoire!}) 3... a6 {In this chapter we look at the solution for the Kan repertoire. White could now transition to the Kan Variation with d4 ; however, the attempts g3 and Be2 , which leave open a later transition to the Open Sicilian, are trickier. In addition, we look at a4 , with which White wants to stop Black's play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 .} 4. g3 ({White decides against the transposition to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 {. However, d2-d4 remains to be reckoned with. White keeps their options open and first develops the bishop to g2 . This is reminiscent of the Closed Sicilian, but there White usually places the knight on e2 , where it does not block the bishop's diagonal.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this move to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} 5. Bg2 Bb7 {Black is threatening to win a pawn with ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d3 ({We deal with the transposition to the Open Sicilian after} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 {in detail via the move order Nc3 e6 Nge2 a6 g3 b5 Bg2 Bb7 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 .}) 6... d6 ({Takes control of e5 and thus prepares ...Nf6 . A difference to the analogous position with the knight on e2 instead of f3 is that the direct} 6... Nf6 $6 {is not good because of} 7. e5 {.}) 7. O-O Nf6 {The black moves are easy. Next on the agenda is ...Be7 and ...O-O . Meanwhile, it's not easy for White to make progress. The knight on f3 blocks the advance of the f-pawn, which would be the natural plan in similar positions in the Closed Sicilian. In practice, White usually chooses between one of the following two approaches:  ➤ preparing f2-f4 by Ng5 or Nh4 ,  ➤ opening the position with e4-e5 (either directly or after the preparatory ) .} 8. Nh4 {Besides 8.Ng5 another possibility to prepare f2 - f4 .} Nc6 9. f4 Be7 {Black makes the usual developing moves. Castling could come next.} 10. f5 {The most common move. I don't see any other way to make progress either. White wants to exchange on e6 and then play against the weakened e-pawn. In fact, this is not a dangerous threat, but I still prefer to avoid weakening our pawn structure.} b4 11. Ne2 e5 {The black pawns dominate the e2 -knight. The black minor pieces are better positioned than the white ones. A good plan is to open up the position with ... d6 - d5 . Black could also play to gain more space on the queenside with ... a5 - a4 . Black is slightly better.} *

