 ...b7-b5 .} 4. g3 ({White decides against the transposition to the Open Sicilian with} 4. d4 {. However, d2-d4 remains to be reckoned with. White keeps their options open and first develops the bishop to g2 . This is reminiscent of the Closed Sicilian, but there White usually places the knight on e2 , where it does not block the bishop's diagonal.}) 4... b5 {This is the advantage of ... a7 - a6 . As is often the case in the Kan Sicilian, Black can use this move to prepare the development of the bishop to b7 and gain space on the queenside.} 5. Bg2 Bb7 {Black is threatening to win a pawn with ... b5 - b4 .} 6. d3 ({We deal with the transposition to the Open Sicilian after} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 {in detail via the move order Nc3 e6 Nge2 a6 g3 b5 Bg2 Bb7 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 .}) 6... d6 ({Takes control of e5 and thus prepares ...Nf6 . A difference to the analogous position with the knight on e2 instead of f3 is that the direct} 6... Nf6 $6 {is not good because of} 7. e5 {.}) 7. O-O Nf6 {The black moves are easy. Next on the agenda is ...Be7 and ...O-O . Meanwhile, it's not easy for White to make progress. The knight on f3 blocks the advance of the f-pawn, which would be the natural plan in similar positions in the Closed Sicilian. In practice, White usually chooses between one of the following two approaches:  ➤ preparing f2-f4 by Ng5 or Nh4 ,  ➤ opening the position with e4-e5 (either directly or after the preparatory ) .} 8. e5 {White opens the position, which has the advantage that the knight ends up on e5 and no longer blocks the f-pawn. On the other hand, this leads to exchanges and also gives Black more freedom of movement.} dxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Bd6 ({Black attacks the knight and prepares castling. The alternative} 10... Nbd7 {also leads to equality.}) 11. Qf3 {After other moves Black finishes development with ... O-O and ... Nbd7 and has comfortable play.} Ra7 (11... Nbd7 {is less accurate. White gets some initiative after} 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Bg5 Qb8 14. Qc6 {.}) 12. Nc6 ({This leads to further exchanges, but there is nothing better.} 12. Bf4 $4 {is a tactical blunder that has already been played in three tournament games and remained unpunished in all of them. Possibly the players involved thought that after} g5 $1 {White had the defense} 13. Nc6 {, but after} g4 $1 {-+ the piece is still lost.}) 12... Nxc6 13. Qxc6+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ (14. Qf3 O-O {is also equal.}) 14... Kxd7 {Since the queens have already been exchanged, it is logical to capture with the king. Firstly, the h8 -rook can now join the action quickly, and secondly, the king can go to c6 and support the queenside. It's a good idea for Black to bring the bishop to the diagonal ... a1 - h8 and exchange the white knight with ... Nd5 . The bishop then puts pressure on the b2 -pawn. Another possible plan is ... Rc8 followed by ... c5 - c4 . Black could then exert pressure along the c-file. The position is equal.} *

