{Once again play has transposed into a position which we will deal with in more detail here e4 c5 Nf3 e6 c4 .} 1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. c4 {This increases White's control over the d5 -square and thus protects the e4 -pawn from attacks by the black d-pawn. Typically, White will develop with Nc3 , g2 - g3 , Bg2 and Nge2 . Later, an advance of the f-pawn may initiate a kingside attack. The drawback of the pawn move is obvious: the d4 -square can no longer be controlled by a pawn.} ({In order for Black to use the square for their own pieces, it is desirable to prevent White from playing d2-d4 .} 2. c4 {is not particularly popular against the Sicilian. However, the pawn structure we are dealing with here is well known from the English Opening. A setup with pawns on c4 and e4 was popularized there by the sixth world champion Mikhail Botvinnik. For example, in the first game of the second world championship match against Vasily Smyslov, he opened with c4} Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O {e4!? .}) 2... e6 ({This position is more frequently reached via the English Opening: c4} 2... e6 {e4 c5 . The Latvian grandmaster Normunds Miezis is a keen advocate of the white strategy: he is already represented in the database with almost a hundred games!}) ({Instead of} 2... e6 {, Nc6 is much more popular. After} 3. Nc3 g6 {Black develops the bishop to g7 and thus takes good control of the d4 -square. I have opted for 2...e6 instead, because the position is similar to the line e4 c5} 4. Nf3 {e6 c4 . Against these two systems it is sufficient to learn only one setup. After 2...e6 we will also fight for the d4 -square, with the knights being the principal protagonists.}) 3. Nc3 ({White continues in the style of the Closed Sicilian. The knight controls d5 and thus suppresses the pawn break ...d7-d5 .} 3. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the line e4 c5 Nf3 e6 c4 Nc6 , and similarly Ne2 Nc6} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {, which we examine via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 c4 Nc6 and now d4 cxd4} Nxd4 {.}) 3... Nc6 {It's important that White doesn't get to d2 - d4 . As a rule, we achieve this by occupying d4 with the knight.} 4. Nge2 Nd4 {White had been threatening to transition to an Open Sicilian with 5.d4 , where the pawns on e4 and c4 restrict Black's counterplay. The knight move prevents this. If White doesn't capture on d4 now, we will strengthen control of this square with ... Ne7 - c6 . If White captures on d4 , the knight on c3 is attacked and White loses time.} 5. d3 Ne7 6. Nxd4 ({With the knight on e2 , White can hardly avoid this exchange, because otherwise development cannot be completed –} 6. g3 {fails to} Nf3# {mate!}) 6... cxd4 *

