1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. c4 {This increases White's control over the d5 -square and thus protects the e4 -pawn from attacks by the black d-pawn. Typically, White will develop with Nc3 , g2 - g3 , Bg2 and Nge2 . Later, an advance of the f-pawn may initiate a kingside attack. The drawback of the pawn move is obvious: the d4 -square can no longer be controlled by a pawn.} ({In order for Black to use the square for their own pieces, it is desirable to prevent White from playing d2-d4 .} 2. c4 {is not particularly popular against the Sicilian. However, the pawn structure we are dealing with here is well known from the English Opening. A setup with pawns on c4 and e4 was popularized there by the sixth world champion Mikhail Botvinnik. For example, in the first game of the second world championship match against Vasily Smyslov, he opened with c4} Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O {e4!? .}) 2... e6 ({This position is more frequently reached via the English Opening: c4} 2... e6 {e4 c5 . The Latvian grandmaster Normunds Miezis is a keen advocate of the white strategy: he is already represented in the database with almost a hundred games!}) ({Instead of} 2... e6 {, Nc6 is much more popular. After} 3. Nc3 g6 {Black develops the bishop to g7 and thus takes good control of the d4 -square. I have opted for 2...e6 instead, because the position is similar to the line e4 c5} 4. Nf3 {e6 c4 . Against these two systems it is sufficient to learn only one setup. After 2...e6 we will also fight for the d4 -square, with the knights being the principal protagonists.}) 3. Nc3 ({White continues in the style of the Closed Sicilian. The knight controls d5 and thus suppresses the pawn break ...d7-d5 .} 3. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the line e4 c5 Nf3 e6 c4 Nc6 , and similarly Ne2 Nc6} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {, which we examine via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 c4 Nc6 and now d4 cxd4} Nxd4 {.}) 3... Nc6 {It's important that White doesn't get to d2 - d4 . As a rule, we achieve this by occupying d4 with the knight.} 4. f4 {White plays a kind of Grand Prix attack, with an extra pawn on c4 . This is a dubious concept, because the many pawn moves lead to weak squares in the white camp.} Nge7 {As in the Grand Prix Attack, I suggest playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 . Here this needs to be prepared.} 5. Nf3 d5 6. d3 ({This looks relatively best. White keeps the position closed and thus limits the damage. Weak is} 6. e5 $6 dxc4 7. Bxc4 Nf5 {Black is already clearly better. The d2 -pawn is weak and backward and the d4 - and d3 -squares are also weakened. Black will play on the queenside with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 . Miezis, N-Petrov, M , Not much better is cxd5 exd5 e5?! Now the d2 -pawn is backward and weak. If it advances, the square e3 is also weakened. Black could, for example, continue with Nf5 and is clearly better, (or initially a6 which prevents Bb5 .)}) 6... g6 {I don't think it's necessary to continue the analysis. Black already has the better game. The dark-squared bishop will be developed to g7 and the light-squared bishop to a6 or b7 . Black can then prepare the opening of the d-file, e.g. by ... Qd7 and ... Rd8 . White has no active ideas. It is possible to keep the position relatively closed with e4 - e5 , but this gives Black the strong square f5 for the knight. According to my database, White has only scored half a point from 8 games. The position was first discussed in Carls,C-Euwe,M .} *

