1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. c4 {This increases White's control over the d5 -square and thus protects the e4 -pawn from attacks by the black d-pawn. Typically, White will develop with Nc3 , g2 - g3 , Bg2 and Nge2 . Later, an advance of the f-pawn may initiate a kingside attack. The drawback of the pawn move is obvious: the d4 -square can no longer be controlled by a pawn.} ({In order for Black to use the square for their own pieces, it is desirable to prevent White from playing d2-d4 .} 2. c4 {is not particularly popular against the Sicilian. However, the pawn structure we are dealing with here is well known from the English Opening. A setup with pawns on c4 and e4 was popularized there by the sixth world champion Mikhail Botvinnik. For example, in the first game of the second world championship match against Vasily Smyslov, he opened with c4} Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O {e4!? .}) 2... e6 ({This position is more frequently reached via the English Opening: c4} 2... e6 {e4 c5 . The Latvian grandmaster Normunds Miezis is a keen advocate of the white strategy: he is already represented in the database with almost a hundred games!}) ({Instead of} 2... e6 {, Nc6 is much more popular. After} 3. Nc3 g6 {Black develops the bishop to g7 and thus takes good control of the d4 -square. I have opted for 2...e6 instead, because the position is similar to the line e4 c5} 4. Nf3 {e6 c4 . Against these two systems it is sufficient to learn only one setup. After 2...e6 we will also fight for the d4 -square, with the knights being the principal protagonists.}) 3. Nc3 ({White continues in the style of the Closed Sicilian. The knight controls d5 and thus suppresses the pawn break ...d7-d5 .} 3. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to the line e4 c5 Nf3 e6 c4 Nc6 , and similarly Ne2 Nc6} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {, which we examine via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 c4 Nc6 and now d4 cxd4} Nxd4 {.}) 3... Nc6 {It's important that White doesn't get to d2 - d4 . As a rule, we achieve this by occupying d4 with the knight.} 4. g3 ({The most common move. On g2 the bishop has more active perspectives than on e2 and further increases the control over d5 .} 4. Nf3 {we examine via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 c4 Nc6 Nc3 .}) 4... Nge7 ({We want to continue with ...Nd4 and ...Nec6 and set up a blockade on d4 .} 4... Nd4 {serves the same purpose and is equally possible.}) ({Let's look at an exemplary line that demonstrates what to avoid:} 4... Nf6 5. Bg2 Be7 6. Nge2 O-O 7. O-O d6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {White has succeeded in opening up the position and is now very active. Black lacks counterplay.}) 5. Bg2 Nd4 6. Nge2 Nec6 {We have a closed position before us, in which the loss of tempo due to the knight moves doesn't play a big role. What is more important is that Black has reliably prevented the opening of the position with d2 - d4 . White is therefore unable to develop active piece play.} 7. O-O ({The order of the moves is not significant. White could also start with} 7. d3 {.}) 7... Be7 {Black could also have fianchettoed the bishop. But it is not clear whether it is better on g7 than on e7 . b2 - b4 is one of White's main ideas and from e7 the bishop makes this plan more difficult. If it is needed on the long diagonal, it can still move to f6 .} 8. d3 Rb8 ({Black's chances lie on the queenside. Black prepares for ...b7-b5 . We encounter a very similar position in the line e4 c5} 8... Nf3+ {e6 c4 . The only difference is the position of the white knight, which is on f3 instead of e2 . If White captures on d4 , the lines transpose.}) ({I like the rook move slightly better than} 8... O-O {, because White could then try to prevent ...b7-b5 :} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Nb1 $1 a6 11. a4 Rb8 12. Na3 {.}) 9. f4 ({White becomes active on the kingside. This is of course not directly possible in the analogous line with the knight on f3 . White cannot prevent Black from becoming active on the queenside. After} 9. a4 {follows} a6 {, e.g.} 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Nb1 b5 12. axb5 axb5 13. cxb5 Rxb5 {with an equal position.}) 9... O-O {Black will continue with ... a7 - a6 and ... b7 - b5 . The light-squared bishop will probably be developed to d7 (after ... d7 - d6 ). The dark-squared bishop could be brought to f6 , where it exerts pressure on the queenside, especially in combination with ... b7 - b5 . How White should continue, however, is less clear. The space advantage on the kingside can't be converted into an attack, because the minor pieces aren't positioned accordingly. I therefore believe that Black has the more comfortable game, even if the position is objectively equal. A good demonstration of White's practical difficulties is the game Hautot-Sedlak , which I have annotated in the sample games chapter.} *

