1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first. About the Hedgehog alternative} ({If you have Hedgehog positions in your repertoire, you could also play} 3... a6 {. I decided against analyzing this as an alternative, because there are some drawbacks with this move order compared to the Kan Variation. Play could continue with} 4. Nc3 Qc7 5. Be2 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. d4 {White transposes to the Taimanov Sicilian. However, the early c2 - c4 is not so critical there, so it shouldn't bother us even if we're actually aiming for a different Sicilian system.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 ({This position can also be reached via the move order e4} 5. c5 {Nf3 Nc6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 e6 c4 .}) 5... Qb6 ({This is a fairly rare move at this point. However, transpositions to more familiar territory from the English Opening are still possible. With} 5... Qb6 {, Black exploits the fact that White cannot defend the knight on d4 . White must now either exchange it or retreat to a less active square.  The queen is well-placed on b6 , as it has the potentially vulnerable pawns f2 and b2 in its sights. Another advantage of the queen's move is that after the exchange on c6 , Black can recapture with the d-pawn without allowing the exchange of queens on d8 .}) ({The main line begins with} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 ({(} 7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. e5 $1 {is better for White.)}) 8. Bd3 {.  In my course on the Sicilian Four Knights I have examined similar positions. However, there the white pawn was mostly on c2 instead of c4 , so Black could go for a setup with d7-d5 . Here it is better to play e5 to prevent White from advancing the e-pawn. Black has good chances for equality.}) ({In the aforementioned game between Carlsen and Caruana there followed} 5... Bc5 6. Nc2 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3 {and White had things under control.}) 6. Nc2 {Not without reason did Carlsen retreat the knight to c2 in a similar position. From here it controls the b4 -square and can later move to e3 , where it strengthens control over d5 . 6.Nc2 looks like the best attempt in the fight for an opening advantage, although it has only been played in a few games.} Nf6 ({It's also possible to start with} 6... Bc5 {, which probably amounts to a transposition.}) 7. Nc3 Bc5 {The f2 -pawn is the weak spot in White's position.} 8. Qd2 {The best move, which White will probably only go for with good preparation, because the following entanglements are difficult to see through at the board. The queen not only defends the f2 -pawn, but also blocks the e1 - a5 diagonal, so that Na4 is now a threat.} Ng4 ({The most principled reply. White can no longer defend f2 well. If you want to avoid the following complications, you can continue with} 8... O-O {. After} 9. Na4 Bb4 {(the only move)} 10. Nxb6 Bxd2+ 11. Bxd2 axb6 {White retains slightly better chances with} 12. f3 {or Be3 due to the bishop pair. However, in the rapid game Artemiev-Caruana , Caruana easily managed to neutralize White's slight advantage.}) 9. Nd1 {White loses time with this defensive move and can therefore pose no problems.} O-O 10. h3 {The two knights have returned, but White has lost an important tempo with h2 - h3 . White is now threatening Na4 .} Nf6 11. Nc3 {The two knights have returned, but White has lost an important tempo with h2 - h3 . White is now threatening Na4 .} d6 {Black defends the bishop and has comfortable play. Next, development can be continued with ... Bd7 .} ({Na4 is already no longer dangerous, because after} 11... Qa6 {Nxc5 dxc5 , Black has a lead in development and good control of the dark squares.}) *

