 Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. d4 {White transposes to the Taimanov Sicilian. However, the early c2 - c4 is not so critical there, so it shouldn't bother us even if we're actually aiming for a different Sicilian system.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 ({This position can also be reached via the move order e4} 5. c5 {Nf3 Nc6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 e6 c4 .}) 5... Qb6 ({This is a fairly rare move at this point. However, transpositions to more familiar territory from the English Opening are still possible. With} 5... Qb6 {, Black exploits the fact that White cannot defend the knight on d4 . White must now either exchange it or retreat to a less active square.  The queen is well-placed on b6 , as it has the potentially vulnerable pawns f2 and b2 in its sights. Another advantage of the queen's move is that after the exchange on c6 , Black can recapture with the d-pawn without allowing the exchange of queens on d8 .}) ({The main line begins with} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 ({(} 7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. e5 $1 {is better for White.)}) 8. Bd3 {.  In my course on the Sicilian Four Knights I have examined similar positions. However, there the white pawn was mostly on c2 instead of c4 , so Black could go for a setup with d7-d5 . Here it is better to play e5 to prevent White from advancing the e-pawn. Black has good chances for equality.}) ({In the aforementioned game between Carlsen and Caruana there followed} 5... Bc5 6. Nc2 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3 {and White had things under control.}) 6. Nc2 {Not without reason did Carlsen retreat the knight to c2 in a similar position. From here it controls the b4 -square and can later move to e3 , where it strengthens control over d5 . 6.Nc2 looks like the best attempt in the fight for an opening advantage, although it has only been played in a few games.} Nf6 ({It's also possible to start with} 6... Bc5 {, which probably amounts to a transposition.}) 7. Nc3 Bc5 {The f2 -pawn is the weak spot in White's position.} 8. Qd2 {The best move, which White will probably only go for with good preparation, because the following entanglements are difficult to see through at the board. The queen not only defends the f2 -pawn, but also blocks the e1 - a5 diagonal, so that Na4 is now a threat.} Ng4 ({The most principled reply. White can no longer defend f2 well. If you want to avoid the following complications, you can continue with} 8... O-O {. After} 9. Na4 Bb4 {(the only move)} 10. Nxb6 Bxd2+ 11. Bxd2 axb6 {White retains slightly better chances with} 12. f3 {or Be3 due to the bishop pair. However, in the rapid game Artemiev-Caruana , Caruana easily managed to neutralize White's slight advantage.}) 9. f3 {White sacrifices an exchange, but the black knight will get lost in the opponent's camp. The game now gets very sharp.} Nf2 {There's no going back.} 10. Na4 Qc7 11. Nxc5 Nxh1 {The last moves were forced. The knight on h1 is trapped and to keep it that way White must now prevent ... Qxh2 .} 12. f4 ({Unlike after} 12. g3 {, White now has e5 covered, but needs a little more time to attack the trapped knight. GM Frederik Svane opted for g3 in a blitz game against Denis Lazavik. Instead of 12...O-O , which followed in the game, I now like} Ne5 {better, with which Black exploits the drawback of White's last move: the f3 -pawn is no longer protected. After the forced} 13. Qe3 {Black plays} O-O {and is now ready to open the position with ...d7-d5 and create threats against the centralized king. It seems to me that the practical chances are more on Black's side, even if Stockfish sees this complicated position in equilibrium.}) 12... O-O {Black first brings the king to safety. The next step is to open the position with ... d7 - d5 . Black must proceed energetically, because sooner or later White will win the knight on h1 and then have a material advantage.} 13. Be2 ({Best. White wants to attack the knight with Kf1-g1 , which at the same time brings the king to safety. After} 13. g3 {,} d5 $1 {gives Black good counterplay.}) 13... d5 {Opening up the position is worth a pawn.} 14. Kf1 ({White is not distracted and prepares to capture the knight. White should decline the pawn. The following line illustrates the dangers:} 14. cxd5 exd5 15. exd5 $2 ({(still,} 15. Kf1 {was the better choice)}) 15... Qe7 $1 {The queen attacks the knight c5 and is at the same time threatening to free the knight h1 with ...Qh4+ .} 16. Qe3 Qh4+ 17. Kf1 Bf5 $1 {Soon the rooks are also activated. Black has a strong attack.}) 14... Qe7 {Before Black captures on c4 , the knight is driven to a worse square. The position remains very sharp. White will win the knight on h1 , while Black will capture on c4 and open up the position with ... e6 -e5 . The position is dynamically equal.} *

