 Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. d4 {White transposes to the Taimanov Sicilian. However, the early c2 - c4 is not so critical there, so it shouldn't bother us even if we're actually aiming for a different Sicilian system.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 ({This position can also be reached via the move order e4} 5. c5 {Nf3 Nc6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 e6 c4 .}) 5... Qb6 ({This is a fairly rare move at this point. However, transpositions to more familiar territory from the English Opening are still possible. With} 5... Qb6 {, Black exploits the fact that White cannot defend the knight on d4 . White must now either exchange it or retreat to a less active square.  The queen is well-placed on b6 , as it has the potentially vulnerable pawns f2 and b2 in its sights. Another advantage of the queen's move is that after the exchange on c6 , Black can recapture with the d-pawn without allowing the exchange of queens on d8 .}) ({The main line begins with} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 ({(} 7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. e5 $1 {is better for White.)}) 8. Bd3 {.  In my course on the Sicilian Four Knights I have examined similar positions. However, there the white pawn was mostly on c2 instead of c4 , so Black could go for a setup with d7-d5 . Here it is better to play e5 to prevent White from advancing the e-pawn. Black has good chances for equality.}) ({In the aforementioned game between Carlsen and Caruana there followed} 5... Bc5 6. Nc2 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3 {and White had things under control.}) 6. Nb3 {The most popular way to retreat the knight. From here it controls c5 . Black can therefore no longer play ... Bc5 and White sometimes gets to c4 - c5 .} Nf6 7. Nc3 ({This position is more often reached via the Symmetry Variation of the English Opening: c4} 7. c5 {Nf3 Nc6 d4 cxd4} Nd4 {Qb6 Nb3 e6 e4 Nf6} 8. Nc3 {.}) 7... Bb4 {The e4 -pawn is under attack again.} 8. Be3 Qc7 9. f3 {A double-edged decision. If Black manages to achieve ... d7 - d5 , the weakening of the e3 -square could be felt.} O-O 10. Be2 ({Ignores the opponent's threat.} 10. Rc1 $2 {also allows} d5 $1 {with a black advantage:} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. exd5 Rd8 {and Black wins back the pawn.}) ({Necessary is} 10. c5 {, with which White preserves approximate equality, e.g. after} d5 $5 11. cxd6 Bxd6 12. Nb5 Bb4+ 13. Kf2 Qb8 {. Harasta, V-Petrik, K .}) 10... d5 {Black takes control.} 11. exd5 ({Or} 11. O-O Bxc3 {( 11...dxe4!? )} 12. bxc3 dxe4 {.}) 11... exd5 12. O-O (12. cxd5 Rd8 {is the tactical point. Black wins back the pawn with an advantage.}) 12... Rd8 {Black can still keep the tension in the center.} 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Be6 {Black wins back the pawn with some advantage. The move f2 - f3 has weakened the point e3 as well as the diagonal h2 - b8 .} *

