1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first. About the Hedgehog alternative} ({If you have Hedgehog positions in your repertoire, you could also play} 3... a6 {. I decided against analyzing this as an alternative, because there are some drawbacks with this move order compared to the Kan Variation. Play could continue with} 4. Nc3 Qc7 5. Be2 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. d4 {White transposes to the Taimanov Sicilian. However, the early c2 - c4 is not so critical there, so it shouldn't bother us even if we're actually aiming for a different Sicilian system.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 ({This position can also be reached via the move order e4} 5. c5 {Nf3 Nc6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 e6 c4 .}) 5... Qb6 ({This is a fairly rare move at this point. However, transpositions to more familiar territory from the English Opening are still possible. With} 5... Qb6 {, Black exploits the fact that White cannot defend the knight on d4 . White must now either exchange it or retreat to a less active square.  The queen is well-placed on b6 , as it has the potentially vulnerable pawns f2 and b2 in its sights. Another advantage of the queen's move is that after the exchange on c6 , Black can recapture with the d-pawn without allowing the exchange of queens on d8 .}) ({The main line begins with} 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 ({(} 7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. e5 $1 {is better for White.)}) 8. Bd3 {.  In my course on the Sicilian Four Knights I have examined similar positions. However, there the white pawn was mostly on c2 instead of c4 , so Black could go for a setup with d7-d5 . Here it is better to play e5 to prevent White from advancing the e-pawn. Black has good chances for equality.}) ({In the aforementioned game between Carlsen and Caruana there followed} 5... Bc5 6. Nc2 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3 {and White had things under control.}) 6. Nb3 {The most popular way to retreat the knight. From here it controls c5 . Black can therefore no longer play ... Bc5 and White sometimes gets to c4 - c5 .} Nf6 7. Nc3 ({This position is more often reached via the Symmetry Variation of the English Opening: c4} 7. c5 {Nf3 Nc6 d4 cxd4} Nd4 {Qb6 Nb3 e6 e4 Nf6} 8. Nc3 {.}) 7... Bb4 {The e4 -pawn is under attack again.} 8. Bd3 Ne5 {Black hurries to pose concrete threats. After slower moves, the space advantage would give White the slightly better game.} 9. O-O Qd6 {This was the unusual idea of the previous move. The pawns e4 and c4 are insufficiently protected; if the d3 -bishop moves away, Black wins one of them. John van der Wiel was the first to play like this against Viktor Korchnoi in 1988.} 10. Bf4 {In practice, this move has been played almost exclusively. Here, too, Black could win a pawn, but it's better to do without it.} ({After} 10. Be2 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nxe4 {White has sufficient compensation for the pawn with the pair of bishops, but no more.}) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qxd3 12. Bxe5 Qxd1 ({Or} 12... Qxc4 $6 13. Re1 {Le-Nepomniachtchi . This gives White dangerous play on the dark squares. It is better to exchange queens.}) 13. Raxd1 ({White can also capture with the other rook, e.g.} 13. Rfxd1 Nxe4 14. Bxg7 Rg8 15. Bd4 b6 16. f3 Nd6 17. c5 {All three tournament games in which this position was reached ended in a draw.}) 13... Nxe4 14. Rfe1 ({White can also win back the pawn directly with} 14. Bxg7 {. After} Rg8 15. Bd4 b6 {the position is equal, but White has the worse pawn structure and must therefore be more careful.}) 14... f6 ({If Black plays} 14... Nf6 {, holding on to the extra pawn, control of the dark squares gives White good compensation.}) 15. Rxe4 fxe5 16. Rxe5 b6 {Black develops the bishop to b7 . If White plays f2 - f4 , Black stops the further advance of the pawn with ... g7 - g6 . White can bring the knight to d6 , but after ... Bc6 no further progress can be made. The position is equal. GM Evgeny Alekseev reached this position in two games: Mareco-Alekseev and Artemiev-Alekseev , both of which ended in draws.} *

