1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first. About the Hedgehog alternative} ({If you have Hedgehog positions in your repertoire, you could also play} 3... a6 {. I decided against analyzing this as an alternative, because there are some drawbacks with this move order compared to the Kan Variation. Play could continue with} 4. Nc3 Qc7 5. Be2 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. Be2 ({White makes a developing move while keeping the option of d2-d4 open. In this respect,} 4. Be2 {is similar to the main move . In both cases, we want to prevent d2-d4 , but the specific circumstances require that we achieve this differently in each instance.}) 4... g5 ({We also encounter this aggressive idea in the chapters on e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5 and the delayed Alapin Sicilian. Basically, it's about White not getting to d2-d4 . Black would then drive away the defender of the pawn with ...g5-g4 . Black can also increase control over d4 with ...Bg7 . In addition to this positional goal, Black has attacking chances on the kingside. The g-pawn can be supported by the h-pawn. Against Nc3 I recommend} 4... Nd4 {, but against Be2 ,} 5. Nxd4 {is less strong. The difference is that White doesn't have to waste time with knight moves after the exchange on d4 .}) ({A good alternative, on the other hand, is} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {. The main line is now} 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 {. This queenless middlegame is close to equality, but doesn't promise Black good winning chances.}) 5. h3 {Defending against ... g5 - g4 , White is again threatening d2 - d4 . The black reply is therefore forced.} Bg7 6. d3 ({White develops the queenside and attacks the pawn on g5 . After} 6. Nc3 h6 {(to prepare ...Nge7 ), White is best off playing} 7. d3 {, which leads to a transposition. Weaker would be 7.O-O , because now the pawn on h3 can become a target. In practice, Black now continued the path taken one move earlier with} Nge7 {, but it is even stronger to adapt to the new circumstances: h5! followed by ...g5-g4 , opening lines on the kingside and giving Black a strong attack against the white king.}) ({The exchange} 6. d4 Nxd4 7. Nxg5 Ne7 {is advantageous for Black. The knight on d4 is very strong.}) 6... h6 7. Nc3 d6 (7... Nge7 {is also good. However, White could have avoided this with the move order d3 h6 Nc3 Bg7} 8. Be3 d6 {h3 .}) 8. Be3 {The battle continues to revolve around the pawn break d3 - d4 . Black should not allow this, because then all the white pieces would be well placed and the d6 -pawn would be weak.} f5 ({An unconventional approach in the fight against d3-d4 . The white minor pieces can now be attacked with ...f5-f4 or ...g5-g4 . The usual method of preventing d3-d4 is to occupy the d4 -square with} 8... Nd4 {. Against this, Stockfish proposes an interesting plan for White:} 9. Nh2 Ne7 10. Bh5 {White wants to open the f-file with O-O and f2-f4 and put pressure on f7 . After} O-O $6 {the other pawn break} 11. h4 $1 {is strong, after which the black king becomes vulnerable.}) 9. exf5 {This pawn trade gives White control of the d5 -square.} exf5 10. O-O ({In Ni-Colovic ,} 10. Nh2 $6 {followed. Now} Bxc3+ $1 11. bxc3 f4 12. Bd2 Nf6 13. O-O Kd7 $1 {would have been very strong. The king goes to c7 , where it is completely safe. Black has the more active pieces and is slightly better.}) 10... Bxc3 ({I like this transformation of the pawn structure. The point is that after this White has no useful pawn breaks on the queenside and in the center.  d3-d4 is still possible, but after an exchange on c5 the two c-pawns would be weak. The more conventional} 10... Nge7 {followed by ...O-O is also playable.}) 11. bxc3 f4 12. Bc1 Bf5 {Black wants to continue with ... Qd7 and ... O-O-O . After that Black could prepare a kingside attack. The position is still equal, but in my opinion Black has the easier game.} *

