1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first. About the Hedgehog alternative} ({If you have Hedgehog positions in your repertoire, you could also play} 3... a6 {. I decided against analyzing this as an alternative, because there are some drawbacks with this move order compared to the Kan Variation. Play could continue with} 4. Nc3 Qc7 5. Be2 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. Be2 ({White makes a developing move while keeping the option of d2-d4 open. In this respect,} 4. Be2 {is similar to the main move . In both cases, we want to prevent d2-d4 , but the specific circumstances require that we achieve this differently in each instance.}) 4... g5 ({We also encounter this aggressive idea in the chapters on e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5 and the delayed Alapin Sicilian. Basically, it's about White not getting to d2-d4 . Black would then drive away the defender of the pawn with ...g5-g4 . Black can also increase control over d4 with ...Bg7 . In addition to this positional goal, Black has attacking chances on the kingside. The g-pawn can be supported by the h-pawn. Against Nc3 I recommend} 4... Nd4 {, but against Be2 ,} 5. Nxd4 {is less strong. The difference is that White doesn't have to waste time with knight moves after the exchange on d4 .}) ({A good alternative, on the other hand, is} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {. The main line is now} 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 {. This queenless middlegame is close to equality, but doesn't promise Black good winning chances.}) 5. O-O {If White decides to castle, it is correct to refrain from h2 - h3 . Otherwise Black would get an attacking target.} g4 {Black gains space and increases control of the d4 -square.} 6. Ne1 h5 7. Nc3 ({With} 7. f4 $6 {, as happened in the rapid game Kabanov-Morozevich , White achieves nothing while depriving themselves of the pawn break f2-f3 . Now} d5 {would have been strong. The white minor pieces are very poorly placed.}) 7... Bg7 8. Nc2 Nge7 {The right square for the knight. It can later be brought to the kingside via g6 . On f6 , however, it would be in the way of the bishop.} 9. d4 ({With this typical pawn sacrifice White can free the position and keep the balance. After} 9. d3 d5 $1 {, Black is slightly better. The white minor pieces have no good squares and Black wants to push them back further with ...d5-d4 .}) 9... Nxd4 ({After} 9... cxd4 10. Nb5 {White wins back the pawn, because Black cannot afford} e5 $2 11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. c5 {, followed by an attack on f7 with Bc4 or f2-f3 .}) 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Nb5 {The point of the pawn sacrifice is to play against the weakened dark squares. The d6 -square in particular is a target of the white attack.} Nc6 12. Be3 ({White wants to exchange a defender of the dark squares.  ➤} 12. Nd6+ $2 Ke7 {is of no use.}) ({➤} 12. Bf4 $6 e5 {is also good for Black.}) 12... e5 ({Forced. Now the f5 -square is weakened. Not} 12... Bxe3 $2 13. fxe3 {after which the rook and queen will join the attack.}) 13. Nd6+ Ke7 (13... Kf8 14. Bxd4 Nxd4 15. f4 {gives White enough play for the pawn.}) 14. Nf5+ Ke8 15. Nd6+ {After other moves, Black plays ... d7 - d6 , when the compensation for the pawn becomes questionable.} Ke7 16. Nf5+ Ke8 ({With a draw by repetition. Black can also continue the fight with} 16... Kf8 {. After} 17. Qd2 d6 18. Nxd4 $1 Nxd4 ({(} 18... cxd4 $2 19. Bg5 Qa5 20. b4 $1 Qxb4 21. Bh6+ Ke8 22. Qg5 {shows the dangers of the position. The white queen invades on g7 .)}) 19. f4 {White has enough compensation for the pawn.}) *

