1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first. About the Hedgehog alternative} ({If you have Hedgehog positions in your repertoire, you could also play} 3... a6 {. I decided against analyzing this as an alternative, because there are some drawbacks with this move order compared to the Kan Variation. Play could continue with} 4. Nc3 Qc7 5. Be2 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. Be2 ({White makes a developing move while keeping the option of d2-d4 open. In this respect,} 4. Be2 {is similar to the main move . In both cases, we want to prevent d2-d4 , but the specific circumstances require that we achieve this differently in each instance.}) 4... g5 ({We also encounter this aggressive idea in the chapters on e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5 and the delayed Alapin Sicilian. Basically, it's about White not getting to d2-d4 . Black would then drive away the defender of the pawn with ...g5-g4 . Black can also increase control over d4 with ...Bg7 . In addition to this positional goal, Black has attacking chances on the kingside. The g-pawn can be supported by the h-pawn. Against Nc3 I recommend} 4... Nd4 {, but against Be2 ,} 5. Nxd4 {is less strong. The difference is that White doesn't have to waste time with knight moves after the exchange on d4 .}) ({A good alternative, on the other hand, is} 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {. The main line is now} 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 {. This queenless middlegame is close to equality, but doesn't promise Black good winning chances.}) 5. d3 ({White develops the queenside and attacks the pawn on g5 .} 5. d4 $2 {leads after} g4 {followed by ...cxd4 to an advantageous exchange of a wing pawn for a central pawn.}) 5... h6 (5... g4 $6 {would be premature, because after} 6. Ng1 $1 h5 {White has the pawn break} 7. h3 {and the advanced black pawns come under pressure.}) 6. Nc3 ({White could also start with} 6. h4 {, which after} g4 7. Nfd2 h5 8. Nb3 Bg7 9. Nc3 {amounts to a transposition.}) 6... Bg7 {The bishop increases Black's control over d4 . Although White has already moved the d-pawn, it's still crucial to prevent d3 - d4 . If White were to open up the position, the black king's safety would be at risk.} 7. h4 ({White's aim is to persuade the g-pawn to move on so that they can subsequently attack it. After} 7. Be3 d6 {, White can play} 8. h3 {and thus transpose to the line h3 Bg7 d3 h6 Nc3 d6 Be3 . In Kostenko-Ganguly ,} g4 $5 {followed instead, with which White prevents ...g5-g4 and is therefore threatening d3-d4 . Ganguly prevented this with} 9. Nd4 {and got a good position. A strong alternative was} f5 $1 {, which gives Black the initiative and also prevents d3-d4 .}) 7... g4 ({There is no good alternative. Compared to} 7... g4 $6 {it is advantageous for Black that the white pawn is already on h4 and White therefore no longer has the break h2-h3 . The other pawn break f2-f3 is less strong, because it goes hand in hand with a weakening of the dark squares.}) 8. Nd2 h5 9. Nb3 {An unusual square for the knight. Nevertheless, it attacks the c5 -pawn and controls the key square d4 once more.} b6 ({The right defensive move. If White plays f2-f3 , Black has the idea ...Qc7-g3 , which would not be possible with a pawn on d6 . If Black plays} 9... d6 {instead, White can play} 10. Bg5 $1 ({(Not} 10. f3 Bf6 {)}) 10... Nge7 ({(} 10... Bf6 11. Qd2 {)}) 11. f3 {, putting pressure on the black kingside. The d6 -pawn prevents Black from getting counterplay by attacking g3 with ...Qc7 .}) 10. Be3 ({The battle for the d4 -square continues.} 10. Bg5 Nge7 11. f3 $6 {would now be dangerous for White. Black continues with} Qc7 $1 {and gets play against the white king, e.g.} 12. fxg4 ({(} 12. O-O Ng6 {)}) 12... hxg4 13. Bxg4 Qg3+ 14. Kd2 ({(} 14. Kf1 $2 Ne5 15. Be2 $2 Qxg5 $1 {)}) 14... Nd4 {with a strong attack. An important tactical motif is} 15. Be2 Rxh4 $1 16. Bxh4 {(necessary is 16.Be3∓ )} Bh6+ 17. Bg5 Bxg5# {A complete triumph on the dark squares!}) 10... Nd4 {White had been threatening to open up the position with d3 - d4 . Black does not allow this.} 11. f3 {The most logical continuation. The bishop on e3 gives the white king position stability, so White no longer has to fear the black queen's foray to g3 .} Nh6 ({The pawn on g4 is now defended ( fxg4 is met with} 11... Nxe2 12. Qxe2 {Nxg4 ) . In this complex position I prefer the black chances. The light-squared bishop can be brought to c6 , where it defends the b5 -square against a possible knight thrust. The queen can be brought into play via f6 or b8 . Another possible reinforcement of the position is ... f7 - f5 , which stabilizes the g4 -pawn. It is less clear what the white ideas are.}) ({If White prepares long castling with Qd2 , then} 11... a5 {is a strong reply. O-O-O does not work now due to} 12. a4 {Na1 a3 , after which the dark squares are decisively weakened, e.g. b3} Qf6 {.}) *

