1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first. About the Hedgehog alternative} ({If you have Hedgehog positions in your repertoire, you could also play} 3... a6 {. I decided against analyzing this as an alternative, because there are some drawbacks with this move order compared to the Kan Variation. Play could continue with} 4. Nc3 Qc7 5. Be2 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. Nc3 {This is the most popular move. White develops a piece and preserves the option d2 - d4 .} Nd4 ({The knight occupies d4 and thus thwarts White's plan to subsequently transition to the Maroczy structure with d2-d4 . We take advantage of the fact that White loses time after an exchange on d4 because the knight c3 is attacked. This idea is familiar from the chapter on the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 $1 {) . If White does not capture on d4 now, we will increase our control of the square with ...Ne7-c6 .}) ({A good alternative is} 4... Nf6 5. Be2 d5 {. The main line is now} 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 {. This queenless middlegame is close to equality, but doesn't promise Black good winning chances.}) ({In the analysis of 4.Be2 , we learned another method with which Black can prevent d2-d4 . Here} 4... g5 {is less effective, because Nc3 is a more useful move than Be2 and White therefore is a decisive tempo up.} 5. d3 ({(Another important difference can be seen after} 5. d4 $5 g4 6. d5 {.)}) 5... g4 6. Nd2 h5 7. Nb3 {It is no longer so easy to prevent d3-d4 .}) 5. Nxd4 {The second most common move.} cxd4 {The knight is attacked and has no good square to retreat to. White is already fighting for equality here.} 6. Ne2 {The knight is poorly placed here, as it obstructs the development of the f1 -bishop. White will need to spend another tempo on Ng3 , where the knight still isn't ideally positioned.} e5 {Defends the d-pawn.} 7. Ng3 g6 {Prepares the subsequent advance of the h-pawn.} 8. Be2 h5 {Threatening ... h5 - h4 .} 9. O-O (9. h4 $2 {doesn't work due to} Be7 {and White can no longer protect the pawn.}) 9... Nf6 ({It's good to leave the pawn on h5 for the time being, because there it supports an attack with ...Ng4 . Concretely, ...h5-h4 followed by ...Nxe4 is now a threat.} 9... h4 {is met with} 10. Nh1 {, after which White plays for the pawn break f2-f4 . The knight later comes back into play via f2 .}) 10. d3 (10. f4 $2 {is desirable positionally, but is refuted tactically:} d3 $1 11. Bxd3 Ng4 {. Black wins with ...Qh4 or a check on the g1-a7 diagonal.}) 10... d6 11. f4 ({If White prevents ...Ng4 , the knight goes to the queenside:} 11. h3 Nd7 $1 12. f4 a5 $1 {The knight should go to c5 . In order for it to stay there it is necessary to prevent b2-b4 first. Black is better, because the white minor pieces have no active prospects.}) 11... Ng4 {That's why we left the pawn on h5 . The threat is now ... Qh4 . Another target of the knight is the weakened square e3 .} 12. Rf3 ({Directed against Qh4 , whereupon White could now play} 12. h3 {or Nf1 .}) 12... Bh6 {Black has strong play on the dark squares. There is the threat of ... exf4 followed by an exchange of the dark-squared bishops. After that the dark squares would be even more vulnerable. The black position deserves preference.} ({After h3 follows} 12... Ne3 {, and White must also part with the dark-squared bishop.}) *

