{After exf5 Rxf5 Black will bring the bishop to b7 , where it will soon put pressure on the knight f3 . It is often possible to accelerate this with the pawn sacrifice ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 , which buys some time compared to ...b7-b6 .} 1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first. About the Hedgehog alternative} ({If you have Hedgehog positions in your repertoire, you could also play} 3... a6 {. I decided against analyzing this as an alternative, because there are some drawbacks with this move order compared to the Kan Variation. Play could continue with} 4. Nc3 Qc7 5. Be2 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. Nc3 {This is the most popular move. White develops a piece and preserves the option d2 - d4 .} Nd4 ({The knight occupies d4 and thus thwarts White's plan to subsequently transition to the Maroczy structure with d2-d4 . We take advantage of the fact that White loses time after an exchange on d4 because the knight c3 is attacked. This idea is familiar from the chapter on the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 $1 {) . If White does not capture on d4 now, we will increase our control of the square with ...Ne7-c6 .}) ({A good alternative is} 4... Nf6 5. Be2 d5 {. The main line is now} 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 {. This queenless middlegame is close to equality, but doesn't promise Black good winning chances.}) ({In the analysis of 4.Be2 , we learned another method with which Black can prevent d2-d4 . Here} 4... g5 {is less effective, because Nc3 is a more useful move than Be2 and White therefore is a decisive tempo up.} 5. d3 ({(Another important difference can be seen after} 5. d4 $5 g4 6. d5 {.)}) 5... g4 6. Nd2 h5 7. Nb3 {It is no longer so easy to prevent d3-d4 .}) 5. Be2 {The bishop is worse on e2 than on g2 , but White is quicker to castle.} Ne7 {The best square for the knight is c6 , from where it supports its colleague on d4 .} 6. O-O Nec6 7. d3 {Both sides make the natural developing moves.} Be7 ({It's not so easy for White to find a good continuation now, because the knight on d4 paralyzes White's play. It is therefore probably best to trade it off. The alternative setup,} 7... g6 {, is a bit slow here and weakens the dark squares. White can seize the initiative with} 8. Nxd4 {followed by 9.Nb5 .}) 8. Be3 {White thus forfeits the option of capturing with the knight on d4 , as Black would have a pawn fork on that square. Nevertheless, the bishop move is played quite frequently.} O-O 9. Nb5 ({It's not so clear what else White should do that makes sense. Meanwhile, Black can improve the position, e.g. with ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7 , and then play for the pawn break ...f7-f5 . With} 9. Nb5 {White finally succeeds in getting rid of the intruder on d4 .}) 9... Nxe2+ {The exchange of the knight for the passive bishop comes with a concrete idea. The exchange on f3 is also good for Black.} 10. Qxe2 f5 {Black gains space on the kingside. The pawn is threatening to advance to f4 , after which Black regains control of d4 . Black is slightly better.  In the game Kritz-Jakovenko , White prevented ... f5 -f4 with 11.Qd2 . Instead of 11...b6  12.Bf4! , 11... a6 12.Nc3 b6 would have been more accurate. The bishop goes to b7 and puts pressure on the e4 -pawn.} *

