 Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. Nc3 {This is the most popular move. White develops a piece and preserves the option d2 - d4 .} Nd4 ({The knight occupies d4 and thus thwarts White's plan to subsequently transition to the Maroczy structure with d2-d4 . We take advantage of the fact that White loses time after an exchange on d4 because the knight c3 is attacked. This idea is familiar from the chapter on the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 $1 {) . If White does not capture on d4 now, we will increase our control of the square with ...Ne7-c6 .}) ({A good alternative is} 4... Nf6 5. Be2 d5 {. The main line is now} 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 {. This queenless middlegame is close to equality, but doesn't promise Black good winning chances.}) ({In the analysis of 4.Be2 , we learned another method with which Black can prevent d2-d4 . Here} 4... g5 {is less effective, because Nc3 is a more useful move than Be2 and White therefore is a decisive tempo up.} 5. d3 ({(Another important difference can be seen after} 5. d4 $5 g4 6. d5 {.)}) 5... g4 6. Nd2 h5 7. Nb3 {It is no longer so easy to prevent d3-d4 .}) 5. d3 {The most popular move. White now threatens to evict the intruder on d4 with 6.Be3 .} Ne7 {The knight goes to c6 to support its colleague.} 6. Nxd4 {This version of the exchange differs slightly from the exchange on the previous move due to the knight position on e7 .} cxd4 7. Nb5 ({There are only a few practical examples of this, but it looks better than the alternative} 7. Ne2 {.}) 7... Nc6 8. Be2 {Best. White prepares castling.} a6 9. Na3 {The knight is less badly placed here than it seems. It protects the c4 -pawn and thus stabilizes the queenside.} b5 {Black gains space and can sometimes capture on c4 .} 10. O-O Rb8 {Black has no worries. Next up is the development of the f8 -bishop and short castling.} *

