ell placed on e2 and also prevents the f1 -bishop from developing.} Nc6 8. a3 {White wants to win space on the queenside with b2 - b4 .} b5 ({With this break Black opens up the position and is better. The white queenside comes under pressure. A few possible continuations:   A ) b4 This gives White space on the queenside, but also gives Black a new pawn break.} 8... Rb8 9. Bd2 a5 $1 {White is not ready for the resulting opening of the position. bxa5 bxc4 dxc4 Ba6 All of White's queenside pawns are weak and the kingside is not yet developed. Black is clearly better. Munoz Pantoja, M-Aroshidze, L}) ({) cxb5} 8... Qa5+ {[%eval 0,0]} 9. Bd2 Qb5 10. b4 a5 {also leads to an advantageous opening of the queenside. After} 11. bxa5 Rxa5 {the white a-pawn will probably soon be lost.}) ({C ) Nf4 This is perhaps relatively best, but here too the black position deserves preference, e.g.} 8... Rb8 {Be2 a5⩱ with pressure on the queenside. Duman, A-Jojua, D}) ({D ) Ng3} 8... h5 $1 {. This is the drawback of the knight position on g3 .   D1 ) After Nxh5 follows bxc4 , threatening the double attack ...Qa5+ , so White must not recapture on c4 .   D2 ) If White wants to stop the h-pawn, they must play} 9. h4 {, but now the h4 -pawn is weak. In the correspondence game Gudok-Goncharenko , there followed bxc4 dxc4} a5 {, after which the b2 -pawn is established as a weakness. The loss of the pawn h5 doesn't matter, because Black will win back the pawn on h4 .}) *

