[PlyCount "28"]

1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we deal with an early c2-c4 . This is possible in two versions: directly on the second move or after the insertion of the moves Nf3} 1... e6 {. Against both versions I recommend an identical setup based on the weakness of the d4 -square.}) ({The positions that arise after c4 and Nf3} 1... e6 2. c4 {are very similar and there are many transpositions.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 {This increases White's control in the center and makes the typical pawn advances ... d7 - d5 and ... b7 - b5 more difficult. Later, White wants to continue with d2 - d4 and thus transition to a Maroczy structure, which can also arise from various Open Sicilians. Often White does not hurry with d2 - d4 , but first plays developing moves such as Nc3 , Be2 and O-O . Black must then expect the transition to the Open Sicilian at any time. Black will try to bring d4 under control.} ({A black knight would feel very comfortable there, because White has weakened the square with the two pawn moves and can no longer attack it with a pawn. One could describe} 3. c4 {as a mixture between the English Opening, 1.c4 , and the Sicilian. The character of many positions is reminiscent of the English and many direct transpositions are possible. c4 was Magnus Carlsen's choice in the third and final tiebreak game of his 2018 World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. He defended his world title with a win.}) 3... Nc6 {The main move. The knight exerts influence on the center and can sometimes go to d4 , effectively preventing d2 - d4 . White can now open the position with 4.d4 , transposing into a sideline of the Taimanov Sicilian, or choose to develop their pieces first. About the Hedgehog alternative} ({If you have Hedgehog positions in your repertoire, you could also play} 3... a6 {. I decided against analyzing this as an alternative, because there are some drawbacks with this move order compared to the Kan Variation. Play could continue with} 4. Nc3 Qc7 5. Be2 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {.  This position could also arise from the Kan Sicilian via the move order e4} 9. c5 {Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 a6 c4 Nf6 Nc3 Qc7 Be2 b6 O-O Bb7 . There, however, Black has the additional option ...Bb4 on the sixth or seventh move. White often plays 7.a3 to avoid 7...Bb4 . Here, White can do without the pawn move and therefore has a favorable version of the Hedgehog. I think it's better not to afford White this luxury.}) 4. Nc3 {This is the most popular move. White develops a piece and preserves the option d2 - d4 .} Nd4 ({The knight occupies d4 and thus thwarts White's plan to subsequently transition to the Maroczy structure with d2-d4 . We take advantage of the fact that White loses time after an exchange on d4 because the knight c3 is attacked. This idea is familiar from the chapter on the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Nc3 Nc6 Bb5} 4... Nd4 $1 {) . If White does not capture on d4 now, we will increase our control of the square with ...Ne7-c6 .}) ({A good alternative is} 4... Nf6 5. Be2 d5 {. The main line is now} 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 {. This queenless middlegame is close to equality, but doesn't promise Black good winning chances.}) ({In the analysis of 4.Be2 , we learned another method with which Black can prevent d2-d4 . Here} 4... g5 {is less effective, because Nc3 is a more useful move than Be2 and White therefore is a decisive tempo up.} 5. d3 ({(Another important difference can be seen after} 5. d4 $5 g4 6. d5 {.)}) 5... g4 6. Nd2 h5 7. Nb3 {It is no longer so easy to prevent d3-d4 .}) 5. d3 {The most popular move. White now threatens to evict the intruder on d4 with 6.Be3 .} Ne7 {The knight goes to c6 to support its colleague.} 6. g3 {White invests a tempo in the bishop's development. It has better prospects on g2 than on e2 .} (6. Be2 Nec6 {will soon transpose to the lines we analyzed after 5.Be2 .}) (6. Be3 {It looks as if White increases the pressure on d4 , but the opposite is the case, as after} Nec6 {White can no longer capture with the knight on d4 and the dark-squared bishop is too important to exchange for the knight.}) 6... Nec6 7. Bg2 Be7 {Black could also have copied the opponent's idea and fianchettoed their bishop as well. However, it is not clear whether it is better on g7 than on e7 . b2 - b4 is one of White's main ideas and from e7 the bishop makes this plan more difficult. If it is needed on the long diagonal, it can still move to f6 .} 8. O-O ({It is not yet a good moment for the exchange on d4 , because after} 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Ne2 {, Black can play} b5 $1 {without further preparation. The pawn is indirectly defended thanks to the queen check on a5 .}) 8... Rb8 ({A small subtlety. Black gets ready for a quick ...b7-b5 . The more natural} 8... O-O {is also playable, but has the drawback that White can prevent the pawn break ...b7-b5 with} 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Nb1 $1 {, e.g.} a6 11. a4 Rb8 12. Na3 {. As a result, the black position is relatively passive.}) 9. a3 ({Similarly, gaining space on the queenside with b2-b4 is a natural plan for White as well. Thanks to the rook move White now achieves nothing with} 9. Nxd4 {. After} cxd4 10. Nb1 ({(or} 10. Ne2 b5 {. Hakiki, K-Fedorchuk, S )}) 10... b5 $1 {Black has activity on the queenside and is already slightly better.}) 9... O-O 10. Rb1 {Further preparations for b2 - b4 ...} a6 ({and for ...b7-b5 . After the direct} 10... b5 11. cxb5 Nxb5 12. Nxb5 Rxb5 {White finally gets in the long sought-after} 13. d4 {and is slightly better. Petrova-Hrebenshchykova}) 11. Bf4 {This also serves to prepare for b2 - b4 : by provoking ... d7 - d6 , White cuts off the e7 -bishop from controlling the b4 -square.} d6 12. b4 {White comes first. The threat is b4xc5 , but apart from that White's play on the queenside is not very dangerous.} Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bg5 {Exchanging the dark-squared bishops gives Black good control of the central squares d4 and e5 .} 14. Bxg5 Qxg5 {We have been following the game Petrova-Vega Gutierrez . Black is on the slightly more comfortable side of an equal position. As before, ... b7 - b5 is a good plan, as it would lead to an advantageous opening of the position. The queen and knight play on the dark squares and the bishop goes to d7 . White will probably prepare f2 - f4 to get counterplay on the kingside.} *

