1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. d3 {This gives White flexibility with regard to the setup on the kingside.} e6 ({There is also no reason not to start with} 2... Nc6 {.}) 3. g3 ({White decides to develop the bishop to g2 . This leads to a King's Indian Attack. The most important alternative is} 3. f4 {, which we examine in the chapter on the Grand Prix Attack .}) (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 {is another way to reach the King's Indian Attack. We arrive at this position via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d3 Nc6 g3 .}) 3... Nc6 ({Or first} 3... d5 {.}) 4. Bg2 d5 ({A popular alternative is} 4... g6 {followed by ...Bg7 and ...Nge7 . d5 is more straightforward.}) 5. Nd2 {With this White avoids a possible queen trade on the d-file. The knight will later be brought to the kingside via f1 .} Nf6 6. Ngf3 Be7 ({Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, as Black would then always have to ensure that e5 is sufficiently protected. We consider this position via the more popular move order} 6... dxe4 {c5 Nf3 e6 d3 Nc6 g3 d5 Nbd2 Nf6 Bg2 Be7 .}) *

