1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Qe2 {With the early queen move White wants to make ...d7-d5 more difficult, e.g. d5 exd5 and the black e-pawn is pinned. However, Black can prepare their play in the center.} Nc6 {Black still keeps their options open on the kingside. In any case, the knight belongs on c6 .} 4. g3 Be7 {It is unusual to develop the bishop before the knight. In this case there is a concrete reason for this: Black wants to play ... d7 - d5 and must first neutralize the white queen on e2 .} 5. Bg2 d5 6. d3 ({White defends the e-pawn. The pawn structure of the King's Indian Attack is emerging.} 6. exd5 {The exchange on d5 doesn't help White, because thanks to the bishop on e7 Black can recapture with the pawn.} exd5 {The queen on e2 is now misplaced.}) ({White can prevent the development of the knight to f6 , but it has another good route:} 6. e5 Nh6 {The knight goes to f5 and is very well placed there.}) 6... Nf6 ({We will look at this position in more detail using the move order} 6... dxe4 {c5 Nf3 e6 d3 Nc6 g3 d5 Qe2 Nf6 Bg2 Be7 .}) *

