1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Qe2 {By leaving the d-file, White avoids a possible queen trade, which would otherwise be possible after the exchange on e4 . Additionally, White preemptively defends the e-pawn. Compared to the main line, 5.Nbd2 , the queen move has the advantage that White retains more flexibility on the queenside. The c1 -bishop can be developed directly and the knight can be brought to c3 (or even a3 ). As we will see, White also pursues a very specific idea which is not possible after 5.Nbd2 .} Nf6 {The standard setup for Black: the knight goes to f6 , where it puts pressure on e4 . If White plays e4 - e5 , the knight goes to d7 and attacks the e-pawn again.} ({The e7 -square is reserved for the bishop. Black could also start with} 5... Be7 {.}) 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O ({White could also start with} 7. e5 {. But after} Nd7 8. c4 O-O {there is nothing better than} 9. O-O {, with a transposition to 7.O-O .}) 7... O-O ({After both sides have brought their king to safety, it is now up to White to decide on a plan. Interesting is} 7... b5 {to prevent c2-c4 . However, White could avoid this possibility with the move order} 8. e5 Nd7 9. c4 {.}) 8. e5 ({White closes the center and prepares the following move. The direct} 8. c4 $6 {would give Black comfortable play after} dxc4 9. dxc4 e5 {.}) 8... Nd7 {The usual square for the knight, which from here ties the white pieces to the defense of the e5 -pawn.} 9. c4 {This is the point of the line starting with 5.Qe2 . We will see in the main line 5.Nbd2 that Black develops a strong attack on the queenside, which is initiated with the move ... b7 - b5 . In contrast, here White has already protected the pawn on e5 and therefore has time to complicate Black's play on the queenside.} a6 ({Black does not lose sight of the goal and again prepares ...b7-b5 . The most common move is} 9... d4 {. After that, however, Black lacks counterplay, while White has a free hand on the kingside. A good illustration is the rapid game Carlsen-Ding .}) 10. Nc3 {White attacks the pawn on d5 and prevents ... b7 - b5 . But the knight move also has a drawback.} Nd4 ({Black should act energetically. The alternative is} 10... d4 {. As with 9...d4 , however, it will be difficult to get counterplay afterwards.} 11. Ne4 $1 {White wants to continue with 12.Bf4 and would then have free play on the kingside. After} Ndxe5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxc5 {, White wins back the pawn and has the more active minor pieces.}) 11. Nxd4 {Forced, otherwise White loses the e-pawn.} cxd4 {This is the aforementioned drawback of the knight position on c3 . White is losing time.} 12. Nb1 ({This looks more natural than 12.Nd1 . The knight finds its way back into the game via d2 . After} 12. Nd1 dxc4 13. dxc4 {, Black gets good counterplay with} Rb8 {and ...b7-b5 .}) 12... dxc4 13. dxc4 Qc7 ({Black is in time. The pawn on e5 is under attack and if White defends it, Black can support their own central pawn with ...Rd8 . White should probably play modestly and agree to an exchange of central pawns.  ➤ After Rd1 Qxe5 Qxe5} 13... Nxe5 {Rxd4 Nc6= After ...e6-e5 an equal position is reached.  Black could also play more ambitiously: Bd7!?} 14. Bxb7 {Rad8 . Black is threatening an invasion along the d-file and has good compensation for the pawn.  ➤ If White plays Re1 instead, Rd8 follows, after which the d-pawn is reliably defended and a trump rather than a weakness. Black next wants to play ...Rb8 and ...b7-b5 to liberate the queenside. In addition, the tactical possibility ...d4-d3 is in the air, e.g. Nd2?!} d3 $1 15. Qe4 ({(After} 15. Qxd3 {Nxe5 Qe2} Nxd3 {Black secures the bishop pair and is slightly better.)}) 15... Rb8 {. Black prepares ...b7-b5 . White can't easily get rid of the pawn on d3 , because after Qxd3 , Black can capture advantageously on e5 . Black holds a slight advantage.}) *

