1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Qe2 {By leaving the d-file, White avoids a possible queen trade, which would otherwise be possible after the exchange on e4 . Additionally, White preemptively defends the e-pawn. Compared to the main line, 5.Nbd2 , the queen move has the advantage that White retains more flexibility on the queenside. The c1 -bishop can be developed directly and the knight can be brought to c3 (or even a3 ). As we will see, White also pursues a very specific idea which is not possible after 5.Nbd2 .} Nf6 {The standard setup for Black: the knight goes to f6 , where it puts pressure on e4 . If White plays e4 - e5 , the knight goes to d7 and attacks the e-pawn again.} ({The e7 -square is reserved for the bishop. Black could also start with} 5... Be7 {.}) 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O ({White could also start with} 7. e5 {. But after} Nd7 8. c4 O-O {there is nothing better than} 9. O-O {, with a transposition to 7.O-O .}) 7... O-O ({After both sides have brought their king to safety, it is now up to White to decide on a plan. Interesting is} 7... b5 {to prevent c2-c4 . However, White could avoid this possibility with the move order} 8. e5 Nd7 9. c4 {.}) 8. e5 ({White closes the center and prepares the following move. The direct} 8. c4 $6 {would give Black comfortable play after} dxc4 9. dxc4 e5 {.}) 8... Nd7 {The usual square for the knight, which from here ties the white pieces to the defense of the e5 -pawn.} 9. c4 {This is the point of the line starting with 5.Qe2 . We will see in the main line 5.Nbd2 that Black develops a strong attack on the queenside, which is initiated with the move ... b7 - b5 . In contrast, here White has already protected the pawn on e5 and therefore has time to complicate Black's play on the queenside.} a6 ({Black does not lose sight of the goal and again prepares ...b7-b5 . The most common move is} 9... d4 {. After that, however, Black lacks counterplay, while White has a free hand on the kingside. A good illustration is the rapid game Carlsen-Ding .}) 10. Rd1 {A very rare move. I want to analyze it anyway because the following line shows what fascinating tactical possibilities there are in the position.} b5 {Black continues with the plan.} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. d4 {Perhaps not the best, but that was obviously the idea of 10.Rd1 .} c4 ({A novelty. Black should keep the position closed and is now threatening ...Nb6 , which would prevent e5-e6 . The mobile pawns on the queenside then give Black a big advantage. Therefore the white reply is practically forced. In Sutormin-Skatchkov, 2023 ,} 12... cxd4 $2 {happened. After} 13. Nxd4 {White was already clearly better because the d5 -pawn is very weak. There followed} Ndxe5 $2 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Nc3 $1 Bb7 16. Nxd5 {when the great activity gave White a winning advantage.}) 13. e6 Nb6 14. exf7+ Rxf7 {In the long run, Black holds the better cards. Next up could be ... Bg4 or (after 15.h3 ) ... Bf5 .} 15. Ne5 {White opens up the position. The game now becomes very tactical.} Nxe5 ({Not} 15... Rf6 $2 16. Nc3 {after which the black position, especially the d5 -pawn, is tactically vulnerable.}) 16. dxe5 {It looks as if White's play was more successful. The d-pawn is about to be blocked with Be3 and would then be a weakness.} d4 {The mobility of the d-pawn is more important than the rook on a8 !} 17. Bxa8 d3 ({Not} 17... Nxa8 $2 18. Qe4 {with a double attack.}) 18. Bf3 {This attempt to give back the material is spectacularly refuted:} Bb7 ({Now both queen and bishop are under attack, so the following moves are forced.} 18... dxe2 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 20. Bxe2 {gives Black compensation for the pawn, but no more.}) 19. Bxb7 (19. Bf4 $2 Qa8 {.}) 19... dxe2 20. Rxd8+ Bxd8 21. Bd2 Rxb7 {Black has won back the material and will next attack the white queenside with ... Na4 . Black is clearly better.} *

