n.} b5 {Black continues with the plan.} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. d4 {Perhaps not the best, but that was obviously the idea of 10.Rd1 .} c4 ({A novelty. Black should keep the position closed and is now threatening ...Nb6 , which would prevent e5-e6 . The mobile pawns on the queenside then give Black a big advantage. Therefore the white reply is practically forced. In Sutormin-Skatchkov, 2023 ,} 12... cxd4 $2 {happened. After} 13. Nxd4 {White was already clearly better because the d5 -pawn is very weak. There followed} Ndxe5 $2 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Nc3 $1 Bb7 16. Nxd5 {when the great activity gave White a winning advantage.}) 13. e6 Nb6 14. exf7+ Rxf7 {In the long run, Black holds the better cards. Next up could be ... Bg4 or (after 15.h3 ) ... Bf5 .} 15. Ne5 {White opens up the position. The game now becomes very tactical.} Nxe5 ({Not} 15... Rf6 $2 16. Nc3 {after which the black position, especially the d5 -pawn, is tactically vulnerable.}) 16. dxe5 {It looks as if White's play was more successful. The d-pawn is about to be blocked with Be3 and would then be a weakness.} d4 {The mobility of the d-pawn is more important than the rook on a8 !} 17. Bxa8 d3 ({Not} 17... Nxa8 $2 18. Qe4 {with a double attack.}) 18. Qe4 Bf5 19. Qc6 Nxa8 {The control of the light squares on the kingside and the strong protected passed pawn on d3 give Black more than enough compensation for the exchange. The knight will come back into play via c7 and Black will try to bring the bishop to the long diagonal a8 - h1 . After that White has to worry about their king safety.} *

