1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Qe2 {By leaving the d-file, White avoids a possible queen trade, which would otherwise be possible after the exchange on e4 . Additionally, White preemptively defends the e-pawn. Compared to the main line, 5.Nbd2 , the queen move has the advantage that White retains more flexibility on the queenside. The c1 -bishop can be developed directly and the knight can be brought to c3 (or even a3 ). As we will see, White also pursues a very specific idea which is not possible after 5.Nbd2 .} Nf6 {The standard setup for Black: the knight goes to f6 , where it puts pressure on e4 . If White plays e4 - e5 , the knight goes to d7 and attacks the e-pawn again.} ({The e7 -square is reserved for the bishop. Black could also start with} 5... Be7 {.}) 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O ({White could also start with} 7. e5 {. But after} Nd7 8. c4 O-O {there is nothing better than} 9. O-O {, with a transposition to 7.O-O .}) 7... O-O ({After both sides have brought their king to safety, it is now up to White to decide on a plan. Interesting is} 7... b5 {to prevent c2-c4 . However, White could avoid this possibility with the move order} 8. e5 Nd7 9. c4 {.}) 8. e5 ({White closes the center and prepares the following move. The direct} 8. c4 $6 {would give Black comfortable play after} dxc4 9. dxc4 e5 {.}) 8... Nd7 {The usual square for the knight, which from here ties the white pieces to the defense of the e5 -pawn.} 9. c4 {This is the point of the line starting with 5.Qe2 . We will see in the main line 5.Nbd2 that Black develops a strong attack on the queenside, which is initiated with the move ... b7 - b5 . In contrast, here White has already protected the pawn on e5 and therefore has time to complicate Black's play on the queenside.} a6 ({Black does not lose sight of the goal and again prepares ...b7-b5 . The most common move is} 9... d4 {. After that, however, Black lacks counterplay, while White has a free hand on the kingside. A good illustration is the rapid game Carlsen-Ding .}) 10. h4 ({Typical play for the King's Indian Attack. The pawn can later be moved further forward, and it also controls g5 . Black need not be afraid of the exchange on d5 .} 10. cxd5 $6 {A positional mistake.} exd5 11. Nc3 Nb6 {Thanks to the exchange on d5 , Black can next develop the light-squared bishop freely. The pawn on e5 is in danger because it can be attacked via the half-open e-file. Black is better.}) 10... b5 11. Bf4 ({Another move typical of the King's Indian Attack. The bishop stabilizes the center and cannot itself be attacked. As before, only Black benefits from} 11. cxd5 $6 {, because the bishop c8 then becomes active.} exd5 {In some games there now followed} 12. e6 $6 Nb6 {(or 12...Nf6∓ )} 13. exf7+ Rxf7 {. Black is now threatening ...Bg4 and after} 14. Ng5 Nd4 {can follow. Black is clearly better. ( Rf6 happened in Chigaev-Bukavshin and is also possible.)}) 11... Nb6 ({Black increases the pressure on the c4 -pawn. With the knight on b6 , Black no longer has to reckon with the exchange on d5 .} 11... Bb7 $6 {is premature:} 12. cxd5 $1 exd5 13. e6 {With this opening of the position, the bishop is needed on c8 .}) 12. Na3 {White defends the pawn on c4 and attacks the pawn on b5 at the same time. The knight is not well placed on a3 , but White is counting on its stay there being only temporary.} Rb8 {The rook leaves the diagonal of the bishop on g2 and targets the pawn b2 . Specifically, Black is threatening to exchange on c4 and then capture the b2 -pawn. Accepting the pawn sacrifice on b5 leads to a bad position for White.} ({The 'win of a tempo'} 12... b4 $6 {would play into White's hands. After} 13. Nc2 {the knight comes to the kingside via e3 and the queenside remains closed.}) ({Black could also play the same way as against 12.Nbd2 , but with the knight on a3 White has a better defense:} 12... bxc4 13. dxc4 a5 14. b3 Ba6 15. Nb5 {. The knight on b5 blocks the diagonal of the bishop a6 and controls the d4 -square.}) 13. cxb5 {White is better off declining this win of a pawn.} axb5 14. Nxb5 Na4 {If the knight on b5 moves, Black wins back the pawn with 15...Rxb2 and is better because the pawns on a2 and d3 are weak.} 15. Qc2 {The best defense.} Nb4 (15... Rxb5 16. Qxa4 Qb6 {is also good for Black.}) 16. Qxa4 Bd7 {Black wins back the piece. White must now take care of the defense of the d-pawn.} 17. Ne1 Bxb5 18. Qd1 {The best square. On a3 or b3 , the queen would be exposed to tactical motifs.} Qa5 {The situation on the queenside is reminiscent of the Benko Gambit. Black exerts strong pressure along the a- and b-files against the white pawns. The second rook could also be brought to the queenside, e.g. with ... Ra8 and ... Rfb8 . In addition, the pawns on e5 and d3 are weak. The knight on e1 and the bishop on f4 are tied to defending these weaknesses. Specifically, Black is threatening 19...Qa6 , winning back the sacrificed pawn. White's position is not enviable. However, winning back the pawn with ...Nxa2 is usually not the best idea, as this would put the knight in an awkward pin.} *

