pawn b2 .}) 13... dxc4 {With the following sequence, Black takes advantage of the unfavorable position of the a3 -knight.} 14. dxc4 (14. bxc4 $2 Na4 {is very bad for White. The pawn on d3 is weak and cannot be protected by a rook on d1 , because then the knight fork on c3 follows. In addition, the knight on a3 is out of place.}) 14... Nd4 15. Nxd4 ({Or} 15. Qd3 Bb7 {. Black has the more active pieces and is therefore slightly better.}) 15... cxd4 {Now the point of Black's play becomes clear. The knight on a3 is attacked and has no good flight square.} 16. Nb1 (16. Nc2 $4 d3) 16... bxc4 17. bxc4 Na4 {From here the knight can go to c5 or – if the knight moves from b1 – to c3 . The knight move also clears the way for the rook, which will be well placed on b2 or b4 . Black retains the better practical chances, even if White can probably keep the balance with accurate play.} *

