he exchange on d5 .} 10. cxd5 $6 {A positional mistake.} exd5 11. Nc3 Nb6 {Thanks to the exchange on d5 , Black can next develop the light-squared bishop freely. The pawn on e5 is in danger because it can be attacked via the half-open e-file. Black is better.}) 10... b5 11. Bf4 ({Another move typical of the King's Indian Attack. The bishop stabilizes the center and cannot itself be attacked. As before, only Black benefits from} 11. cxd5 $6 {, because the bishop c8 then becomes active.} exd5 {In some games there now followed} 12. e6 $6 Nb6 {(or 12...Nf6∓ )} 13. exf7+ Rxf7 {. Black is now threatening ...Bg4 and after} 14. Ng5 Nd4 {can follow. Black is clearly better. ( Rf6 happened in Chigaev-Bukavshin and is also possible.)}) 11... Nb6 ({Black increases the pressure on the c4 -pawn. With the knight on b6 , Black no longer has to reckon with the exchange on d5 .} 11... Bb7 $6 {is premature:} 12. cxd5 $1 exd5 13. e6 {With this opening of the position, the bishop is needed on c8 .}) 12. b3 ({With this defensive move, White keeps open how the knight on b1 will be developed and avoids the concrete problems that Black can pose after both} 12. Nbd2 {and Na3 .}) 12... Bb7 ({Here} 12... bxc4 13. dxc4 a5 {doesn't work so well – White plays} 14. Nc3 Ba6 15. Rad1 {and gets pressure against the d-pawn.}) 13. Nbd2 ({The human move. White develops the last piece. In both games with classical time control in which this position was reached, this move was played. Stockfish suggests} 13. Rc1 {instead. The idea is probably to keep the knight's options open: it could be developed to c3 , d2 , or even a3 .} Qd7 {The queen clears the way for the f8 -rook. A complex middlegame position has been reached in which both sides have equal chances.} ({(} 13... Qc7 $6 14. Nc3 $1 {would be slightly better for White.)}) {In the correspondence game Dawson-Lumsdon , there followed} 14. Nbd2 h6 {(A useful move that stabilizes the kingside. But there was also nothing to be said against 14...Rfc8 .)} 15. d4 {(White resolves the tension in the center.)} bxc4 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. bxc4 Qe7 {with equality.}) (13. Nc3 {allows} Nd4 {. After the exchange on d4 , the knight on c3 must move again.}) 13... Qc7 ({This is stronger than both} 13... Rc8 {and Qd7 , which were played before. Black wants to bring a rook to d8 and can then open the d-file at a favorable moment.}) 14. Rfd1 {Among the many options, this looks like the most logical. White prepares for the opening of the d-file and prepares the regrouping of the knight via f1 .} Rfd8 {The right rook. The a-rook is good on c8 or b8 .} 15. Nf1 {Again, there are many other options, but it's not so clear how White should proceed. Black can strengthen the position with ... Rac8 and ... h6 .} bxc4 ({It's just as good to wait with this decision and strengthen the position with, say,} 15... Rac8 {.}) 16. bxc4 dxc4 17. dxc4 Nd4 {This leads to an favorable exchange.} 18. Nxd4 cxd4 {Black is better. The pawn on c4 is weak and can be attacked by Black's major pieces. On the other hand, White has no good way to attack the d4 -pawn, and it is therefore more of a strength. If White defends the pawn on c4 , Black can further improve their position with ... Na4 . The knight can go to c3 or to c5 , where it supports the d-pawn.} ({A possible continuation is Bxb7 Qxb7 Nd2 (intending Nb3 )} 18... Na4 {(threatening the fork …Nc3 ) Ne4 Rac8 followed by …Qc6 .}) *

