[ECO "C00"]
[PlyCount "32"]

1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Nbd2 {White thus avoids a possible queen trade on the d-file. The knight should later be brought to the kingside via f1 .} Nf6 {The most natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. e5 ({This is somewhat inaccurate. It is better to prepare the advance with} 8. Re1 {.}) 8... Nd7 9. Re1 Qc7 {That's the problem. White actually wants to defend the e5 -pawn with Bf4 , but of course that's not possible here. While we only make moves that fit into our intended setup, White now has to invest a tempo to protect the e-pawn.} 10. Qe2 b5 ({Black adopts the setup we will also see in the main line 8.Re1 . There I have explained the moves of both sides in more detail.} 10... b5 {gains space on the queenside and prepares development of the light-squared bishop to b7 .}) 11. Nf1 Bb7 {The bishop clears the way for the f-rook to go to c8 .} 12. h4 ({The order of the white moves is not very important. It is also possible to play} 12. Bf4 {first, with a transposition after} Rfc8 13. h4 {. 12.h4 prepares the further advance of the h-pawn and vacates h2 for the knight.}) 12... Rfc8 {The rook has no place on the kingside and only prevents the minor pieces from defending there.} 13. Bf4 Qd8 {After the rook has been 'released' from the kingside, the queen returns to its best square. From d8 it helps to defend the kingside, because it controls g5 (if White plays g3- g4 -g5 ) and can go to f8 (which is especially important in case of piece sacrifices on h6 ).} 14. N1h2 a5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside.} 15. h5 h6 {The white pawn must not be allowed to reach h6 .} 16. Ng4 Bf8 {To be on the safe side, Black overprotects h6 and thus prevents possible piece sacrifices. In the main line we reach this position with the white queen on d2 instead of e2 . The queen on d2 makes much more sense as it supports White's attacking ideas on the kingside.} ({With the queen on e2 it is not clear how White should continue the attack. In practice, the most common move is now Qd2 , after which White has lost a whole tempo due to the inaccurate move order. Black then continues with the play on the queenside:} 16... a4 {or} 17. b4 {.}) *

