1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Nbd2 {White thus avoids a possible queen trade on the d-file. The knight should later be brought to the kingside via f1 .} Nf6 {The most natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Here the rook supports the advance e4 - e5 . In addition, White vacates f1 for the knight.} b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. With the move of the b-pawn, Black gains space and at the same time prepares the development of the bishop to b7 . The long-term aim is either to open lines and penetrate the white position with the major pieces or to obtain outpost squares for the knights.} 9. exd5 ({Compared to} 9. e5 {, this is a fairly rare minor variation, but it has been played by some strong grandmasters. White opens up the position and shifts play to the center and the queenside, which makes the character of the position very different from the lines after e5 .}) 9... Nxd5 ({More popular is} 9... exd5 {, after which White usually plays} 10. d4 ({(either directly or after inserting the moves} 10. a4 b4 {)}) {. Black should now settle for an isolated pawn on d5 , because} 10... c4 $6 11. a4 b4 12. Ne5 {is advantageous for White. After other 10th moves (instead of 10... c4?! ), the black position is perfectly fine, but I prefer to avoid the weak pawn on d5 .}) 10. Ne4 {White centralizes the knight and prepares Bg5 . After the bishop exchange the pawn on c5 would be vulnerable.} h6 {It seems easiest to me to immediately prevent the bishop from moving to g5 . Black has comfortable equality. Next could come ... Bb7 and ... Rc8 .} (10... Bb7 {has been played more often, including in the game Svidler-Karjakin . With} 11. Bg5 {White can now complicate the game, e.g. after} h6 {,} 12. Nxc5 $5 hxg5 13. Nxb7 Qc7 14. c4 {would be possible.}) 11. c4 {White forces the events.} bxc4 12. dxc4 Ndb4 {White has the better pawn structure (the pawn on c5 is weak), but Black can compensate for this small disadvantage with the activity of the b4 -knight.} 13. Be3 Qxd1 14. Rexd1 {This is playable, but in the following complications, White has to find some difficult moves to not be worse.} Nc2 15. Bxc5 (15. Rac1 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Rb8 {is slightly better for Black.}) 15... Nxa1 (15... Bxc5 $2 16. Nxc5 Nxa1 17. Ne1 $1 {Black loses both knights.}) 16. Ne5 {The point of the previous move.} Bxc5 ({Or} 16... Nxe5 17. Bxe7 Re8 18. Nd6 $1 {.}) 17. Nxc6 {Black has two pieces under attack, plus the rook on a8 is in danger.} Bb7 18. Nxc5 Bxc6 19. Bxc6 Rac8 20. Nd7 Rxc6 21. Nxf8 Kxf8 22. Rxa1 Rxc4 {At the end of the complications, an equal rook ending is on the board.} *

