st natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Here the rook supports the advance e4 - e5 . In addition, White vacates f1 for the knight.} b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. With the move of the b-pawn, Black gains space and at the same time prepares the development of the bishop to b7 . The long-term aim is either to open lines and penetrate the white position with the major pieces or to obtain outpost squares for the knights.} 9. exd5 ({Compared to} 9. e5 {, this is a fairly rare minor variation, but it has been played by some strong grandmasters. White opens up the position and shifts play to the center and the queenside, which makes the character of the position very different from the lines after e5 .}) 9... Nxd5 ({More popular is} 9... exd5 {, after which White usually plays} 10. d4 ({(either directly or after inserting the moves} 10. a4 b4 {)}) {. Black should now settle for an isolated pawn on d5 , because} 10... c4 $6 11. a4 b4 12. Ne5 {is advantageous for White. After other 10th moves (instead of 10... c4?! ), the black position is perfectly fine, but I prefer to avoid the weak pawn on d5 .}) 10. Ne4 {White centralizes the knight and prepares Bg5 . After the bishop exchange the pawn on c5 would be vulnerable.} h6 {It seems easiest to me to immediately prevent the bishop from moving to g5 . Black has comfortable equality. Next could come ... Bb7 and ... Rc8 .} (10... Bb7 {has been played more often, including in the game Svidler-Karjakin . With} 11. Bg5 {White can now complicate the game, e.g. after} h6 {,} 12. Nxc5 $5 hxg5 13. Nxb7 Qc7 14. c4 {would be possible.}) 11. c4 {White forces the events.} bxc4 12. dxc4 Ndb4 {White has the better pawn structure (the pawn on c5 is weak), but Black can compensate for this small disadvantage with the activity of the b4 -knight.} 13. Be3 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Nc2 15. Re2 Nxe3 {The bishop is eliminated before White can help themselves on c5 . The position remains equal, but I would prefer Black. The bishop pair promises long-term winning chances. Shtembuliak-Stremavicius .} *

