1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Nbd2 {White thus avoids a possible queen trade on the d-file. The knight should later be brought to the kingside via f1 .} Nf6 {The most natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Here the rook supports the advance e4 - e5 . In addition, White vacates f1 for the knight.} b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. With the move of the b-pawn, Black gains space and at the same time prepares the development of the bishop to b7 . The long-term aim is either to open lines and penetrate the white position with the major pieces or to obtain outpost squares for the knights.} 9. exd5 ({Compared to} 9. e5 {, this is a fairly rare minor variation, but it has been played by some strong grandmasters. White opens up the position and shifts play to the center and the queenside, which makes the character of the position very different from the lines after e5 .}) 9... Nxd5 ({More popular is} 9... exd5 {, after which White usually plays} 10. d4 ({(either directly or after inserting the moves} 10. a4 b4 {)}) {. Black should now settle for an isolated pawn on d5 , because} 10... c4 $6 11. a4 b4 12. Ne5 {is advantageous for White. After other 10th moves (instead of 10... c4?! ), the black position is perfectly fine, but I prefer to avoid the weak pawn on d5 .}) 10. c4 {This gives White the better pawn structure, but weakens the d3 and d4 -squares.} bxc4 11. dxc4 ({Worse is} 11. Nxc4 $6 {. In the game Foygel-Bryan , Black had pressure against the b2 -pawn after} Bb7 12. a3 Rb8 13. Bd2 Ba8 14. Qc2 Bf6 {.}) 11... Ndb4 ({The most active square for the knight. From here he can go to d3 .} 11... Nb6 $5 {is a way to avoid the following simplifications. The result is a complex middlegame with equal chances.} 12. Ne5 {can now be answered with} Nxe5 {, because after} 13. Bxa8 Nd3 {both rook and bishop are attacked and Black wins back the material.}) 12. Ne5 {White should force matters. After other moves Black is already slightly better thanks to their active minor pieces.} Bb7 13. a3 {Again the only move with which White can keep the balance. The following moves are forced.} Nxe5 14. Bxb7 Nbd3 {Black saves themselves from the double attack by counter-attacking.} 15. Bxa8 Nxe1 ({After} 15... Qxa8 $2 16. Re3 {Black does not have enough play for the lost exchange.}) 16. Qxe1 Nd3 17. Qe3 ({An equal position is also reached after} 17. Qe2 Nxc1 18. Rxc1 Qxa8 {.}) 17... Nxc1 18. Rxc1 ({It looks as if after} 18. Be4 $2 {the knight is trapped on c1 . But Black saves themselves with} Bg5 19. f4 Bf6 {. The threat is ...Bd4 , so White cannot protect the b2 -pawn.} 20. Kg2 Bxb2 21. Rb1 Bd4 22. Qf3 Na2 {The knight is freed and Black has a healthy extra pawn.}) 18... Bg5 {Or 18... Qxa8 =.} 19. Qe2 ({After} 19. f4 $6 Bf6 {...Bd4 is a threat, winning the queen. White can't save the bishop on a8 and has weakened their own king position with the pawn move.}) 19... Qxd2 20. Qxd2 Bxd2 21. Rd1 Ba5 22. Bc6 Rd8 23. Rxd8+ Bxd8 {We have been following the game Korpa-Kaczur , in which a draw was now agreed. In fact, there is no reason to play on. Neither side has winning chances.} *

