1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Nbd2 {White thus avoids a possible queen trade on the d-file. The knight should later be brought to the kingside via f1 .} Nf6 {The most natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Here the rook supports the advance e4 - e5 . In addition, White vacates f1 for the knight.} b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. With the move of the b-pawn, Black gains space and at the same time prepares the development of the bishop to b7 . The long-term aim is either to open lines and penetrate the white position with the major pieces or to obtain outpost squares for the knights.} 9. exd5 ({Compared to} 9. e5 {, this is a fairly rare minor variation, but it has been played by some strong grandmasters. White opens up the position and shifts play to the center and the queenside, which makes the character of the position very different from the lines after e5 .}) 9... Nxd5 ({More popular is} 9... exd5 {, after which White usually plays} 10. d4 ({(either directly or after inserting the moves} 10. a4 b4 {)}) {. Black should now settle for an isolated pawn on d5 , because} 10... c4 $6 11. a4 b4 12. Ne5 {is advantageous for White. After other 10th moves (instead of 10... c4?! ), the black position is perfectly fine, but I prefer to avoid the weak pawn on d5 .}) 10. a4 {White forces the b-pawn to move and thus gets an outpost on c4 for the d2 -knight.} b4 {There is no alternative. Exchanging the b-pawn for the a-pawn would lead to weak pawns on a7 and c5 .} 11. Nc4 {The logical continuation. The knight supports a4 - a5 , protects b2 (in case Black plays ... Bf6 ) and supports Nfe5 .} Bb7 12. h4 {A useful and typical move for the King's Indian Attack. White can now develop the bishop to g5 or move the h-pawn further forward to provoke weaknesses around Black's king.} Rc8 {Black improves their queenside setup. The bishop now has a flight square on a8 in case it is attacked by the white a-pawn.} ({Another possibility is} 12... h6 {, which prevents the exchange of bishops.}) 13. Bg5 ({Black need not fear the exchange of bishops.} 13. h5 $6 h6 {is unfavorable for White, because the minor pieces are badly positioned for a kingside attack and the pawn on h5 could become a weakness.}) ({The engine prefers} 13. a5 {. We examine this position via the move order a5 Rc8 h4 .}) 13... h6 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. a5 Rfd8 {We have been following the blitz game Wang-Karjakin . Black is fully developed and has centralized pieces. The position is equal.} *

