st natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Here the rook supports the advance e4 - e5 . In addition, White vacates f1 for the knight.} b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. With the move of the b-pawn, Black gains space and at the same time prepares the development of the bishop to b7 . The long-term aim is either to open lines and penetrate the white position with the major pieces or to obtain outpost squares for the knights.} 9. exd5 ({Compared to} 9. e5 {, this is a fairly rare minor variation, but it has been played by some strong grandmasters. White opens up the position and shifts play to the center and the queenside, which makes the character of the position very different from the lines after e5 .}) 9... Nxd5 ({More popular is} 9... exd5 {, after which White usually plays} 10. d4 ({(either directly or after inserting the moves} 10. a4 b4 {)}) {. Black should now settle for an isolated pawn on d5 , because} 10... c4 $6 11. a4 b4 12. Ne5 {is advantageous for White. After other 10th moves (instead of 10... c4?! ), the black position is perfectly fine, but I prefer to avoid the weak pawn on d5 .}) 10. a4 {White forces the b-pawn to move and thus gets an outpost on c4 for the d2 -knight.} b4 {There is no alternative. Exchanging the b-pawn for the a-pawn would lead to weak pawns on a7 and c5 .} 11. Nc4 {The logical continuation. The knight supports a4 - a5 , protects b2 (in case Black plays ... Bf6 ) and supports Nfe5 .} Bb7 12. a5 {White gains space on the queenside and is threatening a5 - a6 .} Rc8 ({Black creates a flight square for the bishop on a8 .} 12... Rb8 {is also good. It is not yet clear where the rook will be better later.}) 13. h4 {A useful and typical move for the King's Indian Attack. White can now develop the bishop to g5 or move the h-pawn further forward to provoke weaknesses around Black's king.} Qc7 (13... h6 {is also possible, but as we have already seen it is not necessary to prevent the exchange of bishops. With Qc7 Black prepares ...Rfd8 . The position can be further reinforced with the moves ...Bf6 or ...Ba6 . Black has no worries.}) ({In the game Korobov-Grischuk .} 13... Bg5 {Rfd8 Bxe7 Ndxe7} 14. a6 Ba8 {followed, with an equal position.}) *

