1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Nbd2 {White thus avoids a possible queen trade on the d-file. The knight should later be brought to the kingside via f1 .} Nf6 {The most natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Here the rook supports the advance e4 - e5 . In addition, White vacates f1 for the knight.} b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. With the move of the b-pawn, Black gains space and at the same time prepares the development of the bishop to b7 . The long-term aim is either to open lines and penetrate the white position with the major pieces or to obtain outpost squares for the knights.} 9. e5 ({White prepares their attack on the kingside. The knight is driven off f6 and Black is deprived of the possibility of exchanging on e4 and d1 , which would have been possible after the direct} 9. Nf1 {.}) ({After} 9. a4 b4 {, White usually plays} 10. exd5 {. We look at the position after Nxd5 via the move order} exd5 {Nxd5 a4 b4 .}) 9... Nd7 {The best square for the knight. White is now tied to the defense of the e5 -pawn.} 10. Nf1 {Why did White spend two tempi to bring the knight to this seemingly passive square? The answer is that this is only a midway point of its journey. White wants to play h2 - h4 and then bring the knight via h2 to g4 , where it is then in threatening proximity to the black king. Black can hardly prevent this and should instead pursue their own ideas on the queenside.} (10. h4 $6 {A standard move and an integral part of the white setup. However, it is more accurate to start with Nf1 .} Qc7 $1 {White must now defend the e-pawn with} 11. Qe2 {instead of Bf4 as desired. We are already familiar with this problem from the analysis of 8.e5?! .}) 10... Bb7 {With this move, Black initiates a deep idea which combines an attack on the queenside with the defense of the kingside: the rook is to be brought from f8 to c8 , as on f8 it hinders the defense. White wants to advance the h-pawn to h6 so that they can then use the square f6 as a gateway for the minor pieces. To prevent this advance, Black would like to play ... h7 - h6 themselves, but then they must always reckon with sacrifices on this square. It is therefore necessary to additionally protect h6 with ... Bf8 . Black could of course prepare this with a rook move to e8 , but on the one hand the rook has no active role there and on the other may still be in the way, because occasionally Black needs the move ... Qf8 to defend the kingside.} 11. h4 {White sets the h-pawn in motion and vacates h2 for the knight.} Qc7 {The queen steps aside to let the rook pass. A convenient side effect: White has to defend the e5 -pawn.} 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {Black has carried out the first part of the plan: the rook no longer interferes with the defense of the kingside.} 13. N1h2 ({The usual route of the knight to the kingside. White could also move the h-pawn first.} 13. h5 h6 $1 {The white pawn must not be allowed to advance to h6 . A quick transposition to our main line is now likely.}) (13. Ne3 {This hardly has any independent significance either. White is now threatening 14.Nxd5  exd5  15.e6 , but the black queen should return to d8 anyway.} Qd8 14. Ng4 {We deal with this via the move order N1h2 Qd8 Ng4 .}) 13... Qd8 {After the rook has been 'freed', the queen returns to its starting square. This is not absolutely necessary here, but it helps the defense if the queen can go to f8 or e8 while keeping an eye on g5 (in case White sends the g-pawn forward).} ({The game is relatively schematic, but care must be taken with the move order. The bishop should only go to f8 when White has played Ng4 . After} 13... Bf8 $6 {comes} 14. h5 h6 {(otherwise White plays h5-h6 themselves)} 15. g4 $1 {followed by g4-g5 . The kingside opens up and White gets good attacking chances. If the knight is already on g4 , this plan is slower, because White would have to retreat the knight first.}) 14. Ng4 {This ends the long knight maneuver for the time being.} Bf8 ({Black adopts the defensive setup on the kingside. The bishop defends the square h6 from f8 , which means that we can react to} 14... h5 {with h6 without having to fear a piece sacrifice. Analysis shows that the sacrifice on h6 was not yet very dangerous here, but in a practical game it is easier not to have to expect it all the time.}) 15. h5 {The logical continuation of the attack.} h6 ({Black must not let the white pawn reach h6 . We consider this position via the move order h5} 15... h6 {Ng4 Bf8 .}) *

