st natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Here the rook supports the advance e4 - e5 . In addition, White vacates f1 for the knight.} b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. With the move of the b-pawn, Black gains space and at the same time prepares the development of the bishop to b7 . The long-term aim is either to open lines and penetrate the white position with the major pieces or to obtain outpost squares for the knights.} 9. e5 ({White prepares their attack on the kingside. The knight is driven off f6 and Black is deprived of the possibility of exchanging on e4 and d1 , which would have been possible after the direct} 9. Nf1 {.}) ({After} 9. a4 b4 {, White usually plays} 10. exd5 {. We look at the position after Nxd5 via the move order} exd5 {Nxd5 a4 b4 .}) 9... Nd7 {The best square for the knight. White is now tied to the defense of the e5 -pawn.} 10. Nf1 {Why did White spend two tempi to bring the knight to this seemingly passive square? The answer is that this is only a midway point of its journey. White wants to play h2 - h4 and then bring the knight via h2 to g4 , where it is then in threatening proximity to the black king. Black can hardly prevent this and should instead pursue their own ideas on the queenside.} (10. h4 $6 {A standard move and an integral part of the white setup. However, it is more accurate to start with Nf1 .} Qc7 $1 {White must now defend the e-pawn with} 11. Qe2 {instead of Bf4 as desired. We are already familiar with this problem from the analysis of 8.e5?! .}) 10... Bb7 {With this move, Black initiates a deep idea which combines an attack on the queenside with the defense of the kingside: the rook is to be brought from f8 to c8 , as on f8 it hinders the defense. White wants to advance the h-pawn to h6 so that they can then use the square f6 as a gateway for the minor pieces. To prevent this advance, Black would like to play ... h7 - h6 themselves, but then they must always reckon with sacrifices on this square. It is therefore necessary to additionally protect h6 with ... Bf8 . Black could of course prepare this with a rook move to e8 , but on the one hand the rook has no active role there and on the other may still be in the way, because occasionally Black needs the move ... Qf8 to defend the kingside.} 11. h4 {White sets the h-pawn in motion and vacates h2 for the knight.} Qc7 {The queen steps aside to let the rook pass. A convenient side effect: White has to defend the e5 -pawn.} 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {Black has carried out the first part of the plan: the rook no longer interferes with the defense of the kingside.} 13. N1h2 ({The usual route of the knight to the kingside. White could also move the h-pawn first.} 13. h5 h6 $1 {The white pawn must not be allowed to advance to h6 . A quick transposition to our main line is now likely.}) (13. Ne3 {This hardly has any independent significance either. White is now threatening 14.Nxd5  exd5  15.e6 , but the black queen should return to d8 anyway.} Qd8 14. Ng4 {We deal with this via the move order N1h2 Qd8 Ng4 .}) 13... Qd8 {After the rook has been 'freed', the queen returns to its starting square. This is not absolutely necessary here, but it helps the defense if the queen can go to f8 or e8 while keeping an eye on g5 (in case White sends the g-pawn forward).} ({The game is relatively schematic, but care must be taken with the move order. The bishop should only go to f8 when White has played Ng4 . After} 13... Bf8 $6 {comes} 14. h5 h6 {(otherwise White plays h5-h6 themselves)} 15. g4 $1 {followed by g4-g5 . The kingside opens up and White gets good attacking chances. If the knight is already on g4 , this plan is slower, because White would have to retreat the knight first.}) 14. h5 ({White uses the h-pawn as a lever to provoke a weakening in the black king position.} 14. c3 a5 15. a4 {This interesting prophylactic approach was tested in Amin-Dominguez Perez . This exciting encounter showcases many of the mutual ideas. I’ve annotated it here.}) {Why is it so important to stop the advance of the white h-pawn in time? The game Korpa-Kovacs provides an illustrative example:} 14... a5 15. h6 g6 {Black has kept the position on the kingside closed for the time being, but the dark squares g5 and f6 are weakened. White prepares a piece invasion.} 16. Ng4 b4 17. Qd2 ({It was possible to start with} 17. c3 {in order to prevent the following defense. After the text move, 18.Bg5 is threatening to exchange a defender of the dark squares and bring the queen to f4 .}) 17... Nd4 ({Black brings a defender to the kingside and prevents} 17... Bg5 {.}) 18. Ng5 Rab8 ({As we see later, the rook is not well placed here. Better is probably} 18... a4 {.}) 19. c3 bxc3 20. bxc3 Nf5 21. Nf6+ {White exploits the rook's position on b8 to open up the position.} Bxf6 ({Tougher was the exchange sacrifice} 21... Nxf6 22. exf6 Bxf6 23. Bxb8 Rxb8 24. Nf3 {.}) 22. exf6 e5 {Korpa-Kovacs The easiest way to an advantage now would have been the following.} 23. Bxe5 Nxe5 24. Rxe5 {White wins, because after...} Qxf6 25. Qf4 {... g3 - g4 is a threat and in connection with the pawn on h6 there are various mating ideas.} *

