or the minor pieces. To prevent this advance, Black would like to play ... h7 - h6 themselves, but then they must always reckon with sacrifices on this square. It is therefore necessary to additionally protect h6 with ... Bf8 . Black could of course prepare this with a rook move to e8 , but on the one hand the rook has no active role there and on the other may still be in the way, because occasionally Black needs the move ... Qf8 to defend the kingside.} 11. h4 {White sets the h-pawn in motion and vacates h2 for the knight.} Qc7 {The queen steps aside to let the rook pass. A convenient side effect: White has to defend the e5 -pawn.} 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {Black has carried out the first part of the plan: the rook no longer interferes with the defense of the kingside.} 13. N1h2 ({The usual route of the knight to the kingside. White could also move the h-pawn first.} 13. h5 h6 $1 {The white pawn must not be allowed to advance to h6 . A quick transposition to our main line is now likely.}) (13. Ne3 {This hardly has any independent significance either. White is now threatening 14.Nxd5  exd5  15.e6 , but the black queen should return to d8 anyway.} Qd8 14. Ng4 {We deal with this via the move order N1h2 Qd8 Ng4 .}) 13... Qd8 {After the rook has been 'freed', the queen returns to its starting square. This is not absolutely necessary here, but it helps the defense if the queen can go to f8 or e8 while keeping an eye on g5 (in case White sends the g-pawn forward).} ({The game is relatively schematic, but care must be taken with the move order. The bishop should only go to f8 when White has played Ng4 . After} 13... Bf8 $6 {comes} 14. h5 h6 {(otherwise White plays h5-h6 themselves)} 15. g4 $1 {followed by g4-g5 . The kingside opens up and White gets good attacking chances. If the knight is already on g4 , this plan is slower, because White would have to retreat the knight first.}) 14. h5 ({White uses the h-pawn as a lever to provoke a weakening in the black king position.} 14. c3 a5 15. a4 {This interesting prophylactic approach was tested in Amin-Dominguez Perez . This exciting encounter showcases many of the mutual ideas. I’ve annotated it here.}) 14... h6 {We shouldn't let the white pawn go all the way to h6 . Now the black pawn on h6 becomes the focal point of our opponent's attack. White could prepare a piece sacrifice on this square, or go for the pawn break g3 - g4 - g5 .} 15. Qd2 {From d2 the queen supports both a possible piece sacrifice on h6 and the g3 - g4 - g5 -pawn break.} a5 ({Black starts the counterplay on the queenside. If possible, this pawn should be advanced all the way to a3 .} 15... Bf8 $6 {Black should only play this defensive move when White has brought the knight to g4 .} 16. g4 $1 {White is threatening g4-g5 . Now the bishop would be better off on e7 .}) ({However, an interesting alternative is} 15... Nf8 {with the idea of bringing the knight to h7 , where it defends the g5 -square. Black first defends the kingside and only then starts the counterplay on the queenside.}) 16. g4 {White plays for the pawn break g4 - g5 .} ({We consider} 16. Ng4 Bf8 {via the move order Ng4 Bf8 Qd2 a5 .}) 16... a4 {As White's play on the kingside cannot be prevented any further, Black pursues their own ideas on the queenside.} 17. a3 {A breather. White prevents the advance of the pawn to a3 .} b4 {After the a-pawn has been stopped, it's the b-pawn's turn. Black wants to open the b-file.} 18. g5 hxg5 ({White continues the attack. We will deal with this position in more detail via the move order Ng4} 18... Bf8 {Qd2 a5 Ngh2 a4 a3} 19. axb4 {g4} Be7 {g5 .}) *

