or the minor pieces. To prevent this advance, Black would like to play ... h7 - h6 themselves, but then they must always reckon with sacrifices on this square. It is therefore necessary to additionally protect h6 with ... Bf8 . Black could of course prepare this with a rook move to e8 , but on the one hand the rook has no active role there and on the other may still be in the way, because occasionally Black needs the move ... Qf8 to defend the kingside.} 11. h4 {White sets the h-pawn in motion and vacates h2 for the knight.} Qc7 {The queen steps aside to let the rook pass. A convenient side effect: White has to defend the e5 -pawn.} 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {Black has carried out the first part of the plan: the rook no longer interferes with the defense of the kingside.} 13. N1h2 ({The usual route of the knight to the kingside. White could also move the h-pawn first.} 13. h5 h6 $1 {The white pawn must not be allowed to advance to h6 . A quick transposition to our main line is now likely.}) (13. Ne3 {This hardly has any independent significance either. White is now threatening 14.Nxd5  exd5  15.e6 , but the black queen should return to d8 anyway.} Qd8 14. Ng4 {We deal with this via the move order N1h2 Qd8 Ng4 .}) 13... Qd8 {After the rook has been 'freed', the queen returns to its starting square. This is not absolutely necessary here, but it helps the defense if the queen can go to f8 or e8 while keeping an eye on g5 (in case White sends the g-pawn forward).} ({The game is relatively schematic, but care must be taken with the move order. The bishop should only go to f8 when White has played Ng4 . After} 13... Bf8 $6 {comes} 14. h5 h6 {(otherwise White plays h5-h6 themselves)} 15. g4 $1 {followed by g4-g5 . The kingside opens up and White gets good attacking chances. If the knight is already on g4 , this plan is slower, because White would have to retreat the knight first.}) 14. h5 ({White uses the h-pawn as a lever to provoke a weakening in the black king position.} 14. c3 a5 15. a4 {This interesting prophylactic approach was tested in Amin-Dominguez Perez . This exciting encounter showcases many of the mutual ideas. I’ve annotated it here.}) 14... h6 {We shouldn't let the white pawn go all the way to h6 . Now the black pawn on h6 becomes the focal point of our opponent's attack. White could prepare a piece sacrifice on this square, or go for the pawn break g3 - g4 - g5 .} 15. Ng4 {White completes the knight maneuver. Now a sacrifice on h6 is in the air.} Bf8 {Black adopts the defensive setup on the kingside. The bishop defends h6 from f8 . Analysis shows that the piece sacrifice on h6 was not yet very dangerous here, but in a practical game it is easier not to have to constantly reckon with it.} 16. Qd2 {White's queen joins in the attack. Once again the sacrifice on h6 is a possibility.} a5 {After having taken all the precautions on the kingside, it's time to pursue some ideas of our own on the queenside. If White allows it, the pawn can be moved all the way to a3 . White now faces a difficult decision, with no clear continuation of the kingside attack.} 17. c3 {Played by Nakamura, among others (via a transposition). White thus prevents the defensive resource ... Nd4 .} a4 ({Black continues to gain space on the queenside. The goal is to open files. Therefore} 17... b4 {is less accurate because White can keep the position closed with} 18. c4 {( Nakamura-Liang ).}) ({However,} 17... d4 {is interesting, forcing the opening of the position.}) 18. Rad1 ({It's not easy to find a good continuation for White. White has prevented ...Nd4 , but the piece sacrifice still doesn't work:} 18. Nxh6+ $2 gxh6 19. Bxh6 Bxh6 20. Qxh6 Qf8 21. Qf4 a3 $1 {White is far from posing threats on the kingside. Meanwhile Black is successfully fighting for squares on the queenside and in the center.} 22. b3 {White tries to keep the position closed.} b4 {Black wants the square b4 for the knight. The following move is therefore forced.} 23. c4 Ne7 {White's compensation for the piece is insufficient. On the kingside Black successfully defends with their queen and the two knights. Black will initiate the opening of the d-file and the long diagonal with ...dxc4 .}) (18. a3 {White stops the a-pawn, but cannot prevent the opening of the queenside in the long term.} Na5 19. Rad1 Nb3 20. Qe2 b4 {Soon the b-file will open and White will be left with a weakness on a3 . Black is clearly better. Baenziger, F-Goessler, M .}) 18... a3 ({The attack on the b-pawn undermines the defense of the c-pawn. Great complications arise after the immediate} 18... d4 $5 19. cxd4 cxd4 20. Nxd4 $1 Nxd4 21. Bxb7 Rab8 22. Be4 b4 $1 ({(} 22... Rc2 {is less convincing here.} 23. Qe3 Bc5 24. Rd2 $1 Bb4 $2 {A tactical mistake.} 25. Qxd4 Bxd2 26. Bxd2 Rxd2 27. Qc3 {The rook is lost.)}) 23. Bxh6 $1 {.}) ({On the other hand,} 18... b4 $6 {is weak, as after} 19. c4 {the queenside remains closed.}) 19. b3 d4 {Black is now threatening to capture on c3 and thus conquer the squares b4 and d4 for their minor pieces.} 20. cxd4 {Without the insertion of the moves 18...a3  19.b3 this would be a good defense. Now it no longer works because of a tactical detail. Chess is complex...} cxd4 21. Nxd4 Nxd4 22. Bxb7 Rab8 23. Be4 ({Of course not} 23. Bxc8 $2 Nf3+ 24. Kg2 Nxd2 {.}) 23... Rc2 24. Qe3 Bc5 {Black wants to capture the pawn a2 . Then Black would not only have a dangerous passed pawn, but would also be threatening ... Nc2 . White is helpless against this.} 25. Rd2 Bb4 ({Black wins the exchange and the game. At this point it becomes clear why Black initially lured the white b-pawn forward. After Qxd4 Bxd2 Bxd2} 25... Rxd2 {Qc3 .}) *

