1. e4 c5 {In this chapter we deal with the King's Indian Attack. This is a setup which White can adopt relatively independently of Black's moves and which can therefore be used against many openings. The King's Indian Attack is characterized by the development of the bishop to g2 and the placement of the pawns on d3 and e4 . White wants to keep the position closed in the center and slowly prepare an attack on the kingside. The white setup is very schematic and can be executed as if on autopilot, as both sides initially only act in their half of the board. As against most other closed Sicilian systems, I recommend counterattacking in the center with ... e6 and ... d5 . As a rule, Black will later defend on the kingside and become active on the queenside.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 ({Normally White starts with the move of the d-pawn to initiate the King's Indian attack. If White starts with} 3. g3 {instead, after} d5 4. d3 {Black has the additional option of exchanging queens with} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ {.}) ({After} 3. d3 {, White can reply to} d5 {with} 4. Nbd2 {or Qe2 .}) 3... Nc6 ({The move order is irrelevant here. It is equally possible to start with} 3... d5 {.}) 4. g3 {The light-squared bishop is best placed on g2 . On e2 it would be very passive.} d5 {Black gains space in the center and is threatening to exchange on e4 and d1 , which White usually does not allow. We will now look at two different setups for White. In the main line, 5.Nbd2 , White keeps the position closed and prepares a slow attack on the kingside. But first we will look at 5.Qe2 , which contains a more concrete idea: White first wants to make Black's counterplay on the queenside more difficult.} ({The other popular setup for Black arises after the moves} 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 {. Black retains flexibility there with regard to the pawn structure in the center.}) 5. Nbd2 {White thus avoids a possible queen trade on the d-file. The knight should later be brought to the kingside via f1 .} Nf6 {The most natural square for the knight.} 6. Bg2 Be7 {Both sides prepare castling. On d6 the bishop would be less well placed, because Black would then always have to ensure that e5 sufficiently protected.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {Here the rook supports the advance e4 - e5 . In addition, White vacates f1 for the knight.} b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. With the move of the b-pawn, Black gains space and at the same time prepares the development of the bishop to b7 . The long-term aim is either to open lines and penetrate the white position with the major pieces or to obtain outpost squares for the knights.} 9. e5 ({White prepares their attack on the kingside. The knight is driven off f6 and Black is deprived of the possibility of exchanging on e4 and d1 , which would have been possible after the direct} 9. Nf1 {.}) ({After} 9. a4 b4 {, White usually plays} 10. exd5 {. We look at the position after Nxd5 via the move order} exd5 {Nxd5 a4 b4 .}) 9... Nd7 {The best square for the knight. White is now tied to the defense of the e5 -pawn.} 10. Nf1 {Why did White spend two tempi to bring the knight to this seemingly passive square? The answer is that this is only a midway point of its journey. White wants to play h2 - h4 and then bring the knight via h2 to g4 , where it is then in threatening proximity to the black king. Black can hardly prevent this and should instead pursue their own ideas on the queenside.} (10. h4 $6 {A standard move and an integral part of the white setup. However, it is more accurate to start with Nf1 .} Qc7 $1 {White must now defend the e-pawn with} 11. Qe2 {instead of Bf4 as desired. We are already familiar with this problem from the analysis of 8.e5?! .}) 10... Bb7 {With this move, Black initiates a deep idea which combines an attack on the queenside with the defense of the kingside: the rook is to be brought from f8 to c8 , as on f8 it hinders the defense. White wants to advance the h-pawn to h6 so that they can then use the square f6 as a gateway for the minor pieces. To prevent this advance, Black would like to play ... h7 - h6 themselves, but then they must always reckon with sacrifices on this square. It is therefore necessary to additionally protect h6 with ... Bf8 . Black could of course prepare this with a rook move to e8 , but on the one hand the rook has no active role there and on the other may still be in the way, because occasionally Black needs the move ... Qf8 to defend the kingside.} 11. h4 {White sets the h-pawn in motion and vacates h2 for the knight.} Qc7 {The queen steps aside to let the rook pass. A convenient side effect: White has to defend the e5 -pawn.} 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {Black has carried out the first part of the plan: the rook no longer interferes with the defense of the kingside.} 13. N1h2 ({The usual route of the knight to the kingside. White could also move the h-pawn first.} 13. h5 h6 $1 {The white pawn must not be allowed to advance to h6 . A quick transposition to our main line is now likely.}) (13. Ne3 {This hardly has any independent significance either. White is now threatening 14.Nxd5  exd5  15.e6 , but the black queen should return to d8 anyway.} Qd8 14. Ng4 {We deal with this via the move order N1h2 Qd8 Ng4 .}) 13... Qd8 {After the rook has been 'freed', the queen returns to its starting square. This is not absolutely necessary here, but it helps the defense if the queen can go to f8 or e8 while keeping an eye on g5 (in case White sends the g-pawn forward).} ({The game is relatively schematic, but care must be taken with the move order. The bishop should only go to f8 when White has played Ng4 . After} 13... Bf8 $6 {comes} 14. h5 h6 {(otherwise White plays h5-h6 themselves)} 15. g4 $1 {followed by g4-g5 . The kingside opens up and White gets good attacking chances. If the knight is already on g4 , this plan is slower, because White would have to retreat the knight first.}) 14. h5 ({White uses the h-pawn as a lever to provoke a weakening in the black king position.} 14. c3 a5 15. a4 {This interesting prophylactic approach was tested in Amin-Dominguez Perez . This exciting encounter showcases many of the mutual ideas. I’ve annotated it here.}) 14... h6 {We shouldn't let the white pawn go all the way to h6 . Now the black pawn on h6 becomes the focal point of our opponent's attack. White could prepare a piece sacrifice on this square, or go for the pawn break g3 - g4 - g5 .} 15. Ng4 {White completes the knight maneuver. Now a sacrifice on h6 is in the air.} Bf8 {Black adopts the defensive setup on the kingside. The bishop defends h6 from f8 . Analysis shows that the piece sacrifice on h6 was not yet very dangerous here, but in a practical game it is easier not to have to constantly reckon with it.} 16. Qd2 {White's queen joins in the attack. Once again the sacrifice on h6 is a possibility.} a5 {After having taken all the precautions on the kingside, it's time to pursue some ideas of our own on the queenside. If White allows it, the pawn can be moved all the way to a3 . White now faces a difficult decision, with no clear continuation of the kingside attack.} 17. c3 {Played by Nakamura, among others (via a transposition). White thus prevents the defensive resource ... Nd4 .} a4 {Black continues to gain space on the queenside. The goal is to open files. Therefore 17... b4 is less accurate because White can keep the position closed with 18.c4 (Nakamura-Liang, 2018). However, 17... d4 is interesting, forcing the opening of the position.} 18. Rad1 {It's not easy to find a good continuation for White. White has prevented ... Nd4 , but the piece sacrifice still doesn't work: 18. Nxh6 +? gxh6 19. Bxh6  Bxh6 20. Qxh6  Qf8 21. Qf4  a3 ! White is far from posing threats on the kingside. Meanwhile Black is successfully fighting for squares on the queenside and in the center. 22. b3 White tries to keep the position closed. b4 Black wants the square b4 for the knight. The following move is therefore forced. 23. c4  Ne7 ∓ White's compensation for the piece is insufficient. On the kingside Black successfully defends with their queen and the two knights. Black will initiate the opening of the d-file and the long diagonal with ... dxc4 . 18. a3 White stops the a-pawn, but cannot prevent the opening of the queenside in the long term. Na5 19. Rad1  Nb3 20. Qe2  b4 Soon the b-file will open and White will be left with a weakness on a3 . Black is clearly better. 1-0 Baenziger,F (2373)-Goessler,M (2219) Graz op-A 2018 (4)} a3 {The attack on the b-pawn undermines the defense of the c-pawn. Great complications arise after the immediate 18... d4 !? 19. cxd4  cxd4 20. Nxd4 ! Nxd4 21. Bxb7  Rab8 22. Be4  b4 ! (22... Rc2 is less convincing here. 23. Qe3  Bc5 24. Rd2 ! Bb4 ? A tactical mistake. 25. Qxd4  Bxd2 26. Bxd2  Rxd2 27. Qc3 The rook is lost.) 23. Bxh6 ! . On the other hand, 18... b4 ?! is weak, as after 19. c4 the queenside remains closed.} 19. b3 d4 {Black is now threatening to capture on c3 and thus conquer the squares b4 and d4 for their minor pieces.} 20. c4 Nb4 {Black has reached their goal. The knight cannot be driven away from here and always reminds White of the weakness of the a2 -pawn. In addition, the b7 -bishop now takes part in the game. Black is better. The only question is whether there is a way through on the queenside. One possible plan is to exchange on c4 . If White recaptures with the b-pawn, Black will prepare an invasion along the b-file. If White takes back with the d-pawn, Black gets a protected passed pawn on the d-file. After appropriate preparation, ... d4 - d3 is an idea, after which the d4 -square can be used by the queen or knight. White faces an arduous defense.} *

