or the minor pieces. To prevent this advance, Black would like to play ... h7 - h6 themselves, but then they must always reckon with sacrifices on this square. It is therefore necessary to additionally protect h6 with ... Bf8 . Black could of course prepare this with a rook move to e8 , but on the one hand the rook has no active role there and on the other may still be in the way, because occasionally Black needs the move ... Qf8 to defend the kingside.} 11. h4 {White sets the h-pawn in motion and vacates h2 for the knight.} Qc7 {The queen steps aside to let the rook pass. A convenient side effect: White has to defend the e5 -pawn.} 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {Black has carried out the first part of the plan: the rook no longer interferes with the defense of the kingside.} 13. N1h2 ({The usual route of the knight to the kingside. White could also move the h-pawn first.} 13. h5 h6 $1 {The white pawn must not be allowed to advance to h6 . A quick transposition to our main line is now likely.}) (13. Ne3 {This hardly has any independent significance either. White is now threatening 14.Nxd5  exd5  15.e6 , but the black queen should return to d8 anyway.} Qd8 14. Ng4 {We deal with this via the move order N1h2 Qd8 Ng4 .}) 13... Qd8 {After the rook has been 'freed', the queen returns to its starting square. This is not absolutely necessary here, but it helps the defense if the queen can go to f8 or e8 while keeping an eye on g5 (in case White sends the g-pawn forward).} ({The game is relatively schematic, but care must be taken with the move order. The bishop should only go to f8 when White has played Ng4 . After} 13... Bf8 $6 {comes} 14. h5 h6 {(otherwise White plays h5-h6 themselves)} 15. g4 $1 {followed by g4-g5 . The kingside opens up and White gets good attacking chances. If the knight is already on g4 , this plan is slower, because White would have to retreat the knight first.}) 14. h5 ({White uses the h-pawn as a lever to provoke a weakening in the black king position.} 14. c3 a5 15. a4 {This interesting prophylactic approach was tested in Amin-Dominguez Perez . This exciting encounter showcases many of the mutual ideas. I’ve annotated it here.}) 14... h6 {We shouldn't let the white pawn go all the way to h6 . Now the black pawn on h6 becomes the focal point of our opponent's attack. White could prepare a piece sacrifice on this square, or go for the pawn break g3 - g4 - g5 .} 15. Ng4 {White completes the knight maneuver. Now a sacrifice on h6 is in the air.} Bf8 {Black adopts the defensive setup on the kingside. The bishop defends h6 from f8 . Analysis shows that the piece sacrifice on h6 was not yet very dangerous here, but in a practical game it is easier not to have to constantly reckon with it.} 16. Qd2 {White's queen joins in the attack. Once again the sacrifice on h6 is a possibility.} a5 {After having taken all the precautions on the kingside, it's time to pursue some ideas of our own on the queenside. If White allows it, the pawn can be moved all the way to a3 . White now faces a difficult decision, with no clear continuation of the kingside attack.} 17. Ngh2 {The most common choice. White clears the way for the g-pawn, since no breakthrough can be achieved with piece play.} a4 {Both sides play on 'their' wing. Black is threatening to move the pawn to a3 in order to weaken the dark squares on the queenside.} 18. g4 a3 {White cannot avoid a weakening on the queenside.} 19. bxa3 Rxa3 ({The pawn a2 is lost in the long run. Black could also play} 19... Be7 {first.}) 20. g5 hxg5 21. Bxg5 Be7 {The bishop has served its purpose on f8 and now makes room for the knight.} ({After} 21... Qc7 $2 22. Qf4 {followed by h5-h6 , the white attack is very strong.}) 22. Bxe7 (22. Bf4 Nf8 {Black focuses on defending the kingside; the queenside can wait. The knight wants to go to h7 . As soon as White plays h5-h6 , Black replies with ...g7-g6 and keeps the position closed.}) 22... Nxe7 {The knight moves to f5 , where it helps with the defense, while the other knight can help defend from f8 . Black can also include the bishop in the defense with ... d5 - d4 , the idea being to exchange it for one of White's pieces. The position remains very complicated, but Black likely has the better chances. Eventually, the threats on the kingside will be exhausted, and Black's queenside advantage will come into play.} *

