1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {The fianchetto of the king's bishop means that White is out for a quiet, positional battle. From g2 the bishop supports the center and aims in the long term towards the black queenside. The position initially remains closed and the situation in the center unresolved. The move has become quite popular in recent years and has been adopted by many top players. GM Wesley So recommends the move in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 on Chessable.} d5 ({The more popular alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, which keeps Black's options open: ...d7-d5 is still possible, but also the blockade of the center with ...e6-e5 or a setup with ...d7-d6 . But d5 is easier in my opinion. We exploit the fact that the bishop's development to g2 is somewhat slow and fight directly for the initiative. Black is prepared to accept an isolated queen's pawn for this. As we will see, however, White does not manage to achieve their strategic goals without making concessions.}) 4. e5 {White plays in the style of the French Advance Variation. However, the fianchetto of the bishop doesn't really fit, because the black center is very stable.} Nc6 5. Bg2 f6 ({Black breaks up the white center and thus ensures that the pieces on the kingside can be developed to good squares. There are many good alternatives for Black: If you're looking for a fierce fight, you'll find} 5... g5 $5 {appealing. With the moves Qc7 or Nge7 , Black can also keep the position closed, which leads to a slower game with maneuvering from both sides.}) 6. exf6 Nxf6 7. O-O Bd6 {The pieces are developed to active squares. White should now attack the black center so that the bishop on g2 takes a more active role.} 8. d4 O-O 9. c4 {Once again, attacking the center is the critical attempt. White either wants to increase the pressure with Nc3 , or exchange on d5 and c5 so that Black is left with a weak pawn.} dxc4 {We are following a game of the Indonesian grandmaster Utut Adianto. Black wins a pawn, at least temporarily.} 10. Nc3 (10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nbd2 {followed in the aforementioned game, Donguines, F-Adianto, U , and here Black would have already had a strong initiative after} e5 $1 12. Nxc4 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 e4 {. The black pieces are very active and the f2 -pawn comes under pressure.}) 10... Be7 {To increase the pressure on d4 .} 11. dxc5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bxc5 {The position is equal, but Black has comfortable play. ... e6 - e5 and the activation of the light-squared bishop are on the agenda. White must watch out for the vulnerable pawn f2 .} *

