1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {The fianchetto of the king's bishop means that White is out for a quiet, positional battle. From g2 the bishop supports the center and aims in the long term towards the black queenside. The position initially remains closed and the situation in the center unresolved. The move has become quite popular in recent years and has been adopted by many top players. GM Wesley So recommends the move in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 on Chessable.} d5 ({The more popular alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, which keeps Black's options open: ...d7-d5 is still possible, but also the blockade of the center with ...e6-e5 or a setup with ...d7-d6 . But d5 is easier in my opinion. We exploit the fact that the bishop's development to g2 is somewhat slow and fight directly for the initiative. Black is prepared to accept an isolated queen's pawn for this. As we will see, however, White does not manage to achieve their strategic goals without making concessions.}) 4. exd5 ({If White defends in the center with} 4. d3 {, we can continue with} Nf6 {. The game will then soon transpose to a King's Indian Attack, which was the topic of the previous chapter .}) 4... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a perennial problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop is no longer blocked by the e-pawn and can be actively developed. However, the altered pawn structure also has drawbacks. White will try to isolate the black d-pawn with d2 - d4 .} {In addition to the direct d4 , White can also focus on development first by starting with Bg2 .} 5. Bg2 {White wants to castle and only then become active in the center. We won't allow that.} Qe7+ {Exploits the opponent's move order. White is prevented from castling.} 6. Kf1 {Of course, White then needs some time to bring the h1 -rook into play. The logic behind this is that the black queen is similarly misplaced on e7 and must lose time.} Nc6 7. d4 (7. Nc3 Nf6 8. d4 {is a transposition.}) 7... Nf6 ({Black first makes the natural developing moves and keeps open what to do with the out-of-place queen on e7 .} 7... Qd8 {would allow a sharpening of the position with} 8. c4 $5 {, as in the game Aronian-Dreev .}) 8. Nc3 ({White increases the pressure on the d5 -pawn. Now} 8. c4 $6 {would backfire. After} Be6 {it is the white center that comes under pressure and Black is better prepared for an opening of the position.}) 8... Be6 {Black overprotects the d-pawn. Long castling is now also a possibility and ... Qd7 is an option as well, as now the queen would no longer obstruct the bishop there.} (8... Bg4 $6 {brings nothing. After} 9. h3 $1 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nxd4 11. Nxd5 $1 {White wins back the pawn and has some advantage with a strong pair of bishops in an open position.}) 9. Be3 {After most of the other moves, Black can free the f8 -bishop with Qd8 or Qd7 and prepare developing the kingside. Now the pawn c5 is under attack.} c4 ({The solid choice. Black closes the center and fends off the white threats. Next on the agenda is a queen move, followed by ...Be7 and short castling. The sharp} 9... O-O-O {is also possible, as in the two games Vasiukov-Larsen and Morozevich-Miezis .}) 10. h3 {A sample line. White has many moves of equal value, but it looks logical to prepare the development of the rook on h1 .} Qc7 {The queen moves to b4 , d8 and d7 are roughly equivalent. However, long castling is no longer as good because White can open files on the queenside with the pawn break b2 - b3 .} 11. Kg1 Be7 12. Kh2 O-O {Both sides will centralize the rooks and have then completed development. A complex middlegame with equal chances lies ahead.} *

