rifice} 7. O-O {gives White some initiative.)})) {O-O .} 6. Bg2 {White would like to get the king to safety first and only then capture on d4 . The move is rarely seen in tournament practice, and for good reason.} Bb4+ {After that it's not so easy for White to win back the pawn.} 7. Bd2 ({After} 7. Kf1 {, White wins back the pawn, but the price is too high: the rook on h1 will take a long time until it can fight for the open e-file.}) 7... Qe7+ {Prevents castling.} 8. Qe2 Bc5 ({As with 7.Nbd2 , White fights to win back the pawn and equalize. In Ajay, K-Low, Z , White failed to prove compensation for the pawn: b4 Bb6 a4} 8... a6 {(Better is Qxe7+ Nxe7 O-O )} 9. c3 Nc6 {a5 Ba7 b5 axb5} 10. Na3 {. Now} d3 11. Qxe7+ Ngxe7 12. Nb5 {Bb8⩱ would have been strongest.}) *

