1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {The fianchetto of the king's bishop means that White is out for a quiet, positional battle. From g2 the bishop supports the center and aims in the long term towards the black queenside. The position initially remains closed and the situation in the center unresolved. The move has become quite popular in recent years and has been adopted by many top players. GM Wesley So recommends the move in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 on Chessable.} d5 ({The more popular alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, which keeps Black's options open: ...d7-d5 is still possible, but also the blockade of the center with ...e6-e5 or a setup with ...d7-d6 . But d5 is easier in my opinion. We exploit the fact that the bishop's development to g2 is somewhat slow and fight directly for the initiative. Black is prepared to accept an isolated queen's pawn for this. As we will see, however, White does not manage to achieve their strategic goals without making concessions.}) 4. exd5 ({If White defends in the center with} 4. d3 {, we can continue with} Nf6 {. The game will then soon transpose to a King's Indian Attack, which was the topic of the previous chapter .}) 4... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a perennial problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop is no longer blocked by the e-pawn and can be actively developed. However, the altered pawn structure also has drawbacks. White will try to isolate the black d-pawn with d2 - d4 .} {In addition to the direct d4 , White can also focus on development first by starting with Bg2 .} 5. d4 {The main move. White wants to capture on c5 at an opportune moment and play against the isolated d-pawn.} cxd4 ({I like this better than the more popular moves} 5... Nc6 {and . The idea behind it is very concrete: Black takes advantage of the fact that the white king is still on e1 .}) (5... Nc6 6. Bg2 cxd4 {would transpose to my recommendation after} 7. Nxd4 {, but White has the additional option} ({( Bg4 is the main move. The pawn sacrifice} 7. O-O {gives White some initiative.)})) {O-O .} 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 {One move is still missing – castling short – and White's opening concept would be a complete success: the pawn on d5 is isolated and weak, giving White a small but permanent advantage.} (7. Nc3 {is very rarely played at this point. After} Nf6 8. Bg2 Bg4 {we have ended up in a position which I examine in detail via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 3.Sge2} 9. Nxc6 {g3 d5 exd5 exd5} d4 {cxd4} 10. Nxd4 {Nf6 Bg2 Bg4 .}) 7... Bc5 {This is the idea of our previous moves. While White can easily fend off the attack on the knight, they cannot do so without making a concession.} 8. Be3 {White would like to maintain the blockade on d4 . But there is a concrete problem with this.} Nxd4 ({Not} 8... Bxd4 $6 9. Bxd4 Qe7+ 10. Be3 {.}) 9. Bxd4 Qe7+ 10. Kf1 {Unattractive, but forced. The white king is not safe afterwards and the rook h1 takes a long time to get into the game.} Nf6 11. Nc3 O-O {Black doesn't have to spend time defending the d-pawn. Winning it would lead to an opening of the position which White cannot survive. Black has an active position and slightly better chances. The bishop will probably be developed to f5 or e6 . The rooks can choose between the squares e8 , d8 and c8 . Meanwhile, White is busy correcting their failure to castle. The maneuver h2 - h3 , Kg1 - h2 looks like the best plan. Black can disrupt this with an attack on f2 by ... Ne4 (after appropriate preparation).} 12. h3 (12. Nxd5 $6 {This is too optimistic and led to a miniature in Roth-Shaw :} Nxd5 13. Bxd5 ({(} 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Qxd5 Qxc2 {is also good for Black.)}) 13... Bh3+ 14. Kg1 Rad8 15. c4 $2 {What was needed was .} Rxd5 16. cxd5 Qe4 {White loses the queen or is mated and therefore resigned.}) (12. Bxf6 $6 {This is also too optimistic in view of the white king position.} Qxf6 13. Qf3 Qb6 {It is worth provoking a move of the b-pawn and thus a weakening of the dark squares.} 14. b3 Qg6 15. Qxd5 ({(Better was} 15. Nxd5 {, but after} Qxc2 {, Black has a strong pair of bishops and the safer king.)}) 15... Bb6 16. Ne4 $2 {The white position was already very difficult after other moves as well.} Bf5 {The black threats are too strong.} 17. h4 Rad8 18. h5 Bxe4 $1 {Black wins a piece, as White is not allowed to recapture on e4 because of the double attack ...Qf6 . Tschernatsch, J-Feuerstack, A}) 12... Bf5 13. Kg1 ({In the blitz game Zubov-Volokitin, 2021 the unnecessary} 13. Rc1 $6 {happened. The rest of the game is a triumph of Black's activity. Note the impressive march of the f-pawn:} Rad8 14. Bf3 Ne4 15. Kg2 Ng5 16. Bg4 $2 Be4+ 17. f3 f5 $1 18. Bh5 f4 $1 19. Bxc5 Qxc5 20. Qg1 d4 $1 21. fxe4 f3+ 22. Kh2 f2 23. Qg2 dxc3 24. bxc3 Qe3 25. Rcd1 Rxd1 26. Rxd1 Nxe4 27. Bg4 f1=Q) 13... Rad8 14. Kh2 Rfe8 {Next Black could play ... Ne4 , or ... h7 - h5 !? with the idea ... h5 - h4 . White has not yet solved all their problems.} *

