rifice} 7. O-O {gives White some initiative.)})) {O-O .} 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 {One move is still missing – castling short – and White's opening concept would be a complete success: the pawn on d5 is isolated and weak, giving White a small but permanent advantage.} (7. Nc3 {is very rarely played at this point. After} Nf6 8. Bg2 Bg4 {we have ended up in a position which I examine in detail via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 3.Sge2} 9. Nxc6 {g3 d5 exd5 exd5} d4 {cxd4} 10. Nxd4 {Nf6 Bg2 Bg4 .}) 7... Bc5 {This is the idea of our previous moves. While White can easily fend off the attack on the knight, they cannot do so without making a concession.} 8. Nxc6 {By exchanging, White doesn't lose any time. On the other hand, the d5 -pawn now receives reinforcement and is no longer isolated. White could later try to attack the black center again with c2 - c4 , but the concrete implementation of this is not so easy.} bxc6 {The exchange has not only strengthened the black center, but also opened up a new perspective for the c8 -bishop: the development to a6 .} 9. O-O Nf6 {The knight is more active here than on e7 and can attack the vulnerable point f2 via g4 or e4 if the opportunity arises.} 10. c4 {White wants to isolate the black d-pawn again.} O-O 11. Nd2 {A modest – but positionally correct – continuation. White protects the c-pawn and thus counters the threat of ... Ba6 .} Ba6 {The threat is ... dxc4 .} 12. b3 Re8 13. Bb2 Qe7 {Black has a good, active position. Next the second rook is activated with ... Rad8 . After that, only the bishop on a6 is not properly participating in the game. Either Black succeeds in activating it with ... dxc4 or it finds its way back into play via c8 . The white position is solid, but somewhat passive – the d2 -knight and the g2 -bishop are particularly noticeable in this regard, as both of them are limited by the d5 -pawn.} *

