1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {The fianchetto of the king's bishop means that White is out for a quiet, positional battle. From g2 the bishop supports the center and aims in the long term towards the black queenside. The position initially remains closed and the situation in the center unresolved. The move has become quite popular in recent years and has been adopted by many top players. GM Wesley So recommends the move in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 on Chessable.} d5 ({The more popular alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, which keeps Black's options open: ...d7-d5 is still possible, but also the blockade of the center with ...e6-e5 or a setup with ...d7-d6 . But d5 is easier in my opinion. We exploit the fact that the bishop's development to g2 is somewhat slow and fight directly for the initiative. Black is prepared to accept an isolated queen's pawn for this. As we will see, however, White does not manage to achieve their strategic goals without making concessions.}) 4. exd5 ({If White defends in the center with} 4. d3 {, we can continue with} Nf6 {. The game will then soon transpose to a King's Indian Attack, which was the topic of the previous chapter .}) 4... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a perennial problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop is no longer blocked by the e-pawn and can be actively developed. However, the altered pawn structure also has drawbacks. White will try to isolate the black d-pawn with d2 - d4 .} {In addition to the direct d4 , White can also focus on development first by starting with Bg2 .} 5. d4 {The main move. White wants to capture on c5 at an opportune moment and play against the isolated d-pawn.} cxd4 ({I like this better than the more popular moves} 5... Nc6 {and . The idea behind it is very concrete: Black takes advantage of the fact that the white king is still on e1 .}) (5... Nc6 6. Bg2 cxd4 {would transpose to my recommendation after} 7. Nxd4 {, but White has the additional option} ({( Bg4 is the main move. The pawn sacrifice} 7. O-O {gives White some initiative.)})) {O-O .} 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 {One move is still missing – castling short – and White's opening concept would be a complete success: the pawn on d5 is isolated and weak, giving White a small but permanent advantage.} (7. Nc3 {is very rarely played at this point. After} Nf6 8. Bg2 Bg4 {we have ended up in a position which I examine in detail via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 3.Sge2} 9. Nxc6 {g3 d5 exd5 exd5} d4 {cxd4} 10. Nxd4 {Nf6 Bg2 Bg4 .}) 7... Bc5 {This is the idea of our previous moves. While White can easily fend off the attack on the knight, they cannot do so without making a concession.} 8. Nxc6 {By exchanging, White doesn't lose any time. On the other hand, the d5 -pawn now receives reinforcement and is no longer isolated. White could later try to attack the black center again with c2 - c4 , but the concrete implementation of this is not so easy.} bxc6 {The exchange has not only strengthened the black center, but also opened up a new perspective for the c8 -bishop: the development to a6 .} 9. O-O Nf6 {The knight is more active here than on e7 and can attack the vulnerable point f2 via g4 or e4 if the opportunity arises.} 10. c4 {White wants to isolate the black d-pawn again.} O-O 11. cxd5 {This was of course the intention of the previous move. But White underestimates the dangers.} Ba6 ({After} 11... cxd5 12. Qc2 {, everything is fine for White.}) 12. Re1 ({The rook no longer protects f2 and is itself vulnerable in some lines. The exchange sacrifice} 12. dxc6 Bxf1 13. Qxf1 {is no better because White cannot protect the f-pawn after} Ng4 $1 {.}) 12... cxd5 {The black pieces are much more active than their white counterparts. Specifically, 13...Qb6 is a threat.} 13. Nc3 ({Relatively best. The knight attacks the d-pawn and can also go to a4 to drive the bishop away from the dangerous diagonal.} 13. Qc2 $2 Re8 $1 {gives Black a decisive attack.}) (13. Be3 {is answered with} d4 $1 {. After} 14. Bg5 ({(} 14. Bxa8 $2 dxe3 {)}) 14... Rc8 {, Black has a big advantage.}) 13... Qb6 14. Be3 ({White already had difficult problems to solve, but now Black wins by force. In both games in which this position was reached, White opted for the bishop move. Needed is} 14. Qc2 {, but here too White is not in an enviable position after} Rac8 {. Among other things, Black is threatening ...Ng4 and ...d5-d4 .} ({(} 14... Ng4 $6 15. Nxd5 Bxf2+ 16. Kh1 {and White survives.)})) 14... d4 {White's reply is forced.} 15. Na4 dxe3 16. Nxb6 ({After} 16. Rxe3 {,} Rad8 $1 {is strongest, e.g.} 17. Qc2 Bxe3 18. Nxb6 Bxb6 {with a material advantage and an attack.}) 16... exf2+ 17. Kh1 fxe1=Q+ 18. Qxe1 Bxb6 19. Bxa8 {Everything else is similarly hopeless.} Rxa8 {Black has three pieces for the queen. If you calculate the value of the pieces in points, the situation would be balanced. However, White can only briefly enjoy this supposed balance: the strong black bishops, coupled with the imminent invasion of the rook, will cost the queen.} ({In McShane-Lagarde h3} 19... Re8 20. Qd1 Re2 {followed and White resigned. Knowledge of this game helped me to a curious victory: my opponent opted for Qc3 and resigned after} 21. Bb7 {. I only had to make a single move of my own Malek-Feuerstack .}) *

