1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {The fianchetto of the king's bishop means that White is out for a quiet, positional battle. From g2 the bishop supports the center and aims in the long term towards the black queenside. The position initially remains closed and the situation in the center unresolved. The move has become quite popular in recent years and has been adopted by many top players. GM Wesley So recommends the move in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 on Chessable.} d5 ({The more popular alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, which keeps Black's options open: ...d7-d5 is still possible, but also the blockade of the center with ...e6-e5 or a setup with ...d7-d6 . But d5 is easier in my opinion. We exploit the fact that the bishop's development to g2 is somewhat slow and fight directly for the initiative. Black is prepared to accept an isolated queen's pawn for this. As we will see, however, White does not manage to achieve their strategic goals without making concessions.}) 4. exd5 ({If White defends in the center with} 4. d3 {, we can continue with} Nf6 {. The game will then soon transpose to a King's Indian Attack, which was the topic of the previous chapter .}) 4... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a perennial problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop is no longer blocked by the e-pawn and can be actively developed. However, the altered pawn structure also has drawbacks. White will try to isolate the black d-pawn with d2 - d4 .} {In addition to the direct d4 , White can also focus on development first by starting with Bg2 .} 5. d4 {The main move. White wants to capture on c5 at an opportune moment and play against the isolated d-pawn.} cxd4 ({I like this better than the more popular moves} 5... Nc6 {and . The idea behind it is very concrete: Black takes advantage of the fact that the white king is still on e1 .}) (5... Nc6 6. Bg2 cxd4 {would transpose to my recommendation after} 7. Nxd4 {, but White has the additional option} ({( Bg4 is the main move. The pawn sacrifice} 7. O-O {gives White some initiative.)})) {O-O .} 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 {One move is still missing – castling short – and White's opening concept would be a complete success: the pawn on d5 is isolated and weak, giving White a small but permanent advantage.} (7. Nc3 {is very rarely played at this point. After} Nf6 8. Bg2 Bg4 {we have ended up in a position which I examine in detail via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 3.Sge2} 9. Nxc6 {g3 d5 exd5 exd5} d4 {cxd4} 10. Nxd4 {Nf6 Bg2 Bg4 .}) 7... Bc5 {This is the idea of our previous moves. While White can easily fend off the attack on the knight, they cannot do so without making a concession.} 8. Nb3 {The most popular continuation. White attacks the bishop c5 and the pawn d5 .} Qe7+ {A key idea in the line with 5...cxd4 . White is prevented from castling.} 9. Kf1 {We already know the problem with this continuation from other lines: King and rook are not well placed.} Be6 {Defends the d-pawn and clears the way for the rook.} 10. Nc3 ({White increases the pressure on d5 . Nf6 would be met by .} 10. Bxd5 $2 Rd8 {would be very bad for White: the bishop is needed to defend the light squares and must not be exchanged. A typical tactic illustrates the dangers:} 11. c4 $2 Rxd5 12. cxd5 Bh3+ 13. Kg1 Qe4 {with mate or the win of the queen.}) ({After} 10. Nxc5 Qxc5 {the opponent's weak king position gives Black some advantage.}) 10... O-O-O (10... Rd8 {is also good.  After the text move, the engine manages to defend White's position with precise moves, but from a human point of view, White's problems should not be underestimated. Black wants to mobilize the rest of their army with ...Nf6 and ...Rhe8 and slowly increase pressure against the white king.}) ({Nxd5 Once again White would be better off foregoing the pawn grab. Bxd5 Bxd5} 10... Nf6 {c4} 11. Nxd5 {A ) cxd5 Qe4! would be terrible for White.}) ({) Qg4+!} 10... f5 $1 {[%eval 0,0] . The queen is lured to the f-file. Qxf5+ Rd7 cxd5 Rf8 The attack on the queen and the f2 -pawn behind it looks decisive, but White has an amazing defense.} 11. Bg5 $1 ({( Qe6? Rxf2+} 11. Ke1 Nb4 {.)})) ({B1 ) Qe8? Qe6! would now be good for White. B2 ) White also defends successfully after} 10... Qd6 11. Bf4 $1 {.}) ({B3 ) Rxf5 Bxe7} 10... Bxf2 $1 {dxc6 Rxe7 cxb7+ Kxb7 . At the end of this forced sequence Black is a pawn down, but will soon win it back with the invasion of a rook on the second rank. Black has good winning chances due to their more active pieces.}) *

