1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {The fianchetto of the king's bishop means that White is out for a quiet, positional battle. From g2 the bishop supports the center and aims in the long term towards the black queenside. The position initially remains closed and the situation in the center unresolved. The move has become quite popular in recent years and has been adopted by many top players. GM Wesley So recommends the move in his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 on Chessable.} d5 ({The more popular alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, which keeps Black's options open: ...d7-d5 is still possible, but also the blockade of the center with ...e6-e5 or a setup with ...d7-d6 . But d5 is easier in my opinion. We exploit the fact that the bishop's development to g2 is somewhat slow and fight directly for the initiative. Black is prepared to accept an isolated queen's pawn for this. As we will see, however, White does not manage to achieve their strategic goals without making concessions.}) 4. exd5 ({If White defends in the center with} 4. d3 {, we can continue with} Nf6 {. The game will then soon transpose to a King's Indian Attack, which was the topic of the previous chapter .}) 4... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a perennial problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop is no longer blocked by the e-pawn and can be actively developed. However, the altered pawn structure also has drawbacks. White will try to isolate the black d-pawn with d2 - d4 .} {In addition to the direct d4 , White can also focus on development first by starting with Bg2 .} 5. d4 {The main move. White wants to capture on c5 at an opportune moment and play against the isolated d-pawn.} cxd4 ({I like this better than the more popular moves} 5... Nc6 {and . The idea behind it is very concrete: Black takes advantage of the fact that the white king is still on e1 .}) (5... Nc6 6. Bg2 cxd4 {would transpose to my recommendation after} 7. Nxd4 {, but White has the additional option} ({( Bg4 is the main move. The pawn sacrifice} 7. O-O {gives White some initiative.)})) {O-O .} 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 {One move is still missing – castling short – and White's opening concept would be a complete success: the pawn on d5 is isolated and weak, giving White a small but permanent advantage.} (7. Nc3 {is very rarely played at this point. After} Nf6 8. Bg2 Bg4 {we have ended up in a position which I examine in detail via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 3.Sge2} 9. Nxc6 {g3 d5 exd5 exd5} d4 {cxd4} 10. Nxd4 {Nf6 Bg2 Bg4 .}) 7... Bc5 {This is the idea of our previous moves. While White can easily fend off the attack on the knight, they cannot do so without making a concession.} 8. Nb3 {The most popular continuation. White attacks the bishop c5 and the pawn d5 .} Qe7+ {A key idea in the line with 5...cxd4 . White is prevented from castling.} 9. Qe2 Bb6 ({Exchanging queens first is also possible. Less strong, however, is} 9... Be6 10. O-O {with some advantage for White. As we will see, it is not necessary to defend the d-pawn.}) 10. Nc3 {The choice of GM Michael Adams in an online rapid game against GM Vidit Gujrathi. He probably overlooked his opponent's reply.} Nb4 {White can no longer protect the c-pawn and is now fighting for equality.} 11. Qxe7+ Nxe7 12. O-O (12. Kd1 $2 Bf5 {Wins the pawn under far better circumstances.}) 12... Nxc2 13. Rb1 {White has good chances to win back the pawn on d5 soon.} Bf5 {Prepares to attack the rook. White must play precisely.} 14. Bf4 {The bishop can move to d6 . But even more importantly, the rook b1 gets additional squares.} (14. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Rd8 $1 16. Bxb7 O-O {The threats against the rooks and the f2 -pawn give Black an advantage, e.g.} 17. Bf4 Nd4 18. Rbd1 Bh3 {and White should give up the exchange with} 19. Nxd4 {. If instead Rfe1? , Black wins with Ne2+! Kh1 Nxf4 gxf4 Bxf2 because the bishops are very strong.}) 14... d4 ({Vidit opted instead for} 14... Rd8 {, which also poses problems for White. With d4 , Black keeps the d-pawn but can no longer defend the b-pawn.}) 15. Nb5 O-O {Black is threatening the double attack ... Bd3 . The move ... Ng6 can also be unpleasant for White, as their pieces are not coordinating well. White must continue to defend.} *

