1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {Against the Sicilian with 2...e6 , the fianchetto of the queen's bishop is a viable sideline. In other Sicilians, Black could easily neutralize the bishop on b2 , for instance by the pawn setup d6 + e5 or developing the king's bishop to g7 . With 2...e6 , however, Black has already signaled that the bishop will be developed on the diagonal ... f8 - a3 and it is also not very tempting to lose a tempo with another move of the e-pawn. This means that the white bishop can take up a strong attacking position on the long diagonal, as it has the black kingside directly in its sights. If Black allows it, White could also later transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or go for the Maroczy structure with c2 - c4 .} a6 {I recommend playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 also against the queenside fianchetto. This is prepared with 3... a7 -a6 , which is, unlike in the Kan Sicilian, less about expanding on the queenside and more about denying the white bishop the b5 -square. The bishop now has no good prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal as long as White has not played d2 - d4 : on c4 it would be easy to attack, on d3 it would be in the way of the d-pawn and e2 is a very passive square.} ({The direct} 3... d5 {allows} 4. Bb5+ $1 {.   A )} Nc6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {transposes to a variation of the Rossolimo Sicilian ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 Bb5 ) . White has very good long-term chances here due to the weakened black queenside.)}) ({) Bd7 is now best, but after Bxd7+ Qxd7 exd5 exd5 O-O White benefits from the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The most common move is} 3... Nc6 {[%eval 0,0] . Here White could already transpose to a kind of Rossolimo-Sicilian with} 4. Bb5 {. More popular, however, is Bb2 . Black now has various moves to choose from, but playing in the center with} d5 {would already be quite dangerous, because after Bb5! dxe4?! (better would be Nf6 or Nge7 )} 5. Ne5 {followed by an exchange on c6 , the shattered pawn structure on the queenside and the strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. d4 {White is not well prepared for this transposition to the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 {White does not achieve the desired Maroczy structure, which would arise after c2 - c4 .} 6. Bd3 (6. Nd2 $6 Qa5 {runs into concrete problems: the threat of ...Nxe4 and ...Qc3 .}) 6... Bc5 7. Nf3 {In the Kan Sicilian, White usually reacts to the attack ... Bc5 with Nb3 , but of course this is not possible here.} (7. Bb2 $2 {loses the f2 -pawn after} Qb6 8. c3 e5 {.}) ({After} 7. Be3 $6 Qc7 8. O-O {(or c4} Nc6 {),  is d5⩱ strong.}) 7... d6 ({Black is playing a very comfortable Sicilian. A good setup would be ...b7-b5 , ...Bb7 and ...Nbd7 . Should White develop the bishop to b2 , Black could block its diagonal with ...e6-e5 . A good alternative is} 7... d5 8. e5 Nfd7 {, which also leads to comfortable equality.}) *

