{Black wins back the pawn with this typical break. The position is equal. Re1 ( cxb5? axb5∓ will not save the pawn d5 and now the pawn on a2 is also weak. Black is threatening ...b5-b4 . White should not defend the pawn c4 with Qb3?! , because Bf5⩱ is very strong with the idea ...Bd3 .) Winning an exchange with b4? Ne4 Bxa1 Qxa1 leads to a bad position for Black. bxc4 Ne5 Bb7 Nxc4 Bxd5 Nxd5 Qxd5 Nb6 Qc6 Nxa8 Bxa1 is a possible way to an early draw.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {Against the Sicilian with 2...e6 , the fianchetto of the queen's bishop is a viable sideline. In other Sicilians, Black could easily neutralize the bishop on b2 , for instance by the pawn setup d6 + e5 or developing the king's bishop to g7 . With 2...e6 , however, Black has already signaled that the bishop will be developed on the diagonal ... f8 - a3 and it is also not very tempting to lose a tempo with another move of the e-pawn. This means that the white bishop can take up a strong attacking position on the long diagonal, as it has the black kingside directly in its sights. If Black allows it, White could also later transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or go for the Maroczy structure with c2 - c4 .} a6 {I recommend playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 also against the queenside fianchetto. This is prepared with 3... a7 -a6 , which is, unlike in the Kan Sicilian, less about expanding on the queenside and more about denying the white bishop the b5 -square. The bishop now has no good prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal as long as White has not played d2 - d4 : on c4 it would be easy to attack, on d3 it would be in the way of the d-pawn and e2 is a very passive square.} ({The direct} 3... d5 {allows} 4. Bb5+ $1 {.   A )} Nc6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {transposes to a variation of the Rossolimo Sicilian ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 Bb5 ) . White has very good long-term chances here due to the weakened black queenside.)}) ({) Bd7 is now best, but after Bxd7+ Qxd7 exd5 exd5 O-O White benefits from the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The most common move is} 3... Nc6 {[%eval 0,0] . Here White could already transpose to a kind of Rossolimo-Sicilian with} 4. Bb5 {. More popular, however, is Bb2 . Black now has various moves to choose from, but playing in the center with} d5 {would already be quite dangerous, because after Bb5! dxe4?! (better would be Nf6 or Nge7 )} 5. Ne5 {followed by an exchange on c6 , the shattered pawn structure on the queenside and the strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. c4 {This prevents ... b7 - b5 and increases control over d5 .} d5 ({This has only been played in a few games, but in my opinion is an easy way to equalize. Most often,} 4... Nc6 {is played. After} 5. Bb2 {Black continues with} Qc7 {, d6 or Nf6 . d5 would now be worse than one move before, because after cxd5 exd5 exd5 the knight on c6 is attacked.}) 5. cxd5 exd5 6. exd5 Nf6 {Black doesn't have to hurry with capturing on d5 and especially not with the queen, because it would be attacked by the white minor pieces.} 7. Bb2 Be7 {Black wants to castle and only then play ... Nxd5 . Then the g7 -pawn would already be protected by the king.} 8. Bxf6 ({White tries to hold on to the extra pawn. In Caruana-Neelotpal ,} 8. Be2 $6 {happened, after which} Nxd5 {would have given Black some advantage. Black has the more active minor pieces and the better pawn structure. Possible ideas are ...Bf6 or ...Nf4 . If} 9. Bxg7 {then} Rg8 {and Black wins back the pawn on g2 .}) 8... Bxf6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be2 Nd7 ({In Totsky-Krensing ,} 10... b6 {followed by ...Bb7 happened, which is also good enough to equalize. Nd7 prepares the attack on the d5 -pawn: either with ...Nb6 or first ...b7-b5 and then ...Nb6 .}) 11. O-O Nb6 (11... b5 {is also good.}) 12. Bc4 {White must not allow ...Nxd5 , because then Black would have the bishop pair and the better pawn structure with equal material.} Nxc4 13. bxc4 b5 *

