1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {Against the Sicilian with 2...e6 , the fianchetto of the queen's bishop is a viable sideline. In other Sicilians, Black could easily neutralize the bishop on b2 , for instance by the pawn setup d6 + e5 or developing the king's bishop to g7 . With 2...e6 , however, Black has already signaled that the bishop will be developed on the diagonal ... f8 - a3 and it is also not very tempting to lose a tempo with another move of the e-pawn. This means that the white bishop can take up a strong attacking position on the long diagonal, as it has the black kingside directly in its sights. If Black allows it, White could also later transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or go for the Maroczy structure with c2 - c4 .} a6 {I recommend playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 also against the queenside fianchetto. This is prepared with 3... a7 -a6 , which is, unlike in the Kan Sicilian, less about expanding on the queenside and more about denying the white bishop the b5 -square. The bishop now has no good prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal as long as White has not played d2 - d4 : on c4 it would be easy to attack, on d3 it would be in the way of the d-pawn and e2 is a very passive square.} ({The direct} 3... d5 {allows} 4. Bb5+ $1 {.   A )} Nc6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {transposes to a variation of the Rossolimo Sicilian ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 Bb5 ) . White has very good long-term chances here due to the weakened black queenside.)}) ({) Bd7 is now best, but after Bxd7+ Qxd7 exd5 exd5 O-O White benefits from the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The most common move is} 3... Nc6 {[%eval 0,0] . Here White could already transpose to a kind of Rossolimo-Sicilian with} 4. Bb5 {. More popular, however, is Bb2 . Black now has various moves to choose from, but playing in the center with} d5 {would already be quite dangerous, because after Bb5! dxe4?! (better would be Nf6 or Nge7 )} 5. Ne5 {followed by an exchange on c6 , the shattered pawn structure on the queenside and the strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. Bb2 d5 {The central advance is a standard idea, though not yet very popular in this specific position. I believe this will change, as many strong grandmasters have played this way recently.} ({It's a good time for ...d7-d5 , as the bishop check on b5 has been eliminated.  If Black waits any longer, White could preempt Black's play in the center. The most popular move is} 4... Nc6 {, but I don't like the fact that White can now determine the character of the game. With} 5. c4 {White can increase control in the center and prevent ...d7-d5 . The developing moves g3 and Be2 give Black more freedom, as 5...d5 would again be possible.  Finally, d4 cxd4} Nd4 {is occasionally played, although Black need not worry about this version of the Open Sicilian, because Qf6! followed by ...Bc5 promises good play.}) 5. exd5 ({White is practically forced to make this exchange.} 5. e5 $2 {would be a positional mistake. Not only does the e5 -pawn block the b2 -bishop's diagonal – it can hardly be saved. Black can increase the pressure further with ... Nc6 , ... g7 - g5 , ... Bg7 etc. and White will soon run out of defensive moves.}) 5... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a typical problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop can be developed freely. White now most commonly plays d4 , which amounts to an exchange against the black c-pawn and subsequent play against the isolated pawn on d5 . Alternatively, White could go for piece activity.} 6. Bd3 ({A rare move, but played by top GMs Harikrishna and Short, among others. White wants to continue with Qe2+ , when, unlike in the variation} 6. Qe2+ {, the bishop is not trapped on f1 and White can castle directly.}) 6... Nf6 7. Qe2+ ({Worse is} 7. O-O $6 Be7 {The bishop on d3 is in the way of the d-pawn. As a result, the b1 -knight cannot be developed to its natural square d2 . It does not have good prospects on c3 and would block the view of the b2 -bishop.}) 7... Qe7 ({Against Qe2+ ,} 7... Be6 {is our choice. Here, however, the knight is already on f6 , which is why Be6?!} 8. Ng5 {(or Bf5 )} Qe7 9. Nxe6 fxe6 {(} 10. Qxe6 $2 {Bxf6! ) O-O leads to a slightly better position for White.}) 8. Ne5 {Harikrishna's choice has a concrete drawback.} b5 ({This exploits the somewhat unfortunate white piece setup. Black is threatening to win a piece with ...c5-c4 and is already slightly better. Let's look at a few defensive attempts: In Harikrishna-El Debs ,} 8... Ng4 9. Nxg4 Bxg4 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {followed with equality.}) 9. Na3 ({This is a creative defense against ...c5-c4 , but a3 is not a good square for the knight.} 9. Qe3 {gives the bishop a flight square, but loses time after} d4 10. Qe2 {. The strongest move now is} Nd5 {with the threat ...Nf4 .}) ({After} 9. c4 bxc4 10. bxc4 d4 {, the bishop on b2 is locked in and the knight b1 does not find its way into the game so quickly either.}) ({The situation is similar with} 9. c3 {. This saves the bishop on d3 , but the bishop b2 and the knight b1 now need a long time to become active. Black will finish development, for example with} g6 {and ...Bg7 or Qe6 and ...Bd6 , and is better.}) (9. Nf3 {is a solid defense, but of course this was not the idea when White played 8.Ne5 .} Nc6 10. O-O Be6 {.}) 9... Ng4 ({After} 9... c4 $2 {White has planned the piece sacrifice} 10. bxc4 bxc4 11. Naxc4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Be6 13. O-O {. Black does not succeed in bringing the king to safety.}) 10. Nxg4 Bxg4 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {Once again Black is slightly better – the knight on a3 is out of play. A possible continuation of development is ... Nc6 , ... Kd7 and – if possible – ... Bd6 .} *

