 7... Qe7 ({Against Qe2+ ,} 7... Be6 {is our choice. Here, however, the knight is already on f6 , which is why Be6?!} 8. Ng5 {(or Bf5 )} Qe7 9. Nxe6 fxe6 {(} 10. Qxe6 $2 {Bxf6! ) O-O leads to a slightly better position for White.}) 8. O-O {This hasn't been played yet, but it looks best.} Qxe2 9. Bxe2 Nc6 {Black wants to complete development with ... Nc6 , ... Be6 and ... Be7 . The order of these moves is not important.} 10. d4 {This looks like the only sensible plan.} Be7 {The resulting loss of tempo is not significant here.} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 {Black now has an isolated queen's pawn, but White is unable to put pressure on it or blockade it. The position is therefore equal. Black achieves a harmonious setup with ... O-O , ... Be6 and the positioning of the rooks in the center.} ({As before, White gains nothing with Bxf6 gxf6 , because the weak pawns on the kingside cannot be attacked.  After Rd1 – in addition to} 11... Be6 {– the counterattack Ne4 is possible.}) *

