1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {Against the Sicilian with 2...e6 , the fianchetto of the queen's bishop is a viable sideline. In other Sicilians, Black could easily neutralize the bishop on b2 , for instance by the pawn setup d6 + e5 or developing the king's bishop to g7 . With 2...e6 , however, Black has already signaled that the bishop will be developed on the diagonal ... f8 - a3 and it is also not very tempting to lose a tempo with another move of the e-pawn. This means that the white bishop can take up a strong attacking position on the long diagonal, as it has the black kingside directly in its sights. If Black allows it, White could also later transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or go for the Maroczy structure with c2 - c4 .} a6 {I recommend playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 also against the queenside fianchetto. This is prepared with 3... a7 -a6 , which is, unlike in the Kan Sicilian, less about expanding on the queenside and more about denying the white bishop the b5 -square. The bishop now has no good prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal as long as White has not played d2 - d4 : on c4 it would be easy to attack, on d3 it would be in the way of the d-pawn and e2 is a very passive square.} ({The direct} 3... d5 {allows} 4. Bb5+ $1 {.   A )} Nc6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {transposes to a variation of the Rossolimo Sicilian ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 Bb5 ) . White has very good long-term chances here due to the weakened black queenside.)}) ({) Bd7 is now best, but after Bxd7+ Qxd7 exd5 exd5 O-O White benefits from the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The most common move is} 3... Nc6 {[%eval 0,0] . Here White could already transpose to a kind of Rossolimo-Sicilian with} 4. Bb5 {. More popular, however, is Bb2 . Black now has various moves to choose from, but playing in the center with} d5 {would already be quite dangerous, because after Bb5! dxe4?! (better would be Nf6 or Nge7 )} 5. Ne5 {followed by an exchange on c6 , the shattered pawn structure on the queenside and the strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. Bb2 d5 {The central advance is a standard idea, though not yet very popular in this specific position. I believe this will change, as many strong grandmasters have played this way recently.} ({It's a good time for ...d7-d5 , as the bishop check on b5 has been eliminated.  If Black waits any longer, White could preempt Black's play in the center. The most popular move is} 4... Nc6 {, but I don't like the fact that White can now determine the character of the game. With} 5. c4 {White can increase control in the center and prevent ...d7-d5 . The developing moves g3 and Be2 give Black more freedom, as 5...d5 would again be possible.  Finally, d4 cxd4} Nd4 {is occasionally played, although Black need not worry about this version of the Open Sicilian, because Qf6! followed by ...Bc5 promises good play.}) 5. exd5 ({White is practically forced to make this exchange.} 5. e5 $2 {would be a positional mistake. Not only does the e5 -pawn block the b2 -bishop's diagonal – it can hardly be saved. Black can increase the pressure further with ... Nc6 , ... g7 - g5 , ... Bg7 etc. and White will soon run out of defensive moves.}) 5... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a typical problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop can be developed freely. White now most commonly plays d4 , which amounts to an exchange against the black c-pawn and subsequent play against the isolated pawn on d5 . Alternatively, White could go for piece activity.} 6. Qe2+ {The queen check is the second most popular move and the engine's favorite. Black needs to play accurately here.} Be6 ({Worse is} 6... Qe7 {. After} 7. Qxe7+ {(or Nc3 Nf6 d4⩲ )} Nxe7 8. Nc3 {White has the more harmonious seetup and – after a later d2-d4 followed by dxc5 – the better pawn structure.}) 7. d4 {According to my database, this has only been played once. In fact, the combination of 6.Qe2+ and 7.d4 doesn't look so logical, because the bishop f1 can't be developed to d3 now. On the other hand, the e6 -bishop could come under attack.} Nc6 8. dxc5 Nf6 {White has no way of defending the c5 -pawn.} 9. Ng5 {Best. After other moves Black would have the better chances, as the queen is out of place on e2 .} Qd7 10. g3 ({Prepares the development of the bishop to h3 . In Shengelia-Mijovic , Black had solved all the opening problems after} 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. g3 Bxc5 {. Next} 12. Bh3 $6 {happened and now Black could have already gained an advantage with} Ne4 13. f4 Nd4 14. Qd3 Nf5 {.}) 10... O-O-O ({Good is also} 10... Bxc5 11. Bh3 O-O-O 12. Nxe6 Rhe8 13. O-O fxe6 {.}) 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Bh3 Kb8 ({It is better not to defend the pawn.} 12... Re8 {would be a loss of time.}) 13. Bxe6 {Principled, but risky. After other moves, Black captures on c5 and doesn't have any problems.} Qc7 14. b4 {The only move. Otherwise Black plays ... Bxc5 and will come to a decisive attack on the e- and f-files.} d4 ({Black restricts the dangerous b2 -bishop. Now the knight c6 can move again. After} 14... Re8 $6 15. O-O {Black cannot benefit so easily from the pin because} Nd8 $2 {fails to} 16. Be5 {.}) 15. O-O ({After} 15. a3 $2 Re8 16. O-O {(or f4?} Bxc5 $1 17. bxc5 Rxe6 18. Qxe6 Re8 {) Nd8 , Black wins the bishop.}) 15... Nxb4 {Black will also win the pawn c5 and has thus restored the material balance. The position is equal.} *

