k is worse} 7... Nf6 $2 {allows} 8. Ng5 {– the square is no longer defended by the queen. After} Qe7 9. Nxe6 fxe6 ({(or} 9... Qxe6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bg2 {)}) 10. Bh3 {, Black comes under strong pressure.}) ({It may seem natural to prepare ...Nf6 with} 7... h6 $2 {, but that is too slow. White's best continuation now is} 8. Bh3 Qe7 9. Bxe6 Qxe6 ({(even worse is} 9... fxe6 $2 10. Ne5 {)}) 10. Nc3 {, after which Nxd5 is a threat. If Black defends the d-pawn, d2-d4 follows along with an exchange on c5 , after which the black d-pawn will be very weak. The defense} d4 $2 {does not work here because of} 11. Nd5 $1 {. Black does not succeed in defending the queenside, e.g. the natural} Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bd6 $2 {loses because of the unusual fork} 13. Nb6 Ra7 14. Nc8 $1 {.}) 8. d3 {With d2 - d3 , White keeps the option open for where to develop the f1 -bishop and prepares to develop the queen's knight to d2 . Placing it on c3 would block the dark-squared bishop’s diagonal.} h6 {White's previous move was somewhat slow and gives Black the time to prevent Ng5 and thus prepare ...Nf6 .} ({The direct} 8... Nf6 $6 {is inaccurate because of} 9. Ng5 Qe7 10. Nxe6 Qxe6 11. Qxe6+ fxe6 12. Bh3 {.}) ({In the game Antipov-Yoo ,} 8... Nge7 {happened with the idea ...Nf5 , ...Be7 and ...O-O , which is also playable.}) 9. Bh3 ({After} 9. Bg2 Nf6 10. O-O Be7 {and ...O-O , Black doesn't have any worries either.}) 9... Qe7 10. Bxe6 Qxe6 11. Qxe6+ fxe6 {The position is equal. We deal with a very similar position in the line with  8.Bh3 .} *

