 strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. Bb2 d5 {The central advance is a standard idea, though not yet very popular in this specific position. I believe this will change, as many strong grandmasters have played this way recently.} ({It's a good time for ...d7-d5 , as the bishop check on b5 has been eliminated.  If Black waits any longer, White could preempt Black's play in the center. The most popular move is} 4... Nc6 {, but I don't like the fact that White can now determine the character of the game. With} 5. c4 {White can increase control in the center and prevent ...d7-d5 . The developing moves g3 and Be2 give Black more freedom, as 5...d5 would again be possible.  Finally, d4 cxd4} Nd4 {is occasionally played, although Black need not worry about this version of the Open Sicilian, because Qf6! followed by ...Bc5 promises good play.}) 5. exd5 ({White is practically forced to make this exchange.} 5. e5 $2 {would be a positional mistake. Not only does the e5 -pawn block the b2 -bishop's diagonal – it can hardly be saved. Black can increase the pressure further with ... Nc6 , ... g7 - g5 , ... Bg7 etc. and White will soon run out of defensive moves.}) 5... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a typical problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop can be developed freely. White now most commonly plays d4 , which amounts to an exchange against the black c-pawn and subsequent play against the isolated pawn on d5 . Alternatively, White could go for piece activity.} 6. Qe2+ {The queen check is the second most popular move and the engine's favorite. Black needs to play accurately here.} Be6 ({Worse is} 6... Qe7 {. After} 7. Qxe7+ {(or Nc3 Nf6 d4⩲ )} Nxe7 8. Nc3 {White has the more harmonious seetup and – after a later d2-d4 followed by dxc5 – the better pawn structure.}) 7. g3 {This not only prepares the development of the bishop to g2 . Black should also pay attention to the possibility of Bh3 .} Nc6 ({After all other moves, Black is worse} 7... Nf6 $2 {allows} 8. Ng5 {– the square is no longer defended by the queen. After} Qe7 9. Nxe6 fxe6 ({(or} 9... Qxe6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bg2 {)}) 10. Bh3 {, Black comes under strong pressure.}) ({It may seem natural to prepare ...Nf6 with} 7... h6 $2 {, but that is too slow. White's best continuation now is} 8. Bh3 Qe7 9. Bxe6 Qxe6 ({(even worse is} 9... fxe6 $2 10. Ne5 {)}) 10. Nc3 {, after which Nxd5 is a threat. If Black defends the d-pawn, d2-d4 follows along with an exchange on c5 , after which the black d-pawn will be very weak. The defense} d4 $2 {does not work here because of} 11. Nd5 $1 {. Black does not succeed in defending the queenside, e.g. the natural} Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bd6 $2 {loses because of the unusual fork} 13. Nb6 Ra7 14. Nc8 $1 {.}) 8. Bh3 {White wants to force a weak pawn on e6 .} Qe7 ({The only move. The queen must keep an eye on the g5 -square.} 8... Qd7 $2 {allows} 9. Ng5 {.}) 9. Bxe6 (9. Bg2 {White could also retreat the bishop and argue that the queen on e7 interferes with Black's development. However, that's not entirely accurate, as ...Qe7 is quite useful here. For instance, it is now possible to trade queens with} Bg4 {or Bf5 , which leads to equality. There is also the sharper O-O-O} 10. O-O h5 $5 {followed by ...h5-h4 with good play on the kingside. (Not Nf6?!} 11. Ng5 {.)}) 9... Qxe6 ({Not} 9... fxe6 $2 {, after which the queen on e7 stands in the way of Black's minor pieces and prevents a quick development of the kingside.}) 10. Qxe6+ (10. Nc3 {brings White nothing due to} d4 {.} 11. Nd5 {is answered with} Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 O-O-O {. This shows why it was important to develop the knight on the seventh move.}) 10... fxe6 {Although the e6 -pawn is technically a weakness, it doesn’t play a significant role since White cannot easily attack it.} 11. O-O ({The direct attack} 11. Ng5 {leads to nothing after} e5 {.}) 11... Nf6 12. Re1 Kd7 {Black has a clear aim: to bring the e-pawn to e5 . Accordingly, the moves ... Bd6 and ... Rae8 are on the agenda. If the advance succeeds, the e-pawn is no longer backward and, together with its colleagues on d5 and c5 , would ensure supremacy in the center. This scenario is best prevented by White with the following move.} 13. Ne5+ ({In the game Simacek-Schlosser , White chose} 13. d4 $6 {instead. Now Black could have gained an advantage with} cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Rc8 {. White cannot get rid of the pressure against the c-pawn easily.}) ({White also makes life more difficult than necessary with} 13. Nc3 {, which was played in the game Garbarino-Bronstein .} b5 ({(After} 13... Re8 {,} 14. Na4 {would probably have followed, although Black is also better here after} Nb4 $1 {. b5} 15. Nb6+ Kd6 16. a4 {gives White counterplay.)}) 14. a4 b4 15. Ne2 Bd6 {Black is ready for ...e6-e5 .  This would be bad news for all of White's minor pieces, as the pawn would take away key squares.} 16. d4 {is therefore forced and now Black could have built up pressure against the f2 -pawn with} Ne4 {followed by ...Rhf8 .}) 13... Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bd6 {The position is equal.} *

