 strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. Bb2 d5 {The central advance is a standard idea, though not yet very popular in this specific position. I believe this will change, as many strong grandmasters have played this way recently.} ({It's a good time for ...d7-d5 , as the bishop check on b5 has been eliminated.  If Black waits any longer, White could preempt Black's play in the center. The most popular move is} 4... Nc6 {, but I don't like the fact that White can now determine the character of the game. With} 5. c4 {White can increase control in the center and prevent ...d7-d5 . The developing moves g3 and Be2 give Black more freedom, as 5...d5 would again be possible.  Finally, d4 cxd4} Nd4 {is occasionally played, although Black need not worry about this version of the Open Sicilian, because Qf6! followed by ...Bc5 promises good play.}) 5. exd5 ({White is practically forced to make this exchange.} 5. e5 $2 {would be a positional mistake. Not only does the e5 -pawn block the b2 -bishop's diagonal – it can hardly be saved. Black can increase the pressure further with ... Nc6 , ... g7 - g5 , ... Bg7 etc. and White will soon run out of defensive moves.}) 5... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a typical problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop can be developed freely. White now most commonly plays d4 , which amounts to an exchange against the black c-pawn and subsequent play against the isolated pawn on d5 . Alternatively, White could go for piece activity.} 6. Qe2+ {The queen check is the second most popular move and the engine's favorite. Black needs to play accurately here.} Be6 ({Worse is} 6... Qe7 {. After} 7. Qxe7+ {(or Nc3 Nf6 d4⩲ )} Nxe7 8. Nc3 {White has the more harmonious seetup and – after a later d2-d4 followed by dxc5 – the better pawn structure.}) 7. g3 {This not only prepares the development of the bishop to g2 . Black should also pay attention to the possibility of Bh3 .} Nc6 ({After all other moves, Black is worse} 7... Nf6 $2 {allows} 8. Ng5 {– the square is no longer defended by the queen. After} Qe7 9. Nxe6 fxe6 ({(or} 9... Qxe6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bg2 {)}) 10. Bh3 {, Black comes under strong pressure.}) ({It may seem natural to prepare ...Nf6 with} 7... h6 $2 {, but that is too slow. White's best continuation now is} 8. Bh3 Qe7 9. Bxe6 Qxe6 ({(even worse is} 9... fxe6 $2 10. Ne5 {)}) 10. Nc3 {, after which Nxd5 is a threat. If Black defends the d-pawn, d2-d4 follows along with an exchange on c5 , after which the black d-pawn will be very weak. The defense} d4 $2 {does not work here because of} 11. Nd5 $1 {. Black does not succeed in defending the queenside, e.g. the natural} Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bd6 $2 {loses because of the unusual fork} 13. Nb6 Ra7 14. Nc8 $1 {.}) 8. Bg2 {The more conventional bishop development is not without its poison – how should Black complete development?} d4 {Shuts out the b2 -bishop, which had put unpleasant pressure on the g7 -pawn. Now Black can proceed with the setup ...Be7 , ...Nf6 and ...O-O .} (8... Nf6 $2 {was played in the top-class online rapid game Chigaev-Le , but, as before, this is no good due to} 9. Ng5 $1 {. After} Qd7 10. Nxe6 fxe6 {,} 11. Bh3 {would have been the strongest continuation.}) ({After} 8... h6 $6 9. O-O Nf6 {as well, White gets strong pressure along the e-file with} 10. Bh3 $1 {.}) ({However,} 8... Nh6 $5 9. O-O Nf5 {is possible, which was under discussion in Sasikiran-Movsesian . The knight defends g7 so that Black can then complete development with ...Be7 and ...O-O .}) 9. O-O Be7 10. Ne5 {With 8...d4 we had taken the b2 -bishop out of play, but on the other hand cleared the view for its colleague on g2 .} ({White tries to exploit this. A developing move like} 10. Na3 {is met with} Nf6 {, after which Black is ready to castle.} 11. Ng5 $6 {is now only a loss of time – the bishop e6 is no longer pinned.} Bd5 {.}) 10... Nxe5 11. Qxe5 Rb8 ({The pawn g7 needs no protection, since the queen would be trapped after Qxg7?} 11... Bf6 {. Now Black is again ready for development of the kingside with ...Nf6 .}) 12. c3 {The hardest test.} b6 ({This doesn't allow White's planned activation of the minor pieces on the queenside. Black sacrifices a pawn for this. After} 12... dxc3 $6 13. Nxc3 {or d3?! Re1} Nf6 {c4⩲ the two white bishops are very strong.}) 13. cxd4 ({The game Ivic-Predke , ended in the repetition} 13. Qe4 Nf6 14. Qc6+ Bd7 15. Qf3 Bg4 16. Qc6+ Bd7 17. Qf3 Bg4 {.}) ({After} 13. Na3 {or Re1 , Black finishes development with} Bf6 {and ...Ne7 .}) 13... Bf6 {It was necessary to prepare this move with 12...b6 because otherwise the pawn c5 would have been unprotected.} 14. Qe2 Ne7 ({Development first. The d4-pawn is pinned and doesn't run away. The knight move is more precise than} 14... Bxd4 $6 15. Bxd4 Qxd4 {, as happened the blitz game Caruana-Chigaev . Here the well-known motif} 16. Bh3 $1 {would have given White some advantage, because after} Qxa1 $2 17. Nc3 Qb2 18. Bxe6 {White wins back material and has a strong attack.}) 15. Qxa6 O-O {Black is currently two pawns down, but will soon regain one of them on d4 . There's still no reason to hurry: instead of ... Bxd4 Black could also play ... Nf5 and ... Nxd4 . White won't have much fun with the remaining extra pawn: The d2 -pawn is weak and backward, the black pieces are active and Black has the outpost square d4 under control. The position is equal.} *

