1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {Against the Sicilian with 2...e6 , the fianchetto of the queen's bishop is a viable sideline. In other Sicilians, Black could easily neutralize the bishop on b2 , for instance by the pawn setup d6 + e5 or developing the king's bishop to g7 . With 2...e6 , however, Black has already signaled that the bishop will be developed on the diagonal ... f8 - a3 and it is also not very tempting to lose a tempo with another move of the e-pawn. This means that the white bishop can take up a strong attacking position on the long diagonal, as it has the black kingside directly in its sights. If Black allows it, White could also later transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or go for the Maroczy structure with c2 - c4 .} a6 {I recommend playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 also against the queenside fianchetto. This is prepared with 3... a7 -a6 , which is, unlike in the Kan Sicilian, less about expanding on the queenside and more about denying the white bishop the b5 -square. The bishop now has no good prospects on the f1 - a6 diagonal as long as White has not played d2 - d4 : on c4 it would be easy to attack, on d3 it would be in the way of the d-pawn and e2 is a very passive square.} ({The direct} 3... d5 {allows} 4. Bb5+ $1 {.   A )} Nc6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {transposes to a variation of the Rossolimo Sicilian ( e4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 Bb5 ) . White has very good long-term chances here due to the weakened black queenside.)}) ({) Bd7 is now best, but after Bxd7+ Qxd7 exd5 exd5 O-O White benefits from the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The most common move is} 3... Nc6 {[%eval 0,0] . Here White could already transpose to a kind of Rossolimo-Sicilian with} 4. Bb5 {. More popular, however, is Bb2 . Black now has various moves to choose from, but playing in the center with} d5 {would already be quite dangerous, because after Bb5! dxe4?! (better would be Nf6 or Nge7 )} 5. Ne5 {followed by an exchange on c6 , the shattered pawn structure on the queenside and the strong bishop on b2 give White enormous compensation for the pawn.}) 4. Bb2 d5 {The central advance is a standard idea, though not yet very popular in this specific position. I believe this will change, as many strong grandmasters have played this way recently.} ({It's a good time for ...d7-d5 , as the bishop check on b5 has been eliminated.  If Black waits any longer, White could preempt Black's play in the center. The most popular move is} 4... Nc6 {, but I don't like the fact that White can now determine the character of the game. With} 5. c4 {White can increase control in the center and prevent ...d7-d5 . The developing moves g3 and Be2 give Black more freedom, as 5...d5 would again be possible.  Finally, d4 cxd4} Nd4 {is occasionally played, although Black need not worry about this version of the Open Sicilian, because Qf6! followed by ...Bc5 promises good play.}) 5. exd5 ({White is practically forced to make this exchange.} 5. e5 $2 {would be a positional mistake. Not only does the e5 -pawn block the b2 -bishop's diagonal – it can hardly be saved. Black can increase the pressure further with ... Nc6 , ... g7 - g5 , ... Bg7 etc. and White will soon run out of defensive moves.}) 5... exd5 {By exchanging, Black has solved a typical problem in the Sicilian with 2...e6 : the c8 -bishop can be developed freely. White now most commonly plays d4 , which amounts to an exchange against the black c-pawn and subsequent play against the isolated pawn on d5 . Alternatively, White could go for piece activity.} 6. d4 {The main line. White wants to capture on c5 later and play against the isolated pawn on d5 .} Nf6 7. Bd3 ({White should only capture on c5 after the f8 -bishop has moved, otherwise Black will save a tempo.} 7. Be2 {is also played, but on e2 the bishop is more passive and blocks the e-file. Black can continue as against Bd3 and doesn't have any problems.}) 7... Be7 8. dxc5 {Since Black has moved the bishop, this is now a logical option.} Nc6 ({Slightly more accurate than} 8... Bxc5 {, after which White has the annoying} 9. Qe2+ {. Nc6 controls b4 , so White cannot defend the pawn on c5 .}) 9. O-O O-O 10. Nd4 ({White voluntarily changes the pawn structure, but gets a little more leeway in return.} 10. Nbd2 Bxc5 {is a very comfortable isolani position for Black. The white position is passive and the knight d2 has no good prospects.} 11. Re1 {is out of the question because of the weakness of the f-pawn after . White's best bet is playing for equality, for instance with c4 or} Ne5 {.}) 10... Bxc5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nd2 {On c3 the knight would be in the way of the b2 -bishop.} Re8 13. Qf3 {The position is reminiscent of a popular line in the Scotch Four Knights. The exchange on f6 is not a threat, as the dark-squared bishop is more important here than the weakened pawn structure. The white plan should be slower and could consist of centralizing the rooks and playing in the center with c2 - c4 . A knight maneuver via f1 to g3 can also be considered.} Bb4 {This somewhat disturbs the harmony in the white position.} 14. Qf4 ({Of course not} 14. Rad1 $2 Bg4 {and similarly} 15. c3 $2 {is not good because of Bg4 , e.g. Qg3} Bd6 {Qh4 Re5!∓ with the threat of ...Rh5 .}) 14... a5 {Black is threatening ... Nh5 , after which the queen could no longer protect the knight.} 15. Rfe1 Be6 16. Rad1 {Not forced, but logical. The queen is relieved of its task as a defensive piece.} Nh5 {Expels the queen from her active position.} 17. Qf3 g6 ({Black could next become active with ...Qg5 . The direct} 17... Qg5 {was no good because of} 18. Re5 {. Black's other ideas include exchanging the strong b2 -bishop with ...Bf8-g7 and counterplay on the queenside with ...a5-a4 . Neither side can hope for an advantage here.}) *

