[Black "14B | Morra Gambit | About th"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B21"]
[PlyCount "18"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The starting position of the Morra Gambit. White sacrifices the d-pawn for fast development, good central control and play on the d-file. However, losing a central pawn is a high price to pay, as White's development advantage is limited and Black’s position is very solid. The Morra Gambit is therefore rarely found in grandmaster games, but at amateur level it is a very popular way of bypassing the Sicilian main lines.} dxc3 ({Accepting the gambit is the principled reaction. After all, Black now has an extra pawn and hence excellent chances of a full point! There are also several ways to reject the gambit. If you have 2...Nf6 in your repertoire against the Alapin Sicilian, you can also play} 3... Nf6 {here. White now has nothing better than} 4. e5 Nd5 {. This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5 Nd5} 5. cxd4 {cxd4 .}) ({Transposing to the Alapin Sicilian with} 3... d5 {is also possible, but I advise against it. After} 4. exd5 {exd5} Qxd5 5. cxd4 {, we don't reach our repertoire. The difference is, that here Black has already exchanged on d4 , which gives White an immediate attack on the queen with Nc3 .}) ({Finally, Black can also reject the gambit with} 3... d3 {. After} 4. Bxd3 {White can play a Maroczy set-up with c3-c4 , or go for a kingside attack with f2-f4 .}) 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 ({(It is not too late to go for the setup I suggest with} 5... e6 {).}) 6. Bc4 e6 ({Black should play this anyway, because} 6... Nf6 $6 {already allows} 7. e5 $1 dxe5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 ({(} 8... Nxd8 9. Nb5 {)}) 9. Ng5 {.}) 7. O-O {The majority of games which have reached this position continue with this move.} Nf6 8. Qe2 Be7 9. Rd1 {White is now threatening 10.e5 .} e5 {Black therefore usually plays this themselves, but this move weakens d5 and the a2-g8 diagonal. White has sufficient compensation for the pawn.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Morra Gambit (2.d4)"]
[Black "14B | Morra Gambit | 6.Bf4 / "]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B21"]
[PlyCount "38"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The starting position of the Morra Gambit. White sacrifices the d-pawn for fast development, good central control and play on the d-file. However, losing a central pawn is a high price to pay, as White's development advantage is limited and Black’s position is very solid. The Morra Gambit is therefore rarely found in grandmaster games, but at amateur level it is a very popular way of bypassing the Sicilian main lines.} dxc3 ({Accepting the gambit is the principled reaction. After all, Black now has an extra pawn and hence excellent chances of a full point! There are also several ways to reject the gambit. If you have 2...Nf6 in your repertoire against the Alapin Sicilian, you can also play} 3... Nf6 {here. White now has nothing better than} 4. e5 Nd5 {. This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5 Nd5} 5. cxd4 {cxd4 .}) ({Transposing to the Alapin Sicilian with} 3... d5 {is also possible, but I advise against it. After} 4. exd5 {exd5} Qxd5 5. cxd4 {, we don't reach our repertoire. The difference is, that here Black has already exchanged on d4 , which gives White an immediate attack on the queen with Nc3 .}) ({Finally, Black can also reject the gambit with} 3... d3 {. After} 4. Bxd3 {White can play a Maroczy set-up with c3-c4 , or go for a kingside attack with f2-f4 .}) 4. Nxc3 e6 {Our typical move is also good here. White will usually develop the light-squared bishop to c4 and then the pawn on e6 is necessary to protect the f7 -point from tactical attacks. However, 4...e6 does not only fulfill defensive purposes. As in most Anti-Sicilians, we will try to play with ... d7 - d5 in the center. That may seem unrealistic here, as White has the square under good control. But with the setup ... Bb4 and ... Nge7 , Black can organize the necessary support.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 {has no independent significance. After} Nc6 6. Nf3 {the game transposes to our main line.}) 5... Nc6 (5... Bb4 {is inaccurate because of} 6. Qd4 $1 {. After the exchange on c3 the dark squares would be weakened and otherwise the bishop has to retreat to f8 .}) 6. Bf4 {White targets the weakened d6 and c7 -squares.} Bb4 {By pinning the knight, Black increases their influence in the center. Since White has not yet castled, ...Nf6 is often a good continuation, with which Black puts pressure on the e4 -pawn. However, as in the main line  6.Bc4 , the plan ...Nge7 and ... d7 -d5 is also possible.} 7. Bd6 {The play on the dark squares is reminiscent of the Four Knights Sicilian. However, White is not in a position to generate strong threats here.} (7. Bc4 {transposes after} Nge7 ({(Black has the additional option} 7... Nf6 $5 8. e5 Ne4 {.} 9. Qe2 $6 {Nxe4! Qxe4} d5 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 {)}) 8. O-O {to the line Bc4 Bb4} O-O {Nge7 Bf4 .}) (7. Bd3 {happened in the blitz game Theodorou-So . Now} Bxc3+ $1 8. bxc3 d6 {would have been strongest. Black wants to play ...e6-e5 and has a healthy extra pawn.}) 7... Bxd6 ({There is also nothing to be said against} 7... Nge7 {.}) 8. Qxd6 Nf6 ({Here as well, the knight could also go to e7 . However, the queen on d6 could not be attacked so easily in this case. This is now possible with ...Qe7 . The direct} 8... Qe7 {is inaccurate because of} 9. Qg3 {.}) 9. e5 {White is not properly prepared for this.} Ng4 {Black is threatening ... Qb6 with an attack on the pawns f2 and b2 on the one hand, and ... Qe7 on the other, after which the pawn e5 cannot be defended.} 10. h3 {This runs into a tactic.} Qb6 11. hxg4 (11. Qd2 $2 Ngxe5) 11... Qxb2 {Black wins back the material.} 12. Nb5 {White's best chance is to counter-attack.} Qxa1+ 13. Kd2 Qb2+ (13... Qxa2+ 14. Ke3 $1) 14. Kd1 Rb8 ({Black is playing for a win. After} 14... Nb4 {White has} 15. Rxh7 $1 {with the idea} Rxh7 16. Nc7+ Kd8 17. Qf8+ Kxc7 18. Qd6+ {with perpetual check.}) 15. Nc7+ Kd8 16. Ng5 {White wins back material, because Black cannot defend f7 .} Qd4+ 17. Qxd4 ({After} 17. Kc2 $2 Qxf2+ {the pawn f7 is protected.}) 17... Nxd4 18. Nb5 (18. Nxf7+ $2 Kxc7 19. Nxh8 b5 $1 20. Rxh7 Bb7 {White has won back the material, but soon Black will generate decisive threats on the queenside.}) 18... Ke7 (18... Nxb5 $6 19. Nxf7+ Kc7 20. Nxh8 Nd4 21. Rxh7 {gives White an important extra tempo compared to 18.Nxf7+ .}) 19. Nxd4 b5 {Black has retained a small material advantage and has a good chance of creating a passed pawn on the queenside. This line was already given by Kamil Plichta in Lifetime Repertoires: Accelerated Dragon .} *

