1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The starting position of the Morra Gambit. White sacrifices the d-pawn for fast development, good central control and play on the d-file. However, losing a central pawn is a high price to pay, as White's development advantage is limited and Black’s position is very solid. The Morra Gambit is therefore rarely found in grandmaster games, but at amateur level it is a very popular way of bypassing the Sicilian main lines.} dxc3 ({Accepting the gambit is the principled reaction. After all, Black now has an extra pawn and hence excellent chances of a full point! There are also several ways to reject the gambit. If you have 2...Nf6 in your repertoire against the Alapin Sicilian, you can also play} 3... Nf6 {here. White now has nothing better than} 4. e5 Nd5 {. This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5 Nd5} 5. cxd4 {cxd4 .}) ({Transposing to the Alapin Sicilian with} 3... d5 {is also possible, but I advise against it. After} 4. exd5 {exd5} Qxd5 5. cxd4 {, we don't reach our repertoire. The difference is, that here Black has already exchanged on d4 , which gives White an immediate attack on the queen with Nc3 .}) ({Finally, Black can also reject the gambit with} 3... d3 {. After} 4. Bxd3 {White can play a Maroczy set-up with c3-c4 , or go for a kingside attack with f2-f4 .}) 4. Nxc3 e6 {Our typical move is also good here. White will usually develop the light-squared bishop to c4 and then the pawn on e6 is necessary to protect the f7 -point from tactical attacks. However, 4...e6 does not only fulfill defensive purposes. As in most Anti-Sicilians, we will try to play with ... d7 - d5 in the center. That may seem unrealistic here, as White has the square under good control. But with the setup ... Bb4 and ... Nge7 , Black can organize the necessary support.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 {has no independent significance. After} Nc6 6. Nf3 {the game transposes to our main line.}) 5... Nc6 (5... Bb4 {is inaccurate because of} 6. Qd4 $1 {. After the exchange on c3 the dark squares would be weakened and otherwise the bishop has to retreat to f8 .}) 6. Bf4 {White targets the weakened d6 and c7 -squares.} Bb4 {By pinning the knight, Black increases their influence in the center. Since White has not yet castled, ...Nf6 is often a good continuation, with which Black puts pressure on the e4 -pawn. However, as in the main line  6.Bc4 , the plan ...Nge7 and ... d7 -d5 is also possible.} 7. Bd6 {The play on the dark squares is reminiscent of the Four Knights Sicilian. However, White is not in a position to generate strong threats here.} (7. Bc4 {transposes after} Nge7 ({(Black has the additional option} 7... Nf6 $5 8. e5 Ne4 {.} 9. Qe2 $6 {Nxe4! Qxe4} d5 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 {)}) 8. O-O {to the line Bc4 Bb4} O-O {Nge7 Bf4 .}) (7. Bd3 {happened in the blitz game Theodorou-So . Now} Bxc3+ $1 8. bxc3 d6 {would have been strongest. Black wants to play ...e6-e5 and has a healthy extra pawn.}) 7... Bxd6 ({There is also nothing to be said against} 7... Nge7 {.}) 8. Qxd6 Nf6 ({Here as well, the knight could also go to e7 . However, the queen on d6 could not be attacked so easily in this case. This is now possible with ...Qe7 . The direct} 8... Qe7 {is inaccurate because of} 9. Qg3 {.}) 9. Bb5 ({The knight thrust} 9. Nb5 $2 {would be fatal if Black did not have the resource} Qa5+ {. Black will capture on e4 next, e.g.} 10. Kd1 ({(or} 10. b4 Nxb4 {)}) 10... Nxe4 {. White cannot protect the pawn f2 .}) 9... Qe7 {The position was reached in four email games, with White only managing a draw in one of them. The poor score is no coincidence, as the compensation for the pawn is clearly inadequate here. If White moves the queen away, Black can occupy the dark squares at the right moment with ... e6 -e5 and ... d7 -d6 .} ({On the other hand, if White allows the queen trade on d6 with O-O-O , Black fights for the dark squares with Qxd6 Rxd6 Ke7 , e.g. Rhd1 Ne8 or} 9... Ng4 {.}) *

