[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The starting position of the Morra Gambit. White sacrifices the d-pawn for fast development, good central control and play on the d-file. However, losing a central pawn is a high price to pay, as White's development advantage is limited and Black’s position is very solid. The Morra Gambit is therefore rarely found in grandmaster games, but at amateur level it is a very popular way of bypassing the Sicilian main lines.} dxc3 ({Accepting the gambit is the principled reaction. After all, Black now has an extra pawn and hence excellent chances of a full point! There are also several ways to reject the gambit. If you have 2...Nf6 in your repertoire against the Alapin Sicilian, you can also play} 3... Nf6 {here. White now has nothing better than} 4. e5 Nd5 {. This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5 Nd5} 5. cxd4 {cxd4 .}) ({Transposing to the Alapin Sicilian with} 3... d5 {is also possible, but I advise against it. After} 4. exd5 {exd5} Qxd5 5. cxd4 {, we don't reach our repertoire. The difference is, that here Black has already exchanged on d4 , which gives White an immediate attack on the queen with Nc3 .}) ({Finally, Black can also reject the gambit with} 3... d3 {. After} 4. Bxd3 {White can play a Maroczy set-up with c3-c4 , or go for a kingside attack with f2-f4 .}) 4. Nxc3 e6 {Our typical move is also good here. White will usually develop the light-squared bishop to c4 and then the pawn on e6 is necessary to protect the f7 -point from tactical attacks. However, 4...e6 does not only fulfill defensive purposes. As in most Anti-Sicilians, we will try to play with ... d7 - d5 in the center. That may seem unrealistic here, as White has the square under good control. But with the setup ... Bb4 and ... Nge7 , Black can organize the necessary support.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 {has no independent significance. After} Nc6 6. Nf3 {the game transposes to our main line.}) 5... Nc6 (5... Bb4 {is inaccurate because of} 6. Qd4 $1 {. After the exchange on c3 the dark squares would be weakened and otherwise the bishop has to retreat to f8 .}) 6. Be2 {This modest bishop move is played extremely rarely, but it is the favorite of the engines. Its advantage compared with the main line  6.Bc4 is that Black cannot attack the bishop with ... d7 - d5 .} Bb4 {Our usual move. We prepare ... Nge7 .} 7. O-O Nge7 {Black is now ready for ... d7 - d5 .} 8. Nb5 {White is threatening Bf4 . This allows White to keep equal chances.} d5 ({Frees the queenside. After} 8... O-O 9. a3 Ba5 10. b4 Bb6 $6 ({(better is} 10... a6 $1 {)}) 11. Nd6 {White has paralyzed the black queenside, which promises more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 9. Bf4 {Now Black cannot defend c7 and must therefore allow Nc7 .} O-O (9... Ba5 $2 10. Nd6+ Kf8 11. Ng5 {And now f7 cannot be defended.}) 10. Nc7 {White's moves are forced. Otherwise White has no compensation for the pawn. Black can now opt for a draw by repetition or for a complicated middlegame.} Rb8 ({The alternative is the exchange sacrifice} 10... dxe4 $5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Nxa8 exf3 13. Bxf3 {. After} e5 {Black has good compensation for the exchange. It is probably not possible to win the knight a8 , but White will have to invest some time in its return while Black enjoys excellent piece play.}) 11. exd5 (11. Nb5 $2 {happened in the game Pechac-Lupulescu after which Black played} Ra8 $2 {and repeated moves. Instead, dxe4! leads to a hopeless position for White, e.g.} 12. Ne5 ({(After} 12. Bb8 {exf3-+ two white pieces are attacked. Black wins material.)})) {Ra8 Nxc6 bxc6! and White no longer has the repetition with Nc7 and has therefore lost two pawns for nothing. Nc7 is met with Nd5 Nxa8 Nxf4-+ .} 11... exd5 ({After that both sides can no longer avoid the repetition. Black could still continue the fight with} 11... Bd6 $5 {. After} 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. dxc6 Qxc6 {, however, a draw remains the most likely outcome.}) 12. Nb5 Ra8 13. Nc7 Rb8 *

