r the exchange on c3 the dark squares would be weakened and otherwise the bishop has to retreat to f8 .}) 6. Bc4 {By far the most common move. The bishop is active here, making ... d7 - d5 more difficult and the move sometimes supports a thematic knight sacrifice on d5 .} Bb4 {We want to develop the king's knight to e7 without locking in the dark-squared bishop, so the bishop is developed first. From b4 it supports the liberating central strike ... d7 - d5 , because it can be exchanged against the knight on c3 at any time. It is important not to hurry with this exchange, as that would leave White with good control of the dark squares. However, if White attacks the bishop with a2 - a3 , the situation is different. Firstly, White loses an important tempo and secondly, the bishop c1 can no longer move directly to a3 , as the square is occupied by its own pawn. 6... Bb4 is only the fourth most common move, but it gives Black active play and is linked to a clear idea. I don't see how White can now get full compensation for the pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Bd2 $6 {is a loss of tempo. We didn't want to capture on c3 anyway.} Nge7) 7... Nge7 {Black pursues the plan already described. On f6 the knight could be attacked by the white e-pawn, while on e7 it is safe. In addition, it can later fight for e5 via g6 .} 8. Nb5 {White attacks the weakened squares d6 and c7 , threatening 9.Bf4 and 9.Nd6+ . However, Black is well armed against this attack.} d5 9. exd5 exd5 10. Bxd5 {White wins back the pawn with a small tactic.} Nxd5 11. Qxd5 O-O {The bishop pair gives Black a small but stable advantage.} 12. Qh5 {In most games, White decides to avoid trading queens.} a6 ({Pinning the knight with} 12... Qa5 {is tempting, but White can save themselves in the following complications:} 13. a3 $1 {The only move, otherwise White loses material.} a6 ({(After} 13... Be7 {follows} 14. Bd2 {.)}) 14. axb4 Qxa1 15. Nc3 $1 {The queen is now trapped on a1 .} Be6 16. Bh6 $1 Qxb2 17. Bxg7 {Black can now accept the perpetual check after} Kxg7 18. Qg5+ {, or give back the exchange, which also leads to an equal position. Karumazondo-Clarke}) 13. Nc3 Bxc3 ({A transformation of the advantage. Black is also slightly better after} 13... Be6 {.}) 14. bxc3 Qf6 {The pawn on c3 is weak. Black can fight for the full point without any risk.} *

