1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The starting position of the Morra Gambit. White sacrifices the d-pawn for fast development, good central control and play on the d-file. However, losing a central pawn is a high price to pay, as White's development advantage is limited and Black’s position is very solid. The Morra Gambit is therefore rarely found in grandmaster games, but at amateur level it is a very popular way of bypassing the Sicilian main lines.} dxc3 ({Accepting the gambit is the principled reaction. After all, Black now has an extra pawn and hence excellent chances of a full point! There are also several ways to reject the gambit. If you have 2...Nf6 in your repertoire against the Alapin Sicilian, you can also play} 3... Nf6 {here. White now has nothing better than} 4. e5 Nd5 {. This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5 Nd5} 5. cxd4 {cxd4 .}) ({Transposing to the Alapin Sicilian with} 3... d5 {is also possible, but I advise against it. After} 4. exd5 {exd5} Qxd5 5. cxd4 {, we don't reach our repertoire. The difference is, that here Black has already exchanged on d4 , which gives White an immediate attack on the queen with Nc3 .}) ({Finally, Black can also reject the gambit with} 3... d3 {. After} 4. Bxd3 {White can play a Maroczy set-up with c3-c4 , or go for a kingside attack with f2-f4 .}) 4. Nxc3 e6 {Our typical move is also good here. White will usually develop the light-squared bishop to c4 and then the pawn on e6 is necessary to protect the f7 -point from tactical attacks. However, 4...e6 does not only fulfill defensive purposes. As in most Anti-Sicilians, we will try to play with ... d7 - d5 in the center. That may seem unrealistic here, as White has the square under good control. But with the setup ... Bb4 and ... Nge7 , Black can organize the necessary support.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 {has no independent significance. After} Nc6 6. Nf3 {the game transposes to our main line.}) 5... Nc6 (5... Bb4 {is inaccurate because of} 6. Qd4 $1 {. After the exchange on c3 the dark squares would be weakened and otherwise the bishop has to retreat to f8 .}) 6. Bc4 {By far the most common move. The bishop is active here, making ... d7 - d5 more difficult and the move sometimes supports a thematic knight sacrifice on d5 .} Bb4 {We want to develop the king's knight to e7 without locking in the dark-squared bishop, so the bishop is developed first. From b4 it supports the liberating central strike ... d7 - d5 , because it can be exchanged against the knight on c3 at any time. It is important not to hurry with this exchange, as that would leave White with good control of the dark squares. However, if White attacks the bishop with a2 - a3 , the situation is different. Firstly, White loses an important tempo and secondly, the bishop c1 can no longer move directly to a3 , as the square is occupied by its own pawn. 6... Bb4 is only the fourth most common move, but it gives Black active play and is linked to a clear idea. I don't see how White can now get full compensation for the pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Bd2 $6 {is a loss of tempo. We didn't want to capture on c3 anyway.} Nge7) 7... Nge7 {Black pursues the plan already described. On f6 the knight could be attacked by the white e-pawn, while on e7 it is safe. In addition, it can later fight for e5 via g6 .} 8. Bf4 ({Like} 8. Nb5 {, the bishop move also targets the weakened dark squares. White is threatening 9.Nb5 .}) 8... Bxc3 {Easiest. White's play is nipped in the bud.} 9. bxc3 d5 10. exd5 ({Also after} 10. Bd3 dxe4 11. Bxe4 Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 f6 $1 {with the idea ...e6-e5 the bishop pair does not offer sufficient compensation for the minus pawn.}) 10... Nxd5 ({White is slightly more active and has the bishop pair. However, these advantages do not outweigh the lost pawn. Black's position is very solid and the c3 -pawn is weak. If the f4 -bishop moves away, Black will castle. After} 10... exd5 11. Bb3 {the bishop pair and the weak pawn on d5 give White compensation for the pawn.}) 11. Bxd5 ({Perhaps this is still best. After} 11. Bg5 Qa5 {or Bg3 O-O followed by ...Qa5 Black increases the pressure on the weak pawn c3 .}) ({If White plays} 11. Bd2 {instead, the bishop is very passive. Black will later complete development of the queenside with ...b6 and ...Bb7 and put pressure on the c-file.}) 11... Qxd5 (11... exd5 $6 12. Re1+ Be6 13. Ng5 {would leave White with a strong initiative.}) 12. Qxd5 exd5 {The opposite-colored bishops give White good chances for a draw.} *

