1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The starting position of the Morra Gambit. White sacrifices the d-pawn for fast development, good central control and play on the d-file. However, losing a central pawn is a high price to pay, as White's development advantage is limited and Black’s position is very solid. The Morra Gambit is therefore rarely found in grandmaster games, but at amateur level it is a very popular way of bypassing the Sicilian main lines.} dxc3 ({Accepting the gambit is the principled reaction. After all, Black now has an extra pawn and hence excellent chances of a full point! There are also several ways to reject the gambit. If you have 2...Nf6 in your repertoire against the Alapin Sicilian, you can also play} 3... Nf6 {here. White now has nothing better than} 4. e5 Nd5 {. This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5 Nd5} 5. cxd4 {cxd4 .}) ({Transposing to the Alapin Sicilian with} 3... d5 {is also possible, but I advise against it. After} 4. exd5 {exd5} Qxd5 5. cxd4 {, we don't reach our repertoire. The difference is, that here Black has already exchanged on d4 , which gives White an immediate attack on the queen with Nc3 .}) ({Finally, Black can also reject the gambit with} 3... d3 {. After} 4. Bxd3 {White can play a Maroczy set-up with c3-c4 , or go for a kingside attack with f2-f4 .}) 4. Nxc3 e6 {Our typical move is also good here. White will usually develop the light-squared bishop to c4 and then the pawn on e6 is necessary to protect the f7 -point from tactical attacks. However, 4...e6 does not only fulfill defensive purposes. As in most Anti-Sicilians, we will try to play with ... d7 - d5 in the center. That may seem unrealistic here, as White has the square under good control. But with the setup ... Bb4 and ... Nge7 , Black can organize the necessary support.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 {has no independent significance. After} Nc6 6. Nf3 {the game transposes to our main line.}) 5... Nc6 (5... Bb4 {is inaccurate because of} 6. Qd4 $1 {. After the exchange on c3 the dark squares would be weakened and otherwise the bishop has to retreat to f8 .}) 6. Bc4 {By far the most common move. The bishop is active here, making ... d7 - d5 more difficult and the move sometimes supports a thematic knight sacrifice on d5 .} Bb4 {We want to develop the king's knight to e7 without locking in the dark-squared bishop, so the bishop is developed first. From b4 it supports the liberating central strike ... d7 - d5 , because it can be exchanged against the knight on c3 at any time. It is important not to hurry with this exchange, as that would leave White with good control of the dark squares. However, if White attacks the bishop with a2 - a3 , the situation is different. Firstly, White loses an important tempo and secondly, the bishop c1 can no longer move directly to a3 , as the square is occupied by its own pawn. 6... Bb4 is only the fourth most common move, but it gives Black active play and is linked to a clear idea. I don't see how White can now get full compensation for the pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Bd2 $6 {is a loss of tempo. We didn't want to capture on c3 anyway.} Nge7) 7... Nge7 {Black pursues the plan already described. On f6 the knight could be attacked by the white e-pawn, while on e7 it is safe. In addition, it can later fight for e5 via g6 .} 8. Qc2 ({Like the main move,} 8. Qe2 {, Qc2 also prepares the rook move to d1 . The queen is not misplaced on c2 : it defends the knight c3 and also has an eye on the black kingside. The latter means that opening the position with ...d7-d5 no longer works well. Qc2 is the recommendation of the Morra expert IM Marc Esserman in his book Mayhem In The Morra .}) 8... O-O 9. Rd1 ({The rook is ideally placed here, because the d6 -square and the d7 -pawn are weak. After} 9. a3 Bxc3 10. bxc3 {Black can develop the queenside with ...b6 and ...Bb7 , for example, while after Qxc3} d5 {is good.}) 9... Ng6 ({Since Black can no longer hope to get ...d7-d5 in, the knight doesn't have any prospects on e7 . From g6 it controls e5 , prevents attacking attempts with h2-h4 as well as Bf4 , with which White could attack the weak dark squares.  In addition, the bishop now has a good flight square on e7 , as an exchange on c3 is no longer in Black's interest.} 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 d5 $6 {would now be dangerous for Black, because White can play for an attack with} 11. Ng5 $1 {.}) 10. Bg5 ({Or} 10. Be3 b6 {followed by ...Bb7 . White doesn't have enough play for the pawn.}) 10... Be7 {Also good is 10... Qa5 .} 11. Bxe7 Ngxe7 ({Black wants to develop the queenside with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 . The rook can then go to a7 , where it defends the d7 -pawn. The pressure along the d-file gives White some compensation for the pawn. Here too, however, this is only enough for good chances of not losing the game. In the analogous position with the white queen on e2 instead of c2 , it is better to capture with the queen on e7 . For concrete reasons this is less accurate here:} 11... Qxe7 $6 12. Nb5 a6 13. Nd6 b5 14. Bf1 $1 {. The bishop is much better here than on b3 , because it can later exert pressure against the black queenside when combined with a2-a4 . With the queen on e2 , White would not have this option. Nb5?! now doesn't lead anywhere because of d5 .}) ({After} 11... e5 {Ng6} 12. Qe2 Qa5 {White has to take care of defending the e-pawn.}) *

