1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The starting position of the Morra Gambit. White sacrifices the d-pawn for fast development, good central control and play on the d-file. However, losing a central pawn is a high price to pay, as White's development advantage is limited and Black’s position is very solid. The Morra Gambit is therefore rarely found in grandmaster games, but at amateur level it is a very popular way of bypassing the Sicilian main lines.} dxc3 ({Accepting the gambit is the principled reaction. After all, Black now has an extra pawn and hence excellent chances of a full point! There are also several ways to reject the gambit. If you have 2...Nf6 in your repertoire against the Alapin Sicilian, you can also play} 3... Nf6 {here. White now has nothing better than} 4. e5 Nd5 {. This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5 Nd5} 5. cxd4 {cxd4 .}) ({Transposing to the Alapin Sicilian with} 3... d5 {is also possible, but I advise against it. After} 4. exd5 {exd5} Qxd5 5. cxd4 {, we don't reach our repertoire. The difference is, that here Black has already exchanged on d4 , which gives White an immediate attack on the queen with Nc3 .}) ({Finally, Black can also reject the gambit with} 3... d3 {. After} 4. Bxd3 {White can play a Maroczy set-up with c3-c4 , or go for a kingside attack with f2-f4 .}) 4. Nxc3 e6 {Our typical move is also good here. White will usually develop the light-squared bishop to c4 and then the pawn on e6 is necessary to protect the f7 -point from tactical attacks. However, 4...e6 does not only fulfill defensive purposes. As in most Anti-Sicilians, we will try to play with ... d7 - d5 in the center. That may seem unrealistic here, as White has the square under good control. But with the setup ... Bb4 and ... Nge7 , Black can organize the necessary support.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 {has no independent significance. After} Nc6 6. Nf3 {the game transposes to our main line.}) 5... Nc6 (5... Bb4 {is inaccurate because of} 6. Qd4 $1 {. After the exchange on c3 the dark squares would be weakened and otherwise the bishop has to retreat to f8 .}) 6. Bc4 {By far the most common move. The bishop is active here, making ... d7 - d5 more difficult and the move sometimes supports a thematic knight sacrifice on d5 .} Bb4 {We want to develop the king's knight to e7 without locking in the dark-squared bishop, so the bishop is developed first. From b4 it supports the liberating central strike ... d7 - d5 , because it can be exchanged against the knight on c3 at any time. It is important not to hurry with this exchange, as that would leave White with good control of the dark squares. However, if White attacks the bishop with a2 - a3 , the situation is different. Firstly, White loses an important tempo and secondly, the bishop c1 can no longer move directly to a3 , as the square is occupied by its own pawn. 6... Bb4 is only the fourth most common move, but it gives Black active play and is linked to a clear idea. I don't see how White can now get full compensation for the pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Bd2 $6 {is a loss of tempo. We didn't want to capture on c3 anyway.} Nge7) 7... Nge7 {Black pursues the plan already described. On f6 the knight could be attacked by the white e-pawn, while on e7 it is safe. In addition, it can later fight for e5 via g6 .} 8. Qe2 {The most popular move. White wants to bring the rook to the half-open d-file.} O-O 9. Rd1 {White exerts pressure along the d-file and makes ... d7 - d5 more difficult.} Ng6 {The game is similar to the line starting with 8.Qc2 . With the rook on d1 , ... d7 -d5 is not so desirable. g6 is a good square for the knight as it controls e5 , prevents h2-h4 and Bf4 , which would allow White to attack the weak dark squares. In addition, the dark-squared bishop now has a good flight square on e7 .} ({More popular is} 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 d5 {, but here White has attacking chances on the kingside and a strong pair of bishops and thus sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 10. Bg5 ({After} 10. Be3 {,} b6 {is good, which is also my recommendation if White puts the queen on c2 instead of e2 . With the queen on e2 , Black could also first exchange on c3 , because here White would have to recapture with the pawn and thus damage their pawn structure. In any case, White does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 10... Be7 (10... Qa5 {is also quite possible.}) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 ({In contrast to the analogous position with the white queen on c2 , it is better here to recapture with the queen instead of the knight.} 11... Ngxe7 {is now followed by} 12. e5 $1 {The weakness of d6 gives White good compensation for the pawn.}) 12. Nb5 {This looks like the only serious attempt. White brings the knight to d6 , where it blockades the black position. After other moves ... a7 -a6 and ... b7 -b5 would have come and White would have had very little to show for the sacrificed pawn.} (12. e5 $6 {is now useless, as Black can immediately shake off the pressure with} f6 13. exf6 gxf6 {.}) 12... a6 13. Nd6 b5 {The bishop now has to leave the diagonal f1-a6 , from where it could have exerted pressure against the black queenside. This is the most important difference to the analogous position with the white queen on c2 .} 14. Bb3 Rb8 {Black prepares ... Bb7 . The bishop will then move to a8 so that the rook is no longer tied to its defense. The knight on d6 looks very annoying, but Black has an effective plan to get rid of it: ... f7 - f6 , ... Nge5 and ... Nf7 . Once again, the conclusion is that the compensation for the sacrificed pawn is insufficient.} *

