1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we look at the Sicilian Wing Gambit ( e4} 1... c5 2. b4 {) and variations of it ( e4 c5 a3 followed by b2-b4 and e4 c5 Nf3} e6 {) .  In the Wing Gambit, White sacrifices the b-pawn to gain better central control. There is a certain logic to this: Black has just played 1...c5 to control the d4 -square. However, sacrificing a pawn is a significant investment for this goal. In contrast to other gambits, White cannot count on an advantage in development and quick attacking chances. White usually does not get full compensation, which explains why the Wing Gambit is a rare guest in the tournament halls. For us, the different move orders with which White can initiate the Wing Gambit don't matter much, because I propose a setup that can be used against all move orders: we take the pawn on b4 and defend it with ...e7-e6 . Then we target the white center.}) 2. a3 {The idea of this mysterious-looking move becomes immediately obvious.} e6 3. b4 ({The Wing Gambit! With this sequence of moves White avoids some critical defenses, e.g. e4 c5} 3. b4 cxb4 {a3 d5 or} 4. e5 {.}) 3... cxb4 ({Black gratefully accepts the sacrifice. We consider this position via the move order e4 c5} 3... cxb4 {cxb4 a3 e6 .}) *

