1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we look at the Sicilian Wing Gambit ( e4} 1... c5 2. b4 {) and variations of it ( e4 c5 a3 followed by b2-b4 and e4 c5 Nf3} e6 {) .  In the Wing Gambit, White sacrifices the b-pawn to gain better central control. There is a certain logic to this: Black has just played 1...c5 to control the d4 -square. However, sacrificing a pawn is a significant investment for this goal. In contrast to other gambits, White cannot count on an advantage in development and quick attacking chances. White usually does not get full compensation, which explains why the Wing Gambit is a rare guest in the tournament halls. For us, the different move orders with which White can initiate the Wing Gambit don't matter much, because I propose a setup that can be used against all move orders: we take the pawn on b4 and defend it with ...e7-e6 . Then we target the white center.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4 {As with 2.a3 , the idea behind this version of the Wing Gambit is that some of Black's defenses are bypassed. However, the knight position on f3 has the drawback that White can no longer bring the queen to g4 .} cxb4 4. a3 Nf6 {Attacks the e4 -pawn. It is generally advantageous for Black to lure it one step forward.} 5. e5 {White gives up the flexibility that is characteristic of the central pawn duo e4 + d4 . The pawn on e5 can later be attacked by the f- or d-pawn.} Nd5 6. axb4 Bxb4 7. c3 {White prepares to occupy the center with d2 - d4 .} Be7 8. d4 d6 {Black attacks the e5 -pawn and vacates d7 to develop the minor pieces on the queenside.} 9. c4 {Where should the knight move to?} Nb4 {An important moment: the knight should not be placed offside ( c7 or b6 ).} ({From b4 it is an active participant in the battle for the important central squares as well as the kingside (it prevents Bd3 ) and can also be brought back to c6 if necessary. More concretely, Black is threatening} 9... Z0 {dxe5 Nxe5 Qxd4 .}) 10. exd6 (10. Be2 $2 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Nc2+ {and Black wins another pawn.}) 10... Bxd6 {Black will castle next and develop the light-squared bishop to b7 . White does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn.} *

