1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we look at the Sicilian Wing Gambit ( e4} 1... c5 2. b4 {) and variations of it ( e4 c5 a3 followed by b2-b4 and e4 c5 Nf3} e6 {) .  In the Wing Gambit, White sacrifices the b-pawn to gain better central control. There is a certain logic to this: Black has just played 1...c5 to control the d4 -square. However, sacrificing a pawn is a significant investment for this goal. In contrast to other gambits, White cannot count on an advantage in development and quick attacking chances. White usually does not get full compensation, which explains why the Wing Gambit is a rare guest in the tournament halls. For us, the different move orders with which White can initiate the Wing Gambit don't matter much, because I propose a setup that can be used against all move orders: we take the pawn on b4 and defend it with ...e7-e6 . Then we target the white center.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4 {As with 2.a3 , the idea behind this version of the Wing Gambit is that some of Black's defenses are bypassed. However, the knight position on f3 has the drawback that White can no longer bring the queen to g4 .} cxb4 4. d4 {White occupies the center.} Nf6 {We attack e4 .} 5. Bd3 d5 ({This forces White to move the e-pawn forward and thus give up the flexibility of the central duo e4 + d4 . It is also possible to start with} 5... Nc6 {.}) 6. e5 {The pawn structure is now fixed and is reminiscent of the French Defense.} Ne4 {Here the knight disrupts White's setup. The d3 -bishop is aimed at the black kingside but remains restricted for the time being.} 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3 {By exchanging pawns, White wants to make the c2 -pawn mobile and open up lines on the queenside, after which the black pawns could come under attack.} Be7 {We continue our development. The exchange on a3 is useless because White develops a piece by recapturing.} 9. axb4 Nxb4 10. Ne1 {White clears the way for the f-pawn. Other moves are not dangerous for Black either.} f5 ({The knight e4 was in danger of being lost after f3} 10... Ng5 11. h4 {. Now it has a flight square on f7 . I don't see sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) *

