1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we look at the Sicilian Wing Gambit ( e4} 1... c5 2. b4 {) and variations of it ( e4 c5 a3 followed by b2-b4 and e4 c5 Nf3} e6 {) .  In the Wing Gambit, White sacrifices the b-pawn to gain better central control. There is a certain logic to this: Black has just played 1...c5 to control the d4 -square. However, sacrificing a pawn is a significant investment for this goal. In contrast to other gambits, White cannot count on an advantage in development and quick attacking chances. White usually does not get full compensation, which explains why the Wing Gambit is a rare guest in the tournament halls. For us, the different move orders with which White can initiate the Wing Gambit don't matter much, because I propose a setup that can be used against all move orders: we take the pawn on b4 and defend it with ...e7-e6 . Then we target the white center.}) 2. b4 {The most direct way to the Wing Gambit.} cxb4 3. a3 ({White wants to open lines on the queenside. Later the black a- and b-pawns could come under pressure. In this respect, the Wing Gambit is reminiscent of the Volga Gambit (} 3. d4 Nf6 4. c4 {c5} d5 {b5 cxb5 a6 ) .}) 3... e6 {We defend the b-pawn and prepare playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 . It's usually better not to capture on a3 . White would recapture with a piece and develop it at the same time.} 4. d4 {Usually White exchanges on b4 beforehand, but it is also possible to occupy the center directly.} ({This position could also arrise from} 4. d4 {e6} bxa3 {.}) 4... Nf6 {We attack the pawn e4 ...} 5. Bd3 (5. e5 Nd5 {is favorable for Black because the knight is very well placed here. Things would be different if the f8 -bishop had already moved: then Black would have to watch out for Qg4 with an attack on the g7 -pawn.}) 5... Nc6 ({and now the d4 -pawn is unprotected and under attack. The pawn attack in the center would be premature:} 5... d5 $2 6. e5 Ne4 7. axb4 Bxb4+ 8. c3 $1 Nxc3 ({(or} 8... Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 Nxc3 10. Qc2 Ne4 11. f3 {, winning the piece.)}) 9. Qb3 {The knight c3 has gone astray and will be lost.}) 6. Nf3 {Good news: we no longer have to keep an eye on the queen thrust to g4 .} d5 {Now this is possible without any problems. The white pawn center loses its flexibility.} 7. e5 Ne4 {Here the knight disrupts the white position. The d3 -bishop is aimed at the black kingside but remains restricted for the time being.} 8. O-O Be7 ({We deal with this position via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 b4 cxb4 d4} 8... Nf6 {Bd3 Nc6 O-O d5 e5 Ne4 a3 Be7 .}) *

