1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we look at the Sicilian Wing Gambit ( e4} 1... c5 2. b4 {) and variations of it ( e4 c5 a3 followed by b2-b4 and e4 c5 Nf3} e6 {) .  In the Wing Gambit, White sacrifices the b-pawn to gain better central control. There is a certain logic to this: Black has just played 1...c5 to control the d4 -square. However, sacrificing a pawn is a significant investment for this goal. In contrast to other gambits, White cannot count on an advantage in development and quick attacking chances. White usually does not get full compensation, which explains why the Wing Gambit is a rare guest in the tournament halls. For us, the different move orders with which White can initiate the Wing Gambit don't matter much, because I propose a setup that can be used against all move orders: we take the pawn on b4 and defend it with ...e7-e6 . Then we target the white center.}) 2. b4 {The most direct way to the Wing Gambit.} cxb4 3. a3 ({White wants to open lines on the queenside. Later the black a- and b-pawns could come under pressure. In this respect, the Wing Gambit is reminiscent of the Volga Gambit (} 3. d4 Nf6 4. c4 {c5} d5 {b5 cxb5 a6 ) .}) 3... e6 {We defend the b-pawn and prepare playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 . It's usually better not to capture on a3 . White would recapture with a piece and develop it at the same time.} 4. axb4 Bxb4 5. Bb2 {The bishop is not as strong here as it seems.} Nf6 {This is the problem for White. The pawn on e4 is under attack.} 6. e5 {The most logical and strongest continuation, but now the bishop b2 no longer attacks the black kingside.} Nd5 7. c4 ({After} 7. Qg4 O-O {Black is better as well.}) 7... Ne7 {The best square for the knight. On b6 or c7 it would not have good prospects.} 8. Qg4 {The position is not ready for an attack on the black king.} O-O (8... Ng6 {is also good. But there is no reason to fear the white attack.}) 9. Nf3 d6 ({This refutes White's setup. Black succeeds in involving the queenside pieces in the defense. After} 9... Nbc6 $6 10. Bd3 {White is threatening the typical bishop sacrifice on h7 .} Ng6 11. h4 {White is objectively worse here too, but at least retains practical chances.}) 10. exd6 (10. Bd3 {is now answered with} dxe5 {. The sacrifice on h7 no longer works:} 11. Bxh7+ ({(} 11. Nxe5 f6 {is no better.)}) 11... Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qh3 ({(} 13. Qh5 Qd3 $1 {is the main point.)}) 13... Re8 14. Qh7+ Kf8 {. White's attack goes no further.}) 10... Ng6 {Besides an extra pawn (the d6 -pawn cannot be saved) Black also has the better position. Next, Black could activate the c8 -bishop with ... e6 - e5 and take control of the center.} *

