1. e4 c5 ({In this chapter we look at the Sicilian Wing Gambit ( e4} 1... c5 2. b4 {) and variations of it ( e4 c5 a3 followed by b2-b4 and e4 c5 Nf3} e6 {) .  In the Wing Gambit, White sacrifices the b-pawn to gain better central control. There is a certain logic to this: Black has just played 1...c5 to control the d4 -square. However, sacrificing a pawn is a significant investment for this goal. In contrast to other gambits, White cannot count on an advantage in development and quick attacking chances. White usually does not get full compensation, which explains why the Wing Gambit is a rare guest in the tournament halls. For us, the different move orders with which White can initiate the Wing Gambit don't matter much, because I propose a setup that can be used against all move orders: we take the pawn on b4 and defend it with ...e7-e6 . Then we target the white center.}) 2. b4 {The most direct way to the Wing Gambit.} cxb4 3. a3 ({White wants to open lines on the queenside. Later the black a- and b-pawns could come under pressure. In this respect, the Wing Gambit is reminiscent of the Volga Gambit (} 3. d4 Nf6 4. c4 {c5} d5 {b5 cxb5 a6 ) .}) 3... e6 {We defend the b-pawn and prepare playing in the center with ... d7 - d5 . It's usually better not to capture on a3 . White would recapture with a piece and develop it at the same time.} 4. axb4 Bxb4 5. c3 {White builds up a strong pawn center.} Be7 {The best square. White cannot win any further tempi with attacks on the bishop.} 6. d4 d6 ({Black thus takes control of e5 . I recommend this cautious setup at this point because the white queen can still go to g4 . After the desirable} 6... Nf6 {, White can play} 7. e5 Nd5 8. Qg4 {. Now 8...O-O would be met with 9.Bh6 , so Black should defend the g-pawn with} Kf8 {or g6 , both of which involve a weakening of the king position.}) 7. f4 ({White reinforces the center with another pawn.} 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. f4 {is a transposition.}) 7... Nf6 {After the insertion of 6...d6  7.f4 , Black no longer needs to fear the advance of the white e-pawn.} 8. Bd3 (8. e5 Nd5 9. Qg4 O-O {Here we see the difference to the analogous variation after 6...Nf6 . The white bishop cannot get to h6 .}) 8... O-O {Short castling is possible without further ado. White does not yet have a strong attack.} 9. Nf3 Nc6 {The knight is developed towards the center. From c6 it supports two possible pawn breaks: ... e6 - e5 and ... b7 - b5 -b4 .} 10. O-O Rb8 {A new move in this position. Black prepares to fight the opponent's imposing pawn center: the b-pawn should be sent to b4 (if necessary with the preparatory move ... a7 - a6 ).   White can then either acquiesce to a pawn trade or advance the c-pawn. Whatever White will choose, the d-pawn will be weakened and can be attacked with ... e6 - e5 . The advance of the b-pawn also has the advantage that Black gains space for their pieces on the queenside. White has visually appealing compensation for the pawn, but I still think Black has the better chances. It's not so clear how White can make progress. If White expands in the center with e4 - e5 , ... Nd5 always follows. The knight is very well placed there and has the important points c3 , e3 , and f4 in its sights. It is important not to exchange pawns first after e4 - e5 , as this would open the c1 -bishop's way to the kingside.} *

