1. e4 c5 2. g3 ({We encounter the bishop development to g2 in many Anti-Sicilians, such as the Closed Sicilian or the variation} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {. Compared to these systems, the direct 2.g3 has the advantage that White retains flexibility concerning the positioning of the knights: they are not always best placed on c3 or f3 . The drawback is that it allows the following move.}) 2... d5 ({Normally we prepare this move with ...e7-e6 , but here the concrete circumstances favor the direct advance. Most often Black plays} 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 {followed by ...Bg7 , but this does not fit with my recommendation against the Closed Sicilian, to which a transposition is possible.}) ({If Black prepares ...d7-d5 with} 2... e6 {, after} 3. Bg2 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ne2 {White gets an improved version of a line in the Closed Sicilian: e4 c5 Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {Nge2 . There Black can play} 6. d4 {with tempo, but here the white knight is not yet on c3 .}) 3. exd5 ({The defense of the e-pawn with} 3. Bg2 {is not particularly good, because White loses time after} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 {. After} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d3 Bg4 7. Nf3 g6 {, for example, Black already has slightly better chances.}) ({After} 3. d3 {Black can transition to the King's Indian attack with} e6 {. In addition, the queen trade dxe4 dxe4 Qxd1+ Kxd1 is an option and promises equal play.}) 3... Qxd5 {Black is posing concrete threats. This justifies the early activation of the queen.} 4. Qf3 Qd6 {The white queen is misplaced on f3 and can later be attacked by the black minor pieces. The black queen supports play in the center from d6 , with ... e7 - e5 coming soon.} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Ne2 e5 {Black has an advantage in the center. In addition, White's queen and the knight on e2 are badly placed. Black is slightly better.} *

