1. e4 c5 2. g3 ({We encounter the bishop development to g2 in many Anti-Sicilians, such as the Closed Sicilian or the variation} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {. Compared to these systems, the direct 2.g3 has the advantage that White retains flexibility concerning the positioning of the knights: they are not always best placed on c3 or f3 . The drawback is that it allows the following move.}) 2... d5 ({Normally we prepare this move with ...e7-e6 , but here the concrete circumstances favor the direct advance. Most often Black plays} 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 {followed by ...Bg7 , but this does not fit with my recommendation against the Closed Sicilian, to which a transposition is possible.}) ({If Black prepares ...d7-d5 with} 2... e6 {, after} 3. Bg2 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ne2 {White gets an improved version of a line in the Closed Sicilian: e4 c5 Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {Nge2 . There Black can play} 6. d4 {with tempo, but here the white knight is not yet on c3 .}) 3. exd5 ({The defense of the e-pawn with} 3. Bg2 {is not particularly good, because White loses time after} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 {. After} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d3 Bg4 7. Nf3 g6 {, for example, Black already has slightly better chances.}) ({After} 3. d3 {Black can transition to the King's Indian attack with} e6 {. In addition, the queen trade dxe4 dxe4 Qxd1+ Kxd1 is an option and promises equal play.}) 3... Qxd5 {Black is posing concrete threats. This justifies the early activation of the queen.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 ({More popular is} 4... Bg4 5. Bg2 Qe6+ $1 6. Kf1 Nc6 {, which leads to a complex middlegame with equal chances. I like 4...Nc6 better because the bishop is not always well placed on g4 .}) 5. Bg2 {This natural move already leads to problems for White. Nevertheless, it is the most common choice.} Qe6+ {White now loses the right to castle.} 6. Qe2 Qxe2+ 7. Kxe2 Bg4 ({Stronger than} 7... Bf5 {, which happened in the game Smyslov-Cramling . Black is threatening the knight check on d4 .}) 8. c3 (8. Kf1 e5 {is similar.}) 8... e5 {Black is threatening ... e5 - e4 , but even apart from that the pawn structure is generally favorable for the second player. On the one hand, Black has d4 firmly under control, which makes counterplay with d2 - d4 unrealistic. On the other, the black pawns deprive the c1 -bishop of its active prospects.} 9. h3 ({After} 9. d3 {,} c4 $1 {is strong when the white king comes under attack. Menshov-Sevdimaliyev .}) 9... Bf5 {Black is slightly better. Possible next moves are ... O-O-O , ... f7 - f6 and ... Nge7-d5 . Either the d3 -square is weak, or the d-pawn if White plays d2 - d3 .} *

