1. e4 c5 2. g3 ({We encounter the bishop development to g2 in many Anti-Sicilians, such as the Closed Sicilian or the variation} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {. Compared to these systems, the direct 2.g3 has the advantage that White retains flexibility concerning the positioning of the knights: they are not always best placed on c3 or f3 . The drawback is that it allows the following move.}) 2... d5 ({Normally we prepare this move with ...e7-e6 , but here the concrete circumstances favor the direct advance. Most often Black plays} 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 {followed by ...Bg7 , but this does not fit with my recommendation against the Closed Sicilian, to which a transposition is possible.}) ({If Black prepares ...d7-d5 with} 2... e6 {, after} 3. Bg2 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ne2 {White gets an improved version of a line in the Closed Sicilian: e4 c5 Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {Nge2 . There Black can play} 6. d4 {with tempo, but here the white knight is not yet on c3 .}) 3. exd5 ({The defense of the e-pawn with} 3. Bg2 {is not particularly good, because White loses time after} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 {. After} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d3 Bg4 7. Nf3 g6 {, for example, Black already has slightly better chances.}) ({After} 3. d3 {Black can transition to the King's Indian attack with} e6 {. In addition, the queen trade dxe4 dxe4 Qxd1+ Kxd1 is an option and promises equal play.}) 3... Qxd5 {Black is posing concrete threats. This justifies the early activation of the queen.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 ({More popular is} 4... Bg4 5. Bg2 Qe6+ $1 6. Kf1 Nc6 {, which leads to a complex middlegame with equal chances. I like 4...Nc6 better because the bishop is not always well placed on g4 .}) 5. d3 ({This is very rarely played at this point. The position is more often reached via the move order e4 c5} 5. d3 {Nc6 g3 d5 exd5 Qxd5 Nf3 . But d3 is also a sensible move in the present position because White can now react to the thematic ...Qe6+ with Be3 .}) 5... Qe6+ ({This untested novelty gives Black a complex middlegame with chances for both sides and avoids the draw by repetition that could arise after} 5... Nd4 {.}) 6. Be3 (6. Qe2 Qxe2+ 7. Bxe2 e5 {is equal.}) 6... Nh6 {The bishop e3 is a target.} 7. Qe2 (7. Nc3 $5 Nf5 8. Nb5 $1 Kd8 $1 {gives both sides equal chances in a complicated position.}) 7... b6 {The bishop e3 is no longer pinned, so Black must defend the pawn c5 .} 8. d4 (8. Bg2 Nf5 {followed by ...Bb7 is equal.}) 8... Nxd4 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Bxd4 Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 f6 {Black would like to occupy the center with ... e7 - e5 .} 12. f4 Bb7 13. Rf1 Nf5 14. Bf2 e6 {The position is equal. Next, Black could fortify the knight f5 with ... h7 - h5 , controlling g4 . The king will castle long or go to f7 .} *

