1. e4 c5 2. g3 ({We encounter the bishop development to g2 in many Anti-Sicilians, such as the Closed Sicilian or the variation} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {. Compared to these systems, the direct 2.g3 has the advantage that White retains flexibility concerning the positioning of the knights: they are not always best placed on c3 or f3 . The drawback is that it allows the following move.}) 2... d5 ({Normally we prepare this move with ...e7-e6 , but here the concrete circumstances favor the direct advance. Most often Black plays} 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 {followed by ...Bg7 , but this does not fit with my recommendation against the Closed Sicilian, to which a transposition is possible.}) ({If Black prepares ...d7-d5 with} 2... e6 {, after} 3. Bg2 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ne2 {White gets an improved version of a line in the Closed Sicilian: e4 c5 Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {Nge2 . There Black can play} 6. d4 {with tempo, but here the white knight is not yet on c3 .}) 3. exd5 ({The defense of the e-pawn with} 3. Bg2 {is not particularly good, because White loses time after} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 {. After} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d3 Bg4 7. Nf3 g6 {, for example, Black already has slightly better chances.}) ({After} 3. d3 {Black can transition to the King's Indian attack with} e6 {. In addition, the queen trade dxe4 dxe4 Qxd1+ Kxd1 is an option and promises equal play.}) 3... Qxd5 {Black is posing concrete threats. This justifies the early activation of the queen.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 ({More popular is} 4... Bg4 5. Bg2 Qe6+ $1 6. Kf1 Nc6 {, which leads to a complex middlegame with equal chances. I like 4...Nc6 better because the bishop is not always well placed on g4 .}) 5. Nc3 {White develops the knight with tempo and then wants to develop the kingside with Bg2 and O-O .} Qe6+ {This denies White a harmonious setup. The white bishop must now move to e2 – either directly, or after the previous exchange of queens. There it is more passive than on g2 .} 6. Ne2 {The attempt to develop the bishop to g2 meets with an unusual refutation.} Qe4 7. Bg2 Nd4 {The double attack on f3 and c2 forces White to take the knight.} 8. Nfxd4 Qxg2 9. Rg1 Qd5 10. Nb5 Qc6 {... e7 - e5 comes next, with a big advantage for Black. The light squares on the kingside are unprotected and White can no longer castle.} ({The game Lezcano Jaen-Kurajica , ended after only three more moves: Nbc3} 10... e5 11. d3 Nf6 12. Bg5 Ng4 $1 {. White cannot prevent the black knight from landing on f3 via h2 and therefore resigned.}) *

