1. e4 c5 2. g3 ({We encounter the bishop development to g2 in many Anti-Sicilians, such as the Closed Sicilian or the variation} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {. Compared to these systems, the direct 2.g3 has the advantage that White retains flexibility concerning the positioning of the knights: they are not always best placed on c3 or f3 . The drawback is that it allows the following move.}) 2... d5 ({Normally we prepare this move with ...e7-e6 , but here the concrete circumstances favor the direct advance. Most often Black plays} 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 {followed by ...Bg7 , but this does not fit with my recommendation against the Closed Sicilian, to which a transposition is possible.}) ({If Black prepares ...d7-d5 with} 2... e6 {, after} 3. Bg2 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ne2 {White gets an improved version of a line in the Closed Sicilian: e4 c5 Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {Nge2 . There Black can play} 6. d4 {with tempo, but here the white knight is not yet on c3 .}) 3. exd5 ({The defense of the e-pawn with} 3. Bg2 {is not particularly good, because White loses time after} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 {. After} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d3 Bg4 7. Nf3 g6 {, for example, Black already has slightly better chances.}) ({After} 3. d3 {Black can transition to the King's Indian attack with} e6 {. In addition, the queen trade dxe4 dxe4 Qxd1+ Kxd1 is an option and promises equal play.}) 3... Qxd5 {Black is posing concrete threats. This justifies the early activation of the queen.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 ({More popular is} 4... Bg4 5. Bg2 Qe6+ $1 6. Kf1 Nc6 {, which leads to a complex middlegame with equal chances. I like 4...Nc6 better because the bishop is not always well placed on g4 .}) 5. Nc3 {White develops the knight with tempo and then wants to develop the kingside with Bg2 and O-O .} Qe6+ {This denies White a harmonious setup. The white bishop must now move to e2 – either directly, or after the previous exchange of queens. There it is more passive than on g2 .} 6. Be2 {If the g-pawn were still on its starting square, the white position would be preferable. White has a lead in development which can even be enlarged by later attacks on the black queen. However, the pawn on g3 changes the assessment of the position. Not only does it not benefit White, but it also seriously weakens the first player's king position.} Nd4 {Black's play is very concrete. Black wants to exploit the fact that White has weakened the light squares on the kingside with g2 - g3 . After exchanging the e2 -bishop these would be insufficiently defended.} 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Nb5 (8. Nb1 h5 $5 {shows another drawback of the early g-pawn move. The opening of the h-file after ...h5-h4xg3 would be very dangerous for White. In Munoz Pantoja-Garrido Fernandez ,} 9. h4 {followed to prevent this, but after} Nf6 {, White had big problems.} 10. O-O {fails to} g5 $1 11. hxg5 h4 $1 {with a mating attack.}) 8... Qc6 {The attack on the rook forces a further weakening of White's position.} 9. f3 (9. O-O $2 {fails to} Bh3 {.}) 9... e5 {Black has everything covered. Now the knight b5 is tactically vulnerable. Black is threatening ... Bf5 .} 10. Bd3 ({A necessary defense against ...Bf5 . In addition, the move prepares Qe2 . After} 10. c3 $2 Bf5 $1 {threatening d4-d3 poses unsolvable problems for White. The nice punch line is winning the queen after} 11. cxd4 $2 Bc2 {.}) (10. O-O {?} Bf5 {threatening ...d4-d3 with a win of the b5 -knight. Black wins at least the pawn c2 .}) 10... Qb6 ({A novelty based on prophylactic thinking. Black would like to drive the knight away from b5 , but after the direct} 10... a6 {, White has the counterattack} 11. Qe2 $1 {, after which the knight cannot be captured and the pawns e5 and d4 are attacked.}) 11. Qe2 f6 {Black has defended everything. Next, the knight can be forced back with ... a7 - a6 . In this unusual position, Black's chances deserve preference. Black can develop all their minor pieces to active squares, while this perspective does not exist for the bishop on c1 .} *

