{(worse is Rxg5 f6 Rh5 e5∓. ) .} 1. e4 c5 2. g3 ({We encounter the bishop development to g2 in many Anti-Sicilians, such as the Closed Sicilian or the variation} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {. Compared to these systems, the direct 2.g3 has the advantage that White retains flexibility concerning the positioning of the knights: they are not always best placed on c3 or f3 . The drawback is that it allows the following move.}) 2... d5 ({Normally we prepare this move with ...e7-e6 , but here the concrete circumstances favor the direct advance. Most often Black plays} 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 {followed by ...Bg7 , but this does not fit with my recommendation against the Closed Sicilian, to which a transposition is possible.}) ({If Black prepares ...d7-d5 with} 2... e6 {, after} 3. Bg2 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ne2 {White gets an improved version of a line in the Closed Sicilian: e4 c5 Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {Nge2 . There Black can play} 6. d4 {with tempo, but here the white knight is not yet on c3 .}) 3. exd5 ({The defense of the e-pawn with} 3. Bg2 {is not particularly good, because White loses time after} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 {. After} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d3 Bg4 7. Nf3 g6 {, for example, Black already has slightly better chances.}) ({After} 3. d3 {Black can transition to the King's Indian attack with} e6 {. In addition, the queen trade dxe4 dxe4 Qxd1+ Kxd1 is an option and promises equal play.}) 3... Qxd5 {Black is posing concrete threats. This justifies the early activation of the queen.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 ({More popular is} 4... Bg4 5. Bg2 Qe6+ $1 6. Kf1 Nc6 {, which leads to a complex middlegame with equal chances. I like 4...Nc6 better because the bishop is not always well placed on g4 .}) 5. Nc3 {White develops the knight with tempo and then wants to develop the kingside with Bg2 and O-O .} Qe6+ {This denies White a harmonious setup. The white bishop must now move to e2 – either directly, or after the previous exchange of queens. There it is more passive than on g2 .} 6. Be2 {If the g-pawn were still on its starting square, the white position would be preferable. White has a lead in development which can even be enlarged by later attacks on the black queen. However, the pawn on g3 changes the assessment of the position. Not only does it not benefit White, but it also seriously weakens the first player's king position.} Nd4 {Black's play is very concrete. Black wants to exploit the fact that White has weakened the light squares on the kingside with g2 - g3 . After exchanging the e2 -bishop these would be insufficiently defended.} 7. O-O Nxe2+ {After this exchange, the weaknesses of the light squares are even more noticeable.} 8. Nxe2 b6 {The bishop moves to the long diagonal where, together with the queen, it creates threats against the white king.} 9. Nf4 Qf5 ({Black wants to continue with ...Bb7 after which ...g7-g5 is a threat, winning a piece. White faces a difficult defense.  Analysis with the engine shows many fascinating complications, e.g. Re1} 9... Bb7 {A ) White could also start with} 10. c4 {, which transposes after} O-O-O 11. d4 {. (} g5 $2 {fails to} 12. Qa4 {Kd8 Ne6+!! fxe6 Ne5} Nf6 13. g4 $1 {, and White wins the queen: Qf4} cxd4 {Qxd4 ) .   B ) d4 O-O-O . (Here g5 is possible. The complications after} 14. Nxg5 $1 {Qxg5 Ne6} Qf5 {Nc7+ Kd8 Nxa8 c4!⩱ end in Black's favor.)   B.1 ) c4 g5} 15. Nd5 Rxd5 $1 16. cxd5 Qxd5 {White cannot save the knight on f3 . Black maintains the slightly better chances.   B.2 ) In the correspondence game Bucsa-Spagnoli , there followed d5 g5! Re5} 17. Qd7+ {Nxg5 f6 Nfe6 fxe5 c4! And the complications continue.}) *

