1. e4 c5 2. g3 ({We encounter the bishop development to g2 in many Anti-Sicilians, such as the Closed Sicilian or the variation} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {. Compared to these systems, the direct 2.g3 has the advantage that White retains flexibility concerning the positioning of the knights: they are not always best placed on c3 or f3 . The drawback is that it allows the following move.}) 2... d5 ({Normally we prepare this move with ...e7-e6 , but here the concrete circumstances favor the direct advance. Most often Black plays} 2... Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 {followed by ...Bg7 , but this does not fit with my recommendation against the Closed Sicilian, to which a transposition is possible.}) ({If Black prepares ...d7-d5 with} 2... e6 {, after} 3. Bg2 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ne2 {White gets an improved version of a line in the Closed Sicilian: e4 c5 Nc3 e6 g3 d5 exd5 exd5 Bg2} Nf6 {Nge2 . There Black can play} 6. d4 {with tempo, but here the white knight is not yet on c3 .}) 3. exd5 ({The defense of the e-pawn with} 3. Bg2 {is not particularly good, because White loses time after} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 {. After} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d3 Bg4 7. Nf3 g6 {, for example, Black already has slightly better chances.}) ({After} 3. d3 {Black can transition to the King's Indian attack with} e6 {. In addition, the queen trade dxe4 dxe4 Qxd1+ Kxd1 is an option and promises equal play.}) 3... Qxd5 {Black is posing concrete threats. This justifies the early activation of the queen.} 4. Nf3 Nc6 ({More popular is} 4... Bg4 5. Bg2 Qe6+ $1 6. Kf1 Nc6 {, which leads to a complex middlegame with equal chances. I like 4...Nc6 better because the bishop is not always well placed on g4 .}) 5. Nc3 {White develops the knight with tempo and then wants to develop the kingside with Bg2 and O-O .} Qe6+ {This denies White a harmonious setup. The white bishop must now move to e2 – either directly, or after the previous exchange of queens. There it is more passive than on g2 .} 6. Qe2 Qxe2+ 7. Bxe2 e5 {Black establishes a solid center which is difficult to attack. The pawn is later supported with ... f7 - f6 . The c8 -bishop has many good squares to choose from and after its development Black can castle long. White will have difficulties finding a useful task for the bishop on c1 , and the knight on f3 will not be very well placed either once Black plays ... f7 - f6 . Black has comfortable equality.} (7... e5 {has only been played in one game so far. In Salimova-Yakubbaeva, 2021 , it was followed by} 8. Nd5 {, though the knight would have had better prospects on e4 or b5 .} Bd6 9. b3 Nge7 10. Nxe7 Kxe7 11. Bb2 f6 {The white position is very passive. Black is slightly better and went on to win the game.}) *

