1. e4 c5 2. b3 ({White fianchettoes the queen's bishop. There are some strong grandmasters who have specialized in this sideline and use it mainly in blitz and rapid chess, such as Durarbayli, Gelashvili, Chigaev and Morozevich. However, compared to the delayed fianchetto} 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {, Black has considerably more freedom here.}) 2... d6 {Against almost all Anti-Sicilians I recommend a setup with ... e7 -e6 , but here I would like to make an exception. If Black sets up with ... e7 -e6 and later ...Be7 , the white bishop will exert unpleasant pressure against the kingside from b2 .} ({With} 2... d6 {, we aim for a setup that neutralizes the b2 -bishop: ...Nf6 , ...g7-g6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . The black king is then very safe. d6 serves to prepare for ...Nf6 by defending against e4-e5 . A good alternative is the direct g6} 3. Bb2 Nf6 {. Nf6 allows} 4. e5 {.}) 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({To my taste, it is still too early for} 3... e5 {, with which Black could try to shut the b2 -bishop out of the game. Since the knight on g1 is not yet developed, White can fight for the long diagonal with} 4. f4 $1 {.}) 4. Nc3 ({The other main line besides} 4. Bb5+ {.}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {is more accurate than the immediate g6 , against which White can react with} 5. Nd5 {. With our move we wait for White's next move and can then decide on the best setup.}) 5. f4 {White first increases control over the center and only then develops the knight.} g6 6. Nd5 ({Inaccurate. White should start with} 6. Bb5 Bd7 {and only then play} 7. Nd5 {.}) 6... Bg7 7. Nxf6+ exf6 {Black will soon build up pressure against the e4 -pawn: ... O-O and ... Re8 . Then the pawn breaks ... f6 - f5 and ... d6 - d5 are in the air.} (7... Bxf6 {is also good.}) 8. Bb5 ({The 12-year-old Maxime Vachier-Lagrave was once confronted with} 8. Bc4 {. After} O-O 9. Ne2 Re8 10. d3 {,} Bg4 {would have led to a black advantage, e.g.} 11. O-O f5 {. Black combines pressure along the e-file with play against the c4 -bishop.}) 8... O-O {This is the difference to Bb5 : the doubling of the c-pawn is no longer dangerous, so Black saves the tempo of ...Bd7 .} 9. Bxc6 ({After} 9. Ne2 {Black could evade the exchange with} Ne7 $5 {, after which the b5 -bishop is prone to attack.}) 9... bxc6 10. Qf3 ({Or} 10. Ne2 f5 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 {.}) 10... Re8 {The pawn on e4 comes under attack. Black is threatening ... f6 - f5 or ... d6 - d5 .} 11. Ne2 d5 ({An improvement over Velickovic-Ivanisevic, 2008, where the more modest} 11... f5 {was played.}) 12. exd5 ({White can't afford that. The lesser evil was the pawn sacrifice} 12. O-O {.}) 12... Ba6 13. d3 ({Or} 13. c4 cxd5 {and White can't avoid losing material.}) 13... Qa5+ 14. Kf2 (14. Kd1 cxd5 {. Black will soon open the position with ...c5-c4 .}) 14... cxd5 ({Qxd5? fails to} 14... Qd2 15. Rhe1 Qxc2 {.}) ({The spectacular} 14... c4 $1 {with the idea} 15. dxc4 Qb6+ {is possibly even stronger, but the text move is simpler. Black wins back the pawn and dominates the position. Black wants to double the rooks on the e-file, while also threatening ...c5-c4 or ... Qb6 . The white king is far from safe.}) *

