1. e4 c5 2. b3 ({White fianchettoes the queen's bishop. There are some strong grandmasters who have specialized in this sideline and use it mainly in blitz and rapid chess, such as Durarbayli, Gelashvili, Chigaev and Morozevich. However, compared to the delayed fianchetto} 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {, Black has considerably more freedom here.}) 2... d6 {Against almost all Anti-Sicilians I recommend a setup with ... e7 -e6 , but here I would like to make an exception. If Black sets up with ... e7 -e6 and later ...Be7 , the white bishop will exert unpleasant pressure against the kingside from b2 .} ({With} 2... d6 {, we aim for a setup that neutralizes the b2 -bishop: ...Nf6 , ...g7-g6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . The black king is then very safe. d6 serves to prepare for ...Nf6 by defending against e4-e5 . A good alternative is the direct g6} 3. Bb2 Nf6 {. Nf6 allows} 4. e5 {.}) 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({To my taste, it is still too early for} 3... e5 {, with which Black could try to shut the b2 -bishop out of the game. Since the knight on g1 is not yet developed, White can fight for the long diagonal with} 4. f4 $1 {.}) 4. Nc3 ({The other main line besides} 4. Bb5+ {.}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {is more accurate than the immediate g6 , against which White can react with} 5. Nd5 {. With our move we wait for White's next move and can then decide on the best setup.}) 5. f4 {White first increases control over the center and only then develops the knight.} g6 6. Nf3 ({This leads to problems for White. White usually plays} 6. Bb5 {. We consider the position after} Bd7 {via the move order Bb5 Bd7 f4 g6 .}) 6... Bg7 {Now ... Nxe4 is a threat. The bishop on b2 is unprotected.} 7. Qe2 ({This was played by GM Morozevich, among others. White wants to castle long. No better is} 7. Nd5 O-O 8. Nxf6+ exf6 {. The e4 -pawn will soon come under attack. After 5.Bb5 , we encounter a similar position , but this version is worse for White because the f1 -bishop has no good prospects.  In the game Bohm-Timman ,} 9. Bd3 d5 $1 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Be2 Bf5 {( Nxd5∓ )} 12. c4 Nc2+ 13. Kf2 Nxa1 {followed. Timman later converted his material advantage into a full point.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O-O e5 {A novelty. Black secures control of d4 and takes the b2 -bishop out of the fight for the time being. Black will play for a queenside attack with ... a7 - a6 , ... b7 - b5 and ... Nd4 . White's position is not enviable, as their piece setup is inharmonious and I don't see a good plan.} *

