1. e4 c5 2. b3 ({White fianchettoes the queen's bishop. There are some strong grandmasters who have specialized in this sideline and use it mainly in blitz and rapid chess, such as Durarbayli, Gelashvili, Chigaev and Morozevich. However, compared to the delayed fianchetto} 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {, Black has considerably more freedom here.}) 2... d6 {Against almost all Anti-Sicilians I recommend a setup with ... e7 -e6 , but here I would like to make an exception. If Black sets up with ... e7 -e6 and later ...Be7 , the white bishop will exert unpleasant pressure against the kingside from b2 .} ({With} 2... d6 {, we aim for a setup that neutralizes the b2 -bishop: ...Nf6 , ...g7-g6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . The black king is then very safe. d6 serves to prepare for ...Nf6 by defending against e4-e5 . A good alternative is the direct g6} 3. Bb2 Nf6 {. Nf6 allows} 4. e5 {.}) 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({To my taste, it is still too early for} 3... e5 {, with which Black could try to shut the b2 -bishop out of the game. Since the knight on g1 is not yet developed, White can fight for the long diagonal with} 4. f4 $1 {.}) 4. Nc3 ({The other main line besides} 4. Bb5+ {.}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {is more accurate than the immediate g6 , against which White can react with} 5. Nd5 {. With our move we wait for White's next move and can then decide on the best setup.}) 5. Nf3 ({This position is more often reached via other move orders, such as e4 c5} 5. Nf3 {Nc6 b3 d6 Bb2 Nf6 Nc3 .}) 5... e5 {This preempts a possible d2 - d4 , because this square is now firmly under Black's control. The b2 -bishop is now biting on granite. Black exploits the fact that White has blocked the f-pawn with 5.Nf3 and can no longer attack the black center.} 6. Bc4 ({The most frequent move. White is threatening Ng5 .} 6. Bb5 {would lead to a similar position after} Be7 {. Black could alternatively develop the bishop to g7 , which is not possible with the text move.}) 6... Be7 {Now Ng5 can be answered with O-O .} 7. h3 ({A useful move that takes ...Bg4 out of the position. White could also play} 7. O-O {first.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O a6 {Black wants to win space on the queenside with ... b7 - b5 .} 9. a4 Rb8 10. Re1 Bd7 {The last two moves have also served to prepare ... b7 - b5 . In order to finally carry out this advance, however, even further preparation is necessary, for example with ... Nb4 or the knight maneuver ... Ne8 - c7 . The position is still balanced, but already more comfortable for Black. The bishop on b2 is passive and White has to deal with Black's ... b7 - b5 idea.} ({In Georgiev-Gaprindashvili , Nh2} 10... Nd4 {( Nb4!? ) Ng4?! followed. This leads to a weakening of White's king position. Nxg4 hxg4 Bh4! Clears the way for the queen to g5 .} 11. g3 h5 $1 {Out of the blue Black develops an attack.}) ({White must not accept the piece sacrifice: gxh4?} 10... Bg4 11. Be2 {Nxe2+ Nxe2 Qxh4-+ White is defenseless against the threat ...Bf3 .}) ({gxh5 Qg5 Re3 The former world champion could now have developed a strong attack with} 10... Kh8 {. Black is threatening to open lines with ...f7-f5 or ...g7-g6 .}) *

