1. e4 c5 2. b3 ({White fianchettoes the queen's bishop. There are some strong grandmasters who have specialized in this sideline and use it mainly in blitz and rapid chess, such as Durarbayli, Gelashvili, Chigaev and Morozevich. However, compared to the delayed fianchetto} 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {, Black has considerably more freedom here.}) 2... d6 {Against almost all Anti-Sicilians I recommend a setup with ... e7 -e6 , but here I would like to make an exception. If Black sets up with ... e7 -e6 and later ...Be7 , the white bishop will exert unpleasant pressure against the kingside from b2 .} ({With} 2... d6 {, we aim for a setup that neutralizes the b2 -bishop: ...Nf6 , ...g7-g6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . The black king is then very safe. d6 serves to prepare for ...Nf6 by defending against e4-e5 . A good alternative is the direct g6} 3. Bb2 Nf6 {. Nf6 allows} 4. e5 {.}) 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({To my taste, it is still too early for} 3... e5 {, with which Black could try to shut the b2 -bishop out of the game. Since the knight on g1 is not yet developed, White can fight for the long diagonal with} 4. f4 $1 {.}) 4. Nc3 ({The other main line besides} 4. Bb5+ {.}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {is more accurate than the immediate g6 , against which White can react with} 5. Nd5 {. With our move we wait for White's next move and can then decide on the best setup.}) 5. Bb5 {The most common continuation. White wants to capture on c6 and damage our pawn structure. The light-squared bishop otherwise has few active prospects in this pawn structure.} Bd7 {We should keep the pawn structure intact. Otherwise the black pawns on the queenside would be rather immobile.} 6. f4 {White first wants to increase control of the center and only then develop the knight to f3 .} ({After} 6. Nf3 e5 $1 {the game develops similarly to the line starting with Nf3 e5 .}) 6... g6 {Now is the right time to develop the kingside.} 7. Nd5 {White still manages to provoke a double pawn – not on the queenside, but on the kingside.} Bg7 8. Nxf6+ Bxf6 (8... exf6 {with subsequent castling and ...f6-f5 leads to similar play. Gusain-Gopal .}) 9. Bxf6 exf6 {The double pawn does not cause Black any problems, on the contrary, it is an additional protector of the king position after castling. Besides, Black has the pawn break ... f6 - f5 . For White, it is not beneficial that the f-pawn is already on f4 . Not only is it itself tactically vulnerable, but its colleague on e4 is also less well protected and e3 can become weak once White later moves the d-pawn. Black has the slightly better chances. Buksa-Beydullayeva .} *

