1. e4 c5 2. b3 ({White fianchettoes the queen's bishop. There are some strong grandmasters who have specialized in this sideline and use it mainly in blitz and rapid chess, such as Durarbayli, Gelashvili, Chigaev and Morozevich. However, compared to the delayed fianchetto} 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {, Black has considerably more freedom here.}) 2... d6 {Against almost all Anti-Sicilians I recommend a setup with ... e7 -e6 , but here I would like to make an exception. If Black sets up with ... e7 -e6 and later ...Be7 , the white bishop will exert unpleasant pressure against the kingside from b2 .} ({With} 2... d6 {, we aim for a setup that neutralizes the b2 -bishop: ...Nf6 , ...g7-g6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . The black king is then very safe. d6 serves to prepare for ...Nf6 by defending against e4-e5 . A good alternative is the direct g6} 3. Bb2 Nf6 {. Nf6 allows} 4. e5 {.}) 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({To my taste, it is still too early for} 3... e5 {, with which Black could try to shut the b2 -bishop out of the game. Since the knight on g1 is not yet developed, White can fight for the long diagonal with} 4. f4 $1 {.}) 4. Nc3 ({The other main line besides} 4. Bb5+ {.}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {is more accurate than the immediate g6 , against which White can react with} 5. Nd5 {. With our move we wait for White's next move and can then decide on the best setup.}) 5. Bb5 {The most common continuation. White wants to capture on c6 and damage our pawn structure. The light-squared bishop otherwise has few active prospects in this pawn structure.} Bd7 {We should keep the pawn structure intact. Otherwise the black pawns on the queenside would be rather immobile.} 6. f4 {White first wants to increase control of the center and only then develop the knight to f3 .} ({After} 6. Nf3 e5 $1 {the game develops similarly to the line starting with Nf3 e5 .}) 6... g6 {Now is the right time to develop the kingside.} 7. Bxc6 ({White wants to continue with Qe2 and long castling. In preparation, the exchange is necessary so that Black does not have ...Nd4 .} 7. Nf3 Bg7 {gives Black comfortable play. Specifically, ...Nxe4 is a threat. After White has defended the pawn, Black castles and has the more harmonious setup.}) 7... Bxc6 8. Qe2 Bg7 9. O-O-O {Black had been threatening ... Nxe4 , but now the b2 -bishop is protected. The aggressive white setup is very successful in practice and scores almost 80% according to my database. However, analysis shows that with accurate play it is actually Black who is in control.} O-O 10. Nf3 {White is threatening d2 - d4 . After that it would be difficult for Black to get counterplay on the queenside.} b5 {Black must not lose any time. ... b5 - b4 is threatening to win the e4 -pawn.} 11. e5 (11. Nxb5 $6 Bxe4 12. Bxf6 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {( Qxe7? fails to Bxd1 Qxd8 Rfxd8 Bxd8 Be2!-+ , winning a piece.)} Bxf6 {is good for Black. The black king is safer than its white counterpart.}) 11... Nh5 12. Qe3 ({White defends the f4 -pawn and is threatening to win the knight on h5 with g2-g4 . In Delgado Ramirez-Cuartas ,} 12. g3 b4 $6 13. Ne4 a5 14. d4 c4 $2 15. d5 c3 16. Bxc3 bxc3 17. dxc6 {followed with a winning position for White. Instead, Black could have gained an advantage with c4 , because now a move of the d-pawn will be met with ...b5-b4 and ...c4-c3 .}) 12... Qc8 {Black prevents g2 - g4 and threatens to win a pawn with ... Qg4 .} (12... Qd7 {follows the same idea and has been played in some games, but the queen is worse on d7 : With the queen on c8 , the pawn break ...f7-f6 is sometimes a good idea. If the queen were on d7 , White could respond with e5-e6 , gaining a tempo.}) 13. Ne2 ({Prophylactically defends the f4 -pawn. White is now ready for d2-d4 again. In the correspondence game Kahl-Mesquita ,} 13. Ne4 {followed. After} Bxe4 $1 14. Qxe4 a5 {and a subsequent ...a5-a4 , Black gets a dangerous attack on the queenside, while White has not yet achieved much on the kingside.}) ({After} 13. d4 {, the complications are good for Black:} Bh6 14. Ne2 {( g3? loses material because of} cxd4 15. Rxd4 dxe5 {and White cannot recapture.) Nxf4!} 16. Kb1 {(} Nxf4 {Qg4∓ wins back the piece. Black keeps an extra pawn.) Bxf3! gxf3 dxe5 dxe5 Nxe2 Qxh6 Qf5∓ White does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 13... Bh6 {Black maintains the pressure. Once again, ... Qg4 is threatening to win a pawn. Black also wants to attack on the queenside with ... a7 - a5 - a4 . The position remains very complicated, but White has the bigger problems to solve.} ({A ) If White defends against the threat of ...Qg4 with Rhf1 , then} 13... f6 $1 {is strong.} 14. e6 ({(After the exchange} 14. exd6 exd6 {the black king is very safe, while White is soon exposed to an attack after ...a7-a5-a4 .)})) ({Ng7⩱ Black wins the pawn on e6 . B ) After Kb1} 13... Qg4 {, White loses a pawn, e.g.} 14. Rhg1 Nxf4 {or} 15. d4 Qxg2 {. But not} 16. Nxf4 $2 {exd6 exd6} d5 {Bxd5 Nxf4 Bxf4} 17. Qc3 {followed by Rxd5 .}) *

