1. e4 c5 2. b3 ({White fianchettoes the queen's bishop. There are some strong grandmasters who have specialized in this sideline and use it mainly in blitz and rapid chess, such as Durarbayli, Gelashvili, Chigaev and Morozevich. However, compared to the delayed fianchetto} 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 {, Black has considerably more freedom here.}) 2... d6 {Against almost all Anti-Sicilians I recommend a setup with ... e7 -e6 , but here I would like to make an exception. If Black sets up with ... e7 -e6 and later ...Be7 , the white bishop will exert unpleasant pressure against the kingside from b2 .} ({With} 2... d6 {, we aim for a setup that neutralizes the b2 -bishop: ...Nf6 , ...g7-g6 , ...Bg7 and ...O-O . The black king is then very safe. d6 serves to prepare for ...Nf6 by defending against e4-e5 . A good alternative is the direct g6} 3. Bb2 Nf6 {. Nf6 allows} 4. e5 {.}) 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({To my taste, it is still too early for} 3... e5 {, with which Black could try to shut the b2 -bishop out of the game. Since the knight on g1 is not yet developed, White can fight for the long diagonal with} 4. f4 $1 {.}) 4. Bb5+ ({The bishop check is favored by Georgian GMs Gelashvili and Paichadze, who are experts on the 2.b3 system. This move ensures that White can exchange the bishop, preventing it from being passively locked behind a pawn chain. Along with} 4. Nc3 {, Bb5+ is one of the main moves.  The doubling of pawns after Bxf6 exf6 is not to be feared, e.g. Nc3} g6 {. Black wants to continue with ...Bg7 , ...O-O and ...f7-f5 . The bishop pair gives Black slightly better chances.}) 4... Nbd7 ({More ambitious than} 4... Bd7 {. White will probably have to exchange the bishop for the knight later, giving Black the bishop pair. Nc6 allows White to damage our queenside pawn structure with} 5. Bc6 bxc6 {, which carries strategic risks for Black. Bd7 Bxd7+ Qxd7 is also playable. (Weaker is Nbxd7} 6. Qe2 {, after which White can attack on the kingside with f2-f4 and g2-g4 .) White now either plays d3 and thus maintains the closed character of the position, or plays against the black pawn structure with Bxf6 gxf6 Qh5 Spassky-Huebner .}) 5. d3 {This reliably defends the e4 -pawn and the knight on b1 can now be developed to d2 .} g6 {Here, too, the bishop is best placed on g7 .} 6. Bxd7+ ({After d2-d3 the light-squared bishop is short on good squares. White should therefore not wait too long with the exchange, because once the black knight can move away from d7 , the bishop is in trouble, e.g. after} 6. Ne2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. f4 $6 {, ( Bxd7! )} Nb6 $1 {followed by ...a7-a6 would be good for Black.}) 6... Bxd7 7. f4 {White gains space, increases control over e5 and lays the foundation for a later attack on the kingside. Play is reminiscent of the Grand Prix Attack.} Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O b5 {Black's chances lie on the queenside. The aim is to gain space and to open files.} 10. c4 ({White wants to avoid the c-pawn becoming backward after a future ...b5-b4 . After} 10. Qe1 {(with the idea Qh4 and f4-f5 ) Black continues with} a5 {and a5-a4 . An attack on the kingside is not in sight and Black is making significant progress on the queenside.}) 10... b4 ({A novelty.} 10... a5 {( Gelashvili-Fedorov ) or bxc4 ( Gelashvili-Zinchenko ) are also promising continuations. With} 11. b4 {, Black takes control of c3 and plans the advance of the a-pawn. It could go as far as a3 and drive the white bishop off the long diagonal, or capture on b3 to open the a-file. Black can play not only on the queenside, but also in the center. The pawn break ...e7-e5 deserves particular attention. After fxe5 Black wins back the pawn with ...Ng4 . Another way to open up the position is ...f7-f5 . This can be prepared, for example, by ...Bh6 and ...Nh5 . Black has the slightly better chances here.}) ({Nbd2 loses a pawn:} 10... Nxe4 $5 {( a5 is also good)} 11. Bxg7 Nd2 12. Bxf8 $2 {( Qxd2 Kxg7⩱ )} Nxf1 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Kxf1 Qf6 {and the pawn f4 falls, because} 15. g3 $2 {is out of the question due to} Bh3+ 16. Kg1 Qb2 {.}) ({a4 With this, White is able to stop Black's play on the queenside, but Black has enough other trumps, e.g.} 10... e5 $5 11. fxe5 Ng4 {and the pawn on d3 becomes prone to attack.}) ({After Qe2 ,} 10... Bh6 $1 {is strong.} 11. f5 {(White does not manage to keep their structure intact: g3 Bh3! Re1} e5 $1 {fxe5 Ng4∓ Besides ...dxe5 , ...Be3+ is a threat.) Nh5 Next, Black can continue with ...Nf4 or ...e7-e6 .}) *

