1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {The drawback of this early bishop move is obvious: The bishop can be attacked by ... e7 - e6 followed by ... d7 - d5 or ... a7 - a6 followed by ... b7 - b5 .} e6 {The central advance ... d7 - d5 , one of Black's key ideas in this repertoire, would now come with tempo. In addition, the black e-pawn restricts the c4 -bishop, which now faces a solid bulwark of black pawns.} 3. Nf3 ({This position is also reached via the move order e4 c5} 3. Nf3 {e6 Bc4 .}) 3... a6 ({This prepares ...b7-b5 , but the central advance ...d7-d5 now also gains strength, as White can no longer respond with Bb5+ . After} 3... a6 {Black scores an astonishing 80%! Objectively, however, the position remains balanced. The good statistics are probably because the bishop development to c4 is often chosen by inexperienced players. The immediate d5 is also playable, but afterwards White can play against the isolated pawn d5 with exd5 exd5} 4. Bb5 Nc6 5. d4 {and a subsequent exchange on c5 .}) 4. d4 {The transition to the Open Sicilian comes with the loss of a tempo.} b5 5. Be2 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bb7 {The result is a Kan Sicilian with a tempo less for White. Black has comfortable play.} *

