1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {The drawback of this early bishop move is obvious: The bishop can be attacked by ... e7 - e6 followed by ... d7 - d5 or ... a7 - a6 followed by ... b7 - b5 .} e6 {The central advance ... d7 - d5 , one of Black's key ideas in this repertoire, would now come with tempo. In addition, the black e-pawn restricts the c4 -bishop, which now faces a solid bulwark of black pawns.} 3. Nf3 ({This position is also reached via the move order e4 c5} 3. Nf3 {e6 Bc4 .}) 3... a6 ({This prepares ...b7-b5 , but the central advance ...d7-d5 now also gains strength, as White can no longer respond with Bb5+ . After} 3... a6 {Black scores an astonishing 80%! Objectively, however, the position remains balanced. The good statistics are probably because the bishop development to c4 is often chosen by inexperienced players. The immediate d5 is also playable, but afterwards White can play against the isolated pawn d5 with exd5 exd5} 4. Bb5 Nc6 5. d4 {and a subsequent exchange on c5 .}) 4. O-O (4. a4 {This defends against ...b7-b5 , but not against} d5 {. After} 5. exd5 exd5 6. Be2 Nf6 {Black has slightly better chances. White has lost too much time.}) 4... b5 5. Be2 Bb7 6. d3 Nc6 {While Black has only made sensible moves, White has moved the bishop twice and thus lost a tempo. On e2 the bishop is not even well placed. Black has a comfortable game. A possible setup is ... d7 - d6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O .} *

