1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {The drawback of this early bishop move is obvious: The bishop can be attacked by ... e7 - e6 followed by ... d7 - d5 or ... a7 - a6 followed by ... b7 - b5 .} e6 {The central advance ... d7 - d5 , one of Black's key ideas in this repertoire, would now come with tempo. In addition, the black e-pawn restricts the c4 -bishop, which now faces a solid bulwark of black pawns.} 3. Nc3 ({White prevents ...d7-d5 , at least temporarily. The position can also result from the move order e4 c5} 3. Nc3 {e6 Bc4 .}) 3... a6 {Prepares an attack from the other side.} 4. a3 {Prepares the retreat of the bishop to a2 . Black now obtains an advantage with natural developing moves.} b5 5. Ba2 Bb7 6. d3 Nc6 7. Nf3 Nf6 {Next comes ... Be7 or... Bd6 and ... O-O . White has not only lost time by moving the bishop twice but has placed it in a passive position.} *

