1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {The drawback of this early bishop move is obvious: The bishop can be attacked by ... e7 - e6 followed by ... d7 - d5 or ... a7 - a6 followed by ... b7 - b5 .} e6 {The central advance ... d7 - d5 , one of Black's key ideas in this repertoire, would now come with tempo. In addition, the black e-pawn restricts the c4 -bishop, which now faces a solid bulwark of black pawns.} 3. Nc3 ({White prevents ...d7-d5 , at least temporarily. The position can also result from the move order e4 c5} 3. Nc3 {e6 Bc4 .}) 3... a6 {Prepares an attack from the other side.} 4. a4 ({White prevents the expansion on the queenside. However, inserting the moves of the a-pawns is favorable for Black: b5 is no longer accessible to the white pieces and b4 could later prove useful for a black knight.} 4. Nf3 b5 5. Be2 Bb7 {Black has won some time and is slightly better. ...b5-b4 is a threat, which would win a pawn.}) 4... Nc6 ({Black takes control of the central squares d4 and e5 . Black could also start with} 4... Nf6 {.}) 5. f4 {White first wants to win space, before developing the knight to f3 . The f-pawn could later go to f5 and put pressure on e6 , or support e4 - e5 . However, this is all wishful thinking. White lacks the time to realize aggressive plans. The move of the f-pawn proves to be weakening.} Nf6 (5... Nge7 {is also good but obstructs the f8 -bishop. Black is now threatening ...d7-d5 .}) 6. e5 (6. d3 d5 {is also better for Black:} 7. Ba2 {( Bb3} Nd4 {) b5!? Black is threatening ...b5-b4 , winning the e4 -pawn. ( Be7⩱ )} 8. e5 Nd7 {The bishop is out of play on a2 and Black has already achieved a lot on the queenside. White is facing a difficult defense. ( axb5? axb5} 9. Nb5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 c4 {followed by ...d5-d4 is winning for Black.)}) 6... d5 {A typical idea, which is mainly known from 1.e4 e5 openings. The counterattack on the bishop allows Black to carry out the central advance without losing time.} 7. Be2 (7. Ba2 {Here the bishop doesn't have any prospects.} Nd7 {followed by ...f7-f6 .}) (7. exd6 Bxd6 {White has managed to keep the bishop on c4 for the time being, but now the drawbacks of f2-f4 , which has left weaknesses in the white camp, are visible. Black can now either align their pieces against the white kingside ( ...b7-b6 , ...Bb7 , ...e6-e5 ) or play against the c4 -bishop ( ...Rb8 , ...Nd4 , ...b7-b5 ).}) 7... Nd7 8. Nf3 f6 ({Black has achieved the dream version of a French pawn structure in which White hasn't even gotten to d2-d4 . If White exchanges on f6 , the break ...e6-e5 could open the position in Black's favor. The best option is probably the pawn sacrifice O-O , which Black can either accept or first continue development with} 8... Be7 {, in both cases with an advantage.}) *

