1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {The drawback of this early bishop move is obvious: The bishop can be attacked by ... e7 - e6 followed by ... d7 - d5 or ... a7 - a6 followed by ... b7 - b5 .} e6 {The central advance ... d7 - d5 , one of Black's key ideas in this repertoire, would now come with tempo. In addition, the black e-pawn restricts the c4 -bishop, which now faces a solid bulwark of black pawns.} 3. Nc3 ({White prevents ...d7-d5 , at least temporarily. The position can also result from the move order e4 c5} 3. Nc3 {e6 Bc4 .}) 3... a6 {Prepares an attack from the other side.} 4. a4 ({White prevents the expansion on the queenside. However, inserting the moves of the a-pawns is favorable for Black: b5 is no longer accessible to the white pieces and b4 could later prove useful for a black knight.} 4. Nf3 b5 5. Be2 Bb7 {Black has won some time and is slightly better. ...b5-b4 is a threat, which would win a pawn.}) 4... Nc6 ({Black takes control of the central squares d4 and e5 . Black could also start with} 4... Nf6 {.}) 5. Nf3 Nf6 {Once again Black is ready for ... d7 - d5 .} 6. d3 d5 7. exd5 {A concession: Now the c8 -bishop can be developed freely. This is by far the most common move in practice.} exd5 8. Bb3 Be7 ({Black has freer play and more control in the center; moreover, the bishop on b3 is misplaced. White has big problems and scores less than 20% in practice. Or} 8... Be6 $5 {with the idea ...Qc7 and ...O-O-O .}) *

