1. e4 c5 2. Na3 ({GM Zvjaginsev played this unusual knight move in three games in the 2005 Russian Championship and thus introduced it into tournament practice at a high level. Since then, there have been many successors who have used the move as a surprise weapon, including former world champion Carlsen. White waits for Black's reaction and adjusts their play accordingly. Nc6 is met with} 2. Bb5 {, after which the game is reminiscent of the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3} Nc6 {Bb5 ), while after other moves, White usually plays c2-c3 in the style of the Alapin Variation. The knight is later brought back towards the center via c2 or c4 .}) 2... e6 ({There is no reason to deviate from our usual setup. Many other moves also give Black good play. The most common is} 2... Nc6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nc6 {It is clear that this is the best square for the knight. The other pieces, however, have various options. It is therefore useful to make their development dependent on the white setup.} 4. Bb5 {In the style of the Rossolimo Variation, White wants to exchange on c6 and damage the black pawn structure on the queenside.} Nge7 {Now Black could recapture with the knight on c6 .} 5. O-O a6 6. Be2 ({After} 6. Nc4 d5 7. Bxc6+ Nxc6 {( bxc6⩱ )} 8. exd5 exd5 9. Re1+ Be7 10. Nce5 O-O {the bishop pair gives Black slightly better chances. Georgiev-Spassov}) 6... d5 {Preempts White's d2 - d4 .} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. d4 Be7 {Black can finish development without interference. The position is equal.} *

