1. e4 c5 2. Na3 ({GM Zvjaginsev played this unusual knight move in three games in the 2005 Russian Championship and thus introduced it into tournament practice at a high level. Since then, there have been many successors who have used the move as a surprise weapon, including former world champion Carlsen. White waits for Black's reaction and adjusts their play accordingly. Nc6 is met with} 2. Bb5 {, after which the game is reminiscent of the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3} Nc6 {Bb5 ), while after other moves, White usually plays c2-c3 in the style of the Alapin Variation. The knight is later brought back towards the center via c2 or c4 .}) 2... e6 ({There is no reason to deviate from our usual setup. Many other moves also give Black good play. The most common is} 2... Nc6 {.}) 3. c3 {White prepares the occupation of the center with d2 - d4 and clears c2 for the knight.} Nc6 ({The knight controls the important central squares e5 and d4 . After} 3... d5 {White could go for the Alapin Sicilian with} 4. exd5 {, or try a version of the French Advance Variation with} e5 {.}) 4. Bb5 {White doesn't achieve anything with this.} Qc7 {Black protects the knight with the queen and thus avoids a weakening of their pawn structure.} 5. Nf3 a6 6. Bxc6 Qxc6 {With the bishop pair, Black has the better chances. The queenside can be developed with ... b7 - b5 and ... Bb7 , while on the kingside ... Nf6 and ... Be7 are the most natural.} *

