1. e4 c5 2. Na3 ({GM Zvjaginsev played this unusual knight move in three games in the 2005 Russian Championship and thus introduced it into tournament practice at a high level. Since then, there have been many successors who have used the move as a surprise weapon, including former world champion Carlsen. White waits for Black's reaction and adjusts their play accordingly. Nc6 is met with} 2. Bb5 {, after which the game is reminiscent of the Rossolimo Variation ( e4 c5 Nf3} Nc6 {Bb5 ), while after other moves, White usually plays c2-c3 in the style of the Alapin Variation. The knight is later brought back towards the center via c2 or c4 .}) 2... e6 ({There is no reason to deviate from our usual setup. Many other moves also give Black good play. The most common is} 2... Nc6 {.}) 3. c3 {White prepares the occupation of the center with d2 - d4 and clears c2 for the knight.} Nc6 ({The knight controls the important central squares e5 and d4 . After} 3... d5 {White could go for the Alapin Sicilian with} 4. exd5 {, or try a version of the French Advance Variation with} e5 {.}) 4. Nf3 ({White is not yet ready for} 4. d4 $6 {, because after} cxd4 5. cxd4 Nf6 {the knight on a3 is missing in the defense of the center. E.g.} 6. e5 {(or f3} Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bxa3 8. bxa3 Nxd4 {)} 9. Bb4 {Bd2 Bxa3 bxa3} Ne4 {and Black has the better pawn structure.}) 4... Nf6 ({This invites a transposition to the Alapin Sicilian with} 4... Nf6 {, where the early knight development to a3 is not critical.}) 5. e5 ({After the alternative} 5. d3 {, Black has many good continuations, e.g.} d5 6. e5 Nd7 7. d4 {. White plays a French with a minus tempo.} f6 8. exf6 Nxf6 {Lagarde-Kirk . I also like the untested Be7 , which does not yet commit Black to either the double or the single step of the d-pawn.}) 5... Nd5 ({The position is more often reached via the Alapin Sicilian: e4 c5 c3 Nf6 e5} 5... Nd5 {Nf3 Nc6 Na3 e6 . There, 5.Na3 is a rare sideline.}) 6. Nc4 {The knight attacks the weakened d6 -square and defends the e5 -pawn, but it is not very stable on c4 .} Qc7 {The queen attacks the e5 -pawn. ... b7 - b5 is a threat.} 7. a4 {White fortifies the knight on c4 . However, the whole operation is very time-consuming.} b6 {Prepares the development of the c8 -bishop.} 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d6 ({Other moves such as} 9... Bb7 {or Be7 also give Black good play. d6 exchanges the bishop pair for the better pawn structure.}) 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Nxd6+ Qxd6 {The d4 -pawn and the b4 -square are weak, which gives Black more than sufficient compensation for the bishop pair.} *

