1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {A flexible move. White could later transition to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or develop the bishop to g2 as in the Closed Sicilian.} e6 ({This is the simplest solution for our repertoire. We make sure that after d4 cxd4 Nxd4 we end up in an e6 -Sicilian. We also prepare ...d7-d5 . Alternatively, Black could try to exploit the white move order by attacking the center directly:} 2... Nf6 $5 3. Nbc3 d5 $1 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Nxd5 Qxd5 {.}) 3. g3 ({The game is now reminiscent of the Closed Sicilian, but some particularities tend to weigh in Black's favor. We examine the position after} 3. Nbc3 {via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 Nge2 , while d4 cxd4 Nxd4 transposes to the Open Sicilian.}) 3... d5 4. Bg2 ({In contrast to the Closed Sicilian, White does not have the possibility} 4. exd5 $6 {because after} Qxd5 $1 {the rook on h1 is attacked.}) 4... dxe4 ({White will lose time to win back the pawn. Meanwhile, Black can transfer the bishop to c6 , where it neutralizes the strong white bishop. After} 4... Nf6 {White could go for an isolated queen's pawn position with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {.}) 5. Bxe4 {This meets a surprising refutation.} Nf6 6. Bg2 Bd7 {The fight for the light squares is worth a pawn and an exchange. Black wants to trade light-squared bishops. This strong move has only been played once.} 7. Bxb7 {Accepting the sacrifice is very risky for White.} Nc6 {The bishop on b7 won't find its way back now.} 8. O-O {White should spurn the exchange.} Rb8 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 {The weakened light squares near the king are a cause for concern for White.} 10. d3 h5 {Black wants to open the h-file with ... h5 - h4 - hxg3 .} 11. h4 e5 {One of many good moves. The idea is ... Qd7 followed by ... Qh3 . Black's attack is very powerful.} *

