1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {A flexible move. White could later transition to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or develop the bishop to g2 as in the Closed Sicilian.} e6 ({This is the simplest solution for our repertoire. We make sure that after d4 cxd4 Nxd4 we end up in an e6 -Sicilian. We also prepare ...d7-d5 . Alternatively, Black could try to exploit the white move order by attacking the center directly:} 2... Nf6 $5 3. Nbc3 d5 $1 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Nxd5 Qxd5 {.}) 3. g3 ({The game is now reminiscent of the Closed Sicilian, but some particularities tend to weigh in Black's favor. We examine the position after} 3. Nbc3 {via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 Nge2 , while d4 cxd4 Nxd4 transposes to the Open Sicilian.}) 3... d5 4. Bg2 ({In contrast to the Closed Sicilian, White does not have the possibility} 4. exd5 $6 {because after} Qxd5 $1 {the rook on h1 is attacked.}) 4... dxe4 ({White will lose time to win back the pawn. Meanwhile, Black can transfer the bishop to c6 , where it neutralizes the strong white bishop. After} 4... Nf6 {White could go for an isolated queen's pawn position with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {.}) 5. Bxe4 {This meets a surprising refutation.} Nf6 6. Bg2 Bd7 {The fight for the light squares is worth a pawn and an exchange. Black wants to trade light-squared bishops. This strong move has only been played once.} 7. O-O ({Stockfish recommends} 7. Ng1 $5 Bc6 8. Nf3 {. This illustrates a fundamental problem with White's setup: If the light-squared bishops are traded, White's king position is weakened. Combining g2-g3 with the development of the king's knight to e2 is therefore risky.} g5 $1 9. h3 h5 {Here, too, White does not succeed in avoiding the exchange of bishops in the long run.}) 7... Bc6 ({Black is better. After the exchange of bishops, the white king is in danger, because the weakened light squares are insufficiently defended.  In the game Galliamova-Ghaem Maghami , d4 Bxg2 Kxg2} 7... Nc6 {dxc5 Bxc5 Qxd8+ Rxd8⩱ followed, after which Black gained pressure on the queenside. Even stronger was Qd5+! Kg1 Nc6 dxc5 Qf5! To fend off the attack, White has nothing better than Qd3 . After Qxd3 cxd3 Bxc5 the d3 -pawn is weak and Black has a huge advantage.}) *

