1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {A flexible move. White could later transition to the Open Sicilian with d2 - d4 , or develop the bishop to g2 as in the Closed Sicilian.} e6 ({This is the simplest solution for our repertoire. We make sure that after d4 cxd4 Nxd4 we end up in an e6 -Sicilian. We also prepare ...d7-d5 . Alternatively, Black could try to exploit the white move order by attacking the center directly:} 2... Nf6 $5 3. Nbc3 d5 $1 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Nxd5 Qxd5 {.}) 3. g3 ({The game is now reminiscent of the Closed Sicilian, but some particularities tend to weigh in Black's favor. We examine the position after} 3. Nbc3 {via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 Nge2 , while d4 cxd4 Nxd4 transposes to the Open Sicilian.}) 3... d5 4. Bg2 ({In contrast to the Closed Sicilian, White does not have the possibility} 4. exd5 $6 {because after} Qxd5 $1 {the rook on h1 is attacked.}) 4... dxe4 ({White will lose time to win back the pawn. Meanwhile, Black can transfer the bishop to c6 , where it neutralizes the strong white bishop. After} 4... Nf6 {White could go for an isolated queen's pawn position with} 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {.}) 5. Nbc3 {White better captures with the knight on e4 .} Bd7 ({It's not worth holding on to the extra pawn:} 5... f5 $6 6. d3 $1 exd3 7. Nf4 $5 {White has a big lead in development and Black has weaknesses on the e-file.}) 6. Nxe4 Bc6 {Black has succeeded in activating the light-squared bishop, which often remains passive in the ... e6 -Sicilian. ... f7 - f5 is threatening to win a piece.} 7. O-O Nf6 8. d3 ({The exchange} 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {works in Black's favor. Next, the bishops are exchanged, weakening White's king position slightly. Additionally, the black queen ties down the c1-bishop to the defense of the b2-pawn.}) 8... Be7 ({Black has equalized and can finish development without interference, for example with ...O-O , ...Nxe4 , and ...Nd7 .  In the game Popovic-Blomqvist , N2c3 followed, as on e2 , the knight was in the way of the major pieces. O-O Qe2} 8... Nd5 $5 {Black evades the exchange. The two white knights are competing for the same squares. If White exchanges on d5 , Black gains more control in the center. Rd1 Nd7 Nb1 This loses too much time. Black could now have gained an advantage with e5 followed by the maneuver ...Nc7-e6-d4 .}) *

