1. e4 c5 {In this chapter, we will look at different versions of White playing d2 - d4 and, after ... cxd4 , recapturing with the queen. While generally, the early development of the queen is not to be recommended, one possible idea is to go for quick queenside castling.} 2. d4 cxd4 3. Qxd4 {A favorite of the Russian grandmaster Shimanov, who likes to play this in blitz and rapid games.} Nc6 {Black wins a tempo with the attack on the queen.} 4. Qd1 {The most popular move, but rarely chosen by titled players. It is not clear what advantages White expects to gain compared with a normal Open Sicilian.} Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {Black has a lot of flexibility and could also choose a different setup. 5...e6 prepares the development of the f8 -bishop. One doesn't need to know much here, but it is helpful to remember that an early ... d7 - d5 is often not the best approach.} 6. Nf3 ({The position is also reached via e4 c5} 6. Nf3 {e6 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qd1 or e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} Nd4 {Nc6 Nf3 . It was already the subject of my course on the Sicilian Four Knights.}) 6... Bb4 {Now the threat is to capture the pawn on e4 followed by a quick ... d7 - d5 . White is already fighting for equality here.} 7. Bd3 Bxc3+ (7... d5 $6 {is the most popular move, but now White has the resource} 8. O-O {!} Bxc3 9. exd5 {, which gives them chances for a small advantage.}) 8. bxc3 e5 {This prevents White from playing e4 - e5 . Black has the more pleasant game here because there is a clear target: the weaknesses on the queenside. Possible next moves include ... O-O , ... d7 - d6 , ... Be6 , ... Na5 , and ... Rc8 .} *

