1. e4 c5 {In this chapter, we will look at different versions of White playing d2 - d4 and, after ... cxd4 , recapturing with the queen. While generally, the early development of the queen is not to be recommended, one possible idea is to go for quick queenside castling.} 2. d4 cxd4 3. Qxd4 {A favorite of the Russian grandmaster Shimanov, who likes to play this in blitz and rapid games.} Nc6 {Black wins a tempo with the attack on the queen.} 4. Qe3 {The queen is not particularly well-placed here. The idea may be to develop the bishop to b2 and castle queenside. However, White is not in time for this plan.} Nf6 {Black continues with normal developing moves and is now ready for ... d7 - d5 .} 5. Nc3 ({Increases control over d5 . After} 5. Nf3 {,} d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 {gives comfortable equality.}) 5... d5 ({This advance allows Black's forces to be activated. A good alternative is} 5... e6 {, which we analyze via the move order e4 c5 Nc3 e6 d4 cxd4} 6. Qd4 {Nc6 Qe3 Nf6 .}) 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. Nf3 Bf5 {Black has the luxury of not only being able to develop the light-squared bishop freely but also to attack a pawn in the process. The kingside can be developed with ... e7 - e5 . Their lead in development gives Black slightly better chances.} *

