1. e4 c5 {In this chapter, we will look at different versions of White playing d2 - d4 and, after ... cxd4 , recapturing with the queen. While generally, the early development of the queen is not to be recommended, one possible idea is to go for quick queenside castling.} 2. d4 cxd4 3. Qxd4 {A favorite of the Russian grandmaster Shimanov, who likes to play this in blitz and rapid games.} Nc6 {Black wins a tempo with the attack on the queen.} 4. Qd3 {Shimanov's choice, who used it to score a rapid chess victory against Magnus Carlsen, among others! White may castle long later. It's also sometimes useful for the queen to defend the e4 -pawn.} Nf6 ({In Shimanov-Carlsen , there followed} 4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. Nd5 {, which demonstrates one of White's ideas. The queen defends the pawn on e4 .}) 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bf4 ({White prepares castling long. On f4 the bishop has an eye on the weakened dark squares.} 6. Nf3 Qc7 {The queen is well placed here and prevents e4-e5 . Black can comfortably continue developing with ...Bc5 , ...d7-d6 , and ...O-O . ( Bb4 , Caruana's choice in a blitz game against Aronian, is playable as well.)}) 6... a6 {Prepares the development of the queenside with ... b7 - b5 .} 7. O-O-O ({The logical continuation.} 7. e5 $6 {is answered by} Nh5 {, after which the pawn e5 is weak. After} 8. Bd2 $6 Nb4 $1 {( Nxe5?} 9. Qe2 {) Qe4} f5 {follows, and White can no longer defend the c2 -pawn. After} 10. Nf3 b5 {e5 , Black can defend with Qc7 .}) 7... b5 8. e5 {After normal developing moves, Black is already better. The white setup lacks harmony and the kingside cannot be easily developed.} Qc7 9. Qf3 Ng8 {Black wants to attack on the queenside with ... Bb7 and ... Rc8 .} 10. Ne4 {White should play energetically.} Bb7 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 Qa5 13. Qg3 ({With this novelty, White preserves equal chances. In Skvortsov-Ter Sahakyan , there followed} 13. Kb1 $6 Nf6 {, after which Black has a lead in development and attacking chances on the queenside.}) 13... Kf8 14. Qb3 Nf6 ({Black is threatening ...Ne4 . White should now play Bd2 , e.g.} 14... Qd8 15. Kb1 Rc8 {with chances for both sides. The rook from h8 can be brought into play with ...h7-h5-h4 and ...Rh5 .}) *

