1. e4 c5 {In this chapter, we will look at different versions of White playing d2 - d4 and, after ... cxd4 , recapturing with the queen. While generally, the early development of the queen is not to be recommended, one possible idea is to go for quick queenside castling.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 {An Open Sicilian?} cxd4 4. Qxd4 {No, White deviates and takes with the queen. The following lines have already been part of my previous course on the Four Knights Sicilian. While against the Sicilian with d6 capturing with the queen is an interesting sideline, here it is less dangerous because Black can attack the white center by playing ...d7-d5 without losing a tempo.} Nc6 5. Qd1 ({The Latvian Grandmaster Viesturs Meijers has played this with success on a few occasions, using the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 Nc6} 5. Nc3 {. Of course, this cannot be critical for Black's setup as White simply loses time. One doesn't need to know much here, but it is helpful to remember that an early ...d7-d5 is often not the best approach.}) 5... Nf6 6. Bd3 ({This position can also be reached via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 d4 cxd4} 6. Nd4 {Nf6 Bd3 Nc6 . Now, Black has a wide choice. Nc3} Bb4+ {We analyze this via the move order e4 c5 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qd1 Nf6} 7. Nc3 {e6 Nf3 Bb4 .} e5 $2 {is a well-known mistake. Nxe5 Nxe5 Qa5+ Nc3 Qxe5+∓ gives Black a healthy extra pawn.}) 6... Bc5 ({I like this aggressive setup. The bishop targets the vulnerable f2 point, opening up tactical possibilities. After} 6... d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {( exd5 may be stronger here)} 8. O-O Be7 9. a3 {followed by c2-c4 , I slightly prefer White's position as they have the more active pieces.}) 7. O-O Qc7 {From here, the queen controls e5 . Additionally, ... Ng4 is now a possible motif.} 8. Nc3 a6 {This prevents Nb5 and is a useful move in general, as Black will often play ... b7 - b5 and develop the bishop to b7 . The position is equal, but more pleasant for Black to play. White's setup seems somewhat aimless.} 9. Bg5 (9. Qe2 {is the most common move, but that invites} Ng4 $1 {. Now the threat is ...Nd4 , winning the queen.} 10. g3 O-O {Black has good control of the central squares and is slightly better.}) 9... b5 ({Instead, Black can play} 9... Be7 {, but I don't think it's necessary. The exchange on f6 would give us the bishop pair and better control of the center, so it is nothing to fear.}) *

