1. e4 c5 {In this chapter, we will look at different versions of White playing d2 - d4 and, after ... cxd4 , recapturing with the queen. While generally, the early development of the queen is not to be recommended, one possible idea is to go for quick queenside castling.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 {An Open Sicilian?} cxd4 4. Qxd4 {No, White deviates and takes with the queen. The following lines have already been part of my previous course on the Four Knights Sicilian. While against the Sicilian with d6 capturing with the queen is an interesting sideline, here it is less dangerous because Black can attack the white center by playing ...d7-d5 without losing a tempo.} Nc6 5. Qe3 ({The queen is not particularly well-placed here. The idea may be to develop the bishop to b2 and castle queenside. However, White is not in time for this plan.} 5. Qd3 {I don't see the merits of this move, even though it was played by Aronian in a blitz game.} Nf6 6. Nc3 {After other moves, ...d7-d5 would be an option.} Qc7 {The queen is well-placed here and prevents e4-e5 . Black can comfortably continue developing with ...Bc5 , ...d7-d6 , and ...O-O . ( Bb4 , Caruana's choice against Aronian, is playable as well.)}) 5... Nf6 {Black continues with normal developing moves and is now ready for ... d7 - d5 .} 6. c4 ({With this setup, White wants to make ...d7-d5 harder to achieve. The more popular} 6. Nc3 {is covered via e4 c5 Nc3 e6 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qe3 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 6... Qb6 {An attack against the pawn on e4 , which would no longer be protected after a queen trade. Besides, there is the threat of ... Bc5 followed by ... Ng4 .} 7. Qxb6 ({Not a bad trade for Black, despite the weakening of the pawn structure: White's e-pawn is not easy to defend and the rook on a8 gets activated. If White instead protects the e-pawn with} 7. Nc3 {, Black starts an attack:} Bc5 8. Qd2 Ng4 {. Now White's best option is to go for the complications after} 9. Qg5 $1 {(but not Nd1} Nxf2 $1 {Nxf2 Bb4-+ ) Nxf2} 10. Qxg7 Rf8 11. Rg1 {, yet Black retains the slightly better chances, e.g. after ...Be3 .}) ({The other way to protect the e-pawn,} 7. Bd3 {, doesn't guarantee an equal game either. The simplest is} Qxe3+ 8. Bxe3 Ng4 9. Bd2 Nb4 {when White has to part with their pair of bishops.}) 7... axb6 8. Nc3 ({The alternatives are worse:} 8. Bd3 Nb4 9. Ke2 d5 $5 {(or Nxa2⩱ )}) (8. e5 Ng4 9. Bf4 Bc5 10. Bg3 Nb4 {, when White loses at least a pawn.}) 8... Bb4 {Renews the attack on e4 .} 9. Bd2 ({After} 9. Bd3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d6 {, Black gets good play against White's weakened queenside.}) 9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Nxe4 11. Bxg7 Rg8 12. Bh6 Nc5 {Black has the initiative. ... Nb4 is a threat.} 13. a3 e5 {Next, Black wants to develop the bishop by playing ... d7 - d6 and ... Bg4 . White is under pressure, as Black's pieces are more active.} *

