1. e4 c5 {In this chapter, we will look at different versions of White playing d2 - d4 and, after ... cxd4 , recapturing with the queen. While generally, the early development of the queen is not to be recommended, one possible idea is to go for quick queenside castling.} 2. Nc3 e6 3. d4 {This interesting move order is the recommendation of the popular Youtuber IM Levy Rozman in his The GothamChess 1.e4 Repertoire .} cxd4 4. Qxd4 ({Unlike in e4 c5 d4 cxd4} 4. Qxd4 {, here ...e7-e6 has already been played, which limits Black's options.}) 4... Nc6 5. Qe3 ({After 5.Qd1 or 5.Qd3 we play 5...Nf6 as well. Both positions are analyzed via the move order e4 c5 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nc6 and now either} 5. Qd1 Nf6 {Nc3 e6 or} 6. Qd3 {Nf6 Nc3 e6 .}) ({In contrast,} 5. Qe3 {has its significance, because after e4 c5 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qe3} Nf6 {Nc3 , I recommended the direct d5 – Black can play this without the preparatory ...e7-e6 .}) 5... Nf6 {The knight moves to its most natural square, increasing control of the center. Next, Black wants to prepare ... d7 - d5 .} 6. Bd2 {White prepares to castle queenside.} Be7 ({There was also nothing wrong with the direct} 6... d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {, which gives Black comfortable equality. By playing the text move, the pin of the e-pawn is first removed, allowing for the possibility of ...exd5 after ...d7-d5 and the subsequent exchange.}) 7. O-O-O {The most popular and consistent continuation.} d5 8. exd5 exd5 {Now it becomes evident that White's setup lacks harmony. White can no longer prevent ... d5 - d4 .} 9. Qg3 {After other moves, Black is better as well.} d4 ({An improvement over an online blitz game by Magnus Carlsen, in which he played the less precise} 9... O-O {first. After d4 , White is left with a shattered position. Black will castle next and then attack the white queenside with ...Be6 or ...Bf5 .}) *

