1. e4 c5 {In this chapter, we will look at different versions of White playing d2 - d4 and, after ... cxd4 , recapturing with the queen. While generally, the early development of the queen is not to be recommended, one possible idea is to go for quick queenside castling.} 2. Nc3 e6 3. d4 {This interesting move order is the recommendation of the popular Youtuber IM Levy Rozman in his The GothamChess 1.e4 Repertoire .} cxd4 4. Qxd4 ({Unlike in e4 c5 d4 cxd4} 4. Qxd4 {, here ...e7-e6 has already been played, which limits Black's options.}) 4... Nc6 5. Qe3 ({After 5.Qd1 or 5.Qd3 we play 5...Nf6 as well. Both positions are analyzed via the move order e4 c5 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nc6 and now either} 5. Qd1 Nf6 {Nc3 e6 or} 6. Qd3 {Nf6 Nc3 e6 .}) ({In contrast,} 5. Qe3 {has its significance, because after e4 c5 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qe3} Nf6 {Nc3 , I recommended the direct d5 – Black can play this without the preparatory ...e7-e6 .}) 5... Nf6 {The knight moves to its most natural square, increasing control of the center. Next, Black wants to prepare ... d7 - d5 .} 6. Nf3 ({White also increases their influence in the center. Now, Black has to reckon with the possibility of e4-e5 . The direct} 6. e5 {would have lost a pawn after} Ng4 {. If you have studied my course on the Sicilian Four Knights, you will already be familiar with this position, which we reach there via the move order e4 c5} 7. Nf3 {e6 d4 cxd4 Qxd4 Nc6 Qe3} Nf6 {.}) 6... Bb4 ({Black increases the pressure on the white center because the direct} 6... d5 {was not as strong due to} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Bd3 {.}) (6... d6 {allows} 7. b3 $5 {, as seen in the blitz game Aronian-Carlsen .}) 7. a3 {The recommendation of IM Lawrence Trent in his course The Dynamic 1.Nc3 - A Unique Repertoire . It makes sense to force the bishop to make a decision.} Ng4 ({The white queen is deflected from defending the knight. After} 7... Ba5 {, White continues with} 8. Bd2 {. If Black now follows my recommendation after 7.Bd2 by playing} d6 {, White can exert unpleasant pressure against the d6 -pawn, which is no longer defended by the bishop, with} 9. O-O-O O-O 10. Nb5 $1 {.}) (7... Bxc3+ {is answered by} 8. Qxc3 {. Since the queen has an eye on the pawn on g7 , Black cannot win the e4 -pawn.}) 8. Qf4 ({Worse is} 8. Qd3 Bc5 {.}) 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qf6 {Exchanging queens is essential; otherwise, White will develop a strong initiative on the dark squares.} 10. Qxf6 Nxf6 {In this queenless middlegame, the chances are evenly distributed. White has a strong pair of bishops but had to accept a weakened pawn structure on the queenside. Black will next focus on activating the bishop, either with ... e6 - e5 followed by a move of the d-pawn, or with ... b7 - b6 and ... Bb7 .} *

