[PlyCount "20"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Be2 {A very rare but quite poisonous move that has been played by some strong grandmasters in recent years. White focuses on development while keeping the option to transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 . Players aiming for the Taimanov Sicilian have no reason to worry about this move sequence. However, those intending to play the Kan Variation or the Four Knights Sicilian must sooner or later abandon the hope of transposing into familiar territory in the Open Sicilian. My recommendations are as follows:  ➤ If you aim for the Kan Sicilian, it is best to choose d5 . This continuation prevents a transposition to the Open Sicilian and is therefore suitable for proponents of other Sicilian systems as well.  ➤ Personally, I prefer Nc6 to d5 , so I recommend this to those who play the Taimanov Sicilian or the Four Knights Sicilian. The path then branches again on move 5.} d5 ({Be2 is a somewhat passive move, which Black can exploit with direct play in the center. With} 3... d5 {, White is deprived of the possibility to transpose to an Open Sicilian. We now get a typical position with an isolated queen's pawn, where the active black pieces compensate for the slight structural disadvantage.} 4. exd5 {is my suggestion for the Kan repertoire. In some places, transpositions to my recommendation for the Four Knights repertoire (} Nc6 5. O-O Nf6 6. Nc3 exd5 {) occur. I provide references to the corresponding lines in the text.}) 4. exd5 exd5 {The change in pawn structure benefits the c8 -bishop, which can now be developed freely.} 5. d4 ({White wants to later capture on c5 , isolating the d5 -pawn.} 5. O-O {has no independent significance, as White has no better plan than central play with d2-d4 and should therefore transpose to it later, e.g., with} Nf6 6. d4 {.}) 5... Nf6 6. O-O Nc6 {We develop the knights first because a move of the f8 -bishop could be met with dxc5 , after which the bishop has to move again. White now has several reasonable continuations.} 7. Bg5 {With this bishop move, White puts pressure on the d5 -pawn, as the defender Nf6 is now pinned and could be exchanged.} h6 ({It is useful to force the bishop to make a decision.} 7... Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 $2 9. Bxf6 {illustrates White's plan: Black must either weaken the pawn structure on the kingside or lose the d5 -pawn.}) 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nc3 ({White puts pressure on the black center. The immediate} 9. dxc5 $6 {is premature on account of} Qxb2 10. Nbd2 Bxc5 {.}) 9... Be6 10. dxc5 {This allows White to win a pawn, but Black gets good compensation.} O-O-O ({The d5-pawn is defended, and Black is threatening ...Bxc5 . A more detailed examination of this position can be found via the Four Knights move order : e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Be2 Nc6 O-O Nf6 Nc3 d5 exd5 exd5} 10... d4 {Be6 Bg5 h6 Bxf6 Qxf6 dxc5 O-O-O .}) *

