1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Be2 {A very rare but quite poisonous move that has been played by some strong grandmasters in recent years. White focuses on development while keeping the option to transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 . Players aiming for the Taimanov Sicilian have no reason to worry about this move sequence. However, those intending to play the Kan Variation or the Four Knights Sicilian must sooner or later abandon the hope of transposing into familiar territory in the Open Sicilian. My recommendations are as follows:  ➤ If you aim for the Kan Sicilian, it is best to choose d5 . This continuation prevents a transposition to the Open Sicilian and is therefore suitable for proponents of other Sicilian systems as well.  ➤ Personally, I prefer Nc6 to d5 , so I recommend this to those who play the Taimanov Sicilian or the Four Knights Sicilian. The path then branches again on move 5.} d5 ({Be2 is a somewhat passive move, which Black can exploit with direct play in the center. With} 3... d5 {, White is deprived of the possibility to transpose to an Open Sicilian. We now get a typical position with an isolated queen's pawn, where the active black pieces compensate for the slight structural disadvantage.} 4. exd5 {is my suggestion for the Kan repertoire. In some places, transpositions to my recommendation for the Four Knights repertoire (} Nc6 5. O-O Nf6 6. Nc3 exd5 {) occur. I provide references to the corresponding lines in the text.}) 4. exd5 exd5 {The change in pawn structure benefits the c8 -bishop, which can now be developed freely.} 5. d4 ({White wants to later capture on c5 , isolating the d5 -pawn.} 5. O-O {has no independent significance, as White has no better plan than central play with d2-d4 and should therefore transpose to it later, e.g., with} Nf6 6. d4 {.}) 5... Nf6 6. O-O Nc6 {We develop the knights first because a move of the f8 -bishop could be met with dxc5 , after which the bishop has to move again. White now has several reasonable continuations.} 7. Re1 ({The most popular continuation. It has the drawback that the f2 -pawn is no longer reliably defended.} 7. dxc5 {allows} Bxc5 {without loss of tempo and therefore benefits Black.}) ({Developing the queen's knight with} 7. Nc3 {is rarely played at this point, but we deal with this position via the move order e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Be2 Nc6 O-O Nf6 Nc3 d5 exd5 exd5} cxd4 {.}) (7. c3 {is also a rare and not very threatening waiting move here, but I have examined it here via the Taimanov/Four Knights move order: e4 c5 Nf3 e6 Be2 Nc6 c3 d5 exd5 exd5} cxd4 {Nf6 O-O .}) 7... Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {The simplest move. Castling is also playable, after which Black can regain the pawn later.} 9. Bd3+ (9. Bg5 $6 {walks into} Bxf2+ 10. Kxf2 Ne4+ 11. Kf1 Nxg5 {.}) 9... Be6 {Black wants to castle next. Subsequently, an important idea is the attack on the f2 -pawn, e.g., with ... Ne4 or ... Qb6 . Black's active pieces compensate for the weak pawn on d5 .} ({The attack on the bishop with Bf5?! or Ng5?! is not to be feared. Black continues with O-O and if White captures on e6 , Black gets an attack on the f2 -pawn. For example:   A ) White does not survive Rxe6? fxe6 Nxe6} 9... Qe7 {Nxf8 Rxf8 .   B ) Nxe6 fxe6} 10. Re6 $2 Ne4 {. Black's attack is too strong. Better would be} 11. Be3 Bxe3 {Rxe3 e5∓ .}) *

