1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Be2 {A very rare but quite poisonous move that has been played by some strong grandmasters in recent years. White focuses on development while keeping the option to transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 . Players aiming for the Taimanov Sicilian have no reason to worry about this move sequence. However, those intending to play the Kan Variation or the Four Knights Sicilian must sooner or later abandon the hope of transposing into familiar territory in the Open Sicilian. My recommendations are as follows:  ➤ If you aim for the Kan Sicilian, it is best to choose d5 . This continuation prevents a transposition to the Open Sicilian and is therefore suitable for proponents of other Sicilian systems as well.  ➤ Personally, I prefer Nc6 to d5 , so I recommend this to those who play the Taimanov Sicilian or the Four Knights Sicilian. The path then branches again on move 5.} Nc6 ({The main move and my recommendation for all who have an Open Sicilian with ...Nc6 in their repertoire. The Kan move} 3... a6 {has the drawback that White waits with d2-d4 and first plays} 4. O-O {. Black now has no continuation suitable both against the transposition into an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 and the Alapin Sicilian with c2-c3 .} b5 {This is premature without a white knight on c3 .} 5. a4) ({(Problematic is also c3 , as after} 3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 {we do not land in our system against the Alapin Sicilian because Black has played the slow a7-a6 .)}) 4. c3 {White transposes to the Alapin Sicilian. However, with the bishop on e2 , it is an unusual version.} d5 (4... Nf6 {is a good alternative here, for example,} 5. e5 Nd5 6. O-O d6 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Be7 {. The bishop on e2 would be better placed on one of the more active squares c4 or d3 .}) 5. exd5 (5. e5 $6 d4 $1 {reminds us of the positions we examined in Chapter 3 on the delayed Alapin Sicilian. Due to the bishop's development to e2 , it is a very favorable version for Black:  ...d4-d3 is already a threat, and the bishop on e2 blocks the e-file, making it difficult to defend the e-pawn. Black is already better.}) 5... exd5 ({We take advantage of White's choice not to develop the bishop to a more active square.} 5... Qxd5 {is also possible and gives White two options:}) ({A ) After d4 cxd4 cxd4} 5... Nf6 {we have transposed into a familiar position from the Alapin Sicilian, which we examined in detail in the first chapter.}) ({) White could also wait with d2-d4 , avoiding well-known theory: O-O!?} 5... Nf6 {[%eval 0,0]} 6. Na3 Be7 7. d4 {because now, after} cxd4 {,} 8. Nb5 {Qd8 Nbxd4 could follow.}) 6. d4 ({This position is usually reached via the move order e4 c5 c3 e6} 6. d4 {d5 exd5 exd5 Nf3 Nc6 . However, the main line and the critical attempt is Bb5 . Developing the bishop to e2 is too passive to challenge Black.}) 6... Nf6 7. O-O cxd4 ({The more popular} 7... Bd6 {allows White to develop a bit more actively:} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bg5 Be6 10. Nbd2 {.}) 8. Nxd4 ({Black is slightly structurally disadvantaged (the isolated d5 -pawn is weak), but compensates with active piece play. In the symmetrical pawn structure after} 8. cxd4 {, White cannot pose any problems. My preference now is} h6 {(to prevent Bg5 )} 9. Nc3 Bd6 {The black king's bishop is more active than the white one.}) 8... Bd6 {The bishop has the white king position in its sights.} 9. Be3 ({White overprotects the knight and prepares Nd2 . After} 9. Bg5 O-O {, White cannot easily develop the b1 -knight:} 10. Na3 {invites the disruption of the pawn structure on the queenside with} Bxa3 {.}) ({(} 9. Nd2 {is answered with} Nxd4 {after which White also gets an isolated pawn.)}) 9... O-O 10. Nd2 Re8 11. Re1 Bd7 {Black completes development without difficulty.} 12. Nf1 a6 {Black takes control of the b5 -square and prepares ... Qc7 , which was not possible before due to Nb5 . A good plan is to double rooks on the e-file with ... Re7 and ... Rae8 . The position of the knights can also be improved: on e4 and c4 , they are very active and put pressure on White's position. Black should generally avoid piece exchanges, as the weakness of the d5 -pawn could play a role in an endgame. In the middlegame, Black has nothing to fear, as piece activity offers full compensation for the structural disadvantage. The chances are equal.} *

