1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Be2 {A very rare but quite poisonous move that has been played by some strong grandmasters in recent years. White focuses on development while keeping the option to transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 . Players aiming for the Taimanov Sicilian have no reason to worry about this move sequence. However, those intending to play the Kan Variation or the Four Knights Sicilian must sooner or later abandon the hope of transposing into familiar territory in the Open Sicilian. My recommendations are as follows:  ➤ If you aim for the Kan Sicilian it is best to choose d5 . This continuation prevents a transposition to the Open Sicilian and is therefore suitable for proponents of other Sicilian systems as well.  ➤ Personally, I prefer Nc6 to d5 , so I recommend this to those who play the Taimanov Sicilian or the Four Knights Sicilian. The path then branches again on move 5.} Nc6 ({The main move and my recommendation for all who have an Open Sicilian with ...Nc6 in their repertoire. The Kan move} 3... a6 {has the drawback that White waits with d2-d4 and first plays} 4. O-O {. Black now has no continuation suitable both against the transposition into an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 and the Alapin Sicilian with c2-c3 .} b5 {This is premature without a white knight on c3 .} 5. a4) ({(Problematic is also c3 , as after} 3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 {we do not land in our system against the Alapin Sicilian because Black has played the slow a7-a6 .)}) 4. O-O ({White continues to develop without committing to either the Open or an Anti-Sicilian. If White now decides on the Open Sicilian, Black can choose after} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {:}) ({➤ Bb4 leads to the Pawn Sacrifice Variation of the Four Knights Sicilian. ➤ Qc7 transposes to the Taimanov Sicilian. ➤ With d6 , Black can also choose the Scheveningen system.} 4. Nc3 {pursues a waiting strategy similar to O-O . We have dealt with this position in Chapter 8 .}) 4... Nf6 {Attacks the e4 -pawn.} 5. e5 {Black is well prepared for this advance.} Ng4 {The e5 -pawn is not easily defended.} 6. d4 {After this, White loses the fight for the center.} cxd4 7. Bf4 (7. Nxd4 $6 Ngxe5 {gives White no compensation for the pawn.}) 7... d6 8. exd6 e5 ({This is stronger than} 8... Bxd6 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Bb5 {, when White regains the pawn and keeps the balance. After} e5 {follows} 11. h3 Nf6 12. Nxe5 $1 Qxe5 13. Re1 Ne4 14. Bd3 f5 15. f3 {.}) 9. Bg3 Bxd6 10. Nxd4 {White wins back the pawn.} Nxd4 11. Bxg4 Bxg4 12. Qxg4 Qd7 ({Black is slightly better. The knight on d4 is very strong, and the white bishop on g3 is somewhat out of play.} 12... Nxc2 $2 {fails due to the double attack} 13. Qa4+ {. O-O is also slightly better for Black.}) ({After Qxg7 O-O-O Na3} 12... h5 {, Black gets a strong attack for the pawn.}) *

