1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Be2 {A very rare but quite poisonous move that has been played by some strong grandmasters in recent years. White focuses on development while keeping the option to transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 . Players aiming for the Taimanov Sicilian have no reason to worry about this move sequence. However, those intending to play the Kan Variation or the Four Knights Sicilian must sooner or later abandon the hope of transposing into familiar territory in the Open Sicilian. My recommendations are as follows:  ➤ If you aim for the Kan Sicilian, it is best to choose d5 . This continuation prevents a transposition to the Open Sicilian and is therefore suitable for proponents of other Sicilian systems as well.  ➤ Personally, I prefer Nc6 to d5 , so I recommend this to those who play the Taimanov Sicilian or the Four Knights Sicilian. The path then branches again on move 5.} Nc6 ({The main move and my recommendation for all who have an Open Sicilian with ...Nc6 in their repertoire. The Kan move} 3... a6 {has the drawback that White waits with d2-d4 and first plays} 4. O-O {. Black now has no continuation suitable both against the transposition into an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 and the Alapin Sicilian with c2-c3 .} b5 {This is premature without a white knight on c3 .} 5. a4) ({(Problematic is also c3 , as after} 3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 {we do not land in our system against the Alapin Sicilian because Black has played the slow a7-a6 .)}) 4. O-O ({White continues to develop without committing to either the Open or an Anti-Sicilian. If White now decides on the Open Sicilian, Black can choose after} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {:}) ({➤ Bb4 leads to the Pawn Sacrifice Variation of the Four Knights Sicilian. ➤ Qc7 transposes to the Taimanov Sicilian. ➤ With d6 , Black can also choose the Scheveningen system.} 4. Nc3 {pursues a waiting strategy similar to O-O . We have dealt with this position in Chapter 8 .}) 4... Nf6 {Attacks the e4 -pawn.} 5. e5 {Black is well prepared for this advance.} Ng4 {The e5 -pawn is not easily defended.} 6. b4 {White sacrifices a pawn to gain control of d4 . Only in this way can 5.e5 be justified.} d6 ({Putting additional pressure on the white center.} 6... cxb4 7. d4 {gives White good control in the center and thus good play for the pawn.}) ({After} 6... Ngxe5 {White regains the pawn with} 7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. bxc5 {as} Bxc5 $2 {fails to} 9. d4 {.}) 7. d4 ({Relatively best. The black c-pawn is forced to make a decision.} 7. exd6 $6 cxb4 {followed by ...Bxd6 wins a pawn for Black.}) ({Inadequate is also} 7. bxc5 $6 dxe5 $1 {after which the c5 -pawn will soon fall.}) 7... cxd4 (7... cxb4 8. h3 Nh6 9. a3 {gives White compensation for the pawn.}) 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. b5 Ne7 10. h3 Ne5 11. Nxd4 ({White has managed to avoid material loss. Not} 11. Qxd4 $4 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Bh2+ 13. Kxh2 Qxd4 {.}) 11... O-O {Black has comfortable play. The queenside can be developed with ... b7 - b6 followed by ... Bb7 . As a result of the early advance of the b-pawn, White has weaknesses on the c-file.} *

