ain, a possible transposition to the Open Sicilian is on the horizon. Those who play the Taimanov Sicilian have no reason to avoid this. I then recommend . Reaching a Four Knights Sicilian, however, is no longer possible, so I suggest to transpose into an isolated pawn structure with d5 here. The passive} 5. d3 {presents no challenges for Black. After} d5 {Black is at least equal. The white bishop on e2 is poorly placed.}) 5... d5 ({The idea from Chapter 8 to prevent d2-d4 with} 5... Nd4 $2 {does not work here because Black has no good answer against} 6. e5 $1 {.}) 6. exd5 exd5 {The advantage of capturing with the pawn is that the c8 -bishop can be freely developed. In return, Black accepts that the d-pawn may become weak after d2-d4 followed by dxc5 .} ({The more popular and also playable move is} 6... Nxd5 {. For example} 7. d4 {( Bb5!? )} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Nxd4 10. cxd4 Bd6 {. The position is close to equal.}) 7. d4 Be6 ({This preemptively protects the d5 -pawn. It is better not to move the f8 -bishop yet.} 7... Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {Black has lost a tempo, as the bishop has had to move twice. After the text move, White has no obviously useful waiting moves.}) 8. Re1 Be7 {After White has moved the rook, it is time to develop the bishop.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 ({Black has now lost a tempo because the bishop has made two moves. On the other hand, the f2 -pawn is no longer reliably protected. Black is threatening ...Qb6 and has good counterplay, e.g., Bg5} 9... Qb6 {Bh4} 10. Ne4 $1) *

