1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Be2 {A very rare but quite poisonous move that has been played by some strong grandmasters in recent years. White focuses on development while keeping the option to transpose to an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 . Players aiming for the Taimanov Sicilian have no reason to worry about this move sequence. However, those intending to play the Kan Variation or the Four Knights Sicilian must sooner or later abandon the hope of transposing into familiar territory in the Open Sicilian. My recommendations are as follows:  ➤ If you aim for the Kan Sicilian, it is best to choose d5 . This continuation prevents a transposition to the Open Sicilian and is therefore suitable for proponents of other Sicilian systems as well.  ➤ Personally, I prefer Nc6 to d5 , so I recommend this to those who play the Taimanov Sicilian or the Four Knights Sicilian. The path then branches again on move 5.} Nc6 ({The main move and my recommendation for all who have an Open Sicilian with ...Nc6 in their repertoire. The Kan move} 3... a6 {has the drawback that White waits with d2-d4 and first plays} 4. O-O {. Black now has no continuation suitable both against the transposition into an Open Sicilian with d2-d4 and the Alapin Sicilian with c2-c3 .} b5 {This is premature without a white knight on c3 .} 5. a4) ({(Problematic is also c3 , as after} 3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 {we do not land in our system against the Alapin Sicilian because Black has played the slow a7-a6 .)}) 4. O-O ({White continues to develop without committing to either the Open or an Anti-Sicilian. If White now decides on the Open Sicilian, Black can choose after} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {:}) ({➤ Bb4 leads to the Pawn Sacrifice Variation of the Four Knights Sicilian. ➤ Qc7 transposes to the Taimanov Sicilian. ➤ With d6 , Black can also choose the Scheveningen system.} 4. Nc3 {pursues a waiting strategy similar to O-O . We have dealt with this position in Chapter 8 .}) 4... Nf6 {Attacks the e4 -pawn.} 5. Nc3 ({Again, a possible transposition to the Open Sicilian is on the horizon. Those who play the Taimanov Sicilian have no reason to avoid this. I then recommend . Reaching a Four Knights Sicilian, however, is no longer possible, so I suggest to transpose into an isolated pawn structure with d5 here. The passive} 5. d3 {presents no challenges for Black. After} d5 {Black is at least equal. The white bishop on e2 is poorly placed.}) 5... d5 ({The idea from Chapter 8 to prevent d2-d4 with} 5... Nd4 $2 {does not work here because Black has no good answer against} 6. e5 $1 {.}) 6. exd5 exd5 {The advantage of capturing with the pawn is that the c8 -bishop can be freely developed. In return, Black accepts that the d-pawn may become weak after d2-d4 followed by dxc5 .} ({The more popular and also playable move is} 6... Nxd5 {. For example} 7. d4 {( Bb5!? )} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Nxd4 10. cxd4 Bd6 {. The position is close to equal.}) 7. d4 Be6 ({This preemptively protects the d5 -pawn. It is better not to move the f8 -bishop yet.} 7... Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {Black has lost a tempo, as the bishop has had to move twice. After the text move, White has no obviously useful waiting moves.}) 8. Bg5 ({The most popular and logical move. By pinning the knight, White increases the pressure on d5 . A waiting move like} 8. h3 {does not significantly improve White's position. Black could now play} Be7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 {.}) {Good alternatives are the waiting move Rc8 and c4 , which takes away White's option to capture on c5 .} 8... h6 ({It is important to first force the bishop to make a decision.} 8... Be7 {would be premature:} 9. dxc5 O-O ({(} 9... Bxc5 $6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nxd5 {.)}) 10. Na4 {Black cannot win back the pawn easily. After} Ne4 {follows} 11. Be3 {.}) 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. dxc5 {White wins a pawn.} O-O-O {The d5 -pawn is defended, so Black is now ready for ... Bxc5 .} 11. Na4 g5 {The situation has intensified significantly in the last few moves. Black plays for a pawn attack on the kingside: ... g5 - g4 and ... h6 - h5 are likely the next moves.} 12. c3 ({A preventive measure against} 12. g4 {, which can now be met with} Nd4 {.}) ({In the correspondence game Van Damme-Hietanen , there followed} 12. Rb1 g4 13. Ne1 h5 14. b4 {and now Black could have developed a strong initiative on the kingside with} Nd4 15. b5 Bf5 {. The position can be improved further with moves like ...Bh6 , ...Be4 , and ...Rag8 .}) 12... d4 ({This activates Black's pieces and prevents White from stabilizing their position with Nd4 . After} 12... Bg7 {,} 13. Nd4 $1 {could follow, for example,} Nxd4 $6 14. cxd4 Qxd4 15. Qb3 {after which White is threatening c5-c6 with an attack.}) 13. Nxd4 ({Worse is} 13. cxd4 $2 g4 {.}) 13... Nxd4 14. cxd4 Rxd4 15. Qc2 Bd7 {Useful to prevent c5 - c6 . The bishop can later be transferred to c6 .} 16. b3 Bg7 {Black has very good compensation for the pawn with active pieces and the strong pair of bishops. The next moves could be ... Kb8 and ... Re8 .} *

