1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 6. Be3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bd3 b6 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qe2 Nb8 14. c4 Qe4 {We have studied the previous moves in the theoretical section . The position is equal, but the fight is still to come, as this game shows. Black will play against the 'hanging pawns' d4 and c4 and White could provoke a weak pawn on the queenside with the break a4- a5 -axb6 .} 15. Nd2 ({Most frequently played is} 15. Ne5 Nc6 ({or} 15... Nbd7) 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 {.}) ({After} 15. Qb2 Rc8 16. Rac1 Nbd7 17. a4 h6 18. Rfe1 Qf5 19. Qb5 Qxb5 20. axb5 a6 21. bxa6 Rxa6 {, GM Pelletier (with strong help from his opponent) managed to squeeze water from a stone and win this completely equal position. Crut, A-Pelletier, Y .}) 15... Qf5 ({The queen is best on the kingside. After} 15... Qb7 {,} 16. Bg5 $1 {is annoying, because Black actually wants to develop the b8 -knight to c6 and not to d7 .}) 16. Rfc1 Nc6 17. Nb3 ({The knight supports the a4-a5 advance and keeps the d4 -pawn protected.  In Khairullin, I-Lerner, K ,} 17. Rab1 h6 18. Rb5 Qg6 {followed and now White opted for the double-edged} 19. d5 {. After} exd5 20. cxd5 Ne7 {(or 20...Na5 )} 21. d6 Ned5 {(instead of Nf5 ) I like the black position better. The d6 -pawn is more of a weakness than a trump.}) 17... Rac8 18. h3 Rfd8 {This is the typical setup for Black. The white center is under good control.} 19. a4 {White also pursues the typical plan. The idea is to weaken the black queenside.} h5 ({An unusual decision.} 19... h6 {looks more solid.}) 20. f3 ({Without any necessity Christiansen weakens his position. Possibly he pursues aggressive intentions and prepares g2-g4 . There was nothing to be said against} 20. a5 {.}) 20... Nb4 ({Targeting d3 . Strong is also} 20... Ne7 {with the idea ...h5-h4 , ...Qg6 and ...Nf5 , which gives Black good play on the dark squares.} 21. g4 {would be very double-edged, because it further weakens the white king position.} Qg6 {.}) 21. a5 ({A bad moment for this advance. Better is} 21. Qd2 {, after which Black best returns to the plan outlined in my comment on the previous move with} Nc6 {.} (21... Qd3 22. Rab1)) 21... Qd3 22. Qxd3 Nxd3 23. Rc3 b5 {Christiansen had probably overlooked this when he played 21.a5 . The c-pawn must now either advance or be traded off. In both cases, Black gets good squares for their knights.} 24. Nc5 ({Relatively best.} 24. Rxd3 $2 bxc4 25. Rc3 {loses because of the intermediate move} Nd5 $1 {.}) (24. c5 Nb4 {The white pawns on the queenside are weak.}) 24... bxc4 25. Rxc4 Nd5 {Black has a comfortable edge. The d4 -pawn as well as the e3 - and f4 -squares are weakened.} 26. Bf2 Ne7 ({With the goal of increasing the pressure on d4 with ...Nf5 .} 26... Nxf2 27. Kxf2 Rb8) 27. Bh4 f6 28. Ra3 {White provokes the following exchange, which is favorable for Black.} Nxc5 29. dxc5 ({This allows the black rooks to become active.} 29. Rxc5 Rb8 $1 {and the d4 -pawn is under strong pressure.} (29... Rxd4 {would be weaker:} 30. Rxc8+ Nxc8 31. Bf2 Rd7 32. a6 {and Black is quite passive.})) 29... Rd1+ 30. Kh2 Nc6 ({The human move. Black initially prevents counterplay. However, stronger was} 30... Rb8 $1 31. c6 Rbb1 32. c7 Nf5 $3 33. c8=Q+ Kh7 {. Black is threatening mate on h1 and White has nothing better than} 34. Rc1 Rbxc1 35. Qxc1 Rxc1 {, leaving Black with an extra pawn and the better position.}) 31. Bg3 e5 32. f4 Rb8 33. fxe5 Rbb1 34. Bf2 Nxe5 35. Rh4 ({That should lose. The rook goes offside. The mistakes in the next moves suggest that both sides were in time trouble. After} 35. Rc2 $1 Rh1+ (35... g5 $6 36. g3) 36. Kg3 g5 37. Bd4 $1 h4+ 38. Kf2 {the white position remains defensible:} Rbe1 $1 39. g3 $1 Rd1 $1 40. Kg2 $1 hxg3 41. Rxg3 Ng6 42. Rg4 $1 Nf4+ 43. Rxf4 gxf4 44. c6 Rc1 45. Rxc1 Rxc1 46. Bxa7 {Of course, such a line cannot be calculated without mistakes at the board.}) 35... Rb2 ({A winning continuation for Black would have been} 35... g5 $1 36. Rxh5 Nd3 37. Be3 {. After} Nf4 $1 38. Bxf4 gxf4 {White is either mated or the rook on h5 is lost.}) 36. Bd4 Rb4 37. Bxe5 ({With} 37. Bf2 {White can defend themselves.}) 37... Rxh4 38. Bb8 Rc4 ({This makes things unnecessarily difficult. Much easier was} 38... a6 39. c6 Rc4 {.}) 39. Bxa7 h4 {Threatening ...Rcc1 with imminent mate.} 40. Ra2 {The only defense.} Rcc1 41. g4 Rd3 (41... Rh1+ 42. Kg2 Rcg1+ 43. Kf3 Kf7 $1 {wins, e.g.} 44. a6 Rxh3+ 45. Kf2 (45. Ke4 Ke6 $1 {with a mate soon following was the idea of 43...Kf7 .}) 45... Rhg3 {.}) 42. Bb8 ({White does not seize the offered chance.} 42. a6 Rcc3 43. Bb8 Rxh3+ 44. Kg2 Ra3 45. Rc2 {, e.g.} ({A ) Rhc3?? Rxc3 Rxc3} 45. a7 {Ra3 c6+- and the black king does not arrive in time.}) ({) Rhe3} 45. c6 {[%eval 0,0] Re8 c7 Rc8 Rd2 followed by Rd8 .})) 42... Rxc5 43. a6 Rdc3 {Black gets behind the a-pawn with a rook.} 44. Rg2 (44. a7 Rc2+ 45. Rxc2 Rxc2+ 46. Kg1 Ra2 {.}) 44... Ra5 45. a7 Raa3 {The game was ultimately decided by tactical mistakes in the time trouble phase. However, the trend was already in Black's favor in the early middlegame when White could no longer maintain the pawn on c4 .} *

