[PlyCount "116"]

{This game between the two world-class grandmasters was played at the 'Superbet Classic' in Bucharest, shortly after Nepomniashchi's world championship match against Ding. The opening phase is a failure for Vachier-Lagrave and demonstrates the dangers for the black position.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 {A surprise! Nepo, armed to the teeth with his World Championship preparation, opts for the supposedly tame Alapin Sicilian. He then demonstrates that this variation is by no means harmless.} d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 6. Na3 {The modern main move.} a6 7. Nc4 Nbd7 8. a4 {A sideline and a good choice. MVL can't remember his preparation and soon finds himself in a difficult position.} b6 ({Black prepares to develop the c8 -bishop, but as we'll see, the b6 -pawn tends to become weak.  My recommendation} 8... cxd4 $1 9. Qxd4 Bc5 {is simpler. If White now avoids the queen exchange with} 10. Qh4 {,} Qe4+ 11. Qxe4 Nxe4 {follows with an attack on f2 . In contrast to the game, Black has not yet played ...b7-b6 and therefore has not given White a target for attack.}) 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O cxd4 {MVL wants to develop the bishop to c5 and therefore decides to trade pawns.} ({The alternative is} 10... Be7 {, e.g.} 11. Bf4 O-O {. White's position looks more active, but it is not clear how progress can be made. In Kolago-Gritsak ,} 12. Ne3 Qc6 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 {followed, with equality.}) 11. Qxd4 Bc5 12. Qh4 ({More often} 12. Qxd5 {is played, but after} Nxd5 {the knight helps to defend the queenside. Black has no worries. Ebeling, D-Indjic, A .}) 12... Qe4 ({Black insists on exchanging queens. After} 12... O-O 13. Rd1 Qc6 14. Bf4 {as well, the white position is more comfortable. The d6 -square can be used by the white pieces.}) 13. Qxe4 Nxe4 14. Nfd2 {After this strong move, MVL realized that his position was difficult, as he said in the post-game interview. After the knight exchange, the queenside would not be well defended and otherwise, White would move the knight to b3 and drive away the c5 -bishop.} Nef6 ({The first new move. In Rusche-Wohlfahrt there followed} 14... Nxd2 15. Bxd2 {. White has strong pressure on the queenside.} Bd5 16. b4 Be7 17. Be3 Bf6 ({After} 17... Bxc4 18. Bxc4 {the black position is solid, but White has persistent pressure on the queenside and a strong pair of bishops.}) 18. Rac1 Rb8 19. Bf4 e5 $2 {(Black should have gone for 19...Bxc4 .)} 20. Be3 O-O {Now} 21. Rfd1 Be6 22. Rxd7 $1 Bxd7 23. Nxb6 {would have been decisive, because the queenside pawns are unstoppable in the long term.}) (14... a5 $5 {is Stockfish's suggestion. The queenside is now more solid because White no longer has the resource b2-b4 .}) 15. Nb3 Be7 16. Bf4 {The d6 -square and the b6 -pawn are weak.} Bd5 (16... O-O 17. Bd6 {is no better.}) 17. Rfd1 O-O 18. Nbd2 Rfc8 ({This allows a tactical sequence, the calculation of which, however, is anything but trivial and was also overlooked by Nepo. Better was} 18... a5 {.}) 19. Ne3 ({The missed opportunity was} 19. a5 $1 {. If Black exchanges on a5 , the pawn a6 would be very weak. The natural reaction is therefore} b5 {, but now comes} 20. Nb6 $1 Nxb6 21. axb6 {. The b6 -pawn is still prevented from advancing by the d5 -bishop, but it can be exchanged with Bf3 . The best move now is} Bc5 22. c4 $1 bxc4 23. Nxc4 {. Again, Bf3 is a threat, so Black has nothing better than} Bxc4 {, which loses the exchange after} 24. b7 $1 Bxe2 25. Rdc1 $1 Ne4 26. Be3 $1 Rab8 27. bxc8=Q+ Rxc8 28. b4 {.}) 19... Bc6 20. Ndc4 a5 {Preventing a4 - a5 and b2 - b4 .} 21. Nd6 Bxd6 ({It was probably better not to give up the bishop pair yet. The position after} 21... Rd8 {is passive, but it's not easy for White to make progress. Black could play ...Nc5 next.}) 22. Bxd6 Nc5 23. Bb5 Nb7 ({An ugly square for the knight. White's advantage increases.} 23... h5) 24. Ba3 Rc7 25. f3 Rac8 26. Rd2 {White controls the only open file.} h6 {Prepares the activation of the kingside, giving Black at least the appearance of counterplay.} 27. Rad1 Bxb5 28. axb5 Kh7 29. Kf2 g5 30. h4 Kg6 31. hxg5 {Nepo is getting impatient. Black has no counterplay at all, so it was better to improve White's position to the maximum first. White could have calmly brought the king to safety on the queenside and only then opened up the kingside.} hxg5 32. g4 ({Black was in time trouble and Nepo wanted to keep up pressure on the clock. This strategy did not work: Within a few moves, he turns a clear, unchallenged advantage into a losing position.  Once again it was better to prepare play on the kingside first.} 32. Rd4 {White subsequently brings the king to safety on c2 .}) 32... Rh8 {For the first time in the game Black, has real counterplay.} 33. Kg3 Rcc8 34. c4 ({After that, the square is no longer accessible to the white pieces.} 34. Rd4 {looks stronger, with the idea Rc4 .}) 34... Rh7 35. Bd6 Nd7 {Prevents Be5 on the one hand, and on the other hand the knight itself could be activated via e5 if the d6 -bishop moves away.} 36. b3 ({MVL suggested that White should simplify into an equal position:} 36. Bc7 $1 Rxc7 37. Rxd7 f6 {.}) ({After} 36. Be7 Ne5 {,} 37. Bxg5 $2 {does not work due to ( 37.Bd8= )} Nxf3 {(MVL).}) 36... f6 37. Ba3 Ne5 {Black is already in the driver's seat. The threat is ... Rch8 with an attack against the f3 -pawn.} 38. Bb2 ({This looks natural, but the exchange on e5 does not provide relief for White. With precise play White could still have defended, e.g.} 38. Re2 Rch8 39. Nf1 {.} Rh3+ {is met with} 40. Kg2 {and} Nxf3 $2 {fails to} 41. Re3 {.}) 38... Rch8 39. Kf2 ({The losing move. After} 39. Bxe5 fxe5 {White cannot prevent ...e5-e4! after which their position is full of weaknesses.}) 39... Nc5 {The b3 -pawn cannot be protected.} 40. Bxe5 fxe5 41. Rd6 Rh2+ 42. Kg1 Rh1+ 43. Kf2 R1h2+ 44. Kg1 e4 {White's king is caught in an attack.} 45. Nf1 (45. fxe4 Rh1+ 46. Kg2 R8h2+ 47. Kf3 Rh3+ 48. Kg2 R1h2+ 49. Kg1 Re2) 45... Rb2 46. Rxb6 (46. fxe4 Rh4) 46... exf3 {MVL has calculated precisely that at the end of the following line the white pawns do not pose a threat.} 47. Rd2 Rb1 48. Rc6 Rxf1+ 49. Kxf1 Rh1+ 50. Kf2 Ne4+ 51. Kxf3 Nxd2+ 52. Ke3 Nxb3 53. b6 Rh3+ 54. Kf2 Rh8 55. Rxe6+ Kf7 56. Re5 a4 57. Rb5 Ke6 58. Ke3 a3 ({Because of Rxb3} 58... Rh3+ {, White resigned. Despite the result, this game shows where the dangers lurk for Black in this opening.}) *

