[Black "3E | Kamsky, Gata – Svidler"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B40"]
[PlyCount "135"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5 4. e5 d4 5. Bd3 Bd7 6. Qe2 Bc6 7. Be4 Bxe4 8. Qxe4 Nc6 9. O-O Nge7 10. c4 ({Kamsky thus prevents ...Qd5 . Stronger is} 10. d3 {, which we consider in the corresponding theory chapter .}) 10... h6 ({After} 10... Ng6 $6 {, the pawn on e5 would be still reliably defended. The bishop must therefore be included in the attack.}) 11. d3 g5 {Black now wants to play ... Ng6 and ... Bg7 , after which the e5 -pawn can no longer be defended. Kamsky therefore takes energetic measures.} 12. h4 Bg7 {Sacrifices the g5 -pawn. Accepting the sacrifice would be dangerous for White, as it would open the h-file.} 13. h5 ({An understandable decision. White thus keeps the kingside closed and prevents ...Ng6 . However, the knight has another route...} 13. hxg5 Ng6 {Black will soon win back the pawn on e5 and has attacking potential along the h-file.}) 13... Nc8 {Black is threatening ... Nb6 - d7 , winning the e-pawn. Once again Kamsky takes radical measures.} 14. b4 Nxb4 ({The opening up of the position after} 14... cxb4 $6 15. a3 {would benefit White. The black king would now no longer be safe on the queenside. In addition, the d4 -pawn would not be reliably defended anymore.}) 15. Ba3 ({After} 15. Qxb7 $2 Nb6 {, Black has the double threat ...Nc2 and ...Nxd3 .}) 15... Qc7 ({With this Svidler goes astray. The b7 -pawn did not have to be protected yet. With the simple defensive move} 15... a5 {he could have kept the advantage. Winning back the pawn with} 16. Qxb7 $2 {leads to a very bad position for White after} Nb6 17. Qe4 Nd7 {. ...Nc2 is a threat and after an exchange on b4 the a-pawn comes under fire.} ({But not} 17... Nc2 $2 18. Bxc5 {.})) 16. Bxb4 cxb4 17. a3 ({Perhaps Svidler had overlooked this strong move. After} 17. Qxd4 $2 Ne7 {with the threat ...Nc6 , White won't be able to defend the e5 -pawn for long.}) 17... Ne7 ({Gives back the pawn. The alternative} 17... bxa3 18. Nxa3 {is no better, e.g.} O-O 19. Nb5 Qc6 20. Qxc6 bxc6 21. Nc7 $1 ({not} 21. Nbxd4 $2 g4 {followed by ...Bxe5 .}) 21... Rb8 22. Na6 {. The knight goes to c5 , where it can hardly be driven away. Black has many weak pawns and squares.}) ({Or} 17... b3 18. Nbd2 {.}) 18. axb4 Nc6 19. Na3 O-O ({Worse is} 19... Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Nb5 Qb8 22. Rae1 {, e.g.} Bg7 23. c5 O-O 24. Nd6 {. White not only attacks the b7 -pawn, but is also threatening f2-f4 with an attack on the black king.}) 20. Nb5 Qe7 21. Nbxd4 ({The pawn sacrifice} 21. Nd6 Nxe5 22. c5 {was an interesting alternative.}) 21... Nxb4 {The material balance remains intact. The unusual pawn structure makes for an exciting middlegame. Objectively, the situation is roughly equal.} 22. Nb5 Nc6 ({Better was} 22... a6 23. Nd6 f5 $1 {.}) 23. Rab1 ({White could have exploited Black's inaccuracy with} 23. d4 $1 f5 24. Qe3 {, when the pawns in the center are strong and restrict the g7 -bishop.}) 23... a6 24. Nbd4 Nb4 {There was nothing wrong with exchanging knights.} 25. Rb3 Rad8 26. Ra1 {Preventing ... a6 - a5 and threatening Ra4 . Svidler defends against this threat by covering a5 .} Qc5 27. Rab1 a5 28. Nb5 f5 ({Misses the opportunity for} 28... g4 29. d4 (29. Qxg4 $2 Nxd3) ({or} 29. Ne1 $2 g3 {are worse.}) 29... Qxc4 30. Na3 Qd5 31. Qxg4 b5 {. The connected passed pawns are now a trump.}) 29. exf6 Rxf6 {After the exchange of pawns, the bishop rejoins the game. However, the pawns e6 and b7 are weak. The position remains tense.} 30. Nbd4 Rf4 (30... Qc8 {.}) 31. Nxe6 ({After} 31. Qxe6+ Rf7 {, Black will later win back the pawn on d3 .}) 31... Rxe4 32. Nxc5 Re7 {In exchange for the pawn, Black has pressure against d3 . In addition, the a-pawn could become dangerous, especially when effectively supported by the bishop.} 33. Re1 Rxe1+ 34. Nxe1 Bf8 35. Na4 g4 {Takes the f3 -square from the knight and cuts the h5 -pawn off from possible support.} 36. Kf1 Kf7 37. g3 Bg7 38. Nc5 b6 39. Ne4 Bf8 40. Ke2 Re8 41. Kd2 Re5 {Black wins back the pawn. The chances remain equal.} 42. Nc2 Rxh5 43. d4 b5 ({This looks risky but is based on concrete calculation. Also possible was} 43... Nxc2 44. Kxc2 Bb4 {.}) 44. c5 Rd5 45. Nxb4 ({Or} 45. Nc3 Rd8 46. Nxb4 axb4 47. Rxb4 Bxc5 {.}) 45... Rxd4+ 46. Nd3 Rxe4 47. Rxb5 a4 48. Rb8 h5 49. Ra8 Bh6+ 50. Kd1 Bg7 ({This is a bit careless. From g7 the bishop can't help in the defense against the c-pawn.} 50... Bf8) 51. Ra7+ Kg6 ({Now Black is getting in serious trouble. What was needed was} 51... Kf6 {. Unlike on g6 , the king cannot be attacked by the knight here.}) 52. c6 Rc4 53. Nf4+ {The knight is brought in with tempo to support the c-pawn.} Kh6 54. Ra5 ({This allows an – albeit difficult – defense. After} 54. c7 Be5 55. Ne6 a3 $5 56. Ra6 $1 ({(} 56. Rxa3 Bxc7 {)}) 56... Kh7 57. Rxa3 Kg6 ({(} 57... Bxc7 $2 58. Ra7 {)}) 58. Ra8 Rxc7 $1 ({(} 58... Bxc7 $2 59. Rc8 {)}) 59. Nxc7 Bxc7 {White is up an exchange, but the endgame is probably unwinnable because White is tied to defending the pawns.}) 54... Bd4 ({The losing move. Necessary was} 54... Kh7 $1 55. Nxh5 ({( or} 55. Rxh5+ Bh6 {)}) 55... Bd4 56. Ra6 a3 {. The a- and c-pawns will exchange and Black still has to defend an endgame with a pawn down.}) (54... Bb2 $2 55. Rxh5+ Kg7 56. Rc5 $1 Rxc5 57. Ne6+ {loses.}) 55. c7 {Threatening Rxa4 .} Rxc7 56. Rxh5+ Kg7 57. Ne6+ Kg6 58. Rd5 {Black loses a piece.} a3 59. Rxd4 Ra7 60. Rxg4+ Kf5 61. Rg7 Ra4 (61... Rxg7 62. Nxg7+ Kg6 63. Kc2) 62. Nc5 a2 63. Nb3 Rb4 64. Ra7 Rxb3 65. Rxa2 Kg4 66. Ra4+ Kf3 67. Rf4+ Kg2 68. Ke2 *

