{After winning the title against Boris Spassky in 1972, Fischer did not play chess for 20 years and only returned in 1992 for an unofficial "rematch" against his former opponent. No wonder he tried to avoid discussions of opening theory. In three games he chose the Closed Sicilian for this purpose.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. exd5 exd5 6. d3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. Bg5 d4 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Ne4 Be7 11. Nf4 O-O 12. O-O Re8 13. Qh5 g6 14. Qd5 Bf5 {Up to this point we know the moves from the corresponding theory chapter . The position is in equilibrium.} 15. Rfe1 Kg7 {Black avoids possible tactics based on Nf6 +.} 16. a3 ({It's not so easy for either side to improve their position. With} 16. a3 {White prevents ...Nb4 .}) 16... Rc8 17. h3 Qxd5 {Spassky doesn't see a way to improve his position further and finally decides to exchange queens.} 18. Nxd5 Bf8 19. g4 {Fischer plays for a kingside squeeze.} Be6 {The exchange on e4 would also have led to an equal position.} 20. Nef6 ({An ambitious move. With} 20. Ng5 {or Nf4 White could have exchanged one of Black's bishops, after which there is not much going on.}) 20... Red8 21. g5 {This is risky, because this pawn could later become weak.} Bd6 {Spassky wants to free himself from the pressure on the kingside with ... h7 - h6 and ... Ne7 . But first he prevents Nf4 .} 22. Re4 {White's attempt to launch an attack won't achieve much. The black position is well defended.} Ne7 23. Rh4 Rh8 ({An interesting alternative was} 23... h5 $1 24. gxh6+ Kh8 {. The black king is very secure behind the white pawn and the white knights are suddenly much less secure. Black will probably win back the pawn soon with ...Nf5 .}) 24. Re1 Nf5 25. Rhe4 h6 {Black takes the initiative.} 26. h4 hxg5 27. hxg5 Rh4 ({This, however, is very tame. With} 27... Bh2+ 28. Kf1 c4 {, Spassky could have opened a second front on the queenside. White has to defend.}) 28. Rxh4 Nxh4 29. Re4 Nf5 30. Nf4 Ba2 {Black would like to keep the bishop pair; moreover, ... Bb1 is threatening to win a pawn.} 31. N4d5 {The rook is now no longer tied to the defense of the knight. White is threatening b2 - b3 , after which the bishop would be trapped.} Bxd5 32. Nxd5 {We have reached an endgame with opposite-colored bishops. The draw seems to be only a matter of time.} Kf8 33. Kf1 Re8 34. Rxe8+ ({Fischer could have tried} 34. Nf6 {, because the exchange of rooks is now bad for Black:} Rxe4 $2 35. dxe4 Ng7 36. e5 $1 Bc7 37. Bxb7 {with good winning chances. Black should therefore play 34...Rd8 .}) 34... Kxe8 35. Nf6+ Kd8 36. Bxb7 Bf4 37. Ne4 Bc1 {Black wins back the pawn.} 38. a4 Bxb2 39. Nxc5 Bc1 40. Be4 ({A winning attempt.} 40. Ne4 Ke7 {followed by ...Nd6 wins back the pawn or leads to a drawn bishop ending.}) 40... Bxg5 41. Bxf5 gxf5 {The position remains equal. It is not easy for either side to attack their opponent's pawns.} 42. Nb3 Bf6 43. Kg2 Kd7 44. Kg3 Ke6 45. Na5 Be5+ 46. Kh4 Bf6+ 47. Kh5 {Fischer continues to play for a win. The game now becomes sharp again.} Kd5 48. Kh6 ({There is no turning back.} 48. Nb3 $2 {loses on account of} Ke5 $1 {followed by ...Kf4 .}) 48... Kc5 49. Kh7 Kb4 50. Nc6+ Kc3 51. Kg8 Kxc2 52. Kxf7 Bh8 53. a5 Kxd3 54. a6 Ke2 55. Nxa7 d3 56. Nc6 d2 57. a7 d1=Q 58. a8=Q {Even the appearance of the two queens doesn't change the evaluation. Black has the initiative, but that's not enough to win.} Qd5+ 59. Kg6 Qe6+ 60. Kh7 Bc3 61. Nd8 Qe7+ 62. Kg6 Qf6+ 63. Kh5 Qh8+ 64. Kg6 Qg7+ 65. Kxf5 Qf6+ 66. Kg4 Qg6+ 67. Kf4 Bd2+ 68. Ke5 Bc3+ 69. Kf4 Qd6+ 70. Kf5 Qd7+ 71. Kg5 Qe7+ 72. Kf5 Qf6+ 73. Kg4 Qg7+ 74. Kf5 Qf6+ 75. Kg4 Qg6+ 76. Kf4 Bd2+ 77. Ke5 Qg5+ 78. Ke6 Qg4+ 79. Kf7 Qd7+ 80. Kg6 {This game was characterized by Fischer's will to fight. From an equal position in the opening, he initiated an attack which was easily repulsed. But even in the resulting equal endgame, he was looking for ways to upset the balance. Ultimately, however, the game never left the drawing zone.} *

