{The present game was played in the 2003 World Rapid Chess Championship, which was held as a knockout tournament. Polgar had lost the first game and was now under pressure to win. She opted for the rare Grand Prix Attack, but Kramnik proved to be well prepared.} 1. e4 c5 2. f4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. O-O Nf6 8. d3 a6 9. Nxf6+ ({White was already fighting to equalize, but this exchange only helps Black. Better is} 9. Bxc6 {, which we look at in more detail in the corresponding theory chapter .}) 9... gxf6 {This puts Black in control of the e5 -square and gives them the half-open g-file for the rook. The king is brought to the queenside and is safe there.} 10. Ba4 Nd4 ({Perhaps due to the tournament situation, Kramnik is happy to simplify the position. His move, however, gives away the advantage.  Stronger is} 10... Qc7 {followed by ...0-0-0 . This would have led to a position similar to the one that arose later in the game, without giving White the chance to simplify.}) 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Be3 {The exchange on d4 would have led to an equal position. Instead, Polgar wants to keep the position complicated. However, the black knight is superior to its white counterpart, as the latter's options are limited by the black pawns.} Nf5 13. Qe2 ({Necessary was} 13. Bf2 Rg8 14. Nh4 $1 {, but then, of course, she could have exchanged knights on move 12 already.}) 13... O-O-O {Black easily manages to find good squares for their pieces, e.g. ... Rg8 , ... Bd6 and ... Qc7 would be a good setup. White, on the other hand, lacks active possibilities.} 14. Bf2 {Now the f4 -pawn is no longer protected. But it's difficult to suggest an improvement.} Qc7 15. Nd2 ({Polgar correctly decides to sacrifice the pawn.} 15. g3 $2 {Gives Black a pawn break:} h5 $1 {followed by ...h5-h4 and a kingside attack.}) 15... Qxf4 {It's not at all clear whether this is best. With the f-pawn gone, the bishop on f2 and the f1 rook become active.} 16. Ne4 Qc7 17. c3 ({With the surprising} 17. g4 $1 {White would have preserved good chances. The knight is driven out of its strong position and White could capture on f6 next.}) 17... Bd6 {This poses big problems for White. The defense of the h2 -pawn is accompanied by a weakening of their king position while after the exchange on d6 , White has no compensation for the pawn.} 18. b4 {Polgar tries to create complications and launch her attack on the black king. Objectively, however, White's position can no longer be salvaged. It takes too long for White to create threats.} Bxh2+ 19. Kh1 Bg3 (19... Rhg8 20. bxc5 Rg6 {followed by ...Rdg8 or ...Rh6 was a more direct win.}) 20. bxc5 Rhg8 21. Kg1 Bh2+ 22. Kh1 Bg3 ({Kramnik is satisfied with a draw and therefore repeats moves.} 22... Rg6 {leads to a winning position.}) 23. Rab1 Rg6 24. Bxg3 Nxg3+ 25. Nxg3 Qxg3 26. Qb2 Rh6+ 27. Kg1 Qh2+ 28. Kf2 Qf4+ (28... Qc7) 29. Ke2 Qe5+ 30. Kd2 Qg5+ 31. Ke2 Qxg2+ 32. Rf2 Qxf2+ 33. Kxf2 Rh2+ 34. Ke3 Rxb2 35. Rxb2 h5 {White's position is hopeless, but since Kramnik only needed a draw for the next knockout round, the game now ended peacefully. The opening was a disaster for Polgar, who never achieved a full game.} *

