1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. g3 d5 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bg2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 Bg4 11. f3 Bd7 {Up to this point we know the position from the corresponding theory chapter . Black has equalized.} 12. Nb3 {Black was ready to attack the white blockade with ... Bc5 . White prevents this and at the same time attacks the d5 -pawn.} Be6 {Black could also have chosen the slightly more active f5 -square for the bishop.} 13. Ne2 Re8 14. Ned4 ({White decides to block the IQP again. The knight could also have moved to f4 to put pressure on the d-pawn.} 14. Nf4 Bf5) 14... Bd7 15. Bf2 Ne5 16. Re1 ({Better was} 16. Nc1 $1 {followed by Nd3 , challenging the strong black knight.}) 16... Qc7 {Black is slightly better. A strong plan now is ... h7 - h5 -h4 to provoke weaknesses in the white king position. The e5 -knight can go to c4 or support play on the kingside from g6 .} 17. c3 Bd6 18. Qc2 g6 ({While this prevents Nf5 as a precaution, it also takes away the g6 -square from Black's knight. I like the direct} 18... h5 {better. If White plays} 19. Nf5 {, then} Bf8 {. The knight can later be driven away with ...g7-g6 .}) ({If, on the other hand, White continues with Re2 as in the game, there is nothing to be said against h4 , because after g4 Black can protect the pawn with} 18... Ng6 {.}) 19. Re2 h5 20. Rae1 h4 {Black might have done better without this now. The pawn could become weak.} 21. f4 ({This weakens the squares g4 and e4 . Better was} 21. g4 {, e.g.} Nc4 22. h3 Bg3 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Rxe8+ Nxe8 25. Nc1 {White brings the knight to d3 and prepares f3-f4 , after which the d5 -pawn would be attacked. Black is now on the defensive.}) 21... Neg4 22. Rxe8+ Bxe8 23. Nf3 {Now e4 is no longer covered by the bishop.} hxg3 ({Black should have played} 23... Nxf2 {first.}) 24. hxg3 ({White could have initiated an attack with the pawn sacrifice} 24. Bd4 $1 {.}) 24... Nxf2 25. Qxf2 Ne4 {White can no longer protect the g3 -pawn.} 26. Qd4 Nxg3 27. Ne5 Bc6 ({It was better to drive away the queen from its active position:} 27... Nf5 28. Qxd5 Qb6+ 29. Nd4 Nxd4 30. cxd4 Rd8 {.}) 28. Bxd5 (28. Ng4 $1 Nh5 29. f5 {gives White counterplay.}) 28... Bxd5 ({It was better to play} 28... Nf5 {first. After} 29. Qc4 ({(} 29. Bxf7+ $2 Kg7 30. Qc4 Bxe5 31. Rxe5 Qxf7 {)}) 29... Bxd5 30. Qxd5 Rd8 {the white king is rather defenseless.} 31. Nxg6 $2 {now fails to} Qb6+ 32. Kg2 ({(} 32. Kh1 Qf2 {)}) ({(} 32. Nd4 Nxd4 33. cxd4 Bb4 {)}) 32... Ne3+ 33. Rxe3 Qxe3 {.}) 29. Qxd5 Rd8 ({With} 29... Re8 {Black would have kept the advantage. The white king is in danger.}) 30. Kg2 Nh5 31. Nxg6 Nxf4+ 32. Nxf4 Bxf4 33. Qe4 {The game is now equal again. Both kings lack protection, so one misstep could be fatal.} Bh6 34. Nd4 Qb6 35. Re2 Rd6 36. Nf5 Rg6+ 37. Kf3 Bf8 38. Rh2 Qg1 {Black seizes the opportunity. The white king comes under attack.} 39. Qe5 Qf1+ 40. Ke3 Qe1+ 41. Kd4 Rd6+ 42. Nxd6 Bg7 43. Qxg7+ Kxg7 {The question now is whether White will manage to build a fortress. However, since White's forces are not yet well coordinated, Black should have good winning chances.} 44. Rg2+ Kf8 45. Ne4 Ke7 ({A loss of time. Stronger was} 45... f5 46. Nd2 Qh4+ 47. Ke3 Qh3+ 48. Kf2 Qh1 {. The queen wants to swing over to the poorly defended queenside.}) 46. c4 (46. Rf2 $1) 46... b6 (46... f5 $1) 47. Rf2 {Now it is no longer so easy for Black to make progress.} Qc1 ({Provokes a move that White wants to play anyway.} 47... Qg1 $1) 48. b3 {Now everything is well defended for White.} Qg1 49. Kd3 Ke6 50. Re2 Qb1+ 51. Kc3 Qc1+ 52. Kd3 Qd1+ 53. Nd2+ Kd6 54. Rf2 Qh5 55. Kc2 f5 56. Rf3 Qg4 57. b4 f4 58. a3 Qf5+ 59. Kc1 Qe5 60. c5+ Kd5 61. cxb6 axb6 62. Kd1 b5 63. Kc2 Qf5+ {Progress is impossible.} *

