{In light of Ra8 White resigned. The game demonstrates the strength of 7...g5 . The white minor pieces were dominated by the black pawns.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 4. Nf3 e6 5. O-O a6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Re1 g5 8. g3 d6 9. Bf1 g4 10. Nh4 Be7 11. Ng2 h5 {We already know this position from the theoretical section . White is already in an unenviable position. We now look at how GM Martirosyan converts the advantage into a full point.} 12. d3 ({Better was} 12. Ne3 {, when after} Ne5 {the defense} 13. Bg2 {would be available.}) 12... Nd4 13. Be2 Nf6 14. Be3 ({White could have driven the knight away from d4 with} 14. Nb1 $1 {followed by c2-c3 . It would therefore probably have been better to move the knight to e5 instead of d4 on move 12 .}) 14... Nd7 {The intention is clear: to bring the knight into the attack on the f3 -square via e5 .} 15. Bxd4 ({White misses another opportunity for} 15. Nb1 $1 {, which would have limited the damage.} Ne5 {can now be met with} 16. Nd2 {.}) 15... cxd4 16. Nb1 Qb6 {Provokes the following pawn move.} 17. b3 {It was better to sacrifice the pawn. Now White won't manage to play the liberating c2 - c3 , which means that their minor pieces don't have good squares.} Qc5 {Prevents c2 - c3 and Na3 , and prepares a move of the b-pawn.} 18. Nd2 b5 ({Better is} 18... b6 {.}) 19. a4 Bb7 ({The last two moves give White unnecessary counterplay. Better was} 19... b4 {, but Martirosyan wanted to keep the c4 -square under control.}) 20. axb5 axb5 21. Rxa8+ Bxa8 {The exchanges relieve White's position somewhat and give them hope of counterplay along the a-file. Nevertheless, their position remains difficult.} 22. f3 Ne5 23. f4 ({This is tantamount to resigning, as it deprives White of all counterplay. Necessary was} 23. fxg4 hxg4 24. Bxg4 Nxg4 25. Qxg4 Qxc2 26. Qe2 {Black is still clearly better, but at least the rook can be activated via the a-file and the knights have squares.}) 23... Nc6 {Threatening ... Nb4 , after which the c2 -pawn could no longer be protected.} 24. Qa1 Bb7 25. Qb2 Kd7 {The rook h8 should help out on the queenside.} 26. Ra1 Nb4 27. Bd1 f5 {Martirosyan's position is so dominant that he can exert pressure all over the board.} 28. Kf1 h4 29. gxh4 Bxh4 30. Qa3 Bf6 31. Qa7 (31. Kg1 Ra8 32. Qb2 Rxa1 33. Qxa1 fxe4 {is no better.}) 31... Qc6 32. Qa5 *

