1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3 a6 4. g3 b5 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. d3 Nc6 7. O-O d6 8. Ng5 h6 9. Nh3 Nf6 10. f4 Be7 11. f5 b4 12. Ne2 exf5 13. Rxf5 O-O {We have looked at the moves up to this point in the corresponding theory chapter . Black has already begun to turn the tables: the white attack on the kingside has come to nothing and the white pieces are inharmoniously placed. Meanwhile, Black has already made great progress on the queenside.} 14. c4 ({White wants to stop ...d6-d5 , which Black could have played after} 14. Rf1 {, for example.}) 14... bxc3 {The trade makes it easier for Black to find attacking targets.} 15. bxc3 Ne5 {The threat is ... c5 - c4 , after which the e4 -pawn would lose its defender.} 16. c4 {Zherebukh thus prevents ... c5 - c4 and at the same time the possible break ... d6 - d5 . The disadvantage of this is that the dark squares e5 and d4 are now weakened. The knight e5 can no longer be driven away.} Bc8 {Caruana adapts to the changed circumstances: Since the white pawn triangle is well fortified in the center, the bishop no longer had any prospects on b7 . It is therefore brought to a more favorable diagonal.} 17. Rf1 Rb8 {First the b-file is brought under control. ... Bg4 could follow next.} 18. Nhf4 {This accelerates the defeat.} g5 {Caruana is not afraid of ghosts. White can't exploit the apparent weakening of Black's king position. With 18...g5 , Black gains time, and the pawn limits the activity of White's pieces even further.} 19. Nd5 ({Or} 19. Nh3 Nfg4 {followed by ...Bf6 . White has no counterplay and has to stand idly by while the black pieces penetrate the white position.}) 19... Nxd5 20. cxd5 Bf6 {Threatening a discovered attack with the knight. White can no longer avoid the loss of material.} 21. d4 cxd4 22. Nxd4 Bg4 23. Qa4 ({Or} 23. Qe1 Nf3+ 24. Nxf3 Bxf3 {and ...Bxa1 .}) 23... Nd3 {The main threat is ...Rb4 .} 24. Qc4 ({After} 24. a3 {there are many winning continuations, e.g.} Bd7 25. Qc4 Nxc1 26. Raxc1 Qb6 $1 27. Rxf6 Rfc8 {.}) 24... Rb4 ({Here too} 24... Nxc1 25. Raxc1 Qb6 $1 26. Rxf6 Rfc8 {was possible. Caruana's move also wins.}) 25. Qxd3 Bxd4+ 26. Be3 Bxa1 27. Rxa1 {White has nothing to show for the exchange. He makes a few more moves and then resigns.} Qf6 28. Re1 Rc8 29. h3 Bd7 30. Qxa6 Rc2 31. Rf1 {White's opening concept proved to be questionable. Caruana played the game flawlessly and didn't give his opponent, a strong GM, the slightest chance.} *

