[ECO "A34"]
[PlyCount "74"]

1. e4 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 Nge7 5. Bg2 Nd4 6. Nge2 Nec6 7. O-O Be7 8. d3 O-O 9. f4 Rb8 {We know this position from the theory part Black prepares play on the queenside: ... a7 - a6 followed by ... b7 - b5 is the plan.} 10. a4 {The weakening of the b4 -square does not matter much here. However, White is unable to permanently stop ... b7 - b5 .} a6 11. Be3 ({After that, White can no longer capture with the knight on d4 unless they make further preparatory moves (which would lose time). I think White should have already played for equality, for example with} 11. Nxd4 {.} cxd4 ({(or} 11... Nxd4 12. Be3 d6 13. b4 {, when White strikes first on the queenside.)}) 12. Nb1 b5 13. axb5 axb5 14. b3 {White keeps the pawn structure intact.}) 11... d6 ({The idea of White's previous move was probably that} 11... b5 {can now be met with} 12. axb5 axb5 13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Nxb5 {. However, Black wins back the pawn with} Qb6 {followed by ...Ba6 .}) 12. Bf2 Bd7 13. Rb1 ({White wants to trade on d4 and play b2-b4 .} 13. Nxd4 {does no longer equalize because the f2 -bishop is out of place.} cxd4 14. Nb1 b5 15. axb5 axb5 16. b3 bxc4 17. bxc4 e5) 13... Bf6 14. Kh1 ({White finds it difficult to do something constructive.} 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. b4 $6 {is not good on account of} ({(} 15. b3 {)}) 15... cxb4 16. Rxb4 Qa5 17. Na2 Qc5 {. The white a-pawn is weak.}) 14... b5 {Black has made all the necessary preparations.} 15. axb5 axb5 16. cxb5 ({After this, White is left with an inferior pawn structure.} 16. b3 {is no better, e.g.} Qc7 {. Black has more space on the queenside, can move the major pieces there and subsequently open up the position.}) (16. Nxd4 Nxd4 {and only now} 17. cxb5 {seems to give White a better chance of equalizing.} Bxb5 {is met with} 18. b4 $1 {(or Nxb5 ) .}) 16... Nb4 ({To avoid} 16... Nxb5 17. Nxb5 Rxb5 18. d4 {. The weakness of the b2 pawn gives Black a permanent advantage. White has hardly any counterplay.}) 17. Qd2 Nxe2 ({(} 17... e5 $5 {)}) 18. Qxe2 Bd4 19. Qd2 e5 20. Bxd4 {There was no need to hurry with this exchange.} exd4 21. Nd5 ({Stronger is} 21. e5 $5 dxe5 22. Ne4 {.}) ({Or} 21. f5 $5 {. After} dxc3 $2 22. bxc3 {, White regains the piece.}) 21... Rxb5 ({Easier is} 21... Nxd5 22. exd5 Rxb5 {. The better pawn structure gives Black good winning chances.}) 22. f5 f6 23. g4 {Playing on the kingside is the only chance of counterplay.} Re8 24. Rf3 ({After that, White can't offer any resistance on the e-file. After} 24. Nxb4 Rxb4 25. h4 {the fight is still open.}) 24... Nxd5 25. exd5 Qe7 26. Rbf1 {It's already too late to suggest improvements.} Qe2 27. Qf4 Qe5 28. Qd2 Qxd5 ({Winning a pawn, but allowing the white forces to be activated. Black didn't have to hurry, e.g.} 28... h6 {or Rb3 look stronger.}) 29. g5 ({White offers no resistance. Now the f5 pawn is weak as well.} 29. Re3 $1 Qf7 30. Rxe8+ Bxe8 31. Re1 {was the best chance.}) 29... Qe5 30. gxf6 Qxf6 31. Rg3 Kh8 32. Bd5 Rbb8 33. Qg2 Re3 ({(} 33... Bxf5 {)}) 34. Rg5 Rbe8 35. Rg1 Re1 36. Rg6 Rxg1+ 37. Kxg1 Qxf5 {This victory was likely not particularly difficult for GM Sedlak: there were no complicated variations to calculate – just knowledge of the common plans was enough to give a stable advantage out of the opening.} *

