[White "Model Games"]
[Black "11C | Bassem Amin – Leinier D"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C00"]
[PlyCount "70"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {This move order is one of the most common paths to the King's Indian Attack.} O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 {We have now reached the King's Indian Attack.} Nc6 ({and now we are in familiar territory . In our repertoire, we reach this position via the move order} 7... dxe4 {c5 Nf3 e6 d3 Nc6 g3 d5 Nbd2 Nf6 Bg2 Be7 O-O O-O .}) 8. Re1 b5 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 Bb7 11. h4 Qc7 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {In 2016, when this game was played, this was still an unusual plan. However, Dominguez had already played like this against Karjakin one year before.} 13. N1h2 Qd8 14. c3 ({A rare move. White normally focuses on the kingside. Accordingly,} 14. h5 {was our main line in the theoretical part. In Andreikin, D-Bukavshin, I , White first played h5 and only after} h6 15. c3 {. After} a5 16. Qd2 ({(} 16. a4 $5 {)}) 16... d4 $1 17. Ng4 dxc3 18. bxc3 Bf8 {Black had achieved a favorable opening up of the position.} 19. Nfh2 Rab8 20. Be4 b4 21. cxb4 {As GM Mekhitarian noted,} c4 $1 {would now have led to big problems for White.}) 14... a5 15. a4 {An interesting idea with which Amin obstructs the black attack on the queenside.} Ba6 (15... b4 {would now be risky, because after} 16. c4 {the queenside remains closed.}) (15... bxa4 {was a good alternative that would have led to positions similar to the game and possibly saved some time.}) 16. axb5 Bxb5 17. b3 {Amin makes another prophylactic move on the queenside to prevent Black from gaining space with ... a5 - a4 .} Nb6 ({Dominguez insists on the idea ...a5-a4 . However, this moves the knight away from potential defensive tasks on the kingside. More solid was} 17... Ba6 {. Black's counterplay is then directed against the b3 -pawn, which can be attacked by the major pieces.}) 18. Ng5 ({Amin should have continued his prophylactic approach and first pushed back the bishop with} 18. c4 $1 {so that it no longer supports ...a5-a4 . After} Ba6 19. Ng5 $1 h6 20. Nh3 {White gets good attacking chances on the kingside. Next, the queen could join the attack from g4 or h5 . Meanwhile, Black has not achieved much on the queenside yet.}) 18... h6 19. Nh3 a4 {Perhaps Amin had overlooked the fact that this is possible.} 20. bxa4 ({The tactical punchline is} 20. c4 $2 axb3 $1 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. cxb5 Nd4 {. The b-pawn is almost unstoppable and worth more than a piece.}) 20... Nxa4 {Now Black has sufficient counterplay on the queenside.} 21. c4 ({With a pawn sacrifice White opens the long diagonal for the g2 -bishop and prevents the defensive move ...Bxd3 . Objectively this should lead to a black advantage, but at the board, it is hardly possible to correctly calculate the ensuing complications.  After the direct} 21. Qg4 $6 {,} h5 $1 22. Qxh5 Bxd3 {is strong. The bishop helps to defend the kingside and Black has an advantage on the queenside.}) (21. Bxh6 $5 {is possible, because after} gxh6 22. c4 $1 {wins back the piece.} Nb2 $1 23. Qg4+ Kf8 24. cxb5 Nxe5 $1 25. Qh5 Nbxd3) ({Black didn't have to take on h6 on move Good alternatives were Nxc3 or Nb2 .} 21. Qc2 {is also very instructive, because according to Stockfish the unexpected sacrifice} Nb4 $1 {is now the strongest move. After} 22. cxb4 cxb4 {the b-pawn is dangerous for White and provides sufficient compensation for the piece.}) 21... dxc4 22. Qg4 cxd3 {There was no good alternative to this because White had been threatening to capture on c4 .} 23. Bxh6 Bf8 ({The alternative} 23... Qf8 $1 {was stronger. Black defends against} 24. Nf4 {with} Nc3 $1 25. Rxa8 Rxa8 26. Nxd3 ({(} 26. Nh5 Ra4 $1 {( d2?} 27. Bd2 {) f4 d2-+ )}) 26... Bxd3 27. Bxc6 Ra2 28. h5 Bf5 29. Qf3 gxh6 30. Qxc3 Qb8 {. These lines are taken from GM Krikor Mekhitarian's analysis of the game for Chessbase magazine.}) 24. Nf4 Ne7 ({From a human point of view, strengthening the defense is the sensible decision. The engine, on the other hand, is less impressed by the white attack and suggests} 24... d2 $1 25. Bxg7 $1 ({(} 25. Red1 $2 Nxe5 {)}) 25... dxe1=Q+ 26. Rxe1 Bxg7 27. Nh5 Kf8 $1 {.} (27... Qf8 $2 {loses, as Mekhitarian shows:} 28. Nf6+ Kh8 29. Qh5+ Bh6 30. Nhg4 Qg7 31. Be4 $1 {and Black has no defense against Nxh6 and the subsequent attack on their king. (Not Nxh6?} Qg6 $1 {)}) 28. Qxg7+ Ke7 $1 ({(Mekhitarian analyzes the weaker} 28... Ke8 $2 29. Ng4 {.)}) 29. Bxc6 Rxc6 30. Qg5+ Kd7 31. Rd1+ Kc7 32. Rxd8 Rxd8 {The position remains sharp and unclear, but the c-pawn is a powerful trump.}) 25. Bg5 ({Amin loses the thread and chooses a continuation that is too slow. Correct was} 25. Be4 $1 d2 26. Bxg7 $1 dxe1=Q+ 27. Rxe1 Bxg7 28. Nh5 Ng6 ({(} 28... Qf8 $2 29. Nf6+ Kh8 30. Qh5+ Bh6 31. Nhg4 {)}) 29. Bxg6 fxg6 30. Qxg6 {and however Black protects the bishop, Nf6 with perpetual check follows, e.g.} Qe7 31. Nf6+ Kf8 32. Nh7+ Kg8 33. Nf6+ Kf8 {(Mekhitarian).}) 25... d2 26. Red1 Nc3 {White loses material.} 27. Bxa8 Nxd1 28. Rxd1 ({Or} 28. Qxd1 Rxa8 29. Rxa8 Qxa8 30. Qxd2 Qa1+ 31. Kg2 Qxe5 {.}) 28... Rxa8 29. Nf3 ({The attack} 29. Nh5 {is rebutted with} Qd4 $1 {.} 30. Bf4 Ng6 ({Qxd4 cxd4 Rxd2} 30... Nc6 {Bf4} 31. Ra1 {Kg2 Bb4-+ (Mekhitarian).})) 29... Ra1 30. Nxd2 (30. Rxa1 d1=Q+ 31. Rxd1 Qxd1+ 32. Kh2 Bc6 33. Kg2 Nf5 {followed by ...Nd4 (Mekhitarian).}) 30... Qd4 {Winning the e5 -pawn; moreover, the white pieces completely lack harmony. The battle is over.} 31. Nb1 Qxe5 32. Kh2 Bc6 33. Nh5 Qe4 34. Qxe4 Bxe4 35. Re1 Bg6 {An exciting, imaginative battle that was on a knife-edge for a long time.} *

